<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-RESENDING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY STUNNED BY CROATIA
</HEADLINE>
 FOR THOSE NEEDING-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ The sense of history wasn't lost on the
Croatians, who have endured so much of the stuff in a few short
years, rarely with the joy that accompanied what they achieved
Saturday night at Stade Gerland.
</P>
<P>
   In what is by far the biggest stunner of this World Cup, of many
World Cups, for that matter, Croatia tiny, inconsequential Croatia
took its place among the final four with a 3-0 romp over three-time
champion Germany in a clash fraught with controversy.
</P>
<P>
   A disputed red card, which forced the Germans to play with only
10 men for more than half the match, provided the means for a
Croatian triumph, an historic conquest that left one side rapturous
and the other bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still not aware of what we have done,'' defender Slaven
Bilic offered after the Croats, playing in their first World Cup,
claimed a spot in Wednesday's semifinal against France in
Saint-Denis. ``This is a dream come true, but we are not afraid of
anybody. ... When (Coach Miroslav) Blazevic said two years ago that
we were the best in the world, we all laughed. But we are laughing
less and less now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' goalkeeper Drazen Ladic added, ``we can say we're
the best team in the world tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a point with which the Germans might argue, given their
mood following Norwegian referee Rune Pedersen's expulsion of
defender Christian Woerns their top player this tournament for a
clumsy attack on Davor Suker in the 40th minute. Their dominance,
unfailing to that point, quickly evaporated, and Robert Jarni's
stirring strike nearly three minutes into injury time provided the
Croats with everything they needed.
</P>
<P>
   When Goran Vlaovic, with a near carbon-copy of Jarni's blast,
and Suker added counterattack goals in the final 10 minutes,
Croatia had avenged a similarly controversial defeat in the
European Championship quarterfinals two years ago to become the
first Cup debutante since Portugal in 1966 to reach the final four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country is going to be burning in celebration,'' said
Suker, whose goal was his fourth of the Cup. ``We played with our
hearts. ... This shows not always do the big teams win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big, big, big, big, big victory for us,'' said Dario
Simic, seeking some sort of perspective. ``We're a small country.
Right now it's incredible what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   To place it in context, Croatia which gained its independence
from Yugoslavia seven years ago is a nation of 4.7 million people;
Germany has 6 million registered players.
</P>
<P>
   The only one that counted, ultimately, was Woerns, whose
midfield challenge on Suker was indeed late he slammed into the
Croat's knee after the ball had been pushed past but didn't appear
premeditated. Pedersen's penalty seemed harsh, but he was
challenged all night by a particularly rough affair, full of shoves
and elbows, in which 54 fouls were whistled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the replay on television,'' Woerns said, ``and I
think that the red card was a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision raised the ire of the Germans, whose win over
Croatia in 1996 was largely determined by a questionable red card
that gave them the advantage. This time, the Croats took charge,
using the extra man to find space in what had been a tight,
organized German defense.
</P>
<P>
   After Jarni's goal a 22-yard blast inside the right post after a
nifty run and feed from Mario Stanic Germany was forced to push
forward, leaving plenty of space for the Croat counter to exploit.
It led to myriad chances, then, finally, Vlaovic's goal in the 80th
minute. Suker added his in the 85th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not us who lost the game, but it was the referee who
cost us the match,'' charged German defender Juergen Kohler. ``The
red-card decision was unjust. It was ridiculous. Why is it always
the Germans who get cheated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very clear that the red card was not a red card,'' said
sweeper Lothar Matthaeus. ``The quality of refereeing was well
below standard. I'm not alone in blaming the referee, but we also
have to take responsibility for the loss. Even with 10 men, we had
our chances. This shows the diminishment of the quality of
refereeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany, which failed in the quarterfinals for the second
successive World Cup after reaching the semifinal round the
previous seven tournaments, had plenty of opportunity to take
charge. Dietmar Hamann put a header just over the bar in the 22nd
minute, and Oliver Bierhoff forced Ladic to make a diving save on
another header in the 31st. That one was especially dangerous Ladic
couldn't hold on to the ball, and Juergen Klinsmann rushed in to
knock home the rebound; Ladic, lying on the ground, booted the ball
away.
</P>
<P>
   Ladic, who has three shutouts and has surrendered only two World
Cup goals in five matches, made another strong save on Bierhoff in
the 52nd, and a Hamann blast off a free kick ricocheted off the
Croatian wall and kissed the left post in the 78th. By the end,
German coach Berti Vogts whose ``David and Goliath'' comments on
Friday angered the Croats had four strikers on the field, to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, it's difficult,'' admitted Vogts, whose team
demonstrated the usual German organization but little flair. ``I
have to say that until Woerns was sent off, there was no doubt that
Germany put on its best performance of the World Cup so far.
There's no point going over and over the question of the red card.
The fact is Croatia goes on to Paris ... and we go back home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
