<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
NOVOTNA GIVES TAUZIAT A SLAM DUNK
</HEADLINE>
 TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Jim Greenidge 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It's a long climb from the grass court, up into the
stands, charging down the aisles between the fans, turning left,
then right, to reach the friends' box at Wimbledon's Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   Jana Novotna wanted to make that climb, no matter how long it
took, after she won her first Wimbledon singles title Saturday with
a 6-4, 7-6 (7-2) victory over Nathalie Tauziat.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Novotna wanted to embrace Hana Mandlikova, her
coach since 1990, who had seen her suffer from nerves in a
three-set loss to Steffi Graf in the 1993 Wimbledon final, a match
Novotna led, 4-1, in the final set before losing.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna's nerves were steadier last year, when she had another
three-set loss, this time against Martina Hingis. But it was a
loss, nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The third time was the charm for the 29-year-old Novotna, who
finally won her first Grand Slam title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said that winning one Grand Slam would mean so much
to me and winning Wimbledon means everything, really,'' said
Novotna, who defeated Venus Williams in the quarterfinals and top
seed Hingis in the semis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I have been working for for many, many years, and
this is a definite dream come true for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna served for the match at 5-4, but hit an easy volley into
the net, made three other errors, and Tauziat converted her third
break point, a forehand volley winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't serve well at all the whole match,'' said Novotna.
``I struggled with my serve simply because I felt so much pressure
from Nathalie. I knew that every second serve she's going to take
it in, she's going to be all over the net, and it would be
difficult to pass her.''
</P>
<P>
   But Novotna held for 6-6 and dominated the tie-breaker, winning
5 straight points from 2-2, closing out the match with a forehand
return for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be aggressive and either it's going to work out or
it's not,'' Novotna said. ``I finally made some first serves and
the beginning of the tie-breaker was really important. I felt like
in the tie-breaker, I was ready to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was totally amazed that she won the title without much help
from her serve, punching in just 67 percent. She blamed Tauziat.
</P>
<P>
   ``She takes the ball very early,'' Novotna said. ``If I served a
hard serve, she didn't really mind. She has such great hands, she
can just block the serve and still give you a very difficult
volley. I had the pressure to hold (serve).''
</P>
<P>
   But Tauziat's second serve was rather passive, more a simple
toss-in than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt me,'' said Tauziat, the first Frenchwoman to reach the
Wimbledon singles final in 73 years. ``If I didn't put the first
serve in, it was tough, and she came in with very aggressive balls,
very low so it was very difficult to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Tauziat's first Grand Slam final, at age 30, and she
was definitely the underdog. Still, with the series between the two
split at four wins each, Tauziat knew she could possibly defeat
Novotna.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew that she has done it before, she beat me a number of
times,'' said Novotna, who, with Mandlikova, sat and watched a tape
of Tauziat's victory over Natasha Zvereva in the semifinals. ``She
knew how to play me, so I think she felt she had a great chance to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She played better than me. She deserved to win Wimbledon,''
said Tauziat. ``I have nothing to regret in this match, that's
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna and the Duchess of Kent chatted a while during the award
ceremony. They had gotten to know one another quite well in 1993,
after the Czech's loss to Graf, when Novotna broke down and cried
on the Duchess's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very nice, and she was pleased that I won this
championship,'' Novotna said. ``She told me she's just as happy as
I am for me, for finally winning this championship. I'm sure she
knows how much this means to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
