<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
NIRVANA FOR JANA AT WIMBLEDON
</HEADLINE>
 TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Bud Collins 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Sometimes funerals are joyous occasions. They had one
at Wimbledon Saturday afternoon where the corpse was laid to rest
at 3:44 in a plot called Centre Court as 13,120 celebrants whooped
and clapped for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Tears gushed from the pale blue eyes of Jana Novotna, though she
wasn't mourning. Absolutely not. She had a racket in her hand that
seemed a spade because she was burying the past for good, and
crying gleefully. Relieved. Exonerated. Redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   She was _ ``at last, at last'' _ the Wimbledon champion, 6-4,
7-6 (7-2), over a worthy, if undervalued, rival, Nathalie Tauziat.
With one last shovelful of yellow tennis ball _ a resounding
forehand swat _ Jana found nirvana, killing the year 1993 and
pronouncing the last rites. Let's call the deceased Pan 1993 (Mr.
1993), as they might in Brno, Czech Republic, where Novotna
originated way back in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Jana came away from the funeral, a friend asks,
``Is Pan 1993 buried now?''
</P>
<P>
   Her face radiating a championship gleam, Jana pauses
thoughtfully, and replies, ``Yes, 1993 is buried. Definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Pan 1993 can be merely a friendly ghost instead of the demon
that had tormented her since that afternoon, just five years
before, when Jana established herself as one of the prime
philanthropists in Wimbledon chronicles. She handed the title to
Steffi Graf on a silver platter _ the huge Rosewater Dish _
emblematic of dominance, 7-6 (8-6), 1-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna, dreamily charging and checkmating Graf for a dozen
games, led, 4-1, 40-30. Then she floated a double fault somewhere
into the stratosphere. Abruptly it was all over, and she gushed
like a busted fire hydrant for love's labor lost. The
prize-presenting Duchess of Kent almost drowned in the lachrymal
tidal wave, and Novotna was, of course, labeled the biggest choker
since the formidable diamond necklaces worn by Queen Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews became an ordeal as she insisted nerves hadn't
betrayed her. ``You journalists did not help in a good way, always
talking about choking,'' Tauziat is defending Novotna Saturday.
``Stop talking about the past. She is a fighter. She has showed it.
Did she choke last year? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless Novotna didn't win that final either, losing, 2-6,
6-3, 6-3, to Martina Hingis, failing to hold a 2-0, 40-30 lead in
the third set.
</P>
<P>
   But this time she was the resilient, rebounding, self-assured
lady. In beating a trio of top 10 rivals (No. 9 Irina Spirlea, No.
7 Venus Williams, and No. 1, the champion Hingis) as well as No. 16
Tauziat, Jana surged from 1-4 against Williams, 0-3 and four break
points against Hingis, and 2-0, 40-15 down against Tauziat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hingis was a piece of cake,'' she says, blithely recalling her
brilliant 6-4, 6-4 semi. ``No pressure there. She was the big
favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would ever refer to Hingis as a pastry patsy? Then what did
that make Tauziat? A piece of stale French toast to choke on again?
</P>
<P>
   It starts to look that way as Novotna works her way to
championship game at 5-4, volleying as the bandit of the barrier,
acrobatically ripping off Tauziat's best shots. The match is on her
racket, in her prestidigitating hands _ but, whoops, her volleys go
awry. It's 0-40. Her legs calcify, she stops racing to the net
behind serve.
</P>
<P>
   Still she fights her way to deuce. Two points from victory. Not
close enough. She subsides, and it's 5-5, then 6-5, for the
Frenchwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struggling with my serve,'' Jana says. ``It had worked
so well against Hingis (no double faults), but not now (seven
double faults). Tension, yes,'' Jana admits. ``Tense all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   As mirror images, daring serve-and-volleyers who understand
grass, it's a wonder they didn't bump heads in their eagerness to
nose in on the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting pressure on each other's serve.'' Jana says. ``I
know if I miss the first one she'll come in on the second. And she
knows that about me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny when I lost my serve to 5-5, I relaxed a little. In the
tie-breaker I said to myself, `This is really wonderful! How can
you win Wimbledon without a serve? But you have to be aggressive
anyway, whether it works or not.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there was pressure _ but,'' she smiles, ``but this time I
believed in myself. I believed.''
</P>
<P>
   Believing meant doing. And doing in Pan 1993. He should have
expired Dec. 31 of his year _ but disagreeably hung around in her
psyche until this golden afternoon for the platinum-haired golden
oldie, edging up to all of 30.
</P>
<P>
   Gelid and gray, it was a good gloomy day for a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did I do on the last point?'' asks Jana, the undertaker,
who didn't miss a first serve in the breaker. ``I can't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   A roaring, winning forehand return of a second serve, she is
informed, a true championship blow, a stake in the heart of Pan
1993.
</P>
<P>
   R.I.P. More importantly, deserved peace as well for Jana, who
danced on the grave.
</P>
</TEXT>
