<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
WINDY CONDITIONS FAIL TO DEFLATE PAK
</HEADLINE>
 GLF-USWOMEN'SOPEN-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Jim McCabe 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Blown away by winds of up to 25 miles per hour,
overmatched at times by a long, difficult golf course, unable to
get at pins on rock-hard greens that are bigger than most
backyards.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, things went pretty well for those playing in
Saturday's third round of the US Women's Open at Blackwolf Run.
Red, white, and blue were the colors of choice, except for
professional egos; they were black and blue.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult were the conditions? Consider Liselotte Neumann,
one of just two players under par beginning the day. She made five
straight bogeys on the back, hit her second shot into the water at
the par-4 18th, came home in 40, shot a 4-over 75 _ and did not
lose any ground.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann is still chasing 20-year-old South Korean Se Ri Pak,
whose three-putt 18 gave her a 75 for a 1-over 214 total. Neumann
is at 215, tied with unheralded Mhairi McKay, who was one of three
players to shoot 73, the low round of the day.
</P>
<P>
   That's correct _ 2-over 73 was the low round of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridiculous,'' said Emilee Klein, who was one of 16 in the
field of 62 to shoot 80 or worse on a day when the field average
was 79.88.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the USGA did a poor job of setting up the course,''
said Donna Andrews, who shot 75 and is at 7-over 220. ``The course
is tough enough. I don't think they took the wind into account when
setting it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, said Andrews after a moment's thought, ``maybe they wanted
to get their reputation back (after last year's 10-under victory
total set a tournament record).''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing of the sort, said Judy Bell, immediate past president of
the USGA who was responsible for setting up the course. ``We
thought the winds would be 5-10 miles per hour,'' said Bell, ``but
they were more like 25 with gusts of 30. It was brutal out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And she wasn't even playing.
</P>
<P>
   For those who were, the experience was something they'll
probably always remember. Though the scores they'd like to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the wind made for intrigue as it blew names all over the
leaderboard. Neumann, for one, wasn't disappointed when she got to
the course. ``I was quite pleased,'' she said. ``It's the same for
everyone but I don't hit it that high, so I had a good positive
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed, for her birdie at the first, coupled with playing
partner Pak's bogey, put the 32-year-old Swede into the lead.
Neumann then birdied the par-4 fourth and had a one-shot lead on
Pak, six on McKay. ``When it's windy, it comes down to chipping and
putting,'' said Neumann. ``And putting is my strength, though it
didn't go my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the touch left her, probably blown away in the wind.
Neumann three-putted the par-3 eighth to set off a string of events
that changed the complexion of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After Pak three-putted from 15 feet on the par-5 10th for a
double bogey to fall two shots back, Neumann returned the favor by
bogeying the par-4 11th. Then the 12th. And the 13th. And the 14th.
And, for good measure, the 15th, too. She three-putted two times in
that sequence and conceded, ``I felt like it was getting me out of
the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   McKay may be unheralded, but she's an unheralded lady from
Scotland who groomed her game at Turnberry, which may explain what
she did at holes 12-14. She birdied them each for the second
straight day and moved into the lead. ``Tougher conditions than
Turnberry,'' said McKay, who played collegiately at Stanford at the
same time as Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Woods reportedly admires McKay's swing, but doubtful he would
have liked what he saw at the par-3 17th when McKay came over the
top and hit it in the water. She made double bogey. Again it was
Pak's turn to have the lead, thanks to a birdie at the par-4 14th
and three straight bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the top spot on the leaderboard was an easy target for
the wind. After McKay made her bogey at 18, the final twosome came
up the fairway, the wind having one more chance to play havoc. It
did, knocking Neumann's approach into the Sheboygan River and
blowing Pak's approach way right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty disgusted with myself,'' said Neumann, who
figured she would go from two shots down to three or four. But on a
day when everything went wrong, so did her thinking. She took her
drop, then chipped in from 35 yards to save par.
</P>
<P>
   When Pak three-putted, Neumann was back within a shot of the
lead, which is where she had started.
</P>
<P>
   As for Pak, who overpowered the course in winning the LPGA
Championship in May and is thus staring at a second major title,
she was asked if she was nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said. ``I don't have nerves. Not nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she's too young, or maybe she lost them in the wind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
