<HEADLINE>
GHO LEADERBOARD ATTRACTS A CROWD
</HEADLINE>
 GLF-GREATERHARTFORDOPEN-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Joe Concannon 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ This was the type of day it was in Saturday's
third round of the Greater Hartford Open at the TPC at River
Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Hammond walked to the 17th tee staring at a 59, hit three
balls into the water on the 441-yard par-4 hole, and took a 10.
Doug Tewell had a share of the lead walking to the 17th tee, and
he, too, found water, ended up with a double bogey, and finished
with a bogey on 18. Hammond and Tewell disappeared from sight, and
there was no shortage of players ready to step up.
</P>
<P>
   When the round began in warm, humid conditions, there were 12
players within three shots of Scott Gump's lead and as the round
wore on it became even more congested atop the leaderboard. When it
ended, Scott Hoch (64), Larry Mize (66), and New Zealander Grant
Waite (65) were tied for the lead at 13-under-par 197. The
threesome of Olin Browne (66), defender Stewart Cink (67), and
Tewell (68) were two astern.
</P>
<P>
   Waite played the incoming nine in 30 strokes to surge into
contention. Mize started with 10 straight pars before playing the
last eight holes 4 under par. Hoch birdied the 18th hole to join
the parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm playing well,'' said Hoch. ``I can't say I ever go
into into a tournament and say, `This is my tournament.' I remember
one time I felt very confident, went in there, and got beat to
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoch started his round by holing a 40-foot birdie putt on the
first hole and followed up by hitting a sand wedge to 5 feet for a
second birdie. After a solitary bogey on the sixth, when he said he
``hit it all over the place,'' Hoch birdied the eighth with a
25-foot putt, the 10th with a 25-foot birdie putt from the fringe,
the 13th (sand wedge, 1 foot), 15th (two putts from 45 feet), and
the 18th, when he hit an 8-iron second shot to 8 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Waite, who still calls North Palmerston on the southern tip of
New Zealand's north island home, started his run with birdies on
the 11th, when he holed out of a bunker, and on the 12th, when he
hit an 8-iron to 6 feet. He picked up steam with a birdie on the
15th when he drove into a greenside bunker and blasted out to
within 1 inch. He followed that with birdies on the 16th, where he
sank a putt from the back fringe, and the 17th (8-iron, 8 feet) to
put him in position for his second PGA Tour victory.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, who has been on a streak since he won the last
three tournaments of 1997, started with a 15-foot birdie putt on
the first hole. He followed with birdies on the fourth (6-iron, 30
feet), 13th (two putts, 20 feet), and 15th (chip, 1 inch), and had
no bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate in the last several months to win leading,
win coming from behind, and win tied,'' said Duval. ``The little
bit of pressure might be more on you if you're leading. I'm looking
forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a good track record at the course, leads the PGA money
list, and was just one of three of the first 13 money winners to
show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm putting actually quite well,'' said Duval. ``I
think I'm going to have to put the ball a little closer to the hole
to have a chance. I haven't made a whole lot of birdies this week.
It's a little surprising no one has been able to get way ahead. It
seems everybody shot the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mize birdied the 11th (8-iron, 10 feet), 13th (pitching wedge, 5
feet), 15th (pitching wedge, 3 feet) and 16th (5-iron, 10 feet) to
get in contention for his first victory since the 1993 Northern
Telecom Open. He was paired with Waite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `We couldn't seem to get anything going on the
front.' We've both played enough to know you have to be patient,''
Mize said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to give yourself a chance for tomorrow. I made a
nice putt to save par on the third hole. You really don't want to
lose one early in the day. I hit a nice chip on seven and the rest
of it was pretty routine. I had a good birdie putt at 18 and just
read it terrible. I played solidly today and it continued to give
confidence. I'm looking forward to tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne, who has New England roots and has played a lot of golf
at The Country Club, stormed into the picture with a 32 going out.
He stumbled with a three-putt bogey-7 on the 10th, but birdied the
13th by sinking a 1-foot putt and the 14th with a putt from inside
4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing in New England,'' Browne said. ``I putted
better this week than I've putted in a while. It's given me some
confidence on the greens. It's taken a lot of the pressure off my
iron game. Tomorrow? Just try to post as low a score as I can and
see where it adds up. It doesn't matter until the last four or five
tomorrow. Something clicked, and when it does you ride it for as
long as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Andrade of Bristol, R.I., who held the course-record 62
that was matched Saturday by Gump, finished on 66_203 and is
enjoying his best tournament since the first of the year in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very frustrating the last three of four months,''
said Andrade. ``I haven't putted well, and if you don't putt well
out here you're going to struggle. When you're not putting well it
puts so much pressure on the rest of your game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
