<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-ASTROS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS PRINT OUT VICTORY OVER ASTROS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Buck Showalter doesn't have a plastic pen holder in
his shirt pocket or wear thick black-rimmed glasses with a piece of
white tape wrapped around the middle. He does, however,
occasionally display tendencies of a computer geek.
</P>
<P>
   According to Showalter's printout, catcher Kelly Stinnett was
3-for-3 and shortstop Jay Bell was 8-for-13 against left-hander
Mike Hampton, Saturday night's starting pitcher for the Houston
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   There were no short-circuits to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett doubled and hit a solo home run and Bell collected a
pair of hits against Hampton. Meanwhile, left-hander Brian
Anderson, the Diamondbacks' starter, gave up two runs, scattered
nine hits and didn't walk a batter as Arizona turned back the
Astros, 7-4, at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   With today's finale of the three-game series remaining before
the All-Star break, the Diamondbacks have reached the 30-victory
plateau (30-57). Houston fell to 52-34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly and Jay did their jobs, and we also were lucky to catch
Hampton on an off-night,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (8-4), activated on Saturday after being on the disabled
list with a pulled groin, gave up 10 hits, walked three and six
runs (three earned) in 4 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson raised his record to 6-7, all of the victories coming
on the road. He continued his pattern of being one of the stingiest
in allowing walks in the National League. Also one of the most
charitable in terms of giving up home runs, he kept the ball in the
yard Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Andy' was outstanding. He got a couple of key double-play
balls (in the fifth and seventh innings) and the no walks were
big,'' Showalter said. ``As well as the Astros hit, you don't want
to put any more guys on and give them any more chances than you
have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Anderson: ``I was pretty happy with my stuff. My change-ups
were working pretty well. The only real hard-hit ball was the one
David Dellucci caught (a lunging grab in deep right-center off the
bat of Carl Everett to begin the second). I'm just happy to get a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona scored first in the second inning when Stinnett led off
with a double down the left-field line and later came home on a
double-play grounder by Yamil Benitez (no RBI).
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci's play against Everett was key, because Sean Berry, the
next hitter, connected for a drive in the same area, except that it
went farther and Berry ended up with a triple. It would have easily
scored Everett. Berry did, however, score on Brad Ausmus' sacrifice
fly to tie it at 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks jumped back in front, 2-1, in the third. Andy
Fox, starting at third in place of the injured Matt Williams
(bruised left foot), doubled to lead off and scored on a one-out
single to center by Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The three unearned runs off Hampton came in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci led off with his second straight hit on the first
pitch. With one out, Danny Klassen, called up from Triple-A Tucson
late Friday night and making his debut at second base, walked.
Anderson laid down an attempted sacrifice bunt in front of the
plate. Hampton turned and fired to third in an attempt to get
Dellucci, but Berry missed the ball and Dellucci scored. Klassen
came home on a groundout by Fox and Anderson scored on a single by
Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett led off the fifth with his seventh homer of the season
to make it 6-1. Ricky Gutierrez's RBI single in the bottom of the
fifth cut Arizona's lead to 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter elected to bring in right-hander Bobby Chouinard in
the eighth inning, and he gave up an RBI double to Moises Alou to
make it 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Fox walked to lead off the ninth against Houston reliever C.J.
Nitowski and scored on White's double to center field to make it
7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Gregg Olson came on in the ninth with no save situation
and struggled a bit, giving up a leadoff walk to Brad Ausmus and an
RBI single to Craig Biggio, but got Derek Bell on a foul to Lee to
end it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
