<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS MAN AGER GOT A CALL FROM ON HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON - Larry Dierker made a bold career move rarely seen in
sports. Last year he left the comfort and security of the radio/TV
booth to become manager of the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, one day you're sitting behind a pressbox mike, wearing
a Hawaiian shirt, saying things like, ``Hi, everybody!'' and ``Oh,
those bases on balls.``
</P>
<P>
   Next day you're in uniform, staring out at the field, teeth
clenched, contemplating a suicide squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing habits are to break, one wonders whether Dierker,
perhaps without even realizing it, still mentally broadcasts every
game.
</P>
<P>
   `` ``Well, that's gotta be it for Hampton. The lef''t-``hander's
tired. Look'' ``for Dierk to make a change. In fact, here I
come'',''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4 skipper ambled out of the Houston dugout in the
fifth inning of the Diamondbacks' 7-4 victory. Before he reached
the mound his starting pitcher, Mike Hampton, eyes averted, flipped
him the ball and walked dejectedly toward the bench, head bowed.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven D-Backs' hits. A fireworks show. Three doubles. A triple.
When Kelly Stinnett homered to lead off the fifth inning Houston
leftfielder Moises Alou didn't move a step. Why bother? The ball
was long gone, and he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't how Dierker and the Astros had hoped to celebrate
our nation's independence on Stars and Stripes T-Shirt Night at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros were surprised they lost, it is understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Under Dierker's gentle whip, the Astros (52-34) have opened a
five-game lead in the National League Central. Houston is one of
the hottest hitting teams in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the ninth, down by four runs, the home team still
believed it could win. So did Dome fans who have come to expect
last-minute heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come from behind so many times in late innings,''
Dierker said. ``I don't know if it's fate or destiny. But when
players experience that they start to think they're supposed to win
the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   It can't be easy managing a big-league team, especially with no
formal training. A manager must deal with large and fragile egos.
He must set the batting order and make roster moves and figure out
the double switch. Billy Martin said the key to surviving as a
manager involves ``keeping the five players who hate you away from
the five who are undecided.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dierker has kept his team happy. He is happy, too. The
first thing you notice is his easy smile. He smiles more than Buck
Showalter. Of course, so does the minted likeness of George
Washington on a quarter-dollar coin.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker brought his breezy, laid-back style as a broadcaster to
the dugout. Those who know him well say the manager is as
comfortable in his job as he is sitting on a stool sipping a tall
fruit drink at the Big Bamboo Lounge, an ersatz tiki hut, at the
Astros training camp in Kissimmee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker is patient, especially with his pitchers. He was a
pitcher himself once, one of Houston's best ever. A bonus baby, as
young stars once were called, Dierker struck out Willie Mays in
Larry's first big-league inning on his 18th birthday. He was the
Astros first 20-game winner.
</P>
<P>
   Most manager go by The Book (if you ever see a copy let me
know). Dierker manages more on instinct. He can relate with former
big-league manager Bobby Bragan, who once said, ``Say you were
standing with one foot in the oven and one foot in an ice bucket.
According to people who believe in (playing) percentages, you
should be perfectly comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker is, for now. Know what the biggest adjustment he said he
faced in his new job? Depth perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't see the field very well from the dugout,''
Dierker said. ``I'd forgotten how bad it was. I remember when I
went upstairs (to the booth) for the first time. I thought every
fly ball was going out of the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker would take exception with those who say he is making
managing look easy, this loss a case in point. But he is breaking
ground. Until Dierker came along, an owner would no more select a
broadcaster for his manager than he would pick a sportswriter,
although most of my colleagues are Deep Thinkers who, had they
chosen baseball over journalism, probably could have become
All-Stars or even Hall of Famers, if not for a lack of talent. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
