<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0819 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALES-     07-05 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ HACKING WAY TOWARD RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, also known as ``Igor'' because of his massive
physical stature, towers over almost everyone in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his exploits, the 6-foot-3 Gonzalez has remained the
American League's unknown superstar, despite being named league
Most Valuable Player two years ago and twice leading the majors in
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey's home run
chase of Roger Maris that has captured the attention of America's
baseball fans.
</P>
<P>
   Few realize that Texas' Gonzalez is on pace to break Hack
Wilson's single-season RBI record of 190, a more difficult
accomplishment in the eyes of some.
</P>
<P>
   With one game remaining before the All-Star break, Gonzalez has
already reached 96 RBIs. He's trying to match Detroit's Hank
Greenberg (1935) as the only other player ever to reach 100 RBIs by
the break.
</P>
<P>
   Some stars play their entire career and are barely able to reach
100 RBIs in a season. With more than 2{ months to go, Gonzalez has
nearly reached the century mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at 16, when he couldn't hit a home run, he always had a
knack for picking up the runners on base,'' said Diamondbacks
Assistant General Manager Sandy Johnson, who signed Gonzalez when
he was working with the Rangers in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of his makeup. I remember, he was gangly, like a
young colt. From the moment he signed, he was destined to be a
superstar in his mind. If I had known he was going to be this good,
I would have given him more money. His batting stance has never
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that batting stance, in which Gonzalez holds the bat high
over his shoulders and stands almost erect, that opposing pitchers
hate to see in the batter's box, especially with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who won't turn 29 until Oct. 16 and probably hasn't
reached his peak yet, entered Saturday's action having played 1,035
games and had 886 career RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   As ridiculous as it sounds, that's one RBI every 1.17 games he's
played as a major leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best RBI guy I've ever played with,'' said Rangers
first baseman Will Clark. ``He constantly proves you don't have to
have the ball over the middle of the plate in order to handle it.
He's a great bad-ball hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has had difficulties handling snubs, from within the
game and outside. As proof he offers the fact that Tuesday will
mark only the second time he's ever been to an All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I have to do to get more attention,''
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's mostly quiet demeanor, especially when he's in
crowds, hasn't helped elevate his stature nationally. By most
accounts from the people closest to him, Gonzalez is somewhat
introverted when he's near people he does not know.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, however, Gonzalez has started to break
out of his shell. Part of his more outgoing personality is derived
from the personal coming out party he had during the 1996 AL
playoffs, when he hit five home runs, had nine RBIs and hit .438 in
a Division Series loss to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all accelerated in the '96 playoffs when he was under the
spotlight,'' Texas Manager Johnny Oates said. ``He had the great
series, and there were a lot of interviews. He really had no
choice. I thought he handled himself very well.''
</P>
<P>
   But probably the biggest reason Gonzalez is more outgoing these
days are his regular sessions with a psychologist, which began
before last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had read where Mark McGwire said he improved as a ballplayer
after he started seeing a professional,'' Gonzalez said. ``We're
human beings, not machines. I'll do anything to help me get better
on the field and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything it's helped me organize my time,
particularly before and after games. I used to throw away my time.
Now I have more time for the important things in life. I'm a happy
person. I spend more time with my two children and my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a minor miracle for Gonzalez, married to his third wife, a
salsa singer who, like him, is from Puerto Rico, to freely admit he
has sought professional help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Latin culture is very macho, and admitting this is not the
thing to do,'' Gonzalez said. ``But I don't care because I know I'm
not crazy. There's nothing wrong with it. If you break a bone, you
see a doctor. This is no different.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase most commonly associated with Gonzalez these days, at
least from those who know him best, is how mature he has become in
recent years, which Gonzalez attributes to the psychological help
he has received.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treats baseball like the game that it is,'' said teammates
and fellow Puerto Rican Ivan Rodriguez, who will also join Gonzalez
at Tuesday's All-Star Game. ``He doesn't put as much pressure on
himself as a few years ago. He's more mature. He's someone strong
who can break down the walls of stereotypes of Latins. He's happier
and more talkative. Of course he can reach the RBI record. Just
watch out he doesn't reach 200.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
