<HEADLINE>
ABOUT TIME FOR TKACHUK TO GROW UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - So this is his home. This is his team. This is where
he wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, explains why Keith Tkachuk is off in Cape Cod,
stewing over broken promises, convinced he's part of a Winnipeg
purge, ready to throw the Coyotes in reverse with another sit-down
strike.
</P>
<P>
   So there are captains, there are leaders and there are guys like
Tkachuk. Guys who must get theirs, guys who never see the big
picture, guys who forget their names already rest on binding
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   A little advice for one of the most divisive, self-centered
captains to have never won a playoff series: Come down off your
number before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   When General Manager Bobby Smith yanked a $33.3 million offer
from the table, followed by a bold yet ominous $17 million
acquisition of Jyrki Lumme, the ending may have already been
written. And soon, you will know a lot about the priorities of this
hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   If the right names are involved, it's a slam dunk. The Coyotes
should trade Tkachuk right now, end a bad marriage, build around a
winning nucleus. Problem is, there are only a handful of teams
willing to pay the shipping costs, and they know what's going on
here. They know Tkachuk's baggage, they smell desperation, they
realize he might be obtainable for Pat Garrity and Bubba Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Tkachuk is fine, but giving him away would be idiotic.
To call his bluff and let another season erode in controversy would
be unforgivable. And to end all talks would confirm what a few
players already are whispering about this organization, that it is
too cheap to win a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: If the right names aren't whispered in Smith's ear
very soon, there should be room for movement. And most of it should
come from Tkachuk, who should fire his agent and realize his lack
of leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk is surely underpaid, chained to a contract that will pay
him $5.8 million over the next two seasons. But he is conveniently
forgetting the $6 million check he cashed when the Jets matched an
offer sheet in 1995. And with the NHL restructuring the face of its
game, enacting rules to put the premium back on skating, the impact
of your physical, lumbering power forwards is sure to diminish.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Smith stretched the truth when he broke off negotiations,
angry that Tkachuk balked at an ``outstanding offer'' that would
raise his annual salary $6.5 million over the next five years.
Well, sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Gilmour and Brett Hull signed for three years at $18
million and $17 million, respectively. And then there's Eric
Lindros, extended for one year at $8.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric Lindros sets the market for Eric Lindros,'' Smith said
tersely, telling you what he thinks about that comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Tkachuk is not Lindros, and we have postseason results
to prove it. He is no Jaromir Jagr or Teemu Selanne, guys who
successfully negotiated new deals with two years left on their
contracts. But if the Coyotes wanted to be fair, they'd give him
Mike Modano money. Seven million per season. And if they really
wanted to test Tkachuk's will to win, dangle a big chunk up front,
a Sergei Fedorov bonus where the incentive rests with the success
of the team, not the man.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tkachuk and Smith are no longer talking to each other.
Tkachuk thinks Smith broke a promise. Smith claims he only vowed to
``roll up his sleeves'' and work toward a compromise. Neither man
has done his part, and the longer this goes, the lies will turn to
war. And the more likely next season will look just like last
season _ a team fueled by poisonous chemistry, staggering along
without all hands on board, destined to end up in disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Great leaders think about their team every so often, and this is
where Tkachuk is all words and little action. He needs to grow up,
forget about the money and win something.
</P>
<P>
   And so do the Coyotes, a team that better have the right motives
and right return if they say good-bye to the captain that never
was. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
