<HEADLINE>
RERUN PUTS MERCURY IN SAME ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ For those of you who missed the first
Charlotte-Phoenix meeting at America West Arena, the teams
re-enacted the plot Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Same blown big lead by the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Same impossible shot from Charlotte's Christy Smith for her
first points and a lead in the waning seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Same available Mercury timeout ignored for a final shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same old thing,'' Phoenix guard Bridget Pettis summarized.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the 72-71 loss two weeks ago, the Mercury was stung
again when it seemed to have an opponent outmatched. This time,
Charlotte overcame an 18-point deficit to win, 68-66, in front of
8,210 at Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to the 11-point lead the Sting erased in the last
6:25 at Phoenix, Charlotte (8-2) cleared off an 18-point deficit by
the first minute of the second half Saturday with a 21-3 run.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix (7-3) got down by as many as seven in the second half
and trailed, 62-56, with 4:10 remaining as Jennifer Gillom sat on
the bench with an ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   That is when Umeki Webb's play at both ends and Michelle Timms'
passing nearly rescued the Mercury. The pair accounted for
Phoenix's last 10 points, starting with a 8-0 comeback that
included Gillom's re-entry. Webb scored six of the last 10, giving
Phoenix a lead twice.
</P>
<P>
   Her steal and layup put the Mercury ahead, 64-62, with 2:19 to
go. When Charlotte's Andrea Stinson hit an off-balance jumper to
tie the score, Webb came back with a bucket from the post for a
66-64 lead with 1:50 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't have even been that close,'' said Webb, the
former North Carolina State star who thrilled 19 friends in
attendance with a 15-point, four-steal game.
</P>
<P>
   Stinson hit another running jumper to knot the score at 66 with
1:15 to go, and Charlotte got the ball back after Timms misfired a
jumper and Pettis missed her 10th straight shot on the put-back.
</P>
<P>
   As the shot clock at one second, Smith sank a 12-foot leaner
with Timms draping her and 17.1 seconds remaining in the game. A
scoreless Smith also hit the same shot for Charlotte's first lead
at Phoenix with 20.3 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just threw it up and got lucky,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Timms said, ``That's as good a shot as anybody in the NBA would
make. We handed it to them. We got a comfortable lead and sat back
and did exactly the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom missed a fadeaway, the shot that gave her most of her
game-high 21 points, with nine seconds to go. Needing two fouls to
get to the bonus, Phoenix sent Smith to the free throw line with
2.7 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   She missed both. Webb rebounded the second and threw the ball to
Pettis, whose 30-footer was after the buzzer and short anyway. The
Mercury had a 20-second timeout remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In the home loss to Charlotte, Tracy Reid hit the go-ahead shot
with 2.4 seconds remaining, and Phoenix inbounded for a desperation
shot instead of calling a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller said a timeout would not have
helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen such a blatant lack of calls by officials
during the stretch than what happened down the stretch,'' Miller
said. ``We didn't do some things in the first half, but by no
stretch of the imagination did the best team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom came out shooting as well as in Thursday's victory at
Cleveland, scoring nine of Phoenix's first 14 points. Charlotte
looked like it did in its last game too, carrying over that 24.6
percent shooting night into a 1-for-11 start Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe we lost this one,'' Gillom said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
