<HEADLINE>
NO-TRADE CLAUSE KEY TO LUMME DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the main reasons  &UR; Jyrki Lumme ruled out returning to the
Vancouver Canucks, his team for the past eight seasons, was because
of the lack of security.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the lack of a no-trade clause. That's why the
highly sought after defenseman rejected the Canucks' multiyear
offer last season that would have paid him an average of $2.7
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   It's also why he passed on several other teams that were in
pursuit of the unrestricted free agent last week, including
Toronto, San Jose, Calgary and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But he got what he wanted, and more, with the Coyotes. In
addition to signing a five-year deal Friday worth $17 million,
Lumme received a no-trade clause, which more star players are
seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we gave him a no-trade clause, but it's only in existence
for the first three years of the deal,'' Coyotes General Manager
 &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Smith said. ``After the third year, we could trade him, but only to
one of 10 teams that have been designated.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Lumme liked living in Vancouver, it's doubtful the
Canucks are one of those clubs. Vancouver probably had the most
disappointing season of any club last season, finishing last in the
Western Conference with a 25-43-14 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, it was pretty tough,'' Lumme said. ``We had such
high expectations and then we just totally crashed. For some
reason, we just didn't click. We had no fight. We were never on the
same page. But that's the past. That chapter of my life is over.'' &QL; 
Canadian grit &QL; 
Last week at the NHL draft in Buffalo, the longest pause came when
Toronto was scheduled to pick No. 8 overall. After several minutes,
the Maple Leafs announced they were swapping picks with Chicago,
trading down to get the No. 10 pick.
</P>
<P>
   What was the holdup about?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Toronto was all set to grab center  &UR; Mark Bell of St.
Paul, Ontario. But word leaked about his appearance a few days
earlier on The Sports Network's ``Off the Record'' program, in
which Bell said he liked to give European players ``a little
extra'' when he hit them because they're ``taking away jobs from
good Canadian players.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, comments like that might endear a player to
management. But the Maple Leafs and  &UR; Mike Smith, &UR; associate general
manager, are famous for drafting European players.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto then swapped with Chicago and took  &UR; Nikolai Antropov
from Russia. &QL; 
McLeod's mystery movie &QL; 
When someone told  &UR; Doug McLeod that the producers of an upcoming
motion picture were looking for a hockey broadcaster for a bit
part, the television voice for the Coyotes, on a lark, sent in a
demo clip.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, he found himself being whisked away to Los
Angeles and winning the role in the upcoming film ``Mystery,
Alaska,'' due out in February. The movie, which stars  &UR; Burt
Reynolds and  &UR; Mike Myers, is based on a hockey game between the New
York Rangers and a group of locals in the small town of Mystery.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod's partner in the broadcast booth was Hall of Famer  &UR; Phil
 &UR; Esposito, general manager of the Tampa Bay Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our way to one of the shoots, Phil leaned over and asked me
how I thought  &UR; Craig Janney would look in a Tampa Bay jersey,''
McLeod said. ``Funny, I didn't think anything about it at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, the Coyotes sent Janney to Tampa for a
fifth-round draft pick and  &UR; Louie DeBrusk. &QL; 
Duck hunting &QL; 
The Mighty Ducks of Anaheim are close to naming a new head coach to
replace recently fired  &UR; Pierre Page. Two of the candidates
reportedly on the team's short list are former coaches, Chicago's
 &UR; Craig Hartsburg and Buffalo's  &UR; Ted Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan won the Jack Adams Award two years ago as the league's top
coach, then was unceremoniously dumped.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, former Coyotes Coach  &UR; Don Hay was relieved of his
duties as an assistant in Anaheim. Hay recently accepted the head
coaching job with the Western Hockey League's Tri-City Americans,
where he also will serve as general manager.
</P>
<P>
   His son,  &UR; Darryl, is a defenseman on the team. &QL; 
Slap shots &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sources in Vancouver say the Canucks would be interested in
trading star right wing  &UR; Pavel Bure to Phoenix for disgruntled left
wing  &UR; Keith
 &UR; Tkachuk. Bure definitely wants out, but the Coyotes likely would
want more in return.
</P>
<P>
   Another source close to the Coyotes said Smith turned down an
offer from Philadelphia GM  &UR; Bob Clarke regarding a straight-up swap
of Tkachuk for star center  &UR; Eric Lindros. Which player would you
rather have?
</P>
<P>
   Smith noted that all major moves in free agency thus far have
involved Western Conference teams. Besides the Coyotes landing a
star in Lumme, Dallas signed St. Louis sniper  &UR; Brett Hull and
Chicago signed New Jersey center  &UR; Doug Gilmour. Detroit, meanwhile,
is said to be close to reeling in defenseman  &UR; Uwe Krupp.
</P>
<P>
   The East won't be far behind, though. Philadelphia is hot after
Rangers goalie  &UR; Mike Richter. The Rangers are eyeing Edmonton
goalie
 &UR; Curtis Joseph. And Carolina has offered a deal to Pittsburgh center
 &UR; Ron Francis, who starred for the club when it was in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was destiny that Detroit's  &UR; Steve Yzerman won the
Conn Smythe Trophy as the Most Valuable Player in the Stanley Cup
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   During the playoffs, Yzerman bought a summer cottage that once
belonged to the man the trophy is named for.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me before the playoffs he was eyeing this cottage and
then he said he bought it. I just thought, `Wouldn't that be
good?'' teammate  &UR; Brendan Shanahan said. &QL; 
Bob McManaman can be reached at 602-444-8326 or at
bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com vie e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
