<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS ROOKIE HITTING QBS ALREADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add courage to the list of Cardinals rookie defensive lineman
 &UR; Andre
 &UR; Wadsworth's many attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth asked probable future Hall of Fame quarterback  &UR; John
Elway of the Denver Broncos a potentially embarrassing question at
last week's NFL rookie symposium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saving this question for someone who couldn't stand up,''
Wadsworth told Elway. ``He has been hurting since he was about 14
years old. In 1988, when Denver played San Francisco in the Super
Bowl, there was a little kid with a big Afro, and he went up to
(Elway) for his autograph, and he didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just gave him a look and walked on by. To this day, he
wants your autograph.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, the third overall pick in April's draft, was
referring to
 &UR; Corey Chavous, the Vanderbilt defensive back picked in the second
round by the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Elway had just finished telling rookies how they should go out
of their way to be nice to fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did I tell you? They never forget,'' Elway told the
rookies. ``That was the one time. I hope he didn't ask right after
the game. When you get beat, 55-10, in the Super Bowl, it's not a
good feeling.'' &QL; 
Send in the clowns &QL; 
Here's how absurd the search for a new owner of the Minnesota
Vikings was: The ``Pro Wrestling Torch'' offered World Wrestling
Federation promoter and owner  &UR; Vince McMahon as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Red McCombs, former owner of the San Antonio Spurs and Denver
Nuggets of the NBA, beat out another NBA owner, Timberwolves'  &UR; Glen
Taylor, among others for the right to buy the team with a bid of
more than $200 million. League officials are expected to approve
the deal this month.
</P>
<P>
   Approval is expected to be contingent on the team's remaining in
Minnesota. Yet concern has surfaced over whether McCombs, a San
Antonio resident who is worth close to $1 billion, could move the
team to the south Texas city's Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon entered the picture after Las Vegas resident  &UR; Shruti
Misra, who owns little more than a 4.6-acre vacant lot, offered to
pay $225 million for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Misra, and her husband,  &UR; Anil Gupta, have been the subject of
numerous lawsuits, and Gupta declared bankruptcy last year,
according to the ``Las Vegas Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sun'' reported that Gupta was not able to make bail when
he was arrested in 1994 in a questionable real estate transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The paper also reported that the pair have been accused of
duping a blind, 74-year-old woman into paying for a newspaper ad
that proclaimed the couple's wealth. Gupta and Misra promised to
donate $5.1 million to Active Blind and Visually Impaired of Nevada
but donated only worthless railroad bonds and unconfirmed real
estate holdings, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't offer any of the $2.4 billion in gold, silver and
platinum they claim to have stored in a Las Vegas warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Knox is the only facility to have such a collection, gold
experts said. &QL; 
Family feud &QL; 
The war for control of the San Francisco 49ers could be settled by
Commissioner  &UR; Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for former 49ers owner  &UR; Eddie DeBartolo and his
sister,
 &UR; Denise DeBartolo York, met with Tagliabue on Wednesday. Both sides
want to run the team.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo signed an agreement in December that gave his sister
control of the team after reports surfaced that he would be
indicted in a Louisiana gambling investigation.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo has reneged on that agreement and claims the case
against him in Louisiana is flimsy.
</P>
<P>
   His sister maintains that the agreement with DeBartolo is valid.
</P>
<P>
   If Tagliabue sides with DeBartolo, he could regain control of
the team once his legal problems in Louisiana are done. DeBartolo
likely would fire club president  &UR; Carmen Policy, his onetime close
friend who has been running the team for DeBartolo's sister. &QL; 
Bad timing &QL; 
Miami Dolphins running back  &UR; Lawrence Philips, being investigated
in Plantation, Fla., for allegedly assaulting a woman who refused
to dance with him, could become the first player to be disciplined
as part of the new anti-violence rule.
</P>
<P>
   The policy went into effect Wednesday, one day after Plantation
police announced they were investigating Phillips, the former
Nebraska star.
</P>
<P>
   Any league employee who is charged with a violent crime is
subjected to a fine or suspension without pay at the discretion of
Tagliabue. A second conviction could result in banishment. &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
New York Giants Coach  &UR; Jim Fassel, the former Cardinals offensive
coordinator, is miffed that linebacker  &UR; Corey Miller attended only
three of 12 off-season workouts. ``I'm not happy that I didn't hear
from him,'' Fassel said. ``I have an answering machine 24 hours a
day. He's looking at the wrong guy if he's playing a game of
chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore punter  &UR; Greg Montgomery is recovering from a sprained
toe suffered while punting for a team promotional video. He kicked
the camera that was filming him. &QL; 
Includes information from other &QL; 
media sources. Steve Schoenfeld &QL; 
can be reached at 602-444-8334 or at &QL; 
steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
