<HEADLINE>
TEEN OFFERS WORM'S-EYE VIEW OF RODMAN'S MANY ACTIVITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old Wesley Tacker has a Bull's eye on Dennis
Rodman's every move at Tacker's site, The Worm's World
(www.wesjen.simplenet.com/rodman).
</P>
<P>
   Tacker, a junior-to-be at Abilene High School, closely tracks
Rodman's every step _ a good thing considering the former South Oak
Cliff High School student might leave the Chicago Bulls for another
NBA team at any time.
</P>
<P>
   It's like having a Doppler radar system fixed on Rodman. One
night Rodman might be on ESPN, the next on the ``Tonight Show''.
Another night he's wrestling on TNT. Tacker documents it all on his
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually have the only site on the Internet that offers
up-to-date Dennis Rodman news,'' Tacker said.
</P>
<P>
   While the authors of some Rodman fan sites try, few fans seem as
dedicated as Tacker, who also writes a weekly editorial and plays
host to a weekly chat at Rodman's official site on America Online
Athlete Direct (keyword: worm).
</P>
<P>
   Tacker started the site in April 1997 as The Dennis Rodman
Current Events Page. When Tacker ran out of space on his Internet
service provider, he moved to another with more room and renamed
the site.
</P>
<P>
   While most Rodman pages focus on only basketball images,
Tacker's gallery contains numerous images on the marketing world of
Dennis Rodman, which includes TV appearances, merchandise,
advertisements and articles.
</P>
<P>
   During the NBA season, Tacker tracks Rodman's statistics. The
site also includes a bi-weekly survey, message board, links page,
chat room, chat transcripts, top-10 lists and archives of all
Rodman updates.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman fans, especially those who want to stay one step ahead of
their unpredictable anti-hero, should check it out.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: (out of five stars) BYTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All-Star coverage (all times Central): CBS SportsLine and Major
League Baseball have collaborated on an All-Star site
(www.mlballstargame.com) for Tuesday's game in Denver. The official
All-Star site includes daily updates, rosters, a schedule of
events, photos, polls, contests, live video, merchandise and chat
options. ... ESPN SportsZone (espn.com) has several chat sessions
scheduled for the All-Star game. Today at 9 a.m., former Cincinnati
Reds star Joe Morgan is scheduled to chat live. Tomorrow's lineup
includes Houston Astros second baseman Craig Biggio at 3 p.m. and
Cleveland Indians outfielder Kenny Lofton at 3:30 p.m. On Tuesday,
it's Hall of Fame pitcher Rollie Fingers at 1:05 p.m.; Boston Red
Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez at 3 p.m., and Atlanta Braves pitcher
Tom Glavine at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the bubble gum? CyberAction, Inc. (www.cyberaction.com),
creator of the first digital trading card, plans to debut its
``Power Hitters and Power Pitchers'' collection on computer kiosks
at the Pinnacle All-Star FanFest this week in Denver. CyberAction's
digital cards feature full-motion video and audio clips of the
featured player on the ``front'' of the card. Each card also
includes five ``flip sides'' that include lifetime statistics,
interactive trivia questions and personal and team information.
Video clips include highlights of the player's greatest hits and
plays. CyberAction's cards are available for download in limited
editions with a serial number and cannot be duplicated after
they're downloaded. The first series of 30,000 cards sell for
$3.95.
</P>
<P>
   Chat highlight: Dallas Burn midfielder Jason Kreis plans to talk
about the World Cup at 8 p.m. Tuesday during a live chat on
Athletic Direct on America Online (keyword: adsoccer).
</P>
<P>
   Digging for Dirk: Yes, Dirk Nowitzki, the 20-year-old German who
announced he intends to play for the Mavericks next season, has a
presence on the World Wide Web. No, he has no known fan sites.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki fans can start with the unofficial site of Nowitzki's
team, the DJK San Oliver Wurzburg X-Rays
(www.wuerzburg.de/djk-basketball). It's a good site to get to know
him and his team, which competed in the Bundesliga second division
of the German Basketball Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Other sources include the German Basketball Federation's page on
Eurobasketball (www.eurobasket.com/ger/ger.htm) or the official
Deutscher Basketball Bund site (www.basketball-bund.de).
</P>
<P>
   Warning: The Deutscher Basketball Bund and Wurzburg sites are in
German. At the Wurzburg site, however, words such as ``monster
block and slam dunk'' can easily be picked out.
</P>
</TEXT>
