<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD, MCGWIRE LOOK LIKE MVPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the traditional midway point of the season. With that in
mind, it's time to take a look at which players are distinguishing
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Submitted, for your approval, are the half-way awards: &QL; 
 &UR; AMERICAN LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MVP: He may not be the sexiest candidate, but Anaheim's  &UR; Darin
Erstad is playing like a future Hall of Famer. When it comes to the
total package, the unselfish Erstad, who has played all three
outfield spots and first base, is the clear choice. Of course,
Texas'  &UR; Juan Gonzalez and Seattle's duo of  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr., and
 &UR; Alex Rodriguez could still have something to say. Too bad we can't
just nominate the entire Yankees roster.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cy Young: It's never been done before, but  &UR; Pedro Martinez, now
with Boston, looks like he could become the first pitcher to win
consecutive Cy Young Awards in separate leagues. Except for a
two-week bout with an intestinal infection, Martinez has been
virtually unhittable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rookie: He came in with all the hype, and  &UR; Ben Grieve of
Oakland has done nothing but live up to his press clippings.
Detroit's  &UR; Matt
 &UR; Anderson looks like the real thing, but he may have been called up
too late to close the gap on Grieve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Anaheim's  &UR; Terry Collins has done a phenomenal job,
but the vote here goes to  &UR; Joe Torre of the Yankees. Yes, he has
the greatest collection of talent in the league, but getting a
great collection of talent to play at a high level is much more
difficult than getting lower-rung players to overachieve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comeback player: Oakland's  &UR; Rickey Henderson leads the majors
in stolen bases and, at age 39, appears to be turning back the
clock. At the very least, he's making a strong case to continue
playing next year. &QL; 
 &UR; NATIONAL LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MVP: Chicago's  &UR; Sammy Sosa? That's the easy pick right now. The
nod still goes to St. Louis'  &UR; Mark McGwire, the Herculean first
baseman who seems to have Roger Maris' single-season record well
within his cross hairs. Watch for  &UR; Andres Galarraga to make a
charge here.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cy Young: What's new? Not much. Atlanta's  &UR; Greg Maddux rises
above everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rookie: It's a close call, but the Diamondbacks'  &UR; Travis Lee
gets the edge over Cubs right-hander  &UR; Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: It's time to stop ignoring the job
broadcaster-turned-manager  &UR; Larry Dierker has done in Houston. He
has the Astros nearly 20 games above .500, and they continue to win
despite three starters on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Comeback player: He was buried so deep on the scrap heap that
 &UR; Gregg
 &UR; Olson had to practically beg for a chance to pitch in spring
training. The Diamondbacks, with little to lose, offered that
chance and now have an established closer on their hands. &QL; 
Please take that knife out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some very harsh quotes from fired Dodgers Manager  &UR; Bill Russell
came to light last week in the ``Long Beach Press-Telegram.''
Russell's comments were apparently made a few days before he and
General Manager
 &UR; Fred Claire were fired and supposedly were made during an
off-the-record conversation with the topic being  &UR; Tommy Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   But columnist  &UR; Doug Krikorian decided the comments were fair
game once the housecleaning took place and wrote Russell's comments
in a column last week. Here are the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy's just killing me and Fred with the Fox people,''
Russell said. ``Fred knows it. I know it. And there's nothing we
can do about it. It's just tough to work under these conditions.
Tommy's just vicious when he wants something. He did the same sort
of thing when he was a coach under  &UR; Walter Alston and wanted
Alston's job. Tommy's been second-guessing me ever since I took
over for him. Why? I don't know. All I know is that we haven't
spoken for months.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Lasorda, known within baseball circles as one of the
biggest phonies in the game, denied everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ridiculous,` he said. ``I haven't been in town that
much this season, and no way I've been campaigning for any job . .
. For him to make a statement like that, I don't understand. I
stayed completely away. I would never politic for either guy's job.
I didn't want anyone to get fired. But it happened, and we have to
go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, who said he has attempted on countless occasions to
speak to Russell since the firings, delivered the eulogy for former
Dodgers GM
 &UR; Al Campanis at a small funeral home in Fullerton, Calif., a
ceremony at which Russell was one of the fewer than 100 people who
attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone told me he was there, which I was glad to hear, but I
never saw him,'' Lasorda claimed. &QL; 
The swinging pendulum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 NL All-Stars, 21 are 30 or older, including seven of
the eight starters elected by the fans. Only three NL All-Stars are
25 or younger. Now you get the idea of why it's called the senior
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the junior circuit, which many believe is the
up-and-coming league, only 12 All-Stars are 30 or older. Six AL
stars are 25 or younger, including shortstop  &UR; Alex Rodriguez. Of
the eight starting position players in the AL, five are under 30. &QL; 
An idea we'd vote for &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia pitcher  &UR; Curt Schilling came up with an outstanding
idea to help fix some of the snubs that take place every year when
it comes to the All-Star Game:
</P>
<P>
   Take away the rule that mandates that every club must be
represented by at least one player. It was fine when there were
eight or 12 clubs in each league, but with 16 NL clubs, it leaves
room for only 12 reserves (14 this year because of expanded
rosters).
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is, I think only the city hosting the game
should have to be represented by at least one player,'' Schilling
said. ``The fans from Paducah aren't going to watch because their
team's player is on the roster. They're going to watch  &UR; Ken Griffey
and  &UR; Mark McGwire and
 &UR; Barry Bonds just like everybody else. It's a very diplomatic
process. And maybe it shouldn't be.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
