<HEADLINE>
NO KIDDING, KLASSEN GETS CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Oh Danny boy, the bigs, the bigs are calling . . .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Danny Klassen could hardly believe when Tucson Sidewinders
Manager
 &UR; Chris Speier told him on Friday night that the Diamondbacks were
summoning him to the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen was called up after third baseman  &UR; Matt Williams fouled
a ball off his left foot Friday night against Houston. Klassen
arrived here about three hours before Saturday night's game and
Manager  &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter immediately scribbled his name into the starting lineup
at second base.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen looked up into the panels of the Astrodome roof and
handled a pop-up by Houston's  &UR; Craig Biggio for the game's first
out. He slid on the artificial turf to field a grounder by  &UR; Derek
Bell and threw him out by an eyelash for the final out of the third
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen walked in his first three at-bats, scoring a run on the
second occasion as part of a three-run fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   He also struck out once and in the field finished with four
putouts and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I needed a plane to get here,'' a beaming
Klassen said before the game. ``I've read where people called up
for the first time say it's hard to explain how they feel. They're
exactly right. It is hard to explain.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Klassen was selected from the Milwaukee Brewers
in the expansion draft. He had not played above Double-A before
this season. He played well at shortstop for the Diamondbacks in
spring training, then was moved to second base at Triple-A Tucson
about a month ago. He has a strong chance to become the club's
second baseman of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition has gone smoothly,'' Klassen said. ``I've had
great teachers. Chris (Speier) had to make the same move during his
career, so he's been showing me all about the different angles when
you're fielding the ball and trying to turn the double play, things
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop  &UR; Jay Bell, who teamed with Klassen on one of the two
double plays, was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good all-around athlete. It seems that he can play
almost anywhere,'' Bell said. &QL; 
Williams sits out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After learning his foot X-rays were negative, Williams, who
walked very gingerly around the clubhouse, was limited to
pinch-hitting duty during the game. He struck out in the ninth.
 &UR; Andy
 &UR; Fox started at third in his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to have to take it a day it a time and see
how it goes,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the All-Star break that begins Monday and the fact
that the Diamondbacks won't play again after today until Friday,
Williams might also sit out again today rather than risk a
re-injury. He has hit in 14 of his past 15 games. &QL; 
Scary situation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The club received a scare before the game when  &UR; Julio Paula,
their primary batting practice pitcher, passed out and was taken to
the hospital for tests.
</P>
<P>
   Paula, who was a coach at the team's academy in the Dominican
Republic, was playing catch in the outfield with pitcher  &UR; Willie
Blair when he became ill. While walking toward the dugout, he felt
as if he were going to vomit but instead passed out. The hospital
tests proved negative. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
