<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES SPARKS GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ There was no second-guessing the coach. No veterans
complaining about playing time. There were also no Germans,
Iranians or Yugoslavians _ just the cheer of a Fourth of July crowd
and of course the sight of the Kansas City Wizards to let Cobi
Jones know he's finally cleared customs.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Au revoir(end ital), France. No. 13 is back.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the most celebrated American player, left the disaster of
the United States' World Cup performance behind and got back to
business Saturday with the Galaxy in front of a season-high 53,655
at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Jones played every minute of the three U.S. losses in the World
Cup, but all he needed was a Galaxy jersey to feel what it was like
to win in a 2-0 victory over the Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Jones, paired with Mexican striker Carlos
Hermosillo on the front line, left out Welton, Major League
Soccer's leading scorer with 33 points. That was the only
controversy in an otherwise normal Galaxy game as the team won its
fourth straight to improve to 15-2 on the season. Kansas City
dropped to 7-10.
</P>
<P>
   When Jones left for the national team, he had a league-high 23
points. He picked up right where he left off, turning a 1-0 Galaxy
lead into a comfortable 2-0 cushion.
</P>
<P>
   Jones started up the left side in the 67th minute, dropping the
ball off for Martin Machon. Machon curled a cross to the back of
the Wizards goal to Hermosillo, whose header hit the near post and
ricocheted in front to a hustling Jones following up the play.
Jones easily placed the ball into an open net for his ninth goal of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he had a feeling-out type of first half and felt the
game start coming to him in the second 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little frustrating in the first half, but things
started opening up a bit in the second half,'' Jones said. ``I got
that first goal and everything kind of floated after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a while for the team to get used to me and remembering
how I play. They realized they can play through me and that I want
the ball in certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri, who shadowed Kansas City's Preki
the entire game, said it was good to see Jones running up and down
the flanks again.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speed and ability to score goals is a great attribute,''
Caligiuri said. ``He's dangerous every time he gets the ball. When
we took the lead early in the first half, we were asking him to
push back more. In the second half we asked him to go forward and
you could see he's much more dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano was pleased with the Galaxy's
performance overall but wouldn't be specific as to why Welton
didn't start. The Brazilian striker came on in the 69th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are issues within the team (as to why Welton didn't
start) and that should remain with us,'' Zambrano said.
</P>
<P>
   Was it disciplinary?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say,'' he said. ``But I was happy that he came
in and he provided a spark for us. He's definitely a player that we
can't keep on the bench for long.''
</P>
<P>
   Ezra Hendrickson, who missed last Saturday's game against San
Jose because of a strained ligament in his right foot, showed no
signs of pain in the early going, setting up his seventh assist of
the season to give L.A. a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The outside attacking defender received a perfect pass from
Mauricio Cienfuegos as he was cutting from the right side into the
penalty area. Hendrickson shouldered off a defender and one-touched
a pass to a streaking Clint Mathis 5 yards in front of the Wizards
goal. Mathis easily tapped his shot past Kansas City goalkeeper
Mike Ammann for an early Galaxy lead in the eighth minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
