<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     07-05 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS SAYS ANGELS ARE LOAFING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels set a franchise record with 22 victories in
June, but after losing their first four in July _ including
Saturday night's 8-3 loss to the Oakland A's before a sellout crowd
of 43,571 at Edison Field _ manager Terry Collins was hot.
</P>
<P>
   Collins ripped his team after the game, implying it hasn't
maintained the tenacity that propelled it into the AL West lead.
</P>
<P>
   The players reaction? Give us a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you're going to have bad days,'' Collins said. ``But
you've still got to play with intensity, play hard, run balls out.
You play the game one way, I don't care if it's June 1, July 1 or
Aug. 1, you play hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things don't just happen. You go out and create things, and we
haven't done that. When you come back in games, you step it up. But
guess what? A lot of times you step it up before the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural thing to eventually have a letdown when you
play as hard as we play. When you have a letdown, you have games
like we did tonight. But if you're fatigued, all you have to do is
walk in here and say `I'm tired.' That's why we've got guys on the
bench.''
</P>
<P>
   The players candidly exercised their right to disagree with
their manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's TC's observation, not my observation,'' shortstop Gary
DiSarcina said. ``I thought we played hard, they just beat us, they
played better than us. Give 'em some credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to look at the big picture. We've had a great first
half, there's no sense panicking now about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Oakland's swinging the bat great,'' designated hitter Tim
Salmon said. ``I don't look at it any deeper than that. We've just
got to pick ourselves up. It's been no different the last four days
than the whole month of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take the losing with the winning. You've got to
be a man about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that intensity level stuff,'' first baseman Cecil
Fielder said. ``We're not going out there trying to lose, we're
trying to win. Sometimes it doesn't work out. What are you going to
do, cry about it?''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels didn't get the type of performance they've grown used
to from starting pitcher Jarrod Washburn. Washburn (4-1) went into
the game unbeaten, and the Angels were 6-0 in games he's started.
</P>
<P>
   But he lasted only five innings because of tightness in his left
(pitching) forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second inning he said his forearm was stiff,'' Collins
said. ``We thought it would loosen up, but in the fifth, his
velocity was down 5 mph, so we got him out of there. It's nothing
serious, we just didn't want to take a chance with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn said the problem is not new to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``One or two times a year it pops up,'' he said. ``You go out to
warm up for the game and it doesn't get loose. But there was no
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The only pain the Angels seemed to feel was Collins' pain
watching the Angels match their longest losing streak of the
season. They lost four in a row May 3-6 and May 23-27.
</P>
<P>
   The A's rallied from a 2-1 deficit to take a 3-2 lead in the
fifth off Washburn. Knuckleballer Steve Sparks entered the game in
the sixth, and gave up a 447-foot home run to Jason Giambi for a
4-2 Oakland lead.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for A's starter Mike Oquist (5-5), who gave up
two runs and five hits in 62/3 innings to get the win.
</P>
<P>
   The A's added four runs in the ninth to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   ``No team is going to win 162 games, I haven't seen that yet,''
Fielder said. ``You can't look at Oakland as a team that can't beat
us. They can beat us.... This game's a trip _ you win some, you
lose some.''
</P>
</TEXT>
