<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-AGENTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK AGENTS SEEK BIGGER SHARE OF MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was only about 10 years ago that sports agent
Raymond Anderson received the biggest shock of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, president of AR Sports, Inc., was trying to land a
star UCLA football player.
</P>
<P>
   An African-American graduate of Stanford and Harvard Law School
who played both football and baseball for the Cardinal, Anderson
didn't get the client. The player, who was black, didn't believe
Anderson would have the same connections as a white agent, even
though Anderson had been in the business since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going with another agent and not us for the simple fact
he believed (pro sports) is a good-ol'-boy industry,'' said
Anderson, a member of the board of directors for the Sports Lawyers
Association and the Black Sports Agents Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, he thought a (white) agent would just naturally
be able to get a contract for him because the establishment was
much more comfortable with dealing with those type of folks than
African-Americans. That was the reason and only reason he was not
coming with us. He sincerely believed all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the UCLA player was not satisfied with his agent and
decided to make a change. Again, he opted for a white agent.
</P>
<P>
   As for Anderson, his clientele includes Tampa Bay Buccaneers
coach Tony Dungy, Minnesota Vikings coach Denny Green, Stanford
coach Tyrone Willingham, Atlanta Falcons offensive tackle Bob
Whitfield and Baltimore Ravens wide receiver Ray Lewis, all
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Today, African-American agents are still fighting to gain a
share of the market. According to figures released by the
respective leagues, African-Americans make up 70 percent of all NBA
players, 67 percent of the NFL and 17 percent of professional
baseball players. Approximately 11 percent are represented by
African-American agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came out, it was just kind of the norm to have a white
agent,'' said D'Marco Farr, whose brother/agent Andre is chairman
of the Black Sports Agents Association. &QL; 
Matter of perception
</P>
<P>
   Black sports agents only recently have impacted the industry.
For years, many African-American athletes believed it was a risk to
have someone of their race handling their financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
   American University sports researcher Charles Farrell believes
it's due to the ``colder ice'' theory. Farrell's theory _ based on
an old fable _ is blacks would rather buy ice from a white man
instead of a black man because they believe the white man's ice is
colder.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the black community, we've been brainwashed to believe
that,'' said Farrell, who also runs the Sports Perspective
International Institute that helps promote sports opportunities for
blacks. ``(Blacks) go to a white doctor or a white attorney because
we think they are better. It is a terrible stereotype to overcome
and many black athletes have grown up with this stereotype.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Raiders and ex-Michigan defensive back Charles Woodson
debunks the theory. Instead, the fourth overall pick in the first
round of the 1998 NFL Draft has decided to go with Charles and
Kevin Poston, two African-American agents.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson considered David Falk, the well-known agent who
represents Michael Jordan and many other NBA stars. But he opted
for the Postons, who represent NBA All-Star Penny Hardaway and the
St. Louis Rams' Orlando Pace _ the first overall pick in the 1997
NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only way to go for me,'' said Woodson, 21. ``I
don't know of anybody that can represent me better than those two
right there. It wasn't really a black or white issue. I just felt
they deserved a chance more so than a white agent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late '70s, Anderson said he was one of about eight black
sports agents. In its last calculations, the BSAA said there are
1,096 African-American agents but less than 40 percent are
certified through the professional leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Jim Steiner, who is white, said the colder ice theory is
no longer prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that has gone by the wayside now because a number of black
agents are doing a good job for their clients,'' said Steiner, who
has black clients Jerry Rice and 1998 NFL first-rounder Marcus Nash
of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Celtics guard Kenny Anderson, who is black, was coveted
by agents before he was selected as the second player overall in
the 1992 NBA draft out of Georgia Tech. Although the New Jersey
Nets' all-time assist leader said he interviewed several agents
when he decided to leave school after his sophomore year, he didn't
consider any black agents.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't because he didn't feel comfortable with a black
agent, he said, he just wasn't approached by any.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson said the coaches and peers of many
African-Americans are trying to push them toward black agents. But
if he was coming out of college, he says his decision on an agent
would not be based on race. Rather, he would choose a
representative based on his experience and success rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not prejudiced and I'm not one who will go the opposite
way,'' said Kenny Anderson, who started with a white agent before
switching to Falk. ``I'm about who is going to handle my business
right. When I was coming out, there weren't that many black
agents... I didn't have a choice. I went with someone that was
going to take care of my business and give me a decent contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been around (like Falk), you get a lot of deals
and make it happen. The players who want a good deal are going with
someone (with a good reputation).'' &QL; 
Familiarity factor
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is black athletes feel comfortable with black
agents because of their shared experience. That is something many
black agents say gives them an edge over their white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I would do better and feel more comfortable with
someone of my own race,'' said Cincinnati Bengals first-round pick
Takeo Spikes, who has African-American agent James Sims. ``They
have been through what I've been through during the years. It
builds a special relationship between you and the agent. I didn't
really consider a white agent. Choosing a black agent is something
I felt comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodson said, ``A black agent just knows how it is to be a black
man. No white agent can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson disagrees. He said athletes should only be
concerned with how their agent handles their contracts and business
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my agent gets my deal, I say, `Thanks a lot, here's your
four or five percent,''' Anderson said. ``The color issue is
overrated. I go with the best guy for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Steiner believes many black agents use race to gain an advantage
with black athletes. Still, he said, what matters is doing the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The color of your skin doesn't negotiate a better deal for
that player,'' Steiner said. ``It is the person's experience,
knowledge or wherewithall to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his second year as chairman of the BSAA, Farr looks to the
future. He sees a day when agents will be judged solely on
expertise and competence, a day when black agents are more visible
in the industry. And at that time, being a white or black sports
agent won't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I want to level the playing field,'' Farr said.
``If we do that, the entire industry will change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
