A0837 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-AGENTS-SIDE-LADN     07-05 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-AGENTS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK AGENTS RARE FOR WHITE ATHLETES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Although the number of black athletes represented
by black agents is low, the number of white athletes represented by
black agents is just as astonishing. Many members of the BSAA's
Board of Directors said less than one percent of white pro athletes
are represented by black agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``White athletes have never given black agents a chance. Never
done that... never will,'' said black agent Kevin Poston.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Steiner, a white sports agent, agrees with Poston but feels
the situation is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will change, but it will take much longer,'' Steiner said.
``That is the way of the world and it is way it is. I can't think
of any other reason other than that is the evolution of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Zandofsky, however, is an exception to the rule.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year NFL offensive lineman _ who is white _ has spent his
entire career with a black agent, Raymond Anderson. ``He works as
hard on my $500,000 contract as he does for a $5 million contract
for another player,'' Zandofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Zandofsky said when he was with the Atlanta Falcons, three black
teammates were shocked to know he was represented by the same agent
as they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter what race (Raymond) was to me or anyone
else,'' Zandofsky said. ``You should go with the guy that is going
to do the best job for you whether he is white or black. You would
think that people would think in terms of his professionalism and
how well-prepared they are.''
</P>
<P>
   While signing white players hasn't been easy, some
African-American agents say that part of the blame lies with
themselves. The overwhelming majority of black agents stick with
just the NFL and NBA _ both predominantly black leagues _ because
the two leagues give them the safest route of success.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said black agents must use the same confidence in
signing white athletes as they use to sign black athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as black agents also have to take some responsibility to
target non-African-Americans as guys we want to do business with,
too,'' he said. ``We go after a handful, but it always has to be a
profile that fits us.''
</P>
<P>
   BSAA chairman Andre Farr, an ex-UCLA football player, said, ``We
can't survive representing African-Americans alone. With the new
millennium coming up, we have more opportunities. How can we call
ourselves successful agents if we don't go into soccer, baseball or
golf? We have to go into uncharted waters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
