<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLBUS-ADS-COX     07-05 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLBUS-ADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Caution light for school bus ads
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Jackie Dyer, superintendent of a poor school
district in far West Texas, thought he hit upon a perfect idea for
raising extra money to finance safety equipment for school buses.
</P>
<P>
   Dyer, who heads the Fabens Independent School District, did not
go to taxpayers for help. He went to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Fabens' 12 yellow school buses now bear McDonald's, Coca Cola,
American Airlines and other ads. And thanks to the ad revenue, the
buses carry two-way radios and flashing red stop signs that unfold
into traffic when children board or exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way for us to earn some extra dollars,'' Dyer said
of the advertising, which generates $18,000 annually for his
district _ the 13th poorest of the state's more than 1,000
districts.
</P>
<P>
   But his new source of money may be dried up by actions playing
out in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Public Safety, responding to a law
passed in 1997, is devising rules to regulate advertising on school
buses. If passed in their current form, the regulations would
severely limit the space and placement of advertising on buses _ in
the name of safety.
</P>
<P>
   Dyer's case points up a dilemma faced by school districts across
the state and nation. Strapped for cash, some increasingly are
turning to advertising for new money to finance school activities.
But bright, colorful advertising emblazoned across school buses may
go too far, posing safety risks for students, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are more important than income,'' said Sen. Teel Bivins,
R-Amarillo, chairman of the Senate Education Committee. ``We
parents are entrusting our children's lives to these vehicles, and
I think we should be very cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   New state rules regulating advertising on school buses would
have far-reaching effects. Aside from the Fabens school district,
Socorro in West Texas and the Lake Worth district near Fort Worth
also are carrying ads. And the San Marcos district _ as well as
others _ may not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Texas Department of Public Safety, which
regulates school bus transportation, say they are proceeding with
caution in drafting the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed rules, advertising would be limited to only
two places on a school bus _ the left rear quarter panel and above
the windows on either side of the bus.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to balance the needs of school districts, who are
looking for additional money to finance school activities, against
the safety of children who ride the school buses. DPS officials
worry that ads would distract drivers and detract from the effect
of the school buses' bright yellow color.
</P>
<P>
   ``Placing advertising on the sides of the school bus within a
student's reach could entice a student to enter or linger in the
`danger zone' with the intention of touching the advertisement,''
DPS Director Dudley Thomas said in a March 1998 letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school bus is one of the most widely recognized vehicles
on the road due to its shape, yellow color and school bus
markings.''
</P>
<P>
   Eye-catching ads on the exterior of a bus might distract drivers
or interfere with their ability to easily recognize a school bus.
That, in turn, could lead to more accidents involving school buses.
</P>
<P>
   Dyer is not buying that explanation. His district buses have
rolled along the streets of Fabens for two years without incident
or accident because of the ads, he said. And he points to school
districts in six other states, whose buses are bearing ads, he
says, apparently without an increase in accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado districts in 1994 were the first to offer school buses
for advertising. Since 1997, five additional states have adopted
rules. Because programs are new, there is not enough data to know
if ads are causing more accidents, according to the DPS. In
Colorado Springs, where ad contracts for school buses and hallways
total $8 million annually, safety has not been a primary issue.
</P>
<P>
   Texas DPS officials say that before rules are approved and put
on the books, the public will have a chance to comment on them.
</P>
<P>
   Dyer said DPS has not done its homework thoroughly. He calls it
a case of big government picking on little government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had come down here and stood on the street corner and
witnessed two or three accidents, then I could understand it,'' he
said. ``I might as well not advertise if they make me take them
(ads) off from all but the back panel (of the bus).''
</P>
<P>
   Dyer has solicited the help of Gov. George W. Bush and U.S. Sen.
Phil Gramm to stop the rules, or at least loosen them to allow more
advertising in more places on a school bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to force these rules on us,'' he said. ``Yes,
we are poor. But it's not right for them to push us around.''
</P>
<P>
   The district, with 2,760 students, has a dozen buses that
display ads, which sell for $250 each. Aside from McDonald's, Coca
Cola and American Airlines, the buses carry ads from 14 other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   If Fabens in rural West Texas can raise $18,000 a year through
such a program, San Marcos _ with about 60 school buses _ could
pull in about $100,000, figures Hector Montenegro, superintendent
of the San Marcos Consolidated School District south of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most taxpayers would probably support our interest to
look at other options to finance district-related activities,''
Montenegro said. ``We are looking into that as an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro said school districts have entered an era of greater
collaboration between corporations and schools. The school bus
advertising program seems ``a natural segue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others aren't so sure. They said that increasingly,
corporate America is aggressively reaching into the nation's
schools to the captive audience of schoolchildren. And schools,
strapped for cash, are willing partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some concerns about the growing commercialism in
schools and the impact on our kids,'' said Melissa Anderson, a
spokeswoman for the National Education Association. ``Kids are in
school to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the trend hardly is expected to let up because
schools are constantly looking for new sources of money to
supplement tax dollars, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lake Worth district, a recorded message greets callers:
``Thank you for calling the Lake Worth Independent School District,
educational partners with Lake Worth National Bank and American
Airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said the decision of whether to offer school buses,
hallways or school score boards to advertisers is a local decision.
But he added, regulating ads on school buses is a safety issue that
belongs to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins offered one creative solution to the dilemma of school
bus advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe all the advertising could be yellow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
