<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHRATE-DECLINE (Stockholm, Sweden) _ Driven largely by the
prosperity and freedom of the modern world, millions of women _
here and in nearly every country on earth _ are having fewer
children than ever before. As a result, birth rates in many
countries are now in a rapid, sustained decline.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-ECON (Washington) _ A year after Thailand devalued its
currency, triggering the Asian economic meltdown, there is no end
in sight. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA-ASSESS (Washington) _ Analysis: Clinton thinks he
found his Gorbachev in China's leader Jiang Zemin. The problem is,
Jiang is more likely China's Brezhnev. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-RDP (Portadown) _ The British government used hundreds
of combat-ready troops and Northern Ireland policemen on Sunday to
prevent several thousand Protestants of the patriotic Orange Order
from marching, as it has since 1807, through the small Roman
Catholic enclave of Drumcree in this town 35 miles west of Belfast.
By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-AIRPORT (Hong Kong) _ The old airport moves to the new.
By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-DISNEY (Marne-la-Vallee) _ Mickey Mouse has been on the
picket lines here at Disneyland Paris for almost two weeks. Captain
Hook wants more money, and so does Pluto, who says he loves his
work but hardly has a bone to gnaw on come the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-MERGER (New Orleans) _ National Education Association
delegates vote on merger plan with American Federation of Teachers.
By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES (Mims) _ Evacuees return to this small town in
fire-ravaged northeastern Florida. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-TOBACCO-TRIAL (Undated) _ For cigarette makers, it's been an
expensive year in the Sunshine State. But with the start on Monday
in Miami of jury selection in a massive class-action case brought
on behalf of smokers in Florida, that legal tab might jump
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   HMO-CUTBACK (Washington) _ Complaining of cuts in government
payments for their services, the nation's biggest health
maintenance organizations are quitting managed care programs that
states and the federal government promote as a means to provide
good care while holding down the cost. The retreat is most
pronounced in Medicaid programs for the poor. Starting a little
more than a year ago and accelerating lately, managed care
organizations like Aetna U.S. Healthcare, PacifiCare, Oxford Health
Plans, Kaiser Permanente, and a few Blue Cross and Blue Shield
Associations, have been shutting down services in at least 14
states, including New York, New Jersey, Connecticut, California,
and Florida. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-POLITICS (Washington) _ The battle for the House this
year is being fought in trench warfare, district by district. For
the first time in a decade the voters are not angry, but lulled by
the good economy. This means that control of the House could ride
on such factors as a decision by Representative Wes Watkins not to
retire and the role of the Green Party as a spoiler in New Mexico.
The story will look at where the hottest races are, what the
strategies of the two parties are for victory and level of their
fundraising. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by William Safire;
details later.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by Anthony Lewis;
details later.
</P>
