<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, July 6:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-ART-MARKET (London) _ The high price recently paid for a
Monet became something of a symbol here as the most important weeks
of the summer art season unfold. Its importance was not that it was
the third-highest price ever paid for a work of art in London, or
that the work was extremely rare, since many of the artist's works
are in museums. It was a sign of strength for the London art
market, which has been increasingly unstable the last several
years. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-ARTS-CENTER (Newark) _ Pronouncing their first season a
rousing artistic success, officials of the New Jersey Performing
Arts Center said the center had attracted a large and broad-based
audience of half a million people since its opening in October and
was sparking interest in revitalizing downtown Newark. By Ronald
Smothers.
</P>
<P>
   FREUD-EXHIBIT (Undated) _ A long-delayed Freud exhibit is set to
open at the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   SNAKE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Bernstein reviews ``The
Snake Charmer'' by Sanjay Nigam.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-OUTSIDER-BOOM (Madrid, Spain) _ Spain has not had it this
good in years. As much of Europe adopts the euro as a single
currency, a remarkable divergence is taking place: poorer countries
like Spain, Portugal, and Ireland are booming much faster than
bigger and wealthier neighbors like France and Germany. By Edmund
L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   KINKO-PEOPLE (Undated) _ At last count, there are nearly 40
million Americans working out of their homes with the help of
electronic conveniences such as cell phones, fax machines and
handheld organizers. And on any given day, tens of thousands of
them stop by a Kinko's Copy store. For many home-based workers, the
attraction is often less about what equipment Kinko's provides than
what their own home offices don't: other people. As millions more
people join the work-at-home trend each year, Kinko's appears to be
doing what many people envisioned cybercafes would do -- that is,
offer an escape from the isolation that this abundance of modern
technology seems to have created. By Laurie Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-DISKS (Undated) _ Two years after its debut, the DVD disk
for movies is beginning to pick up market momentum. But in the
video rental business, the recent rollout of a competing format _
Divx _ risks causing consumer doubt and confusion. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TCI (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T shares continue to plummet in the wake
of its deal to acquire TCI, questions are beginning to emerge about
how low the stock may go _ and whether AT&AMP;T shareholders will be
willing to approve it. But at least TCI has the solace of a $1.75
billion break-up fee, should the deal unravel. By Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL-IGNORE (Undated) _ How well do consumer-products
companies respond to the E-mail that they invite consumers to send
in, with questions or comments or seeking product information? Not
very well, according to a non-scientific survey of two-dozen big
companies. By Pam O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPUS-MARKETING (San Francisco) _ A controversial plan by the
California State University system to give Fujitsu, GTE, and other
companies semi-exclusive marketing opportunities on their campuses
in exchange for network equipment and training has collapsed. By
Laurie Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Digital Commerce column; details
TK. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   BRILL-MEDIA (Undated) _ While media critics, talk show hosts and
reporters, chewed over the scoop about Kenneth Starr in the first
issue of Brill's Content, an entirely different group tipped their
hats and took notes: magazine publicists. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   ENQUIRER-COSBY-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ How The National Enquirer
became a player in the Ennis Cosby trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
