<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded s)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES (New York) _ New York vs. Baltimore. By Buster
Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports column on Orioles-Yankees
game. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES (New York) _ A look at the Yankees at the half-way
point. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-BRAVES (Atlanta) _ New York vs. Atlanta. By Jason
Diamos.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HOMERUNS (Undated) _ The highlight of the all-star
festivities could be the home-run contest at Coors Field on Monday.
But it will be the home run contest that resumes after Tuesday
night's all-star game that will command the attention of fans. The
pursuit of Roger Maris' 37-year-old record of 61 home runs clearly
dominated the first half of the season and will intensify as the
games and weeks go by and the season approaches September. By
Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-LPGA (Kohler, Wis.) _ Women's U.S. Open, final round. By
Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-TOMFOOL (Elmont, N.Y.) _ The $150,000 Tom Fool at Belmont.
By Joseph Durso.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN (Wimbledon, England) _ Sampras beats
Ivanisevic. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-CROATIA (Paris) _ Croatia gained its independence
from Yugoslavia only six years ago and is already participating in
its first World Cup. Yet the country, with a mere 4.7 million
residents, has now joined traditional powers France, Brazil and
Holland as the four remaining teams with a chance to win soccer's
world championship. Not since Portugal in 1966 has a team advanced
this far in its first appearance in the World Cup. By Jere Longman.
</P>
</TEXT>
