<SLUG> BC-RADIO-SPORTSBABE-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FABULOUS SPORTS BABE DOES NOT SUFFER FOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Fla., N.Y.)   (ART ADV.: two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling 212
556-4204.) 
 (mk) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nanci Donnellan is interested in jazz, opera and
popular culture, but you would never know it from her radio
persona: the self-described Fabulous Sports Babe, the only female
host of a nationally syndicated sports talk show.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime broadcaster and celebrity in her own right, the Babe,
as she demands to be called, is not cowed by the bluster of George
Steinbrenner, owner of the New York Yankees, who made an appearance
on her show the night after a brawl between his team and the
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   She can also build rapport with athletes like the slugger Ken
Griffey Jr., known for his reticence off the field. She is equally
well known for her opinionated, gravelly over-the-air bellow and
lightning-quick repartee. Sports fans who bore the Babe are blown
off the show with the sound of an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know not to diddle around,'' Ms. Donnellan said. ``I do
not suffer fools lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the risk of such ignominy, about 250,000 sports fans
each month call the Babe's 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. daily call-in show,
transmitted live from New York to 187 stations. It is one of the
few radio programs to generate nearly $1 million in annual revenue.
As a measure of its success, nearly two-thirds of the 300 stations
that broadcast news, sports and talk exclusively are Babe
affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ms. Donnellan's show is not heard in the nation's
largest market. In New York, the first all-sports station, WFAN,
holds sway over sports enthusiasts with its own well-known local
hosts. Neither is she on in Los Angeles or San Francisco, where the
time difference means her show starts during morning drive time,
often the most lucrative part of the day and generally ceded to a
local host.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep trying,'' said T.J. Lambert, a vice president in
Dallas for ABC Radio, owned by Walt Disney Co. ABC Radio took over
the distribution of the Babe's show in April 1997 after Ms.
Donnellan alienated the management of ESPN, the Disney cable
network that had given her a national platform.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN, then an ABC division and the undisputed leader in sports
TV, hired the Sports Babe in 1992 as the centerpiece of its
expansion into radio. The move into the big leagues enhanced Ms.
Donnellan's credibility, but her on-air persona, caroming between
irreverent and motherly to cranky and flirty, stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did not blend into the woodwork; it rubbed them the wrong
way,'' said Mark Mason, program director for WINS-AM in New York
and a former general manager of ESPN radio, who helped hire Ms.
Donnellan. ``At ESPN, the call letters are the star, and anyone who
rises above a certain level of notoriety is problematic.'' Similar
complaints, he said, have contributed to the departure of other
stand-out ESPN hosts like Keith Olbermann.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final coup de grace,'' Mason said, was ``The Babe in
Boyland,'' an obscenity-filled memoir, published in 1996 by
HarperCollins, in which Ms. Donnellan takes shots at nearly
everyone in sports, including her bosses and the leagues her bosses
court for broadcast rights. ``They wanted to turn me into the Cokie
Roberts of sports broadcasting, a place where the hardest sports
news is explained in the most mind-numbing manner possible,'' she
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the contretemps has left Ms. Donnellan unscathed, as the
sports business flourishes on radio as well as television. Radio is
now served by two 24-hour sports networks and three daily
syndicated shows, including the Sports Babe's. The other hosts are
Tony Kornheiser on ESPN and Jim Rome on Premiere Radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cares about X's and O's,'' said Rick Scott, a sports
radio programming consultant. ``It's not about information; it's
about opinion and a unique perspective. The Babe's got a real grasp
on the entertainment aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Scott who recruited Ms. Donnellan to KVN in Seattle,
where she raised the station's audience share from 0.04 percent to
6 percent. Her barbed tongue was honed as sports director and
afternoon host in Tampa, Fla. And it was there, bedridden from a
golf injury, that she blurted out an invitation to her audience to
spend the afternoon in bed with a ``fabulous sports babe.'' The
name stuck.
</P>
<P>
   In both intellect and proportion, Ms. Donnellan is the
antithesis of an empty-headed anorexic bimbo. She is a news addict
who watches dozens of televised sports events and takes to the
stands whenever affiliates seek her for a personal appearance.
October is frantic, with baseball and football seasons overlapping.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is to skunk her competitors by being the first with
news. She also grills guest athletes with questions that interest
ordinary fans. ``It's not brain surgery,'' she conceded. ``We talk
a lot of issues, like racism, having seven children with six women,
choking the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophically, her game plan is to stoke the show's energy
with the unexpected friction from undercutting stereotypes. That
might mean taking a call from a fan with a hard-to-understand
accent or inviting a female sportswriter as a show guest. ``I don't
miss an opportunity for that,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
