<SLUG> BC-QUESTIONS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: 20 QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time again to ask 20 questions about advertising, marketing
and the media.
</P>
<P>
   _ Is the ``it'' referred to in advertising for the Gatorade
sports beverage sold by Quaker Oats Co. that asks ``Is it in you?''
the same ``it'' referred to by Seagram Co. in advertising for
Chivas Regal Scotch whisky that asserts ``You either have it or you
don't''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Is it a sly inside joke when a woman in a commercial for the
Salon Selectives line of hair care products sold by Unilever
proclaims that her appearance gives her ``the power to conquer the
world ... or maybe just Cincinnati'' _ home of Procter &AMP; Gamble
Co., the principal rival of Unilever in such competitive fields as
hair care?
</P>
<P>
   _ How many history teachers complained to CBS about a
promotional commercial for a special program, ``People of the
Century,'' in which Dan Rather quoted Theodore Roosevelt's saying
as ``Walk softly and carry a big stick''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Wouldn't the corporate world be less insufferable if more
executives had a sense of humor like those at the Target retail
unit of Dayton Hudson Corp., who saluted shoppers' affectionate
references to ``Target'' stores by running ads carrying the theme
``C'est Target''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Couldn't someone at the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee have proofread a direct-mail solicitation letter that
sought opinions from New Yorkers on significant issues so their
responses could be shared with ``Senator Daniel Patrick Moyni''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Was it an accident that one recent morning on the cable
television system serving the Upper West Side of Manhattan, three
infomericals for compact disk collections were playing in
progressive sequence, so that Channel 50 peddled a collection of
music from the 1950s, Channel 51 the 1970s and Channel 52 the
1980s?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the move by the Sunshine Biscuits unit of Keebler Foods
Co. to stop embossing the word ``sugar'' on its Vienna Fingers
sandwich cookies help millions of noshers turn trim?
</P>
<P>
   _ Did anyone at People magazine notice that an ad on page 91 of
the July 6 issue, showing a woman standing behind an X-ray machine
to promote the calcium content of the Total line of cereal sold by
General Mills, was nearly identical to an ad that appeared 12 pages
later, showing a boy standing behind an X-ray machine to promote
the calcium content of the Sunny Delight juice drink sold by
Procter &AMP; Gamble?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco unit of BAT Industries
promotes redesigned packages of Kool cigarettes with ads carrying
the headline ``NU look,'' will Northwestern University become
popular with smokers?
</P>
<P>
   _ When Hoechst AG decided to run an ad about its research on
Alzheimer's disease, which carried the headline ``Imagine being in
your 90s and still able to recite every word Springsteen ever
wrote,'' did someone remember to ask Bruce Springsteen about it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Wasn't it a marvelous moment of media convergence coincidence
when the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance Publications
sponsored a newspaper ad supplement as part of a trade campaign
carrying the theme ``The accent is on content'' just as Steven
Brill was bringing out the first issue of Brill's Content magazine?
</P>
<P>
   _ As ``road rage'' continues to concern motorists, is it smart
for General Motors Corp. to promote the Chevrolet Monte Carlo Z34
by showing Taz, the Tasmanian devil cartoon character, in ads
carrying the headline ``Inside every Monte Carlo driver is a wild
side''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that Procter &AMP; Gamble has run newspaper ads in which the
company acknowledges that Crest Multicare toothpaste does not help
reduce and prevent gingivitis and reduce plaque while a competitive
brand, Colgate Total, does, can consumers look forward to
subsequent ads that are as scrupulously honest about the
shortcomings of other products?
</P>
<P>
   _ After The Wall Street Journal advised readers to visit ``the
legendary Nat King Cole bar'' at the St. Regis Hotel in Manhattan,
how many showed up and asked the pianist to play ``Unforgettable''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Are the Marlboro cigarette billboards in the Richmond, Va.,
area carrying the headline ``You get a lot to like'' _ a line from
one of the brand's early jingles _ a precursor of a retro-chic
national campaign from Philip Morris Cos. that would include a
concert tour by Julie London, who sang the jingles?
</P>
<P>
   _ Is a coupon for the Soft Scrub line of cleansers sold by
Clorox Co. that expires on ``April 31, 1998'' actually good
forever?
</P>
<P>
   _ If George Steinbrenner ever moves the New York Yankees from
Yankee Stadium, could disgruntled fans insist that the Lipton Brisk
tea commercial set there, which features him along with Babe Ruth,
Reggie Jackson, Mickey Mantle and Billy Martin, be re-edited to
show the rest of them clobbering him with their bats?
</P>
<P>
   _ Wasn't it classy of the Clairol unit of Bristol-Myers Squibb
Co. to pay a posthumous tribute to Shirley Polykoff, who created
the line ``Does she or doesn't she?'' for Clairol hair dyes?
</P>
<P>
   _ When executives of the U.S. Tobacco unit of UST Corp. decided
to promote Copenhagen Long Cut snuff with the slogan ``It
satisfies,'' wasn't there anyone there to remind them that
Chesterfield cigarettes were once sold with the slogan ``They
satisfy''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Marlon Brando, Gary Cooper, Marilyn Monroe and the other
Hollywood stars featured in a Levi's jeans campaign carrying the
theme ``Our models can beat up their models'' next start to
threaten an advertising columnist by warning him, ``You ask a lot
of questions for someone from Brooklyn''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNAKE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     07-05 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SNAKE CHARMER': MAN BITES SNAKE AND PAYS THE PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: India)  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The snake charmer of Sanjay Nigam's title is a man named
Sonalal, and the designation is literal, not symbolic. Sonalal is
one of those wizened men who wait for the tourist buses in front of
Hamayun's tomb in New Delhi, playing tunes on a dried-out gourd
while a cobra rises out of a wicker basket. On the day that this
novel opens, Sonalal makes a mistake that changes the rest of his
life and out of which Nigam spins an engaging, light-as-a-feather
tale of a comically stubborn struggle for both moral absolution and
a few dollops of worldly pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Nigam, the dust jacket tells us, is an Indian-born physician and
medical researcher who now lives in Boston. Writing novels is, in
other words, a kind of avocation for him but one for which he
clearly has some talent. He has a deceptively simple, intentionally
naive style, one intended, it seems, to mimic the tradition of
Indian folk tales. But while his story of the Delhi streets zips
along like a bicycle rickshaw, it passes through what is actually
some pretty serious cultural and intellectual traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Nigam's Sonalal, illiterate and superstitious, is several
things: an illustration of the complexity of ordinary people, a
morally honest traveler through the shadowy landscape of
contemporary India, an afflicted Everyman, and an alienated artist
striving to gain recognition for an ignored masterpiece. It would
be sentimental to say that he achieves nobility in Nigam's
portrayal of him. Indeed, Nigam maintains a tender but never
sentimental narrative voice. But one does come to appreciate
Sonalal for the depth of his fractured humanity as well as for the
all-too-human quality of his frailty and foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   On the day that changes his life forever, Sonalal leaves home
early, his faithful co-performer, an aging cobra named Raju, curled
in its basket. An international sporting event, ``the Games,'' is
opening in New Delhi on this day, so business is particularly
brisk. When a group of foreign journalists arrives at Hamayun's
Temple, Sonalal, greedy for more rupees to be tossed in his
direction, pushes the tired and unwilling Raju through one more
performance. He plays ``variations on Raju's favorite tune, such
beautiful variations that, had they been recorded, might have
guaranteed Sonalal's immortality.'' Suddenly, however, the
exhausted Sonalal hits a false note, noticed only by Raju who,
enraged, strikes at the snake charmer's calf. And though the snake
was defanged and stripped of its poison glands, the bite throws
Sonalal into a paroxysm of anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonalal felt no pity. His eyes became wild. He bent down,
grabbed the listless snake by the head and tail, and stretched it
to its full length.'' Then, while the astonished foreigners looked
on, he bit the snake in two, killing ``his eldest son,'' as he
thinks of Raju, and setting into motion his picaresque adventure in
search of penance and consolation.
</P>
<P>
   In India, of course, snake bites man is no story, but man bites
snake is a sensation. Sonalal, showered with money and attention by
the foreign journalists, becomes briefly rich and famous. But in
his way, Sonalal is morally superior to his unwarranted good
fortune, knowing that it is undeserved, based on an act of
momentary savagery. Sonalal feels guilty. He also worries that
Raju's mate will seek him out and murder him in vengeance. Sonalal
has bad dreams. He develops an unbearably bitter taste in his
mouth. He becomes impotent, even in the presence of his favorite
prostitute, Reena. He quarrels with Sarita, his long-suffering
wife. He starts uncontrollably biting his tongue. He seeks the help
of doctors whom Nigam, a doctor himself, portrays with satirical
panache.
</P>
<P>
   ``The universe is mysterious, unpredictable,'' Sonalal is told
by one of them, Dr. Seth. ``The mind of the Creator has endless
depth that cannot be completely fathomed even by great scientists
like Darwin, Freud, Einstein, and myself.'' Another doctor provides
a direct diagnosis. ``What's the matter with me, doctor sahib?
What?'' Sonalal asks. ``Dr. Basu looked Sonalal straight in the eye
and said, `It's called guilt.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nigam carries us quietly and unaffectedly through Sonalal's
trials, allowing his character to reveal himself as an entirely
earthbound figure capable of thoughts of the sublime. Sonalal
remembers the beauty of the music he played in the minutes just
before Raju's death and he wonders whether the gods were actually
playing it, or merely present as listeners during an act of human
genius. ``Can you understand what it's like to know greatness for
just a moment and then know that, no matter how hard you try, it
will never happen again?'' he asks Reena. He contemplates suicide
and attempts it by stuffing his mouth full of ground chili pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Sonalal, in short, is a marvelous creation, a captivating figure
of both strangeness and recognizability. If there is a fault in
Nigam's account of his adventures, it is that he strays here and
there into adorableness. Nigam minimizes the dark side or, more
accurately, holds it in check so that Sonalal's character never
carries him into full tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The image that occurs and recurs throughout is that of the snake
that bites its own tail. Nigam uses the image in several clever and
unexpected ways, among them as a metaphor for a kind of second
chance he gives to Sonalal near the end of his story when the snake
charmer's modest history almost repeats itself. By then Nigam has
struck a poignant, almost elegiac tone made up in part of the
simple passage of time in the world he has created but also of the
sense that as India changes, the places, literal and metaphorical,
set aside for snake charmers like Sonalal will slowly disappear.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
