<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been developments involving four large accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. named Zenith Media Services and Media Direct
Partners, both of New York, to handle its consolidated media buying
account, with billings estimated at $125 million to $200 million.
Those duties had been handled by various agencies including Zenith,
which is a joint venture of Cordiant Communications Group PLC and
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a review that had also included Arnold
Communications in Boston, part of Snyder Communications, in
partnership with Draft Worldwide in Chicago, part of Interpublic
Group of Companies; TBWA Chiat/Day in New York, part of Omnicom
Group, and TN Media in New York, part of True North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Fila USA Inc., part of Fila Holdings SpA, selected Leo Burnett
Co. in Chicago to handle its account, with billings estimated at
$15 million. The account had been handled for eight months by
Arnell Group Brand Consulting in New York until that agency and
Fila parted ways in March.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett was awarded the account after a four-month review that
also included the New York office of Fallon McElligott; Cliff
Freeman &AMP; Partners in New York, part of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi; W.B.
Doner &AMP; Co. in Southfield, Mich., and Toth Design and Advertising
in Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Focus Agency in Dallas, owned by Omnicom, resigned the
consumer market account of Qwest Communications after only eight
months, attributing the decision to ``creative differences and the
direction of the relationship.'' The account was initially
described as having billings estimated at $50 million, but the
agency said that ``never materialized.'' Telephone calls to Qwest
executives seeking comment on whether a review would now begin were
not returned.
</P>
<P>
   And Dreyfus Corp. unit of Mellon Bank Corp. narrowed a review on
its account to three finalists from six semifinalists. The account,
with billings estimated at $12 million to $15 million, had been
handled for three years by Citron Haligman Bedecarre in San
Francisco until that agency and Dreyfus parted ways in April.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Roth, president of Richard Roth Consulting in Chappaqua,
N.Y., who is helping manage the review, identified the finalists,
all of New York, as: Partners &AMP; Shevack, part of Wolf Group, and
two agencies owned by Interpublic, Ammirati Puris Lintas and
Angotti, Thomas, Hedge. Three agencies in New York were eliminated
from the review: Bozell Worldwide, part of True North; Grace &AMP;
Rothschild, and Rapp Collins Worldwide, a unit of Omnicom. A
decision is expected by mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS Appoints Key Executive
</P>
<P>
   Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS in New York, part of the Lowe Group unit of
Interpublic Group of Cos., has named William Sawyer managing
director of its San Francisco office. Sawyer, 44, joins from Wieden
&AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore., where he had been managing director of
the Amsterdam office and head of European operations. Sawyer
succeeds Bob Jeffrey, who left in March to become executive vice
president and managing director of J. Walter Thompson New York,
part of WPP Group PLC.
</P>
</TEXT>
