<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Monday, July 6. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HMO-CUTBACK (Washington) _ Complaining of cuts in government
payments for their services, the nation's biggest HMOs are quitting
managed care programs that states and the federal government
promote as a means to provide good care while holding down the
cost. The retreat is most pronounced in Medicaid programs for the
poor. Managed care organizations like Aetna U.S. Healthcare,
PacifiCare, Oxford Health Plans, Kaiser Permanente and a few Blue
Cross and Blue Shield Associations, have been shutting down
services in at least 14 states, including New York, New Jersey,
Connecticut, California and Florida. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-POLITICS (Washington) _ The battle for the House this
year is being fought in trench warfare, district by district. For
the first time in a decade the voters are not angry but lulled by
the good economy. This means that control of the House could ride
on such factors as a decision by Rep. Wes Watkins not to retire and
the role of the Green Party as a spoiler in New Mexico. The story
will look at where the hottest races are, what the strategies of
the two parties are for victory and level of their fund-raising. By
Alison Mitchell. With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-ECON (Washington) _ A year after Thailand devalued its
currency, triggering the Asian economic meltdown, there is no end
in sight. By David E Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-MERGER (New Orleans) _ National Education Association
delegates vote on merger plan with American Federation of Teachers.
By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES (Mims, Fla.) _ Evacuees return to this small town in
fire-ravaged northeastern Florida. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
