<HEADER>
A0999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONDON-ART-MARKET-NYT     07-05 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-ART-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN GLOW SURROUNDS LONDON ART MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ On July 28, 1954, an English collector wandered into a
London art gallery and spent about $7,000 for a colorful Monet.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, ``Waterlily Pond and Path by the Water,'' was one
of six the artist had made of his water garden in Giverny in 1900.
Until it was offered for sale at Sotheby's here last week, it had
been hanging in that same collector's house for the last 44 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, in a hushed salesroom, five telephone bidders
battled for the painting; it ended up breaking previous records for
the artist anywhere, selling for a staggering $33 million, more
than three times its estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Sotheby's refused to give either the buyer's name
or his nationality. All they would say was that he wished to remain
anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   The high price paid for the Monet became something of a symbol
here as the most important weeks of the summer art season unfold.
Its importance was not that it was one of the highest prices ever
paid for a work of art in London, or that the painting was
extremely rare, since most of the artist's waterlilies are in
museums. It was a sign of strength for the London art market, which
has been increasingly unstable for several years.
</P>
<P>
   There is the perception in the art world that the United States
is where the big money is, and, therefore, it is to a seller's
advantage to send works of art to Manhattan for sale. Further
hampering the London art market is a 3-year-old import tax imposed
on works of art arriving in European Union countries. That tax can
make selling art cheaper in New York City, which has no such tax.
</P>
<P>
   Works of art from places like Switzerland (not a European Union
member) that would normally have gone straight to London for sale
now cross the Atlantic. Making matters worse for London is the
growing threat that it will soon be eclipsed by Paris, as the
French government is scheduled to open its auctions to non-French
auctioneers this fall. So the high price fetched for the Monet was
greeted here as proof that great art can sell anywhere. Since the
painting was already in England and the import tax was not an
issue, the owner, identified only as a member of an old English
family, was quite happy to take a gamble on the London auctions. He
proved to be right: by making it the star of the London sale, it
had little competition.
</P>
<P>
   (The previous world record for a Monet painting was ``Dans la
Prairie,'' which sold at Christie's in London in 1988 for $24.4
million.)
</P>
<P>
   Another domestic star was a 1918 Modigliani portrait of a Polish
emigre known only as Baranowski. The sellers were Sir Robert and
Lady Sainsbury, who decided to sell the portrait to raise money to
establish a department for Japanese cultural studies at the
University of East Anglia. Estimated to bring $6.6 million to $10
million, it sold to the Namad brothers, who run galleries in both
London and Manhattan, for $7.1 million. (Final prices include the
auction house's commission, 15 percent of the first $50,000 and 10
percent of the rest. Estimates do not reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair to compare Sotheby's results with Christie's
because Sotheby's has stuck to the traditional format, selling
Impressionist and modern art in one sale and contemporary art
(works roughly dating from 1945 to the present) in another.
Christie's, however, has reclassified the way it sells art, pairing
19th-century and Impressionist works in a sale that took place here
two weeks ago. It performed poorly, in part because of the weak
offerings and because it was a week before the rest of the
auctions. The entire evening brought in only $19.3 million, about
$14 million less than the Monet alone sold for at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's did hold what it now calls its sale of 20th-century
art last week. (Contemporary art, which it now defines as works
dating from 1970 to the present, was sold in the spring.) While
collectors are still finding it strange to see a Picasso next to a
David Hockney, good material there fetched reasonably strong
prices. A 1917 Klee, one of the few that the artist was able to
paint during World War I and estimated to sell for $330,000 to
$490,000, ended up selling to an unidentified European collector
for $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Today's buyer does his homework and when works are overpriced,
no one is fooled. Christie's tried to stir up interest in
Magritte's ``Enchanted Domain,'' a series of eight paintings made
in 1953, by putting one on the cover of its international magazine
and holding a cocktail party two nights before the sale. Waiters,
mimicking the artist's famous images, wore bowler hats and served
canapes like cloud-shaped crackers and green apples.
</P>
<P>
   The works, which were a study the artist made for ``The
Enchanted Domain,'' a mural in the Casino Communal at
Knokke-le-Zoute in Belgium, had been for sale recently as a group
both in Japan and New York. Christie's estimates when they split
them up were considered by experts to be far too high. The first
one sold for its high estimate, bringing $2.7 million, but of the
seven others, one failed to sell and the rest went for less than
their low estimates.
</P>
<P>
   One striking fact that emerged from these sales was the strength
of European buyers. ``In just the last three months, Europeans have
begun buying again,'' said Leslie Waddington, one of London's
leading modern and contemporary art dealers. This was certainly
true at Sotheby's sale of contemporary art on Thursday night, when
only two of the top 10 works for sale were bought by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The same evening, just before its contemporary art auction
began, Sotheby's offered 49 works of German and Austrian art, and
Europeans bought of these as well. ``Seascape,'' a magical painting
by Gerhard Richter showing a turbulent sea and sky from 1970, sold
to Simon de Pury, a former chairman of Sotheby's in Europe who is
now a private dealer and art consultant, for $2.3 million, more
than three times its $664,000 high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the buyer for whom de Pury purchased the Richter was
not revealed. In fact, secrecy seemed to be even more evident at
these sales than it was in Manhattan in May and June. Most of the
buying took place over the phone. Even dealers in the salesroom
tried to be discreet. At Sotheby's sale of Impressionist and modern
art on Tuesday night, for instance, David Nash, a former Sotheby's
veteran who is now a New York dealer, was seen glued to a cellular
phone. He wasn't talking to his client, but instead was heard
bidding to Michel Strauss, Sotheby's chairman of Impressionist and
modern art, who was talking on a telephone only inches away.
</P>
<P>
   Nash was thought to be buying the Monet for Paul G. Allen, a
founder of the Microsoft Corp., who recently spent $12.1 million at
Sotheby's in Manhattan for another expensive Monet, ``Grand
Canal,'' a 1908 view of Venice. A Sotheby's representative from its
London office ended up taking the winning bid, also by telephone,
which only helped to fuel speculation that the painting might stay
in Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
