</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZZFEST-98-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEEN-AGE BASH WITH COOL OASES OF MATURITY 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLMDEL, N.J. _ The many moods of a 14-year-old: vainglorious,
deluded-heroic, foolishly cathartic, cravenly rebellious, callowly
self-obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   If that's condescending, it's no more so than Ozzfest '98, the
touring bonanza for white suburban teen-age males, which had its
first United States stop here on Friday at the PNC Bank Arts
Center. Last year's Ozzfest was the second-highest-grossing concert
tour of the year, and if the socko turnout on Friday was
indicative, it might do excellent business again.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, you'd think an 11-hour day of heavy music _ it would
be mostly misleading to call it metal _ could provide a few more
diversions for $42.50 than tables of sex stuff for beginners
(magnetized face-studs, cheapo underwear, Trojan condom stations)
and a few slapped-together stands where one could throw a dumb dart
at a dumb balloon for a free CD.
</P>
<P>
   The music? Right, the music: Those who weren't marooned in
hourlong lines for soda and pretzels might have wished that the
music was less homogeneous.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe last month, the tour included Pantera, the Foo
Fighters and Black Sabbath. American audiences lost out on these
worthwhile acts: Most of the 16 entries on the bill were new bands
with their eye depressingly riveted on the main chance. At the
moment, that's a rap-metal fusion. The good aspects of the
Afro-Americanization of white-suburban-heavy music are mostly
theoretical (Rage Against the Machine, not on the bill, is a
complicated exception). In practice, Sevendust, Coal Chamber,
Kilgore and Limp Bizkit, all of whom played the festival, make
indistinguishably leaden songs that are all about the constant
whomping downstroke. They're shouting party bands with slightly
different levels of humor, anger or soul-searching spookiness, but
desperately thin musicality.
</P>
<P>
   Limp Bizkit, however, had the audience's number better than
perhaps any other band all day. Its lone stage prop was a
20-foot-high toilet. After berating the audience and himself,
crying in rhyming tantrums that nobody loves him, and raising minor
crowd eruptions by running up the middle of the amphitheater, Fred
Durst, the band's singer, hopped up on the rim of the toilet to
enact some king-sized bathroom humor. After that, cardboard cutouts
of Posh Spice and Zac Hanson popped up out of the bowl; he
ceremoniously depressed the giant lever to flush them back down,
yelling at them in turn (to the immense delight of the crowd) for
slatternliness and insufficient manliness.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most committed heavy-metal singers become hippielike
with age, which lends their music a charge of humanism; with the
flick of a sensibility, music for children becomes music for
adults. The Brazilian band Soulfly, led by the dreadlocked singer
and guitarist Max Cavalera, formerly of Sepultura, floated out some
nonmetal musical concerns amid crunching guitars: he chanted Bob
Marley lines and flirted with pre-electric elements. Motorhead,
headlining the second stage with its simple and persuasive bar-band
metal, was the day's other dose of maturity. Lemmy Kilmister, 25
years into the job, continues on exactly the right path between
taking his music seriously and not at all. Both bands exuded a
hard-working cheer, which was lacking in Megadeth's perfectionist
but businesslike set.
</P>
<P>
   System of A Down, ranting about CIA conspiracies and chemical
corporations, showed that there were alternatives to solipsistic
anger in reaching the desired audience. The music was comparatively
captivating, too, using Arabic scales and suitelike structures.
Tool, whose participation may be the most crucial to the festival,
had the benefit of being the one mysterious band on the bill. Its
riffs lingered rather than pounded; its singer, Maynard James
Keenan, appeared bare-chested, in white face paint and thick-soled
shoes, and he writhed spasmodically as he sang xenophobic character
sketches and songs of ritual violence. If you buy Keenan, you buy
him completely, and you buy him as a tortured artist.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was Ozzy Osbourne, the Grandpa Munster of hard
rock, a smiling, harmless creature onto whom one may now project
anything so long as it keeps him in the Ozzy business. As if to
prove his free-agentry, his show was preceded by a short sequence
of music videos and film clips into which Osbourne had been edited
and superimposed. We saw him being sketched in the nude by Leonardo
DiCaprio in ``Titanic''; cavorting rudely through videos by Hanson,
the Spice Girls and Fiona Apple (for the benefit of the boys in the
crowd who hate their sisters); killing Kenny in a short slice of
``South Park,'' and finally in Jack Nicholson's place, axing his
way through the door in ``The Shining.'' The man himself finally
appeared behind a screen in a great silhouette; he raised his hands
for a mass benediction and stuck out his middle fingers.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was standard-issue Ozzy, a mixture of Black
Sabbath songs and latter-day music of his solo career by a good,
young four-piece band. Osbourne was in fine voice and repeatedly
urged the crowd to go crazy, spraying water at the front rows with
a hose. Compared with the sure-footed, macho plodders on his tour,
he moves lightly and comically; he clapped his hands as if calling
a square dance, batted his eyelashes vacantly, performed jumping
jacks. He was genuinely funny. To what other crowd but teen-agers,
battered by hours of same-sounding music, could Ozzy Osbourne
become an oasis of comedic warmth?
</P>
</TEXT>
