u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-ARTS-CENTER-1     07-05 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ARTS-CENTER-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFORMING ARTS CENTER TAKES A BOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Pronouncing their first season a rousing artistic
success, officials of the New Jersey Performing Arts Center said
the center had attracted a large and broad-based audience of half a
million people since its opening in October and was sparking
interest in revitalizing downtown Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of incipient new life in the city, which even the most
optimistic said would take years to materialize, include more than
the four new restaurants growing up in the center's shadow or the
milling crowds outside the building on show nights. Officials have
cited recent purchases of nearby office towers and plans to acquire
downtown properties for redevelopment as a turn-of-the-century
village by a new foundation financed by Prudential Insurance Co. A
minor-league baseball stadium is under construction and the
long-stalled plans for a $75 million riverfront esplanade have been
revived with the promise of federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wrong in my prediction,'' said a smiling Lawrence
Goldman, executive director of the performing arts center, as he
recalled his suggestion only last summer that it would be at least
two years before redevelopment began to spread from the 12-acre
site of the $180 million center.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the center cannot yet claim to have altered the cultural
landscape of the metropolitan area, as some grandly predicted it
would. Attendance at Lincoln Center and Carnegie Hall in New York
City has not suffered noticeably because of New Jersey defections.
And officials of other performing arts and presenting groups said
the center has not fostered their fortunes in a state where
donations to the arts have remained static.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the audience figures and the filling of 82 percent of
its seats over 357 performances in 244 days that was most
encouraging to Goldman and others. It suggested that the center's
first season, which ended June 30, was working. Offerings included
a broad mix of classical programs with top performers, popular
artists like Bob Dylan and David Copperfield, Broadway touring
companies of ``Annie'' and ``Grease,'' and nontraditional and often
risky fare from Portugal, Latin America and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance exceeded projections by 100,000. Of the half million
visitors to the center, with its soaring glass facade and red-brick
walkways, 26 percent were members of minorities, according to
surveys by the arts center. And while 29 percent were from Newark
and surrounding Essex County, 70 percent were from suburban areas
in Bergen, Union, Morris and Middlesex Counties.
</P>
<P>
   As the new home of the New Jersey Symphony, the center has
seemingly unleashed a lot of pent up demand. Subscribers for the
touring state symphony's Newark series, which until last season had
been held in Symphony Hall, quadrupled from 2,100 to 8,600, said
Lawrence Tamburri, executive director of the orchestra. Some of the
new subscribers were people who usually patronized symphony
programs in scattered sites around the state.
</P>
<P>
   The results, Goldman said, have ``shattered the two negatives''
that shadowed the center's birth as an idea more than a decade ago:
that it would not attract suburbanites back to downtown Newark and
that blacks and Hispanics who make up the majority of the city
would not be drawn to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers tell us that we have succeeded in being a
statewide performing arts center,'' he said, ``and succeeded in our
ambition to throw open the doors to new audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Stern, an Englewood dentist and longtime subscriber to the
symphony, also praised the new center but lamented the loss of some
of the annual performances by the orchestra in the John Harms
Center for the Arts in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were sort of cultural room service coming to Englewood,
but the truth is that I probably won't travel a lot for room
service,'' he said, noting that he was likely to use the time it
takes to go to Newark to travel to Lincoln Center for superior
fare.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the apparent success could be the honeymoon
effect, the New Jersey Performing Arts Center's first season
results, particularly in attracting members of minorities, is
drawing some approving and somewhat amazed nods from its peers
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Wilker, president of the Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts in Washington, called the 26 percent minority
attendance ``really good and a testament to the way they have
marketed themselves and removed barriers.'' The New Jersey center,
he said, seemed to have avoided the label of an elitist institution
from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Szakacs, the marketing director of the Playhouse Square
Foundation in Cleveland, called the first-season results for the
New Jersey venue ``impressive'' and ``wonderful'' in terms of
drawing new audiences and promoting arts education through
community programs.
</P>
<P>
   A Bellwether For Arts Patrons
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Performing Arts Center is being watched closely
for how well it does in holding traditional audiences for the arts,
creating new audiences and weaving itself into the fabric of a
city's life, said Steve Wolff, president of AMS Planning and
Research in Fairfield, Conn., an arts management and audience
survey company. AMS has done consulting work for the performing
arts center and many of the 28 centers around the country that,
like Newark's, are in large urban areas and not affiliated with a
university.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have made it an inviting place and as such the New Jersey
center is very much one of the new models of performing arts
centers,'' Wolff said. ``In the first three or four years of
performing arts centers there is a lot of learning going on. And
the early returns certainly suggest that they have done a lot of
things really right.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples of how the center has woven itself into life here
beyond the performances it presents have been evident recently. On
two days last December it held performances of ``Cinderella'' by
the American Ballet Theater in the 2,800-seat Prudential Hall, a
Kwanzaa program in the 514-seat Victoria Theater, a bar mitzvah in
one of the smaller halls, and the annual cotillion of the Essex
County Links, a black service group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In June, Newark's Science High School held its graduation at the
center. And early last month, one of the state's premiere law
firms, Sills Cummis Zuckerman Radin Tischman Epstein &AMP; Gross,
rented the Victoria Theater, where James Carville and Mary Matalin
entertained about 400 of the firm's prized clients. The event
replaced its annual golf outing to a suburban country club.
</P>
<P>
   Events like these are signs that the Newark center is a place to
commemorate important events in people's lives, as much a community
center as a cultural pavilion, Wolff said.
</P>
<P>
   This status has much to do with the 101,000 children, parents
and educators who have been served by special daytime performances
or the more than 15 arts-training performance development programs,
said Philip Thomas, vice president for arts education at the
center.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also the result of a mix of programming that has tried
to balance the traditional, the popular and the unusual. Stephanie
Hughley, vice president for programming, noted that among the
seasons sellouts were Itzhak Perlman, the New Jersey Symphony's
``Carmina Burana,'' Isaac Stern, Yo Yo Ma and Emanuel Ax with the
Laredo Quartet. Other sellouts were B.B. King, the Alvin Ailey
American Dance Theater, Bob Dylan, David Copperfield and the Harlem
Nutcracker.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman noted two setbacks. For one, they discovered too late
that there was little appetite for opera on Monday nights among the
4.6 million New Jerseyans within a 25-mile radius. They also found
to their disappointment that some of the lucrative pop acts see no
need to book performances in Newark if they are booking New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   But what he and Ms. Hughley seemed the most proud of was the
past season's World Festival. To reach out to Newark's and northern
New Jersey's sizable Portuguese-American community, the festival
featured performers from Portuguese-speaking countries around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   It was a risk artistically, said Ms. Hughley, because although
the performers were excellent artists who were popular in their
home countries of Mozambique, Portugal or Cape Verde, they were not
known here. Though some of the programs were not as well attended
as anticipated, they did bring in varied audiences and had
unquantifiable effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we created a safe space for people to come and see
things that they wouldn't go to see in other places,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Next season's World Festival will focus on pan-African works,
including a stage adaptation of ``Things Fall Apart,'' a book by
the Nigerian writer Chinua Achebe, and will introduce American
audiences to ``Waramba,'' the French and Mandenka-language opera
from Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors at other performance halls in the state look at the
New Jersey Performing Arts Center's first season with mixed
feelings. Their initial fears about the Newark center's impact on
their audiences was offset by hopes that they would get a benefit
from its programming and that it would raise the level of donations
for cultural events statewide, said David Rodriguez, director of
the 1,300-seat John Harms Center in Englewood.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of those things has happened, he said, but nor do
neighboring stages think they have lost audiences to the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that they would be a catalyst for greater arts
giving in the state,'' said Rodriguez, ``but the pot of money for
the performing arts has not increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Englewood center and the State Theater in New Brunswick
lost a portion of their New Jersey Symphony dates to the
orchestra's new home base in Newark, but officials of both centers
said that their overall subscription programs had not suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a lot of single ticket sales, but we saw an increase
in our subscriptions,'' said David Fleming, director of the State
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   A Catalyst For Urban Rebirth
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, there has been almost unalloyed enthusiasm about
how the center is affecting revitalization in downtown Newark. One
clear indication of this was the recent municipal elections in
which some candidates who might have been expected to contrast the
resources lavished on the center with the amount focused on the
neighborhood chose not to do so. Instead, most sought to associate
themselves with the center's success and trumpet its possibilities
for a broader renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Sharpe James, who called the rash of new development plans
unequivocally an outgrowth of the success of the performing arts
center's first season, has reorganized the city government's
economic development arm to package development plans and
incentives better, as well as to steer some of the expected new
largess to local neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Among its tasks will be to review the plans of Prudential's New
Newark Foundation, whose conceptual planner is Tony Goldman, a New
York real estate developer who is not related to Lawrence Goldman,
the performing arts center's president. Tony Goldman, who helped
reshape Miami's South Beach into an Art Deco tourist magnet, has
been eyeing downtown Newark for clues to what he calls the city's
soul and ways to link it to the $180 million arts center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They created this fabulous cultural center and want it to be
an economic and inspirational stimulus for the downtown of the
state's largest city,'' he said of the public and private forces
that built the center. ``I was asked to come in and help stimulate
things so that this initiative wouldn't be hanging out there as an
oasis, a passive thing, in a development desert.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
