<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGICOM-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FUTURE OF THE INTERNET: ONE PIECE OR MANY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the proposed acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc. by
AT&AMP;T was almost as full of unlikely promises as the cable giant's
notoriously unfulfilled plans to merge with the Bell Atlantic Corp.
in 1993, the reaction of the news media has matured. The former
frenzy has given way to the kind of skepticism that only five years
of Internet-driven market chaos could have inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, not much has been said about how the deal will affect
one of the most vibrant new industries that now finds itself
directly in AT&AMP;T's path: the largely local, independent Internet
service providers, or ISP's.
</P>
<P>
   The service provider industry includes more than 4,000
companies, according to Boardwatch Magazine, each of which serves
as a gateway to the global Internet and all of which, in concert,
transfer trillions of bits of data around the world every day.
</P>
<P>
   Service providers range from tiny companies serving a couple of
hundred customers to the gargantuan Worldcom Inc., which owns three
of the largest such services _ Uunet, ANS and the network services
of Compuserve _ and also controls the biggest portion of the
``Internet backbone,'' the high-speed, high-capacity fiber optic
cables, routers and national access points to which smaller service
providers are connected.
</P>
<P>
   The service provider industry is already being consolidated.
Even before the AT&AMP;T deal, it had been expected to shrink to as few
as 100 companies over the next three to four years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever other impact consolidation might have, as more control
of Internet access moves into the hands of fewer and larger
companies, there is a growing fear among industry watchers that the
larger, more powerful access providers may end up tearing the
Internet to pieces in a competitive frenzy of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Small access providers lease connections from larger ones and
from backbone owners. Because no single company or group owns or
controls the Internet, these competing access providers move data
over the global network by a cooperative arrangement called
peering, whereby they agree to send one another's data through
their own networks without charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weird business, where companies compete and cooperate
at the same time,'' said Bill McCarthy, managing editor of
Boardwatch, which follows the Internet access industry and
publishes a directory of access providers twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy is not among the analysts who think that AT&AMP;T's new
push into the consumer Internet market via At Home, the high-speed
cable modem business owned in part by TCI, will mortally wound
smaller access providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them don't want to deal with consumers anyhow,'' he
said, and those who do will be compelled to provide a higher level
of customer hand-holding than big companies are willing to offer.
</P>
<P>
   But McCarthy is more wary of another possible outcome of a
further consolidation of Internet access into a few large
companies: that for the sake of competition, big access providers
will stop cooperating with competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big fear is that if one company decides not to peer with
other networks, then you no longer have an Internet,'' McCarthy
said. ``You have separate networks, connected to one company's
infrastructure but not to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy's point of view, though not necessarily his degree of
concern, is shared by one of the founding fathers of the Internet,
Robert Kahn, who helped develop the set of protocols, or computer
communication rules, that gave birth to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Until the commercial Internet was born, Kahn said, there was
always a way to ``bootstrap'' everyone to the same level of
service. Everyone can send and receive e-mail, for example, and get
files and Web pages using standard Internet protocols.
</P>
<P>
   But when a big access provider starts to provide enhanced,
proprietary services _ ``like Internet video, for an extreme
example,'' he said _ it creates a fragmentation that until now was
unheard of on today's largely homogenous Internet and World Wide
Web. In fact, it would return us to the kind of America Online,
Compuserve and Prodigy models that existed before the Internet
became the great digital melting pot _ islands of on-line services
that were incapable of interaction with one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be a stupid thing to do by our measure,'' McCarthy
acknowledged. ``Breaking up the Internet would defeat the
purpose.'' But he added, `` `Stupid' doesn't mean it's not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn is relatively circumspect about such a trend. ``There's so
much in flux today that what you think is today's problem might
look like ancient history,'' he said. ``These are serious issues,
but you have to keep them in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   But for McCarthy, solving today's problem _ especially regarding
access providers and peering _ is crucial for tomorrow's Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm AT&AMP;T and you've got a little $20,000 network, why
should I allow you to use my network for free, rather than be my
customer?'' he said. ``But by allowing me to choose which role you
play, I can literally choose my competitors and create a role for
myself as a dominant player.''
</P>
<P>
   This rather remarkable ability could become a cause for alarm
if, as McCarthy asserts, all access providers, big and small, are
moving in the same strategic direction as Worldcom and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all trying to provide the complete digital pipe so you
can get all your services _ local telephone, long distance, Web
services, video, and any other data services you might need _ all
at once,'' he said. ``With that in mind, the industry had better
set down some rules about this, or the government will do it for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
