<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENQUIRER-COSBY-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYES ON THE ENQUIRER IN COSBY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Trial watchers here are saying People of the State
of California vs. Mikail Markhasev may not have come to pass were
it not for The National Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   In the prosecution of Markhasev, the man accused of killing Bill
Cosby's son, Ennis, there have been two critical pieces of
evidence: a .38-caliber Taurus revolver said to be the murder
weapon and a series of letters the prosecutors say the defendant
wrote after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Both were uncovered with the help of The Enquirer. It offered a
$100,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and
conviction of Ennis Cosby's killer, going beyond the media's
traditional role of announcing rewards offered by others to
actually becoming a direct player.
</P>
<P>
   The offer prompted a witness, Chris So, to lead police to the
Taurus revolver, found wrapped in a stocking cap that investigators
have tied to Markhasev by DNA testing of a hair. Copies of the jail
house letters, in which the prosecution says Markhasev describes
the Cosby killing as a robbery gone bad, were first sent to The
Enquirer; the paper notified the Los Angeles Police Department,
which obtained the originals from jail.
</P>
<P>
   The Enquirer's reward has posed troubling questions: Does it
undermine the credibility of the government witness by allowing the
defense to argue, as it has, that he was motivated by financial
gain? And does it encourage crime witnesses to hold out for the
biggest payday before cooperating with authorities? Those are
issues The Enquirer's editor in chief, Steve Coz, said he
considered before offering the reward as well as the publicity and
additional scoops it would generate.
</P>
<P>
   Coz said the reward was first suggested by Bill Cosby himself,
and The Enquirer posted it because of a cooperative relationship it
has had with the entertainer over the years. David Brokaw,
spokesman for the Cosby family, confirmed the relationship but said
relations soured after a subsequent story about Camille Cosby's
reaction to her son's death.
</P>
<P>
   Coz said police and prosecutors supported the reward. While
recognizing the potential inducement for embellishment, Coz said
that the police investigation backed up So's tip and that he did
not think the reward offer would have a longer-lasting negative
impact on the justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of have to look at justice as something that always
manages to rise to the top, through police work, through The
Enquirer,'' Coz said. ``Justice always seems to prevail in these
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the tabloid's sleuthing has earned the media any
appreciation from the courts or the prosecutors in the Cosby
matter. Judges have gone to extraordinary lengths to keep the press
at bay. Rather than following the usual practice of holding a
public preliminary hearing to determine whether Markhasev should be
bound over for trial, prosecutors presented the case to a grand
jury convened in private, and transcripts of the sessions were
ordered sealed. A gag order has been imposed on all lawyers and
parties in the case, and television and still cameras have been
banned in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   This is not The Enquirer's first time as a player in a
high-profile case. During the O.J. Simpson civil case, it obtained
photographs of Simpson wearing the same type of shoes that left
bloody tracks in the Brentwood condominium where his wife, Nicole
Brown Simpson, and her friend, Ronald Goldman, were killed.
(Simpson was acquitted of murder charges but found liable for
wrongful death in a civil case.)
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Loeb, editor of The Columbia Journalism Review, said he
generally opposes rewards. ``It gives a news organization an
investment in the story,'' he said, ``and it tempts the news
organization to give the story more play _ bigger splashier
headline, bigger splashier photos, bigger splashier stories _ than
they otherwise would.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Woods, a teacher of media ethics at the Poynter Institute
for Media Studies in St. Petersburg, Fla., said The Enquirer's
reward does not threaten the credibility of the news media because,
he added, the publication does not have credibility anyway. As long
as the practice does not spread to the mainstream media, it is not
a significant issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Laurie Levenson, a law professor at Loyola Law School who is
following the case, argues that The Enquirer's ability to break
these cases is actually enhancing its reputation. ``It's making
them a player in criminal cases,'' she said. ``They're able to
break criminal cases that no one else can; they're able to get
evidence that no one else can. You may not like them, but they get
the job done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 1744EDT &QL; 
