<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S VISIT TO CHINA TIES PROSPERITY TO PERSONAL FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: This Independence Day is particularly significant in
light of how President Clinton's historic trip to China has
re-emphasized the symbiosis of political freedom and economic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The ostensible reason for the president's China expedition was
to exert moral suasion to encourage a kinder and gentler approach
to governance and international relations. Clinton's strategic
approach, however, focused on the economic rewards China could
expect to reap by liberalizing the way it conducts its political
business.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Clinton never would have risked so much of his own
political capital by visiting China unless he was convinced that
overwhelming U.S. economic self-interest also was at stake. Thus,
the subliminal theme of the exercise seemed to be that political
and economic freedom go hand in hand and prosperity isn't possible
without personal liberty.
</P>
<P>
   This is the great universal truism of humankind's existence. The
best recent example of why the impoverishing nature of
authoritarian government cannot endure was the disintegration of
the former Soviet Union and its communist-style socialism. As
Soviet citizens came to learn how much better relatively free
people lived, it was only a matter of time until the system's
political center collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   As an essay in Investor's Business Daily pointed out recently,
the purpose of economic activity is to provide opportunities for
exchange in pursuit of material well-being. Such activity is by its
nature individualistic and its success depends on personal freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with authoritarian and totalitarian governments is
that they deprive individuals of the freedom to pursue their
self-interest by making spontaneous economic exchanges at will.
Instead, a relatively few powerful bureaucrats assume the power to
make generalized economic decisions for the many. Those decisions
always are made to serve the interests of the powerful few and
their power is the coin of the realm.
</P>
<P>
   The authoritarian can't abide economic freedom because it
invariably leads to political freedom. This is why impoverished
totalitarian regimes such as North Korea and Cuba must go to
excruciating lengths to keep outside reality from making itself
known.
</P>
<P>
   China's leaders seem to understand that such isolation is
possible only with small areas and populations and that Beijing
can't duplicate it without risking the same fate that befell the
Soviet Union. Thus, China's search now is for a middle ground that
will allow retention of as much authoritarian power as possible
while advancing economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   China's invitation to Clinton was a risk for its leaders, too,
but one they had to take. China can't prosper without expanding its
global economic options, and its leaders probably can't retain
power without achieving prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Nobel laureate Milton Friedman understands the interdependence
of political and economic freedom better than most economists.
Friedman and his wife, Rose, have just completed their memoirs, Two
Lucky People, in which they reaffirm their lifelong commitment to
``the promotion of human freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to predict how much the president's visit will
advance the cause of political and economic freedom in China. It
did make an important contribution, though, because it set the
stage for a new era in political and economic relations between the
two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
