<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Sunday,
July 5, 1998. If you have any questions, please call the Star's
News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ This Independence Day is particularly
significant in light of how President Clinton's historic trip to
China has re-emphasized the symbiosis of political freedom and
economic freedom. Economics column by JERRY HEASTER. Story will
move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WAR-POET (Undated) _ George Hamby went off to World War I,
serving in the same division as a first lieutenant named Harry
Truman. Fought at Verdun and in the Argonne, returned home, found
that his fiancee was dead of the flu. He became a steelworker and
outlived two wives. An unremarkable life, except for this: When he
died two years ago, this uneducated man left behind poetry written
from the trenches. Some of it sad. Some of it funny. By BARBARA
HOLLINGSWORTH. Will move in ``a'' category.
</P>
