</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-POET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE'S POETRY REVEALS EMOTIONS AND IMAGES OF WORLD WAR I 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HOLLINGSWORTH  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ The verse, scratched in pencil 80 years ago,
has faded, but the images that rise from the words are still fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Back with the teams, back to the rear,
</P>
<P>
   Driver and horse, not wanted here...
</P>
<P>
   Soon a shell bursts, two drivers reel,
</P>
<P>
   Two saddles bar, swing and wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Written amid the mud and mayhem of World War I, the words George
Hamby stored in a little green journal are a mix of the high-minded
patriotism of the day and the gripes of a 20-year private about
army life.
</P>
<P>
   Hamby didn't have a high school diploma, and some of his lines
don't rhyme, but he clearly had the heart of a poet. He filled page
after page of grid paper with the emotions and images of the
conflict around him.
</P>
<P>
   All that might have died with him two years ago, but his
companion, Bessie Hines, decided to show the journal to The Kansas
City Star. It might make a good Fourth of July item, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamby returned from France, she said, settled in Independence
and became a welder. There is no evidence that he ever wrote
another lyric in his life.
</P>
<P>
   His six long poems described the ``hell'' of war, the German
shells and fronts he fought on. He wrote proudly of his ``brave
comrades'' of E Battery, part of the 35th Division, the same
division in which a future president named Harry Truman served.
</P>
<P>
   A soldier's gripes also came through in the poetry _ too many
bugs and too little good food, such as when he complains about the
``belly rubbers convention.''
</P>
<P>
   It's composed of a mess sergeant and a cook or two,
</P>
<P>
   Who could stand a few lessons about making a stew,
</P>
<P>
   They draw butter and jam, which they put on the shelve,
</P>
<P>
   They don't put it out for they eat it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, soldiers commonly wrote letters or poetry, as
Hamby did, to reflect on the pains and more amusing points of Army
life, said Doran Cart, director and curator of the Liberty Memorial
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these fellows, especially the Americans, had never
left home before, and they were in France in the World War,'' Cart
said. ``They were seeking some way of expressing what they were
going through, what they were thinking and hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the other 27,500 soldiers from Missouri and Kansas
who went to France with the 35th Division, Hamby risked his life
before he had much of a chance to live it.
</P>
<P>
   At 19, he had said goodbye to family, friends and a fiancee and
joined up for the ``war to end all wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Slip of a boy, little but true,
</P>
<P>
   Trained half a year, fighting for you,
</P>
<P>
   Light as a twig, not twenty-one,
</P>
<P>
   But fitted to drive in the lead of the gun.
</P>
<P>
   He turned 20 a month before his first battle. In late September
1918, his division, as part of the American First Army, headed into
battle between the Meuse River and Argonne Forest in France. A
victory would take away the Germans' control of a railroad line on
which they received vital supplies.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the 26th,
</P>
<P>
   About four twenty-five,
</P>
<P>
   Hell broke loose up in the hills,
</P>
<P>
   Then they began the drive.
</P>
<P>
   For three long hours we shelled them,
</P>
<P>
   Without a single stop,
</P>
<P>
   Our dough boys awaited a given hour,
</P>
<P>
   And poured out over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamby later would talk about pushing the artillery pieces into
firing position, Hines said. He also recalled delivering messages
between outfits, including one trip when a shell killed the horse
he was riding but left him uninjured. Another time, he recounted:
</P>
<P>
   At two we were silently eating,
</P>
<P>
   Out there in the slimy mud,
</P>
<P>
   When the silence was suddenly broken,
</P>
<P>
   By the falling of a dud,
</P>
<P>
   For the benefit of the ignorant,
</P>
<P>
   I'll try and explain a bit,
</P>
<P>
   A dud is only a german shell,
</P>
<P>
   With the hell taken out of it.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, 1918, the 35th Division was relieved and placed in
reserve because of casualties of up to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The division re-entered the front line weeks later, not far from
the bloody fields of Verdun, ``on the front that was known to be
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Our next advance was the same as usual,
</P>
<P>
   We had them on the run,
</P>
<P>
   What else was there for them to do,
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees hell had come,
</P>
<P>
   On November the 10th it wasn't so bad,
</P>
<P>
   And not so good at that,
</P>
<P>
   But for every one the Huns sent over,
</P>
<P>
   We sent them eleven back.
</P>
<P>
   The next day was the Armistice.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming home to Independence, Hamby collected the names
and addresses of soldiers who lived in the Midwest, especially in
the Kansas City area. He listed them at the end of his journal.
</P>
<P>
   Hamby never married the girl he left when he went to war. She
died of influenza while he was away.
</P>
<P>
   A steelworker and welder for 35 years, he outlived two wives and
never had children. Hamby died in 1995 at age 97 and was buried
with a military funeral at Green Lawn Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Hines, his companion until his death, said Hamby would captivate
people, especially younger generations, with his stories of how he
shook hands with the Germans at the end of the war and how deep he
would sink into the shell-churned mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could really tell those tales.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines, 82, said Hamby came across his poems one day and gave
them to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was funny that he could sit in that foxhole and
write those poems about the war,'' she said. ``When I read it, I
said, `How could you write that sitting in a foxhole, men dying all
around you?' And he said, `Well, I did it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
