<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLSTAR-MCGWIRE-COX     07-05 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-MCGWIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All-Star derby features big bat of McGwire
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As Mark McGwire's traveling home-run show appears in
Denver tonight for the annual All-Star Game home run derby, the
burning baseball question is not if he will break Roger Maris'
single-season home run record of 61, but when.
</P>
<P>
   Late August, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, cautions Henry Aaron, who hit more homers than
anyone in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think if anybody has a chance to do it, he can,''
Aaron said. ``But the whole key will be going into that last month
well ahead of Maris' pace. If he's not six or so homers ahead of
the pace, I don't think he can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is two homers ahead of the pace, but Aaron thinks things
will get tougher for the St. Louis Cardinals' first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure and the teams he will be facing,'' Aaron
explained. ``If he is facing contending teams, they are not going
to pitch to him. And the television exposure. I know what it is
like, and it is worse now. It was very testy for Maris when he did
it. I remember my encounter. You get the same question over and
over again, and you get them from people who don't know anything
about the game. It's going to very interesting to see if he can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said he plans to relax and enjoy the All-Star
festivities, beginning with tonight's home run derby. He'll be
free-swinging at Coors Field, the homer-friendliest park in the big
leagues, and he'll be competing against some of the best home run
hitters in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best part of the All-Star Game,'' said McGwire, who
won the event in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   And the best part of the first half of the season certainly has
been McGwire. His 37 homers have traveled almost 15,392 feet (three
miles), an average of 416 feet a shot. He has filled ballparks in
both leagues, made pre-game batting practice a social gathering,
damaged scoreboards, hit balls through stadium doors, and hit three
homers in one game at Veterans Stadium in Philadelphia that
traveled a combined 1,362 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very fitting Godzilla is opening this week; I think it
opened a day early in Philly,'' said Philadelphia center fielder
Doug Glanville, who later complained of a sore neck.
</P>
<P>
   That is just one of many McGwire stories that have developed
during the first half of the season:
</P>
<P>
   _ THE SHOW: Opposing parks are opening their gates early to let
fans watch McGwire take batting practice. It has been routine for
25,000 fans to gather in St. Louis several hours before gametime.
NBC announcer Bob Costas took his son, Keith, to see batting
practice in St. Louis recently, and McGwire responded by hitting 22
of 25 pitches out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres drew 30,000 for McGwire's batting practice. Cardinals
catcher Tom Pagnozzi summed the moment: ``I saw something like this
on TV when I was a kid. I think they called themselves the
Beatles.''
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, the left-field bleachers were filled 90 minutes
before the game. McGwire hit four balls into the fourth deck of the
Astrodome, sending so many fans fighting for the balls that police
had to be called to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE PROMOTIONS: Despite being five games under .500 and 11 1/2
games out of first place, the Cardinals are averaging 37,971 a
game. If McGwire hits a home run into a certain section of the
upper deck in the left-field bleachers _ the McDonald's promotion
calls it ``Big Mac Land'' _ fans get free hamburgers. On a night
when attendance was 47,549, McGwire hit the spot, leaving McDonalds
facing the possibility of handing out $95,000 worth of free Big
Macs. On the day after the game, lines were 60 deep for hours at
the area stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, this was the most unbelievable ticket-stub
turn-in we ever had,'' said John McCook, owner of four St. Louis
franchises.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE FANS: When McGwire hit three home runs in a game against
Arizona on April 14, Debbie Durrwater crawled across the dugout to
give him a high five. ``They escorted me out promptly,'' she said.
``It was worth it, though. I have good karma with him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, 38,000 Royals fans stood to cheer when McGwire
walked to the plate. Kansas City and St. Louis are heated rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he does it,'' Cardinals second baseman Delino
Deshields said. ``He signs more than a thousand pieces of
memorabilia a day. Fans come to see him take batting practice. And
they sometimes boo if he doesn't hit a home run. I don't know if I
would like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Cincinnati, more than 50,000 fans, double the Reds'
average attendance, came to see McGwire. Flashbulbs went off every
time he walked to the plate. Fans booed when he was walked twice
and hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE COVERAGE: One radio station in Houston broadcasted a live
account of McGwire's batting practice, in which he hit nine homers.
``Ridiculous,'' he said. ``I felt like a caged lion and didn't like
it.'' McGwire then considered not taking batting practice for the
rest of the season. He reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   But the stress level is increasing. After McGwire hit No. 32 in
another Cardinals' loss, he was repeatedly asked about the home
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just lost a game, so why talk about a home run?'' McGwire
asked. ``Why is hitting a home run important to the American
public?''
</P>
<P>
   _ THE FEARS: Third base coach Rene Lachemann said he's not
trying to make a spectacle of himself by leaving the coaching box
and standing down the left-field line during McGwire's at-bats.
``I'm trying to save my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE DAMAGE:
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit a massive home run against the Twins that almost
scraped the Metrodome roof. ``It was up there so long my neck
started to hurt,'' Twins manager Tom Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   On May 16 at Busch, McGwire hit a ball 545 feet to center field
that put a dent in the St. Louis Post-Dispatch sign. Two days
later, a 4 1/2-foot Band-Aid covered the spot. He also hit one off
the concrete facade above the Stadium Club in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people up there in that Stadium Club were ducking,''
Marlins coach Rich Donnelly said. ``If that ball had hit the
window, it would have knocked a few turkey-clubs across the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Donnelly best sums the McGwire phenomena by issuing a
warning for Denver-based aviation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With certain teams, those air-traffic controllers ought to be
on alert right now,'' Donnelly said. ``Bring in that 747 _ and here
comes a McGwire on Runway No. 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Mac lands in Denver tonight. But his homers . . . well, they
may land in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
