<HEADER>
A1010 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-PRIVATEPRISONS-COX     07-05 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-PRIVATEPRISONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Corrections department look to corporate sector for helpBy
Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia prison system is moving into uncharted
waters with the addition of three privately-run prisons, an
operation that other states have found troubling.
</P>
<P>
   But the Georgia Department of Corrections has no reservations
about its new venture that starts in mid August with a 750-bed
prison on the edge of the Okefenokee Swamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to overreact,'' said Mike Murdock, who is
overseeing the project for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Several states that have hired corporate America to house their
criminals have had some problems, some of them dangerous _ but that
doesn't bother officials at the Georgia Department of Corrections.
Georgia is convinced it has all bases covered.
</P>
<P>
   With one false start behind it after one company won a bid last
year and then withdrew, Georgia signed contracts with two companies
to build and operate three private prisons in South Georgia _ one
with Cornell Corrections Corp. for a prison in Charlton County,
Ga., near the Okefenokee, and the other with Corrections Corp. of
American for prisons in South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of communities, especially those that are economically
depressed, have been sold a bill of goods that's not accurate,''
said Rebecca Feaster of the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees, which has opposed private prisons in
several states.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very enticing situation but people need to be aware
they aren't going to get the cost savings and they will be stuck
with a lot of bills,'' Feaster said. ``The prisoners that are
brought in are a lot more dangerous and the jobs they (local
residents) are getting are lower paying and there is a huge
turnover. These jobs do not provide the long term stability these
communities want.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Georgia officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The first guards hired by Cornell of Houston, Texas has been
completed and a second has started for guards who will work at the
750-bed medium-security Charlton prison near the Okefenokee.
</P>
<P>
   By mid August, the first group of 50 inmates will arrive at
Charlton, Georgia's first for adult inmates imprisoned by a
for-profit company.
</P>
<P>
   And possibly by the end of November, Memphis-based Corrections
Corp. of America will open the two private prisons in Coffee and
Wheeler counties, both also designed to hold 750 medium-security
Georgia inmates. Like Cornell, CCA plans to expand the prisons next
spring , adding ``speculative'' beds, to hold 1,600 inmates each,
hoping that Georgia or some other state with crushing prison
populations will be eager to pay the company to take care of their
criminals in the additional 2,550 beds .
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is final but we have been in discussions with Georgia
correctional officials'' about using all 1,600 beds in each prison,
said CCA Vice President Susan Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell Executive Vice President Steven Logan said his company
has not yet talked to Georgia prison officials about using the
additional beds, but ``we feel comfortable'' that the state will
need the additional prison beds.
</P>
<P>
   Murdock said the two companies would house out-of-state inmates
in those additional cells if Georgia cannot use them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no reason for trepidation'' aboout the private
facilities, Murdock said. But he admits ``it should be at least a
year before we know if it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   And once the three prisons are completed, with a total of 1,600
prison beds each, they will be larger than any state-run prison.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Corrections Commissioner Wayne Garner believes the
savings will be significant.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia taxpayers will pay Cornell between $37.09 and $45.13 per
inmate per day, or almost $116.2 million over the next decade and
possibly another $101 million if the state uses the additional
beds.
</P>
<P>
   CCA, which signed two separate contracts after the Charlton
County agreement was sealed, will get more per inmates than
Cornell. The charge for inmates at both prisons will be between
$44.95 and $48.10 per inmate per day for 20 years, or more than
$363.500 million from the 20-year contract and another $556.6
million if the additional 750 prison beds are used.
</P>
<P>
   Correction officials calculate the average cost for each inmate
in a state prison is $54.14, which includes the cost of
construction and interest on the debt. That daily cost also is an
average that takes into account the high cost of the medical prison
and housing high security inmates in less-expensive institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell and CCA are supposed to cover the cost of inmates'
medical expenses, clothing, food and education and substance abuse
programs under the private program.
</P>
<P>
   The prisons must supply a certain number of guards and they must
offer education and treatment programs and work every inmate eight
hours a day, five days a week, something the state has been unable
to do because there are not enough jobs for all the state's
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Though Georgia has never had any private adult prisons, the
state has had some experience with privatizing its prisons for
juveniles and with the company that will operate the adult private
prison in Charlton County. Cornell was hired to run a 120-bed
facility in Pelham for juvenile girl, but Georgia canceled the
contract two months later because the Houston company could not
staff the facility at the level the state wanted at the price the
company was charging.
</P>
<P>
   DOC says state monitors - two former warden - will prevent such
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies have encountered problems in other states
where Cornell runs 42 private private prisons and CCA operates 77.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   Two sex offenders from Oregon incarcerated in Texas escaped from
the CCA Houston Processing Center which was built for undocumented
immigrants about to be deported. Texas authorities could not arrest
the fugitives, however, because at the time there was no state law
making it a crime to escape from a private prison.
</P>
<P>
   Such a dilemma is not unusual, Feaster said. ``Only 27 states
have private prisons and not all those states have legislation on
the books that covers everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia law allows local law enforcement to arrest any inmates
who escape from one of the private prisons in this state, however.
</P>
<P>
   Out of a CCA facility in Youngstown, Ohio, several months ago
came numerous reports of stabbings and excessive force and staff
charges of discrimination, harassment and poor working conditions.
It was only then that Youngstown learned that the inmates from
Washington, D.C. that were sent to the 2,000-bed medium-security
prison were much more dangerous than they were led to believe.
Also, CCA initially refused to let the local sheriff in the
facility to investigate the stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   Murdock said the state's agreement with both companies dictates
that state corrections and law enforcement officers can come inside
at any time, and both companies will be accountable to the state
and the communities where they are located.
</P>
<P>
   Feaster of the government employees union said that has not been
the case in other states and she questioned whether the three
private prisons in Georgia would be more open since they had not
started operating. She pointed out, however, that since both
companies are publicly-traded their first responsibilities are to
their stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be aware these people are in for a profit,'' Feaster
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
