<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heat will build over the central and southern Plains as high
pressure at 20,000 feet expands over the region. The high pressure
aloft marks a region of unusual warmth at high levels which will
limit afternoon thunderstorms over much of the region. Afternoon
highs between 95 and 105 degrees will be common. But moisture from
a dissipating tropical disturbance will bring slow-moving downpours
to parts of central and western Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt across western parts of the
Northern Plains near a front separating the very hot air to the
south from somewhat cooler conditions over southern Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A volatile combination of a vigorous jet-stream disturbance and
increasing humidity will bring the risk of large thunderstorms with
damaging winds, hail, and a few tornadoes during the afternoon and
evening. The cluster of thunderstorms will drift into the upper
Mississippi Valley overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will be partly to mostly sunny with comfortable
humidity as high pressure moves across New England. Active
afternoon sea breezes will keep coastal areas several degrees
cooler than the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry weather will linger over the Southeast. Afternoon thunder
will occur near a front in the Carolinas and southern Appalachians.
While scattered thunderstorms will occur near the fire-plagued
areas of northern Florida, no persistent rain is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the West will be warm with afternoon thunder
scattered through the Rockies and Southwest. Clouds will linger
much of the day near the Washington coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The First Bolts
</P>
<P>
   All lightning is dangerous, but the first strokes in a storm may
be the most powerful of all. Lightning results when a difference in
electric charge in the atmosphere overcomes the resistance of the
air. Most thunderstorms have positive charges near the top and
negative charges at the bottom. Strong high-level winds can cause
the thunderstorm to tilt, with the positive charges drifting to the
front of the storm. As a result, the first strokes tend to lower
positive charges to the ground. Measurement of electric currents
shows that these positive bolts can be twice as strong as negative
lightning.
</P>
</TEXT>
