<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1024 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON-G     07-05 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON-GIANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER'S GAMESMANSHIP, OREL WERE RIGHT ON TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM KEOWN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intrigue and espionage hit the Giants-Dodgers rivalry Friday
night, as if it needed the boost. There was already a sellout crowd
and a January-in-Bismarck bite in the air. Longtime fan favorite
Orel Hershiser was ready to take the mound against his old team, so
why not throw in a healthy undercurrent of bad blood to thicken the
plot?
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Baker had inside information _ his ``Dodger sources'' he
said _ that Barry Bonds was going to be sent a message, most likely
in the form of a fastball to the ribs. The Dodgers were going to
retaliate against Bonds for his post-homer flamboyance (two
pirouettes, for those of you judging at home) in the memorable
series between the two teams last September.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's news traveled via reporters, from Baker to Bonds to
Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman. It traveled in accordance with a law
of nature, like birds bringing food back to the nest. Bonds
expressed disdain with Baker, the Dodgers professed total ignorance
and Baker just smiled and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   The motives will be misinterpreted in any number of convoluted
ways, but Baker's mission was accomplished. Frankly, the guess here
is he doesn't care much about Bonds' reaction, even if it did
include an invitation for Baker to kiss Bonds' rear. If this is a
``feud'' it's a one-way feud. Baker was unbothered by any of it.
</P>
<P>
   What the manager was doing was protecting his best player, and
he didn't arrive at his method of communication randomly. Granted,
this was out of character for him; he doesn't normally confide
sensitive information like that to a semicircle of reporters.
That's what made it seem as if he would break into a smile and let
loose with a hearty laugh at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   But think about what he accomplished: Whether his information
was correct or not, his pre-emptive strike _ delivered via reporter
_ let the Dodgers know he wouldn't take any of it. If Bonds didn't
understand the method, he can at least be thankful for it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, just because the freeway is closed doesn't mean you
can't get to where you want to go. Sometimes you have to use the
gravelly backroads of your imagination.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hershiser didn't disappoint anybody. In a
thoroughly professional manner, he crafted a game in the Catfish
Hunter style. He allowed a couple of solo homers but wisely grouped
them around a whole lot of outs. He weaved in and out of trouble,
never appearing to have complete control.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, this is exactly the kind of pitcher he is right
now. He's 40 years old, and he survived seven innings on a
hypercharged _ and damned cold _ night. He even managed to get
through perhaps the worst at bat known to man, his sixth-inning
strikeout that consisted of two thrown bats sandwiched around an
awkward bunt attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't need to keep myself down before the game,'' he said.
``I haven't been on a winning streak, so all the energy I could get
I was willing to accept. If I felt anything extra, I wanted to keep
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Hershiser's appeal is his refusal to buy into the party
line. He didn't pretend this was just another game, and he showed
that when he hugged J.T. Snow on the bench after Snow's three-run
homer in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't usually hug on the bench, but that was pretty big for
me,'' Hershiser said. ``I wouldn't have wanted to stand here
talking about a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow's season is starting to take on a strong resemblance to the
one he put together last year. It starts chaotically. Tangential
events crowd the center of the stage. The batting average dips into
the land of the backup shortstop, and then ... presto, he becomes a
different guy.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Snow singled, hit a three-run homer and doubled.
The homer put the Giants up 4-2 and, perhaps more importantly,
allowed Hershiser to take a deep breath for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Cepeda stopped Snow in the clubhouse before the game and
remarked on the recent streak that has elevated Snow's average to
.235. Snow shrugged and said, more than once, that it's a matter of
him seeing the ball better than before.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a cliche, but that doesn't mean it isn't true.
Sometimes the simplest explanations just happen to be the best
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Snow's final at bat produced an off-field bloop double that
dropped in exactly one micron fair. What that ball fell in, no
further proof was needed: Snow is living right.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the Giants as a whole. Except for a
couple of hold-your-breath injuries Friday night _ Bill Mueller and
Rich Aurilia _ they look ready to hold their ground until the
All-Star break comes and Jeff Kent returns.
</P>
<P>
   They might even be able to take the Dodgers completely out of
the picture, although Baker's response, especially in light of the
night's events, was telling: ``We're not looking behind us,'' he
said. ``We're looking ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
