<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-05 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     BALDWINS TO THROW BASH FOR CLINTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Alec Baldwin  &LR; and  &UR; Kim Basinger  &LR; are throwing a ``summer lawn
party'' fund-raiser for  &UR; Bill Clinton  &LR; at their home in the
Hamptons on August 1. Tickets will cost from $250 to $1,000 -- do
guests in the low-price range have to stand on crabgrass or
downwind from the barbecue? -- reports the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these plans, Baldwin, who said last year he had his eye
on a Senate race, told USA Today this week that nothing about
politics ``has any decency or honor anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   And Basinger seems less than enthusiastic about joining the
political fray. ``Up until now,'' she said in a recent interview,
``when we'd get into those long discussions about politics, I would
run to my bathroom, put on my favorite CD and turn it up as loud as
I could.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - In London,  &UR; Madonna &LR; 's been shooting a rock video wherein she
walks out of Claridges Hotel and into a pack of paparazzi, in much
the manner of  &UR; Princess Diana &LR;  on the night she died.  &UR; Mohamed &LR; 
 &UR; Al Fayed &LR; , father of Di's late boyfriend,  &UR; Dodi &LR; , told The Mirror
that he thinks the hotel scenes are ``tasteless.''
</P>
<P>
   - The question ``What do spies eat?'' is answered fully (Chicken
and Ham Salad Veronique; Lemon Champagne Punch) in a new book,
``Spies, Black Ties &AMP; Mango Pieces: Stories and Recipes from CIA
Families All Over the World'' (Community Communications; $19.95).
 &UR; Karola Craib &LR;  is looking forward to the Ames Antipasti.
</P>
<P>
   - Petaluma artist  &UR; Pele de Lappe &LR;  was murky on the details, but
knew that her father had been married once before, to
screenwriter &UR; Frances Marion &LR; , before he married her mother.
Browsing in the bookstore at the Pacific Film Archive's just-over
film series on women screenwriters, de Lappe found ``Without Lying
Down _  &UR; Frances Marion &LR;  and the Powerful Women of Early
Hollywood,'' which included seven full pages on the marriage. The
detail that grabbed her most was the image of the couple, holding
hands on a San Francisco park bench, when the earthquake struck on
April 18, 1906.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; GAME PLANS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - At the Marin County Fair over the weekend,  &UR; Richard O'Lone &LR; 
saw a woman riding the Ferris Wheel with two boys, all the while
speaking on a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   - You're sitting there at the breakfast table, and you haven't
said anything to your spouse or children since, ``Who has the
sports section?''  &UR; Gary Krane &LR; 's new book, ``Simple Fun for Busy
People'' (Conari; $12.95) purports to provide 333 free ways ``to
enjoy your loved ones more in the time you have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Undercover Penny,'' a game for two, employs one penny and
a bed. ``One person throws a penny under the covers. Both scramble
to find the penny, hopefully without bumping heads. The one who
finds the penny and picks it up wins.''
</P>
<P>
   A few caveats: ``Be sure not to have any furniture, sharp or
hard objects, or fragile items near the bed that you could possibly
hit with your head or foot. Be sure to keep your head far enough
away from the other person's knees and feat. Or to be 99 percent
safe, wear a helmet with a face guard.'' Furthermore, ``Be sure you
don't have a bad back or any other serious bone, muscular or
internal problem. ... Shower beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps you'd rather play ``Office Kidnapping'': ``Hide an
office item belonging to a co-worker, such as a stapler, and leave
an obvious ransom note.'' Here again, a helmet might be required.
</P>
<P>
   - Pursuant to tips that appeared recently for extricating
oneself from conversation, No Flak Press has forwarded one of its
``Get Out of Conversation Free'' cards, entitling the bearer to
abruptly terminate ``any conversation you find degrading,
embarrassing, tiresome, pointless or just plain boring. No apology
or explanation necessary.'' No Flak, which is at 6114 LaSalle
Avenue, Oakland 94611, is selling these for $2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Have you crossed the `ma'am' threshold yet? ... Trouble &LR; 
 &UR; is, I've outgrown `miss.' Most of us have. Clearly, we need a &LR; 
 &UR; new term, something analogous to the classic `sir,' which &LR; 
 &UR; refuses to distinguished between men on the basis of marital &LR; 
 &UR; status or age. But what? `Ms.' sounds too much like an annoying &LR; 
 &UR; insect. `Woman' reduces us to gender only. ... Perhaps we &LR; 
 &UR; should go back to the elegant `Madam,' as in Madam President. &LR; 
 &UR; That's a term we'll need to use soon enough; might as well start &LR; 
 &UR; practicing on each other.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Kathy Witkowsky &LR;  in Glamour magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
