<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Silicon Valley Trade Group to Help Out With Commute Woes   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Here's a liberating thought for this holiday weekend. The Silicon
Valley Manufacturing Group is doing a survey that eventually could
help ease traffic in the South Bay.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The SVMG is trying to find out where people who work in Santa
Clara County live. To get this data without snooping, the group has
asked its 130 member firms to provide it with the home ZIP codes of
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The SVMG expects to compile this ZIP code info by the end of
July and turn it over to the Valley Transportation Authority, which
sets mass transit policy for Santa Clara County.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Authority will create two maps: one showing
where workers live, and the other displaying mass transit routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see if there are huge commute corridors that are
unserved by mass transit, and if so, whether we can make changes,''
said Leslee Coleman, vice president of the Manufacturing Group.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy of the survey will depend on getting as much ZIP
code data as possible.
</P>
<P>
   SVMG's member firms _ which include Intel, National
Semiconductor and Sun Microsystems _ employ 250,000 people or about
one-third of the private-sector workforce in Santa Clara County,
Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the members have already supplied their employees'
ZIPs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Santa Clara County employers who  &LR; aren't &LR;  part of the
Manufacturing Group can still take part in the survey by visiting
the Web site ( &LR; www.svmg.org &LR; ). Click on the line that says:
``Commute Service Survey Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Food for thought: &LR;  Americans take freedom for granted. But on
this day of barbecues and fireworks, take a minute to think about
those who brave imprisonment or death for their beliefs. All you
have to do is visit the Amnesty International Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Amnesty site,  &LR; rights.amnesty.org &LR; , was just named one of
the 50 best pages on the Web by CIO Magazine, a trade publication
aimed at the people who run corporate information systems.
</P>
<P>
   The site was created in part by Icon Medialab and Circumstance,
two Web design firms in San Francisco, with assistance from the
Digital Artists and Writer's Group in Mill Valley.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Mother lode? &LR;  Last month I wrote about venture capitalist
George Zachary, who flew to Sweden to advise that country on how to
rev up its economy, lest its young flee for greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I heard from Swedes who've already followed the lure
of high-tech riches to the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a new gold rush,'' said Svante Rodegard, a Swedish
emigre in San Francisco. ``This time it's not gold in the streets
that draws us, but the lure of IPOs in Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact there are so many Swedes on the local high-tech scene
that they've formed a group, the Silicon Vikings, which gets
together monthly. (For details e-mail  &LR; hlindh &LR; lwi.xerox.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Rodegard said Swedes back home enjoy a great standard of living.
Even so, many of them are caught up in the ``romantic dream'' of
instant riches that seems to pervade news coverage of the American
economy.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of Sweden's wanderlust, Rodegard cites the
popularity of a rock musical produced by members of the pop group
Abba. The musical tells of the time between 1880 and 1920 when a
quarter of the Swedish population went abroad _ many to America _
to escape starvation and religious feuds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This show has been sold out for over three years, as I see it
because of (this) romantic idea and view of America,'' Rodegard
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Laughing matter: &LR;  Stand-up comic Dan St. Paul knows how people
can tell if their high-tech friends used to be cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Clue number one: ``When you say `Draw!' he pulls out his Palm
Pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul will be gunning for laughs when he performs as the
warm-up act for country singer Vince Gill at the Mountain Winery in
Saratoga next Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Math 101: &LR;  Steven Kishi, marketing manager at Extensity,
recently gave me this business plan tip. Extensity is an Emeryville
startup that sells programs for controlling business expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magic numbers for a startup are one, eight, 15, 30,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Put a dollar sign in front of each number, and six zeroes
behind, and those are the figures an investor wants to see in a
startup's revenue projection for its first four years.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Whodunit? &LR;  Walt Shugert routinely downloads closing stock
prices using a portfolio-tracking service on Excite. So he was
momentarily stunned when an unexplained glitch erroneously showed
that his AT&AMP;T shares plunged 99 percent _ overnight!
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``That was a one-time aberration,'' Shugert said. ``But
imagine (if some) old geezer with a bad heart saw that. Someone
could write a murder mystery ...`I found gramps slumped over his
computer, clutching his mouse.'''
</P>
<P>
   Excite spokeswoman Melissa Walia said she's never received
any &UR;  &LR; complaints about the stock-tracking service. (Of course dead
geezers tell no tales!)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at
sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
