<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR QUITS VIAGRA-SELLING WEB SITE AS REGULATORS CLOSE IN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Colorado doctor said Thursday that he has
resigned as medical director of a controversial Web site that sells
Viagra and other drugs without prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The physician, Dr. Benjamin T. Johnson, said the furor over the
Internet sales of Viagra _ the wildly popular new impotence drug _
``could cost me my career.''
</P>
<P>
   An article in Thursday's Chronicle raised ethical and legal
questions about the Web site, which is operated by a company called
Performance Drugs Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, noting that regulators are scrutinizing the Web site,
said that it ``will probably not be open'' anymore as of Friday.
The site appeared to still be operating Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he agreed to get involved in the Web site after being
advised that there was nothing illegal about the online pharmacy's
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going under some initial legal advice about the
statutes regarding telemedicine and the fact that there have been a
number of sites practicing medicine over the Internet for over a
year now,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our understanding that there was nothing illegal about
this practice. Before putting significant thought into it, I felt
like issuing Viagra this way was not that big of a deal. But
obviously the majority of physicians think it was significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulators in California and Denver, responding in part to
questions raised by The Chronicle article, said they are exchanging
information and gathering documents about Internet drug dispensing.
</P>
<P>
   At least two sites are being examined, according to a
spokeswoman at the California Medical Board in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's report about easy access to Viagra comes against
a background of increasing concern about the potential dangers of
the popular impotence pill manufactured by Pfizer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, D.C., noted consumer advocate Sidney Wolfe
accused Pfizer and the Food and Drug Administration of downplaying
the drug's side effects. He issued a report this week about
potentially deadly interactions between Viagra and other medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge numbers of people are taking this drug who should not be
taking it,'' Wolfe said Thursday. ``Whether Pfizer is responsible
directly or not, if they are aware of illicit traffic they should
do something about it. It's not that difficult to figure out where
it's coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions raised by The Chronicle, a Pfizer
spokeswoman said the company already has been ``closely
monitoring'' the Internet along with other venues where people may
be selling Viagra without adequate physician oversight.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials defended their decision to allow sales of the
drug, saying that precautions are already in place. Questions about
specific prescribing practices generally fall outside the FDA's
purview, a spokeswoman said, although the agency attempts to track
improper drug claims on the Internet and in other media.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's story disclosed how a Chronicle reporter was able to
easily obtain 10 tablets of Viagra, plus 10 doses of a purported
``female erectile cream'' containing a prescription asthma drug,
through the mail by filling out a brief form on the Performance
Drugs Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The address of the Web site is performancedrugs.com.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the site contained a new advisory indicating that all
customers would be contacted by a physician before orders are
filled. The site's online ``medical history'' questionnaire already
had been revamped, with several additional questions added, since
The Chronicle placed its order two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left at Performance Drugs' Seattle call center were not
returned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Johnson, who had signed The Chronicle's drug
prescription order, were unsuccessful until after the story
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson finally came to the phone Thursday, describing a career
in a virtual shambles as lawyers and other physicians heaped
condemnations on him.
</P>
<P>
   He said he quit a few days after the reporter's order was
processed because he started to suspect that his role in the Web
project had been a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said there are ``probably at least 20 sites'' on the
Internet offering essentially the same service as those provided by
Performance Drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, physicians renewed their warnings against taking
Viagra without a doctor's advice. Dr. Charlotte Yeh, physician in
chief of the emergency department at New England Medical Center in
Boston, said emergency rooms are running a major new risk of
administering nitrate drugs to heart-attack patients taking Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   The nitrates are known to interact with Viagra in a way that can
lead to fatal reductions in blood pressure. Yeh endorsed a new call
by the nonprofit organization Medicalert to issue special medical
tags for Viagra takers so that doctors can avoid giving
nitroglycerine.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, Johnson said another doctor who had
been running a clinic in San Francisco that Johnson owns quit in
response to Thursday's article.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left on the answering machine of the San Francisco
clinic, called the Body Enhancement Center, were not returned
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson declined to identify the doctor, and he said the San
Francisco operation was not connected to the controversy over the
Performance Drugs Web site.
</P>
</TEXT>
