<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ATHLETICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY NANCY GAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
A's Light Fireworks on Padres  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ That much-anticipated fireworks show at the
Coliseum got off to a quick start last night, courtesy of San Diego
pitcher Sterling Hitchcock. The Padres left-hander, only one outing
removed from his no-hit bid, dished up a sixth-inning, belt-high
fastball that was so enticing, it would have been absolutely
criminal not to knock the stuffing out of it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And justice would have it that a guy in the throes of a hitting
slump, A's shortstop Miguel Tejada, would do the honors. With two
out and runners on first and second, Tejada put the brakes on his
2-for-21 skid and crushed Hitchcock's mistake over the outfield
wall in right for his second home run of the year. Coliseum
officials sent a few rockets into the foggy evening to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   But the home team was not done yet.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Mitchell drove in a run and scored another in the seventh,
and the A's won the three-game interleague series with an
impressive 7-2 victory that juiced up the packed house of 40,374,
the second-largest crowd at the Coliseum this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pitch,'' said Tejada, who last homered June 15.
``It felt good to hit one like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty to cheer _ the A's finally won on a scheduled
fireworks night (the first time since 1996), and A's left-hander
Kenny Rogers pitched his second complete game to raise his record
to 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could feel it in our dugout, the way Kenny was throwing the
ball, that the game was over at that point,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers would not go that far. ``I never feel like the game is
over; I've been humbled too many times to feel that way,'' he said,
``but I had an idea how I wanted to go after each hitter, got some
double-play balls when I needed them at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I got some room to breathe, yeah, it was real nice.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the kind of ball the A's have been promising all along,
the timely two-out hits, solid defense and efficient pitching that
front-runners such as the Padres regularly employ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I've said, when we put things together, we can play with
anybody,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the A's took their cue from San Diego. They
pounded out 30 hits in the series, 10 Thursday night, and gave
themselves a nice boost heading into a tough series at Anaheim, the
final three games before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   How's this for timing _ the A's have dropped 14 of their past 15
games against the Angels. Now they are on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any series (win) is a big lift for us, at this point,'' said
third baseman Mike Blowers, who was 2-for-4 with a pair of singles
and scored off Tejada's three-run blast. ``When you play a club
that's young and down in the standings, a lot of guys get pretty
fired up to play a series like this. I think that was the case for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego jumped to a 2-0 lead in the second when catcher Jim
Leyritz hit Roger's first-pitch fastball over the wall in center
field.
</P>
<P>
   But Rickey Henderson put the A's on the board in the bottom of
the inning, driving in his 36th run and stealing his 36th base.
Catcher A.J. Hinch hit a two-out single and scrambled to second on
a wild pitch, and Henderson lifted his RBI line-drive single over
the head of shortstop Chris Gomez. He went on to swipe second.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Stairs' seventh-inning line drive single drove in Mitchell,
and he celebrated by making an appearance at first base in the
ninth inning. It was the first time Stairs played first base since
he injured his left shoulder April 21 in a collision with the
Twins' Paul Molitor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
