<HEADER>
A1033 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GIANTS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-05 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY HENRY SCHULMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
Snow Blasts Angels  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Interleague play is over, but the Giants plan
to hide this information from first baseman J.T. Snow. They will
tell him that those guys visiting 3Com Park tonight in the ``LA''
caps are from another league. Why not? Events of the past several
weeks suggest they are from another planet.
</P>
<P>
   Snow claimed the title of Interleague King last season when he
hit .379 with 20 RBIs and a majors-best 10 homers in 16 games, and
he fairly defended it this year by hitting .366 with five homers
and 14 RBIs in 13 interleague games.
</P>
<P>
   He finished the 1998 AL-NL series loudly last night with two
homers, a double and four RBIs in the Giants' 7-4 victory over the
Anaheim Angels, their fourth win in six games, which moved them
within 41/2 games of first-place San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Snow now has 42 RBIs, third-best on the team behind Barry Bonds
(59), who missed the game with an illness, and Jeff Kent (49), who
has not played since June 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels traded Snow to the Giants two winters ago, and he has
punished them in interleague play ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good. I won't lie about that. Anytime you play well
when you're going up against your former team you want to do well.
I'm no different,'' said Snow, who has been asked a gazillion times
why he does so well against the American League. His answer is
always the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coincidence, I guess. I can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow's desire to throttle the Angels grew in the seventh inning
when they finally retired him on a line drive to right. During the
at-bat, pitcher Pep Harris was shaking off a lot of signs, and Snow
stepped out of the box a few times. Angels coach Larry Bowa started
hollering at Snow to get back in, and that ticked him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was coming from the area where the coaches stand. I didn't
think it was very professional, especially coming from a coach,''
Snow said.
</P>
<P>
   It was already a 7-1 game by then. Snow had hit a two-run homer
in a three-run first inning, an RBI double in the third and another
homer leading off the sixth, all off starter Jason Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   Snow's hitting helped the Giants finish their interleague
schedule at 8-5 _ they were 10-6 last year _ and now they train
their guns on the Los Angeles Dodgers, who are 6-4 under new
manager Glenn Hoffman after a sweep of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants won their 50th game of the season without Kent or
Bonds, who was down with a bout of gastroenteritis, perhaps brought
on by a bad piece of chicken from the night before. He was
dehydrated and had to take intravenous fluids at a nearby hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Dusty Baker had a hot hitter to replace Bonds in the
third spot. Stan Javier brought a six-game hitting streak and a
.537 average over his last 13 games into the contest, and he
quickly fattened the numbers further.
</P>
<P>
   After Dickson walked Bill Mueller with one out in the first
inning, Javier smashed a run-scoring double to the wall in
right-center. Charlie Hayes grounded out, but Snow then hit a
two-run homer. Javier had two of the Giants' 10 hits, as did Rey
Sanchez, who had a two-run single in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   All that offense helped Kirk Rueter (10-3) become the league's
fifth 10-game winner. Rueter was in damage-control mode all night
as he allowed nine hits. But the Angels mustered just one run in
his 51/3 innings, Darin Erstad's homer leading off the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rueter seemed inclined to give the whole 3-0 lead back right
there when he allowed singles to Dave Hollins and Jim Edmonds after
the home run. Baker then emerged for a very long chat with his
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a 20-second timeout, just to take the wind out of
the ball,'' Baker said. ``Most of the time things happen real
quickly. I just wanted a break in the action to let him get his
composure.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's timeout did the trick. Tim Salmon flied out, Cecil
Fielder struck out on an inside fastball at the knees, and Garret
Anderson popped out to short left.
</P>
<P>
   Baker finally removed Rueter amid another Angels rally in the
sixth, and Julian Tavarez came to the rescue by getting an
inning-ending double-play ball from hot-hitting rookie Justin
Baughman.
</P>
<P>
   A three-run Hollins homer off Rich Rodriguez in the ninth made
the score closer than the game really was.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
