A1034 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENKS-JENKINS-SFCHRON     07-05 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKS-JENKINS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
   Grass Is Greener on Novotna's Side 
 
 By BRUCE JENKINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Jana Novotna can't lose it now. Absolutely
out of the question. The loud, lingering applause of Centre Court
Thursday told Novotna that the tournament is hers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no one left in her way, unless you count Nathalie
Tauziat, and only Tauziat is counting. These are two fine
grass-court players, but Tauziat's game is 1965 to Novotna's
cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   Just as importantly, it appears that nerves are no longer an
issue.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Tauziat is a steely, hardened competitor. She took
the unpopular route in her native France by severing ties with the
national federation, she humbled world No.2 Lindsay Davenport in
the quarterfinals here, and she shook off a terrible first set
Thursday to beat Natasha Zvereva 1-6, 7-6 (7-1), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   But Novotna, on the eve of Saturday's final, is suddenly
everyone's darling. That would include her friend and doubles
partner, No.1 seed Martina Hingis, who managed many smiles after
losing to Novotna 6-4, 6-4. ``Jana deserves this,'' said Hingis.
``She's just the better player. She's a great champion.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Novotna is not a champion of anything. Just months
from her 30th birthday, she never has won a Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   But to everyone around the All England Club Thursday, Novotna
had the champion's look. She has reached the finals twice before _
the horrendous collapse against Steffi Graf in '93 and a three-set
loss to Hingis last year. Saturday, there can be no choking.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is . . . one shudders at the prospect. A loss
tomorrow and Novotna makes the Buffalo Bills look like
Montana-to-Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with Zvereva in a zone, the same one that carried
her so effortlessly through the draw, and she made child's play of
the first set.
</P>
<P>
   After the laser-beam rockets of Steffi Graf and Monica Seles,
Tauziat's shots must have looked like moonballs to Zvereva. Tauziat
stumbled and shrieked and looked so outclassed, you wondered why
they didn't call the whole thing off.
</P>
<P>
   But Tauziat has spent a lifetime fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   She was born and spent some of her formative years in Africa,
honing her strokes in a highly unlikely setting. When she moved to
France and chose a controversial, outspoken coach, Regis de
Camaret, she lost the support of the French federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he speaks, he says what he thinks, and sometimes it's not
nice to listen to,'' Tauziat said. ``With that I was put out of the
(system). For many years I have played for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva is no stranger to rebellion, having pioneered the
Russian players' fight to keep their prize money in the late '80s
and early '90s, but this was an unfamiliar stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in this situation before,'' she said. ``I
think about people like Steffi and Monica doing it over and over,
just incredible, and for me just once was really draining. I'm so
tired. I think I need a mental institution break (laughter).''
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva might have the best hands in women's tennis, as Seles
said before the tournament, but the legs are a different story. She
looked frustrated and weary as the relentless Tauziat kept the
pressure on. In a tough eighth game of the second set, Tauziat
fought off two break points to take a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum seemed clearly reversed at that point, and with
Zvereva netting a series of easy forehands in the tiebreaker, the
match seemed anything but even. In fact, the third set was strictly
a formality.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I'm not on the moon already,'' said Tauziat, who lay
flat on her back, then pounded the grass ecstatically when the
match was over. ``But almost.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tauziat-Zvereva match looked like something out of a
30-year-old tennis film, maybe Rosie Casals vs. Francoise Durr (the
great French player who, despite the federation squabbles, watched
with great interest from the Friends Box Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   Then came Hingis-Novotna, the ultimate fast-forward: Hingis,
with her cerebral, change-of-pace game against Novotna, looking so
much like Martina Navratilova with her spectacular athleticism and
all-court game.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of play was invigorating, a taste of big-time tennis
after nearly two weeks of tedium. Although Hingis made one candid
admission _ ``I'm not the player I was last year'' in terms of
conditioning _ she had no answers to Novotna's ingenuity. ``I hit
so many shots that, against other players, I win the point,'' said
Hingis. ``But Jana always gets it. I have to keep coming back,
again and again. I take this as it is: She was the better player.''
</P>
<P>
   For everyone who watched or attended the 1993 Wimbledon, there's
the indelible memory of Novotna blowing a 4-1 lead in the third set
of the final against Graf. She got a little misty at the consoling
words of the Duchess of Kent, then completely broke down in a
torrent of tears. So the question was inevitable: If she wins this
year, what will she say to the duchess?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, right,'' she scoffed. ``Like I know what I'm going to
say to her already. I just finish an hour ago and I know already
what I'm going to say to the duchess, right? That's really good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say anything,'' said Novotna, smiling now.
``I mean, she will be the one who talks to me. So I will just
reply, let's hope.''
</P>
<P>
   It has come to that at the '98 Wimbledon _ an unfettered
sentiment for Jana Novotna. It's her time and nobody else's. Let
her pass this test and forever be a champion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
