<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Funds Stagnant in 2nd Quarter   By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
U.S. equity mutual funds went nowhere during the second quarter.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 2,068 domestic stock funds surveyed by Morningstar Inc.
suffered a 0.29 percent decline on average, lagging the overall
stock market by a substantial margin.
</P>
<P>
   While the funds were heading south, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index _ the market bellwether _ continued its upward march. It rose
3.3 percent (including reinvestment of dividends) during the
quarter, for its 14th consecutive quarterly gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough second quarter, but it's still a good year,''
said Morningstar President Don Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of 1998, stock funds rose an average of
11.7 percent, compared with a 17.7 percent gain in the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   The 772 international stock funds surveyed by Morningstar did
worse than the domestic funds, skidding an average of 5.5 percent
last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They were dragged down by huge declines, averaging around 20
percent, in the Asian and Emerging Markets funds.
</P>
<P>
   On the international scene, the only bright spot was Europe,
which has been undergoing a dramatic economic recovery. The 61
funds specializing in European stocks rose an average of 4.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 371 specialty funds _ those that invest in only one industry
_ did poorly, declining an average of 1.7 percent. Natural-resource
funds were pounded the hardest, suffering a 9.8 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   Only 19 percent of the funds surveyed by Morningstar beat the
S&AMP;P last quarter. That proportion, give or take a few percentage
points, has remained stable for more than four years.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many investors have abandoned managed funds and
shifted to index funds, which are designed to track the performance
of various market averages.
</P>
<P>
   The second-largest fund of all, with $60.8 billion in assets, is
the Vanguard Index 500 Fund. Like the S&AMP;P 500, it enjoyed a 3.3
percent gain last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The only larger fund _ Fidelity Magellan, with $74.6 billion in
assets _ performed slightly better than the Vanguard Index 500 last
quarter, gaining 3.4 percent. Despite its unwieldy size, it has
performed well lately under current manager Robert Stansky, who
took over in 1996 after a disappointing performance by predecessor
Jeffrey Vinik.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Magellan still has some catching up to do. Its average
annual return during the past three years has been a 22.1 percent
gain _ well behind the 30.2 percent annual gain in the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   Fund expert Kurt Brouwer, of Brouwer &AMP; Janachowski in Tiburon,
insists that investors should still give managed funds a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Although the high-capitalization growth stocks that make up the
S&AMP;P 500 have been the market's darlings for the past several years,
that trend could change overnight, Brouwer warns. Many of those
stocks are way overvalued, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have Coca-Cola selling at 50 times earnings and a lot of
other S&AMP;P stocks selling for 40 to 50 times earnings,'' Brouwer
observes. ``The companies aren't worth that, yet they keep going up
because everyone likes them and the bandwagon effect is very
strong. If I were making a long-term bet, I would focus on solid
companies that are not so well-recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   The best-performing fund last quarter was IAI Value Fund _
relatively tiny, with only $30 million in assets _ which rose a
phenomenal 24.8 percent. It invests in both large and small
companies that it considers undervalued _ particularly those that
recently have made promising changes in management or strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The gain was due entirely to the fact that one of its larger
holdings _ privately held telecommunications supplier Pathnet Inc.
_ has announced plans to go public. The fund had been valuing its
Pathnet holdings at cost, but the IPO added 28 percent to the
fund's value in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   Janus Twenty Fund, with $8.1 billion in assets, was the
next-best performer, with a 14.5 percent gain last quarter. It
holds a lot of popular high-cap growth stocks, a Janus spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among its largest holdings are such spectacular performers as
Dell Computer, Pfizer, Microsoft and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-performing fund by far was the Lexington Troika Dialog
Russia Fund, which invests only in Russian stocks. It tumbled 55
percent last quarter. That performance mirrors the overall decline
in the Russian stock market.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Russian stock market last year was the
strongest in the world, rising more than 160 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Lawrence Kantor, managing director of New Jersey-based
Lexington Management, which operates the fund jointly with Russia's
Troika Dialog brokerage firm, said the calamitous turnaround was
caused largely by a slump in the world crude-oil market. The
Russian economy depends heavily on oil sales.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Russian companies have been under-paying taxes they
owe the Russian government, Kantor says, and this could damage the
economy by drying up the nation's currency reserves. Unlike the
United States, Russia is not considered creditworthy enough to
raise substantial new capital in international markets.
</P>
<P>
   Just yesterday, the Russian government threatened to seize the
assets of Gazprom, a gas producer and one of the country's largest
companies, to recover unpaid taxes. Gazprom promptly agreed to pay
the government $700 million a month in back taxes starting this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom is one of the largest Lexington Troika Dialog holdings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
