<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAFFIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Some State Courts OK Online Traffic Schools   By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Welcome to the new traffic school: no bad comics, no bloody-asphalt
videos, no teenage speed demons in the next seat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now traffic offenders can clean up their driving records by
logging onto the Web from a personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite objections from the California Department of Motor
Vehicles, a handful of California courts are allowing violators do
penance online rather than in a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saved me a whole mess of time,'' said Sandy Serna, 54, a
Pacifica resident who completed an Internet course in two hours
versus six to eight hours in traditional traffic school.
</P>
<P>
   The DMV says online programs are ripe for fraud and abuse,
because it is difficult to verify who is sitting at the computer.
So the DMV has not given its stamp of approval to any online
traffic courses.
</P>
<P>
   To have a ticket erased from a driving record, a violator
usually must attend a DMV-sanctioned traffic school. But some
counties also recognize non-DMV approved schools, including online
ones.
</P>
<P>
   So far, San Mateo and Solano are the only Bay Area counties that
let drivers who get tickets in their counties go to virtual traffic
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was a service to the public,'' said Peggy Thompson,
executive officer for Superior Court in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It simplifies life,'' Thompson said. ``In today's world, we're
all kind of running behind the time clock. With this you can do it
from your home and do it on your own clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Municipal Court was the first in the nation to
approve an online traffic course, in March last year. Since then,
18,000 students have graduated from the Los Angeles-based On-Line
Traffic School ( &LR; www.onlinetraffic.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Cyberclasses arrived in the Bay Area in December, when San Mateo
approved a course offered by Santa Rosa's TrafficSchoolOnline
( &LR; www.trafficschoolonline.com &LR; ). More than 3,500 students have
completed the course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Since then, a few other online traffic schools have popped up,
all hoping to grab a niche in the lucrative traffic school
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 950,000 Californians attend traffic school annually,
most of them paying between $20 and $45. Assuming an average cost
of about $30 per class, that adds up to a $28.5 million industry.
</P>
<P>
   In a sample of online traffic schools, tuitions were $20, $21
and $34. The schools can charge less than sit-down classes partly
because they require fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Fong, a Hayward resident, said price was part of her
motivation in choosing an online program over a traditional course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, `Wow, I don't even have to go somewhere _ plus
it's cheaper,''' said Fong, 31, a biochemical technician at
Genentech in South San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Although online traffic schools claim that their lessons take
six to eight hours to complete, many participants, including this
reporter, finished in less than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Most programs require students to read information about driving
rules, then answer some true/false and multiple-choice questions.
Students can keep retaking the test until they pass _ at which
time, the site sends the court a certificate certifying that you
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worry that students will skim the material without
absorbing as much as they would in an eight-hour lecture.
</P>
<P>
   TrafficSchoolOnline founder Steve Soldis said he is improving
the program to check whether students are cruising through it too
fast.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, ``We try to tell the courts that time
shouldn't be the issue. Of course, it's not going to take as long
as a sit-in class, but people are still learning from it.''
</P>
<P>
   His site prevents students from clicking the ``back'' button
during the exam _ which would let them look at the previous
material.
</P>
<P>
   But the DMV's biggest concern is that students might hire other
people to take the online exams for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we licensed it and approved it, I know exactly what would
happen _ college students would do the program for a fee,'' said
Tom Novi, chief of the Occupational Licensing branch of the DMV in
Sacramento. ``You'd have a cottage industry springing up.''
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason why Santa Clara County will not approve the
program, said Susan Myers, chief assistant executive officer for
the consolidated courts of Santa Clara County.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Department of Motor Vehicles isn't prepared to
recognize online traffic school, then the court has problems going
that far,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lisa Riches, 31, founder of On-Line Traffic School, said
there is probably just as much fraud in regular traffic school as
in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic school is not foolproof either,'' she said. ``People
use fake IDs. And even if they do show up, they sleep through
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Students are also required to pass a test to graduate from
old-fashioned traffic school.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some are still not convinced by the idea of spending
free time in front of the computer. San Francisco resident John
Kurtz recently chose regular traffic school over the online option.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to be in prison for a day, I'd rather go into a
class where maybe the guy would be funny,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
