<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAMBUS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-05 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMBUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Wall Street is hot for Rambus' chip technology   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Pay no attention to the soaring stock price of Rambus Inc., which
has shot up 54 percent in the past two weeks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geoff Tate, the president and chief executive of Mountain
View-based Rambus, shrugs off the rise as Wall Street's odd
response to ``old news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to ignore the stock price when it goes up or down,''
said Tate, 43. ``When our stock price goes up, I am quick to remind
everybody here, `This is great, but don't think this means we got
smarter today. We're the same people we were before.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rambus is an anomaly in many ways. In a chip industry that's
hitting a rocky spell, Rambus is on a roll. Rambus doesn't even
make anything; it licenses its technology to chipmakers, and
encourages computer makers to use chips made with Rambus
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In a stock market that rewards companies for short-term
earnings, Rambus keeps its eye on the horizon. Yet unlike other
companies whose stocks levitate on promises of future profits _
firms like Yahoo and Amazon.com spring to mind _ Rambus operates in
the black, and has ever since its initial public offering last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should become one of the most profitable semiconductor
companies ever,'' said Mark Edelstone, an analyst with Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter in San Francisco. ``Its stock will probably hit
$150 in five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambus was founded in 1990 by P.Michael Farmwald, a former chief
scientist at chipmaker MIPS Technologies, and Mark Horowitz, an
engineering professor at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   They recognized a bottleneck that was slowing down the
processing power of computers and video games.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Intel made microprocessors run faster and faster,
but computers and game consoles couldn't take full advantage of
that speed because memory chips had not advanced at the same rate.
The system could only move as fast as the weakest link in the
chain.
</P>
<P>
   Farmwald and Horowitz, who remain on Rambus's board of
directors, came up with a way to speed up the memory chips, and
they persuaded venture capitalists to invest $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   That was a start, but if Rambus was going to build these faster
memory chips, it would need a fabrication facility, and that would
cost a whopping $1billion.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than contract with another foundry to build the chips,
Rambus chose what Tate calls a software model: It would license its
intellectual property to chipmakers, and collect a royalty every
time they sold a chip with Rambus technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small royalty on billions of dollars can mean big dollars to
a small business like us,'' Tate said.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: Even with the market for dynamic random access
memory chips _ known as DRAM _ in a prolonged slump because of an
oversupply, it's still a huge market. Tate said it has grown from
$10 billion in 1990 to $26 billion today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the most dire projections of the memory market going
forward are $15 billion,'' said Dataquest analyst Nathan Brookwood.
</P>
<P>
   Rambus has already signed deals with all of the major makers of
DRAM in the world, most of which are based in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has positioned their technology to become the next
standard for main memory used in PCs,'' said analyst Edelstone.
``Within the next five years, I expect that Rambus technology will
dominate the DRAM market.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, only 1 percent of DRAM chips manufactured use
Rambus technology, Tate said. Even in a shrinking market, if Rambus
doubles its market share to 2 percent, it rakes in a tidy sum.
``Small companies can grow through down cycles and up cycles,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company faces no direct competition, although Tate notes
that the DRAM makers are trying to come up with their own standard.
</P>
<P>
   If memory vendors find their own way of making chips run faster
without infringing any of Rambus' 40 patents, the company could
face a tough fight, Dataquest's Brookwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Tate, a Canadian, came to Rambus after its founding. He had
already left his job as vice president in charge of chipmaker AMD's
microprocessor and logic group. ``I had left to run my own startup,
but this idea seemed even crazier,'' Tate said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was growing up, Tate said he never listened to his
mother very much, but he does recall her advice: ``Do what's fun.
If you aren't having fun, you aren't going to be good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   He's tried to instill that atmosphere at Rambus. The company
takes workers and their families to a baseball game every year.
Employees work hard, Tate said, but turnover is low, and ``there's
no perks for the hierarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   He runs an egalitarian operation, in which he works in a
cubicle, and doesn't even have a secretary _ or a better computer
than anyone else. He hopes to avert the bureaucratic underpinnings
of big companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rambus went public in May 1997, again following what Tate
called &QL; 
``counter-intuitive'' thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective in going public was not to raise cash,'' he
said. ``We already had $30 million in the bank and a positive cash
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tate said, the company sought to reward employees who
had received much of their pay in stock options and were wondering,
``Is this paper ever going to be worth anything?''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, being in the market raised Rambus's visibility.
</P>
<P>
   The stock peaked in August at $86.50, but gradually fell to a
52-week low of $35.50 last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't I buy that one when it was $35?'' analyst Brookwood
asked, somewhat rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   The stock began its latest ascent on June 22, when Rambus
announced that Santa Clara-based Intel, the world's largest
chipmaker, was testing Direct Rambus DRAMs made by Toshiba and LG
Semicon. In addition, personal computer makers Compaq and Dell
confirmed their intention to ship PCs using Direct Rambus next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody saw something, I assume, in the press release,'' Tate
said. ``It was just another milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock stampeded up, from $38.81 Friday, to $46.50 Monday, to
$57.25 Tuesday. It has stayed at roughly that level, or slightly
higher, in heavy trading since then.
</P>
<P>
   But Tate's eye is not on the ticker, and the analysts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to keep your eye on the longer term,'' said Morgan
Stanley's Edelstone. ``The revenues and earnings the company is
generating today will pale in comparison to what you can expect in
2003 and 2004.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
