<HEADLINE>
SO MANY WAYS TO HAVE FUN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The usual prescription for women's mental and physical health,
writes  &UR; Susan &LR;   &UR; Jane Gilman  &LR; in the Utne Reader, is ``a cocktail of
consumerism, subjugation and self-hatred.'' Organized exercise is
fascism, she writes, and other ``calm-down'' activities touted in
women's magazines encourage ``passivity, obsessiveness, deprivation
and needless spending.''
</P>
<P>
   The author advises instead a trip to Las Vegas, ``the perfect
antidote to all the sexist stereotypes and expectations constantly
imposed upon women.''
</P>
<P>
   There, nobody cares about weight, beauty, style, sexiness or
``whether you speak English. All people in Las Vegas care about is
money. As long as you can afford the $4.99 all-you-can-eat buffet
plus a few quarters for the slot machines, the Vegas folks are
thrilled to wait on you hand and foot. ... You can stay up all
night, chow down on pancakes and prime rib 24 hours a day, wear
gaudy clothing and comfortable shoes, ride from casino to casino in
a trolley, dance, scream, laugh and flirt, and nobody will
encourage you to do otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, to me, is better for the heart and the soul than
anything in a vicious little gymnasium.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jeannie Matteucci &LR; , aficionado of Living a la  &UR; Martha &LR; 
 &UR; Stewart &LR; , passes on this advice for July 3: ``Divide overcrowded
bearded iris after they bloom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Big numbers: Realtors overheard at John's Grill on Wednesday
said  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR;  and her man moved this week from a
$15,000-a-month apartment on Bush Street to a $7 million house in
Sea Cliff.
</P>
<P>
   _ A half-hour before her wedding to  &UR; James Brolin &LR; ,  &UR; Barbra &LR; 
 &UR; Streisand &LR;  ordered the caterers to ditch the Pellegrino water and
replace it with Perrier. They did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOUR GENERATIONS AT THE MOVIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday night's preview festivities (benefiting the Giants
Community Fund and the ALS Association) for the AMC 1000 Van Ness
theater complex,  &UR; John Field &LR; 's pleasure was both professional and
personal.
</P>
<P>
   Field, a partner in Field Paoli, was chief architect for the
project, which combines movies, restaurants, a gym and
condominiums. His son,  &UR; Matt Field &LR; , put together the deal that
converted the old car showroom into the entertainment/living
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Before them,  &UR; John Field &LR; 's father had run a chain of movie
theaters in Iowa and Minnesota. Architect Field's brother owned
some of the first multiplexes in the country, in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   And in the early '20s, in the first layer of this
four-generation family sandwich, John Field's grandfather opened
his first theater in downtown Minneapolis, in a storefront with
folding chairs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dollywood, the  &UR; Dolly Parton &LR; -themed amusement park that is
Tennessee's second top tourist attraction (just after the Great
Smoky Mountains National Park), has announced plans for a new
roller coaster and gospel museum (separate installations). The
roller coaster will include a ``double butterfly loop'' that the
singer says has been designed in homage to her figure.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Latrell Sprewell &LR;  Warriors jerseys are on sale for $21 at
SportSpirit &LR;  in San Francisco, notes  &UR; F.X. Moonan &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ In keeping with the summer smog season, which is now,  &UR; Julia &LR; 
 &UR; Fishman &LR;  of the Bay Area Air Quality Management District says that
hair spray in the Bay Area _ generally thought to be a small-hair
part of the country _ puts eight tons of smog into the air every
day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAG TEAMING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco schoolkids in a weeklong workshop with the ODC
dance company gave a recital last Friday that included a group
performing dance moves _ to the music of a sole drummer _ based on
words beginning with the letter ``B.'' The inspirations: baseball,
battle, buckle, busted, blow, bowling, bummer, back, bow, biceps,
bend and band. Do try this in your own home.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Supathra &LR;  and  &UR; Rich Lane &LR;  of Burlingame, Calif., sent a copy
of the birth announcement for their twins,  &UR; Herbie  &LR; and  &UR; Rosie &LR; , in
which each has a page listing future accomplishments. Rosie will be
president from 2053-2061, for example, win the Nobel Prize for
peace in 2063, and climb Mount Everest with Herbie to celebrate
their 100th birthdays. Herbie will be NFL Rookie of the Year in
2020, chairman of IBM, AT&AMP;T and GM from 2093 to 2100, and make the
climb with his sister. On Jan. 1, 2101, they are to celebrate three
different centuries together.
</P>
