<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO MANY WAYS TO HAVE FUN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The usual prescription for women's mental and physical health,
writes  &UR; Susan &LR;   &UR; Jane Gilman  &LR; in the Utne Reader, is ``a cocktail of
consumerism, subjugation and self-hatred.'' Organized exercise is
fascism, she writes, and other ``calm-down'' activities touted in
women's magazines encourage ``passivity, obsessiveness, deprivation
and needless spending.''
</P>
<P>
   The author advises instead a trip to Las Vegas, ``the perfect
antidote to all the sexist stereotypes and expectations constantly
imposed upon women.''
</P>
<P>
   There, nobody cares about weight, beauty, style, sexiness or
``whether you speak English. All people in Las Vegas care about is
money. As long as you can afford the $4.99 all-you-can-eat buffet
plus a few quarters for the slot machines, the Vegas folks are
thrilled to wait on you hand and foot. ... You can stay up all
night, chow down on pancakes and prime rib 24 hours a day, wear
gaudy clothing and comfortable shoes, ride from casino to casino in
a trolley, dance, scream, laugh and flirt, and nobody will
encourage you to do otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, to me, is better for the heart and the soul than
anything in a vicious little gymnasium.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jeannie Matteucci &LR; , aficionado of Living a la  &UR; Martha &LR; 
 &UR; Stewart &LR; , passes on this advice for July 3: ``Divide overcrowded
bearded iris after they bloom.''
</P>
