<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANTS-BBN-SFCHRON-GIANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUELLER'S BLAST WINS IT FOR GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY SCHULMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Giants are learning what many of the Anaheim
Angels' opponents already know. A 2-0 lead against these guys is as
worthless as a dime at a downtown San Francisco parking meter. Of
the 22 games the Angels won in June, they came from behind in 12.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels are learning something about the Giants, too:
Their guests from the north have some pretty strong innards
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When the Angels came back to tie Wednesday night's game 2-2 in
the eighth inning, the Giants did not slither into the darkness and
let Anaheim win. Instead, they attacked, and they rode Bill
Mueller's improbable three-run homer off Greg Cadaret in the 10th
inning to a 6-3 victory that did not sit well with 24,299 fans at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are tough at home. They're as tough at home as we
are,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``The visiting team rarely
wins extra-inning games on the road, so we defied two odds
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller hit his sixth homer on a 1-2 pitch after twice failing
to sacrifice pinch-runner Shawn Estes to third and Darryl Hamilton
to second.
</P>
<P>
   The other key play in the rally was also a bunt. After Brent
Mayne opened the inning with a single, Hamilton was asked to
sacrifice Estes to second. But his bunt rolled hard past a diving
Cadaret, and nobody could field it. Hamilton had a single, and the
Giants had two on and nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller fouled off his first bunt try and fouled off the second.
Cadaret then did Mueller's job for him by throwing a wild pitch
that advanced the runners to third and second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a stroke of good luck,'' said Mayne, whose sacrifice
fly in the fifth inning broke a scoreless tie. ``He had a couple of
chances to lay the bunt down, and the guy wild-pitches them over
anyway. You know things are going your way then.''
</P>
<P>
   A mere single could have scored two, but Mueller ripped the next
pitch into the left-field bullpen for a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those strange things,'' Baker said. ``The guys on
the bench were saying, `Who gave him the bunt sign?' They were
joking about it. The key was the wild pitch. That was good
baserunning by Shawn to get to third.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer should not have been a huge surprise. Mueller hit
eight of his first 12 career home runs in games pitched by Estes.
Estes did not throw Wednesday night, but he was on base, and the
mere sight of him seems to make Mueller's forearms bulge.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, anytime Mueller hits a homer he surprises himself. At
least he wasn't mad at himself for missing those bunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the wild pitch, my job is to get a fly ball and get a
run in. You can't worry about what you didn't do. You've got to
worry about what you can do. You have to live in the present, not
the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants added a run on a Charlie Hayes double and J.T. Snow
single, completing a four-run outburst that made a winner out of
new All-Star Robb Nen (6-1), who started his night by striking out
the side in the ninth inning. The Angels scored an unearned run off
him in the bottom of the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Darwin and John Johnstone combined on a four-hit shutout
through seven innings, and the Giants were leading 2-0 when the
inevitable Angels comeback occurred in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   New pitcher Rich Rodriguez walked Dave Hollins with one out, and
Jim Edmonds brought him home with a first-pitch double into the gap
in left-center. Steve Reed entered the game, and pinch-hitter
Orlando Palmeiro tied it at 2-2 when he hit a soft line drive that
barely eluded a diving Hamilton in center.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Poole, the third pitcher of the inning, retired Garret
Anderson on a soft fly to center to keep the game even.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants forged their 2-0 lead on Mayne's sacrifice fly and a
sixth-inning homer by Barry Bonds, his 18th. Bonds was in a
1-for-19 funk, but he spent a lot of time in the dugout watching
Anaheim starter Steve Sparks throw his knuckleballs and figured he
could time one if he stayed patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys I was going to hit one,'' Bonds said. ``I
said, `If he throws a knuckler and hangs it up there, I'm going to
hit it out.' I'm not going to make that bet ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   One bet that seems safe: When the Giants and Angels meet, the
game is not over until somebody is shaking hands on the mound. &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
