<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS DONE IN BY NOVOTNA, TEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE JENKINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ For the first time in memory, people could
truly relate to Venus Williams on Wednesday. She comes from a very
different background _ home-schooled, Jehovah's Witness, out of a
Compton ghetto _ but everyone knows what it is like to cry. To try
to fight back. To resume the task at hand with your cheeks still
flushed from tears.
</P>
<P>
   It was entirely the wrong thing to do, of course. Tennis is a
game of composure, and if you insist on throwing tantrums, you had
better be pretty damned good. Venus Williams is just 18 years old
and playing her second Wimbledon. But in a 7-5, 7-6 (7-2)
quarterfinal loss to Jana Novotna Wednesday, her world seemed a bit
closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   This whole day had been tumultuous on the women's side. Natasha
Zvereva knocked off Monica Seles in a result that surprised even
Natasha herself. Lindsay Davenport, No.2 in the seedings and the
world, found herself being dominated 6-3, 6-3 at the hands of
Nathalie Tauziat. And Martina Hingis was run around the court
without mercy before outlasting Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, 6-3, 3-6,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   It means that Hingis will meet Novotna in Thursday's semifinals,
a rematch of last year's Wimbledon final. It brings the
incomprehensible Zvereva-Tauziat matchup in the other semifinal.
But if there is a lasting image from Wednesday's play, it is the
coltish, haughty Venus Williams showing some real emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, she just couldn't take it any more. A couple of
dubious calls had gone Novotna's way, right along with the first
set, and Venus was trailing 0-2 when a looping Novotna forehand was
called ``good'' in the top left corner of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Venus went haywire _ especially by her standards. She cried out,
stomped around, gestured menacingly toward the linesperson and the
chair umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Television replays showed the ball was either good or a
half-inch out, but for Venus, it was highway robbery. ``I've never
seen her get that upset,'' said former tour player Pam Shriver, who
has followed Williams since her debut at the Oakland Coliseum Arena
four years ago. ``She never loses it like she did right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus clawed her way back into the set, and it was 3-3, 15-30 on
her serve when another close call went Novotna's way. Williams
double-faulted on the next point, handing the game over like a
gift, and her lips were trembling as she sat during the changeover.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an all-out sobbing fit, but she got a little misty.
She dabbed at her eyes with a towel. Then, most remarkably, she
stormed out there with fresh resolve, breaking Novotna's serve for
4-4.
</P>
<P>
   The match turned toward Novotna from that point on, for one big
reason: Novotna has played the serve-and-volley game all her life
(without Martina Navratilova, she's the only one left on the
women's tour), and Venus is still trying to figure it out. So the
result was not a big surprise. Venus' temperament was a bigger
issue.
</P>
<P>
   After being convinced that she was crying _ at first she denied
it _ Williams said, ``I was upset. If I wasn't so dark, I would
probably turn red (laughter). I don't have a tendency to do that.
But I think maybe the crowd enjoyed my emotional outbursts. Someone
probably turned on the channel, saw some girl screaming and kept it
there. I know I would. It probably brightened up someone's day.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's day was about as bright as soot, so overwhelming was
Tauziat's performance. Davenport said she ``had a good cry, for
about two minutes'' afterward, but then took heart in one of her
better Wimbledon tournaments. ``Nathalie's great on grass, and
that's the best she's ever played against me,'' said Davenport, who
had won the last seven meetings. ``She was just a better player by
far.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hingis, every match is rife with doubt. She's out of shape,
she's overconfident, she doesn't look that great _ the criticism
comes from all angles. But always she's there at the finish,
flashing an Audrey Hepburn smile to the crowd, pleasantly signing
autographs and moving on to the next round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arantxa was just chasing everything down, really running me
around,'' said Hingis. ``So it's lots of running on grass. I think
maybe I strained my back a little. Grass looks like it's soft, but
it's not. Like the England-Argentina (soccer) game, at the end,
everybody was holding their backs after the match. I feel the same
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis seemed to favor the 30-year-old Tauziat against Zvereva,
saying, ``Nathalie is very smart and clever. She's been around, she
can close it out. She's not afraid of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   And for one day, Venus Williams wasn't afraid to show some
emotion. At this relatively drab Wimbledon, that's fast-breaking
news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
