A1053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      07-05 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: BRACELET FOR MONITORING PAROLEES; CONTACT LENS FOR
INTENSIFYING LIGHT; FAMOUS WRITER'S SCRAPBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1960s television series ``The Prisoner,'' the captors of
a British spy known as No. 6 have constant knowledge of his
whereabouts, thanks to large glowing spheres that guard the island
on which he is confined.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Heiser, a lawyer turned entrepreneur, has just patented
a different type of technology that nonetheless sounds as if it
could have kept efficient track of No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Heiser said he was not developing his tracking technology to
keep tabs on wayward spies, however. Rather, his idea was to
constantly monitor the location of felons who are on parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent of all crime is committed by the same 20
percent of people over and over again,'' Heiser said. ``The major
function of this is to shut down recidivist crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Heiser and his colleagues have patented a bracelet embedded with
a computer chip that receives and transmits radio signals. The
bracelet triangulates the parolee's position every 30 seconds and
relays this information back to a central computer.
</P>
<P>
   Such a system could instantly monitor parole violations _ if,
say, a parolee failed to show up for work or left a prescribed
geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   The bracelets would have three lights, according to Heiser:
green, yellow and red. ``Yellow means that there is a problem and
you have 30 minutes to call in,'' he said. ``Red means the police
are notified.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important feature of Heiser's invention, however, is
that police can enter the time and place of recent crimes into a
computer and receive a printout of every parolee who was nearby at
the time of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``To eliminate the taste of Big Brother, this is the only kind
of routine inquiry permitted,'' Heiser said. ``Without a court
order, they can't ask us where you were for the past three weeks.`
</P>
<P>
   The bracelet could help relieve prison overcrowding by letting
low-risk offenders out early, Heiser said. ``It's cheaper to put
people on the bracelet than keep them in prison _ especially if
they aren't going to walk around the corner and kill someone,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Heiser, who plans to test the technology next year in Lincoln,
Neb., said the system would rely on radio transmissions subleased
from entities that already have the rights to certain frequencies.
The advantage of such a system _ which uses transmissions from
land-based towers rather than satellite signals _ is that the
transmissions could be encrypted and would be less likely to be
interrupted by tall buildings or mountains, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But couldn't the bracelets just be cut off, as some home-arrest
bracelets have been? Yes, but this is not something Heiser worries
about. ``If you do that, you have just put yourself on a short list
of suspects,'' he said. ``After all, you didn't cut it off because
it clashed with your tuxedo.''
</P>
<P>
   Patent 5,748,148 was granted to Heiser as well as Joanna Mary
Malvino, Charles M. Wohl, and Fausto Poza, all of whom are
affiliated with HMW Consulting Inc. of Reno, Nev., which has been
assigned the patent.
</P>
<P>
   New Contact Lens Intensifies Light
</P>
<P>
   Some years ago, Patricia Bowling began suffering from a viral
inflammation that infected her eyes and impaired her vision. So Dr.
Bowling, who is a physician, began researching retinal disease,
including macular degeneration _ a leading and incurable cause of
blindness in old people.
</P>
<P>
   What these eye diseases had in common, she discovered, was an
across-the-board reduction in the number of rods and cones, the
retinal cells that perceive light and color.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to Dr. Bowling that if she could focus and intensify
light on the remaining rods and cones, she could improve vision. So
she developed a special contact lens that does exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bowling makes a computer printout of the good areas of the
eye in an individual patient and then uses this to impose a pattern
of pinholes on the contact lenses that match the areas of the eye
that are still dense with rods and cones.
</P>
<P>
   These pinholes allow light to strike the rods and cones
perpendicularly. At this 90-degree angle the retinal cells perceive
light to be much brighter than they otherwise would. (The lenses
are kept from shifting by a tiny weight that keeps them in place.)
</P>
<P>
   The lenses will require approval by the Food and Drug
Administration before they can be sold. But does Dr. Bowling use
the lens herself? ``You bet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bowling received patent 5,719,656. Bruce Lagerman, an
intellectual-property attorney, in Reston, Va., who represents Dr.
Bowling, said she would like to license it to a large contact-lens
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   A Little History Lesson
</P>
<P>
   And now for a brief quiz on patent trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Question: What important American writer patented a self-pasting
scrapbook 125 years ago this summer?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Mark Twain. He received his patent on June 24, 1873.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
