<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fall in AT&AMP;T Stock Raises Concern
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AT&AMP;T have fallen 16 percent since its planned
acquisition of Tele-Communications for $31.8 billion in stock was
announced last month, leading some to speculate that the deal may
have to be renegotiated in light of the poor shareholder reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Access for Small Fry
</P>
<P>
   Media commentators have greeted the proposed
AT&AMP;T-Tele-Communications merger with a certain skepticism. But not
much has been said about how the deal will affect one of the most
vibrant new industries that now finds itself directly in AT&AMP;T's
path: the largely local, independent Internet service providers.
The cooperative agreements under which 4,000 or so of these
providers transfer trillions of bits of data around the globe, a
system known as peering, could be endangered by competition for
access.
</P>
<P>
   Million-Dollar Sports Talk
</P>
<P>
   Nanci Donnellan, the only female host of a nationally syndicated
sports talk show, is well known for her opinionated, gravelly
over-the-air bellow and lightning-quick repartee. About 250,000
sports fans each month call her 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. daily call-in
show, transmitted live from New York to 187 stations. It is one of
the few radio programs to generate nearly $1 million in annual
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Some E-Mails Are Never Answered
</P>
<P>
   A major consumer-products company's customer-service center
received about 20,000 e-mail messages via the Internet in a recent
month. But only 2,000, or about 10 percent, received attentive
replies, and some of these not for several weeks, because many
companies, even those with a seemingly sophisticated presence on
the World Wide Web, continue to treat customer e-mail as
second-class communication.
</P>
<P>
   Online Company Adding 21 Sites
</P>
<P>
   Avram Glazer has letters of intent to buy 21 World Wide Web
sites and aggregate them under one site, www.Zap.com, which is
named after his company, Zapata. Earlier Zapata acquired the online
magazines Word and Charged.
</P>
<P>
   More Globe Columns Questioned
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe's investigation of Patricia Smith, the
columnist who resigned last month after it was discovered that she
had invented some of the people she described, has produced
evidence that her fabrications might be far more numerous than
originally reported.
</P>
<P>
   Tabloid Offers a $100,000 Reward
</P>
<P>
   A .38-caliber Taurus revolver that is believed to be the weapon
that killed Ennis Cosby, the son of entertainer Bill Cosby, was
discovered with the help of The National Enquirer, which offered a
$100,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and
conviction of the killer of Cosby. The tabloid's reward went beyond
the media's traditional role of announcing rewards offered by
others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
