<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Sun Microsystems To Cut 200 Jobs In Reorganization   By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Sun Microsystems Inc. said yesterday it will cut about 200 jobs _
out of 13,000 in the Bay Area _ as part of a reorganization.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sun's first layoff since 1994 reflects increased pressure from
the Microsoft-Intel juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   Sun is the only big maker of high-powered workstations and
servers that still uses proprietary technology rather than cheaper
Intel chips and the Microsoft Windows NT operating system.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``Sun has to be almost superhumanly efficient'' to
maintain its profit margins, said Peter ffoulkes, analyst at
Dataquest in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   He said the layoffs were a good pre-emptive strike against
possible bloat at the Palo Alto-based firm. Wall Street seemed to
agree, boosting Sun's share price up $1.50 to $44.94 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Sun had hinted at the layoffs in April when it announced it
would reorganize its subsidiaries into seven business units. Sun
said the job cuts were designed to eliminate overlap between the
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Sun said it notified the 200 employees Tuesday that their jobs
would be cut and gave them 90 days to find employment within the
company.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, Sun agreed yesterday to buy closely-held
corporate software maker NetDynamics Inc. for an undisclosed price.
</P>
<P>
   NetDynamics makes software that gives Internet users access to
information on a corporate database. Companies use it, for example,
to let customers order books or compact discs through the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 1846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
