u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRILL-MEDIA-1     07-05 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRILL-MEDIA-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MAGAZINE PUBLISHING, THE NAME OF THE GAME IS BUZZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While media critics, talk show hosts and reporters
rehashed the scoop in the first issue of Brill's Content about
Kenneth Starr's leaks in the Monica Lewinsky case, an entirely
different group tipped their hats and took notes: magazine
publicists.
</P>
<P>
   This was buzz of a whole different order, the publicists knew _
buzz that started before the magazine even hit the newsstand and
kept going far into a second week of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Call the magazine publicists the warrior class of buzz.
Responsible for trying to wrest attention for their publications in
the midst of a media glut, they are proliferating as magazines
devote increasing energy, resources and sophisticated tactics to
promoting themselves _ and only once in a great while does an
article like the one in Brill's do the work for them to that
extent. The result is a kind of incestuous moment in the food chain
of buzz, when one media outlet tries to pitch to another. Buzz _
which has been criticized for encouraging journalistic excess _
enhances circulation and advertising sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of clutter on the newsstand; there's a lot of
clutter in the mail,'' said Efrem Zimbalist III, president and
chief executive of Times Mirror Magazines, which publishes Field
and Stream and Popular Science. ``So we're all looking for ways to
get our names out in front of the public at every opportunity we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Kaplan, vice president of corporate communications at
Conde Nast Publications, has four people working for her to promote
magazines like Details, Self and Bride's. Susan Ollinick, director
of public affairs at People magazine, has six people working for
her to publicize People, Teen People and People Espanol. Keith
Estabrook, vice president of communications at Hachette Filipacchi
Magazines, has five people working for him to promote magazines
like Elle, George and Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the magazine publicity machine has intensified. In
addition to sending out news releases, planning parties, pitching
story ideas and trying to plant items in gossip columns, publicists
say they are trying to position the publications they represent as
newsmakers and experts on the topics they cover. If a television
program is doing a report on increases in airline ticket prices,
Ms. Kaplan said, she wants that program turning to Conde Nast
Traveler for comment. And if a newspaper is doing an article on
weddings, Ms. Kaplan wants them to turn to Bride's as an authority
on marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago, it was a much more simplistic view of
editorial publicity; you would get the page proofs and you would
promote what's in the magazine,'' Ms. Kaplan said. ``Today it's
much more strategic. It's like the Big Bang theory: We're looking
to every issue every month to get the biggest bang we can for the
magazine out in the marketplace, to have the biggest share in the
mind of the reader and the advertiser.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go to TV anymore with one idea,'' she said. ``I go
with a five-part series idea, and I go six months in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding where to go is a crucial part of the process,
publicists say. As Estabrook sees it, there are three kinds of
magazine publicity: industry press, meaning coverage by trade
publications; image-building press, coverage that promotes the aura
of a magazine, not specific content; and what he calls
``bread-and-butter press,'' basics like items in gossip columns.
``And what really makes it work,'' he said, ``is when you have all
three working together cohesively.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Klores, whose public relations firm represents New York
Magazine and Esquire, among others, said he was careful to focus
his pitches. He will go to television to promote an investigative
or large-scale lifestyle article; to gossip pages with
celebrity-driven items; to news pages with newsworthy articles, and
to trade publications with information about a magazine's increase
in ad pages, personnel moves or changes in design.
</P>
<P>
   ``You identify three to six promotable stories,'' Klores said.
``Then you decide, `Where am I going to go?'''
</P>
<P>
   The good news, publicists say, is that newspapers and television
news programs have grown increasingly dependent on magazines as
sources of content. ``I call it, `Feed the monster,''' said Paul
Wilmot, who was in charge of public relations at Conde Nast for two
years and now has his own firm. ``They have to be filled. ''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, these interdependent relationships have been
formalized in joint ventures such as Good Housekeeping's
arrangement to have its articles featured on ``Primetime Live'' on
ABC and People's similar deal with ``Dateline'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Publicists say they can count on certain tried-and-true motifs:
celebrities who say something newsworthy, magazine surveys,
magazines that rate things _ the 10 best this, the six worst that _
trends, controversy, gossip about job changes or one magazine
stealing another magazine's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But while magazine items have become a staple of the gossip
columns, Richard Johnson, who writes Page Six in The New York Post,
decried them as ``basically sort of filler.'' He also said he
resented the extent to which publicists try to control the process.
``They try to fine-tune and micromanage their publicity so much
that they will leak different stories to different columns in the
same newspaper in the same day,'' Johnson said. ``I don't know why
I have to be in some pecking order where I get the second- or
third-best thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some publicists say they are in a position to pick and
choose, like Ms. Ollinick at People, who said she had to sift
through requests from news organizations. ``We always look for a
credible environment,'' she said. ``We never deal with the Hard
Copys and the slugfests _ the talk shows _ except Oprah.''
</P>
<P>
   As to how far a gossip column item can go toward getting a
publicity bounce, Wilmot said: ``A magazine with 1 million
circulation can sell 30,000 to 40,000 copies off a good item:
`Madonna reveals in Harper's Bazaar,' `Sharon Stone admits in
Vogue.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
