<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Lucent Plans Bell Labs Unit In Silicon Valley   By Jonathan Marshall  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Bell Laboratories, the research arm of Lucent Technologies, is
opening a new branch in Silicon Valley, in part to foster Lucent's
local venture investments.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The labs will house as many as 130 people at a new facility to
be completed next year in Stanford Research Park and will focus on
data networking, semiconductors, communications software, wireless
communications and optical networking.
</P>
<P>
   It also will supply expertise to Lucent Venture Partners, a $100
million fund the company announced in February to back startups
that complement Lucent's own development efforts. Many major
technology companies, including Microsoft and Intel, have similar
venture arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Labs will help identify and evaluate promising new
technologies,'' said Lucent spokesman Gary Bonham. ``The point
isn't simply to gain an equity position, but to have a hands-on
involvement to move the technology along. We'll give the startups
access to our business units and distribution channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Venture Partners already has funded at least four new
companies, said John Hanley, its managing partner. He declined to
name the companies or report the level of investment.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanley said the fund is working closely with half a dozen
other venture funds, including Accel Partners in Palo Alto and
Mayfield Fund and U.S. Venture Partners in Menlo Park, to identify
investment candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Fong, a general partner at Mayfield Fund, said Lucent
might use its venture fund to promote commercial development of
technology dreamed up at Bell Labs. And it could further attract
promising startups in the networking industry because Lucent is
widely viewed as a counterweight to networking goliath Cisco
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent also said yesterday that Lucent Technologies Foundation
will contribute $2.6 million to endow a professorship and two
graduate fellowships at Stanford University to promote research and
teaching on communications networking.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has made several major acquisitions in the Bay Area
independent of its venture unit. Last year, it bought Octel
Communications, a Milpitas firm that makes unified messaging
software for corporate networks, for $1.8 billion. It also
purchased Livingston Enterprises in Pleasanton, a networking
company, for $650 million in stock. In February, it announced plans
to buy a wireless technology division of Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bell Labs group will be led by Bill Coughran, head of
Lucent's Internet software research team, and Ron Schmidt, who left
the board of Bay Networks in April. Bay announced last month that
it was being acquired by Northern Telecom, a Lucent competitor in
the telecommunications equipment industry.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the new Bell Labs group will be housed with Lucent
Venture Partners on Sand Hill Road in Menlo Park, before both move
to the Stanford Research Park next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRILL-MEDIA-2NDTAKE-N     07-05 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRILL-MEDIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: in Vogue. ' '' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even one short item on a gossip page, publicists say, can be the
spark that ignites other media interest. And publicists are looking
for volume. They measure their successes in ``impressions,'' the
number of times a given issue is mentioned in other media. Among
the widely commended recent public relations successes was Time
Magazine's 75th-anniversary celebration at Radio City Music Hall,
an embarrassment of celebrity riches that juxtaposed the likes of
Henry Kissinger and Sophia Loren, Tom Cruise and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the occasional home run, publicists say their work _
like that of anyone in public relations _ is mostly made up of base
hits and plenty of strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Publicists also have to deal with damage control. Yes,
publicists say, there is such a thing as bad publicity. One need
look no further than last week for two examples: Fortune magazine's
scathing profile of Steven Florio, the president and chief
executive of Conde Nast Publications, and Time magazine's
retraction of its article with CNN that asserted the Army used
lethal nerve gas during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   What seems like a public relations nightmare can occasionally
turn into a dream. For example, when Kathie Lee Gifford held up a
copy of Redbook magazine that featured an unflattering article
about her on camera and said, ``Do not buy this magazine,'' sales
went up about 20 percent, according to someone who worked with
Redbook at the time.
</P>
<P>
   And is there such thing as too much buzz? Paradoxically, one
publicist said Brill's Content was just such an example, that so
much hype inspires media figures to get the knives out, as many
have for Steven Brill, the magazine's editor. Some say the same was
true about George magazine, which was widely anticipated when it
first came out in 1995 because of its editor, John Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   And some say buzz can backfire, as when Esquire magazine put the
actor Kevin Spacey on the cover and implied that he was gay, which
prompted a flurry of negative reaction.
</P>
<P>
   But does imperfection matter? In the June 20 issue of National
Journal, William Powers wrote: ``To cause an uproar, a piece must
have a veneer of fairness, but a tendentious heart. It must be
bold, but not quite realized, and maddeningly flawed. Then people
will talk and argue about it endlessly, flaws being more
interesting than perfection. If you can do all this and also come
up with a chunk of real news, then you'll be a buzz magnet, and
that most precious of commodities _ `impact,' with its promise of
commercial success _ will be yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicists say the celebrity of their editors is their best
weapon. Klores pointed to Tina Brown, the editor of The New Yorker,
and Graydon Carter, the editor of Vanity Fair, as prime examples.
``They've taken this to a new level,'' he said. ``The idea that
they themselves have made themselves into people who need to be
invited to functions and `If only I was invited to theirs.' It
makes a lot of the other jobs at those places easier _ it makes ad
sales easier, it's easier to get people to say, `Yes, I'll do that
interview.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although publicists are trying to build subscriptions, newsstand
sales and advertising revenue, they say their first concern is
reaching the media; the rest follows. Media executives say that
press coverage gives magazines the imprimatur of legitimate news,
which impresses potential readers. And when a magazine seems talked
about and written about, publicists say, advertisers respond.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how effective the public relations effort,
publicists say, ultimately magazines will not rise or fall on
flash. ``I've succeeded when advertising revenues and pages are up
and circulation is up,'' Klores said. ``That's success. PR on its
own cannot do it. You need a great publisher; you need a great ad
sales staff; you need a great editor. You can't do it just by
making news.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
