<HEADER>
A1076 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEST-SCORES-SFCHRON &LR;      07-05 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-SCORES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE PUPILS RANK BELOW U.S. AVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NANETTE ASIMOV and LORI OLSZEWSKI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Most of California's English-speaking students
scored below the national average on the state's controversial new
achievement test, according to results released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In most grades, reading and math levels lagged behind the
national average. Scores were especially poor in spelling and high
school science.
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot was language skills _ such as vocabulary and
grammar _ where most grades performed above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The new test sits at the center of California's politically
charged bilingual education debate. Because of a legal battle over
whether non-English speakers should have to take the test in
English, the state did not release scores from schools and
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it posted only the percentage of students in each grade
who scored above the 25th, 50th and 75th percentile on the 99-point
multiple-choice test. A score of 50 represents the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of heightened concern about the quality of California
schools, the test showed plenty of reasons to worry:
</P>
<P>
   -- In reading, performance dropped off significantly by high
school, with ninth- and 10th-graders scoring far below the national
average, then improving only slightly by 11th grade.
</P>
<P>
   -- In math, students generally performed at or just below the
national average. Only 10th-graders scored far lower.
</P>
<P>
   -- In spelling, a subject that for years has been neglected in
California schools, students demonstrated a particular need to
study their ABCs. Only fifth-graders and seventh-graders came even
close to performing at the national average in this basic area.
</P>
<P>
   -- Only high school students were tested in science and social
studies. Social studies numbers were below the national average,
and results were particularly poor in science.
</P>
<P>
   -- In language, students in almost every grade scored somewhere
around the national average. Only 10th-graders scored far below
average.
</P>
<P>
   In the first measure of student performance in four years, 4.1
million children in grades 2 through 11 took the Standardized
Testing and Reporting (STAR) exam this spring. About a quarter of
them spoke little or no English, but were required to take the test
in English under California's controversial new testing law, backed
by Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of the test calculated the national averages by means
of a statistical survey of children who were nearly all English
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland and Berkeley school districts sued to block the
release of non-English speakers' scores. Last week, a judge blocked
the state's plans to publish district-by-district results. Tuesday,
an appeals court upheld that decision, pending a July 16 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the state offered Tuesday the averages of
English-speaking students only _ while districts, not bound by the
court ruling, dispensed crazy-quilt numbers of their own. Some
released the English-only results, some handed out all the figures,
and some declined to disclose anything.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state numbers only fueled a bitter debate between
Wilson and Superintendent Delaine Eastin, who is running for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Eastin called the results ``pretty good.'' Referring to
California's last-place showing four years ago on a national exam,
Eastin said: ``At least we're not standing in the deepest hole.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson took a far less charitable view of the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're deplorable,'' he said, discounting the value of any
scores just under 50, the national average. ``We've been seriously
short-changing California children in the quality of their
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastin pledged to focus attention on science, and she chastised
state lawmakers for turning down her bid last year to include
laboratory science in high school graduation requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature turned us down flat,'' she said. ``And members
of both parties whined about how expensive it would be to build
science labs. But this state is the home of the biotech industry,
and we need to strengthen our science requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the state Board of Education is in the process of
choosing new science standards, Eastin said they will mean little
unless such courses are required for graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he favors holding students back a grade if they do
not satisfy academic requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Most districts had released their scores by Tuesday, but many
San Francisco Bay Area school systems would not, including San
Francisco, Oakland, Hayward, West Contra Costa, San Jose and
Ravenswood City in East Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley also opted to withhold its scores _ but only after
giving them out in advance of the court order.
</P>
<P>
   Overall scores in Berkeley hovered above the national average in
every subject but spelling. In general, its scores were also better
than the state's _ even though Berkeley's included those of
non-English-speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relatively good showing, Berkeley Superintendent
Jack McLaughlin objected to releasing the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The figures . . . give an unfair snapshot of a child's, a
school's and a district's performance,'' said McLaughlin, summing
up the objections many educators have about testing children in a
language they do not understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People reading this information are not going to come back in
a month or two months to compare figures. They are going to look at
this information today and say, `That isn't a good school.' Worse,
they will say, `Those (limited-English-speaking) students are
pretty dumb.' That's a horrific label to carry with you when you're
only 7 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Alameda County, Piedmont Unified posted scores that
were far above average _ even in spelling.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Piedmont students outperformed more than 80 percent of
test-takers around the country. Nevertheless, even Piedmont
spellers did flag slightly, scoring generally within the 70th
percentile.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Piedmont scores are good, Patrick Gemma, an
assistant superintendent, said he supports the position that
non-English speakers should not have been tested and included in
the results.
</P>
<P>
   On the Peninsula, children in the well-to-do Portola Valley
schools also posted sky-high scores _ generally outscoring 80 to 90
percent of other children nationwide in reading and math.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Rosa, school officials separated the results of
students who speak the language from those who do not. The
difference is vast.
</P>
<P>
   The average reading score of an 11th-grader who grew up speaking
English is 57. But for a student in the same grade who speaks
little English, the average score is only 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DISCS-ART-NYT     07-05 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DISCS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DVD LEADS RACE FOR MOVIE DISCS, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The companies backing DVD, the CD-size digital disc
that contains a feature-length movie, are boasting a lot these
days, telling anyone who will listen that their product is selling
faster than either compact-disc players or VCRs did at the
corresponding points after they were introduced.
</P>
<P>
   By late June, a little more than a year after the introduction
of DVDs, manufacturers had sold nearly 600,000 DVD players. By
comparison, in March 1985, 16 months after the compact disc was
introduced, only 320,000 players had been sold. For VCRs in
September 1979, the number was 515,000.
</P>
<P>
   As pleased as equipment makers and Hollywood studio executives
are, some acknowledge that in some ways the achievement is hollow
because DVD is in a race for its survival, sprinting to gain a
significant foothold in American homes ahead of two headstrong
rivals. The odds of success are uncertain at best.
</P>
<P>
   One of the competitors is Divx, an upstart hybrid DVD format
that went on sale last month in two test markets, Richmond, Va.,
and San Francisco. A full-scale national introduction is scheduled
for September.
</P>
<P>
   But the other more important adversary is digital cable
television, which is expected to make picture-perfect, digital,
pay-per-view movies a ubiquitous feature in American homes within a
few years, said Warren Lieberfarb, president of Warner Home Video,
the largest distributor of DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of a horse race, not just against Divx, but
against AT&AMP;T and TCI, against Comcast cable _ and the whole
migration to digital pay per view,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, AT&AMP;T Corp. agreed to buy Tele-Communications Inc.,
the United States' second-largest cable company, for $31.8 billion.
One goal of the merged company is to bring pay-per-view movies on
demand to millions of homes. Comcast Corp. and other cable
companies have similar plans, as do some broadcasters, after
digital broadcasting begins in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Liebfarb fears that movies on demand will short-circuit the sale
of movies on discs. Why buy a DVD when you can dial up the same
movie on your television set whenever you want? The medium will
fail, he says, unless DVD is already an entrenched part of family
life, as VCRs are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have three years,'' he said. ``Three years from now
we need to be in 10 million homes.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a tall order, given that the industry has sold only
578,604 DVD players in the last 15 months, according to the
Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association. Initial industry
projections were that 800,000 DVD players would sell in the first
year.
</P>
<P>
   DVD originally stood for digital videodisc. But that name was
abandoned when the designers realized that the discs could be used
for computer files and audio recordings, too, offering seven times
the storage capacity of CD-ROMs and CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the format is simply known as DVD. Though DVDs offer
high-resolution pictures and digital surround-sound, the format
faces its own daunting challenge: most Americans still know nothing
about it.
</P>
<P>
   A study commissioned by the Video Software Dealers Association,
which backs the format, found that 62 percent of those surveyed in
May had never heard of DVD. The study did find some improvement; in
a similar survey a year ago, the number was 81 percent. In the
latest survey, Yankelovich Partners interviewed 1,938 people, all
of whom were at least 18 and owned a VCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally I think it shows that we are seeing an uptick in
consumer awareness,'' said Jeffrey Eves, association president.
</P>
<P>
   But Eves, Lieberfarb and many others worry that Divx (pronounced
DIV-ix) may stand in the way of further progress.
</P>
<P>
   Divx, a technology backed by the Circuit City chain of
electronics stores and a Los Angeles law firm, originally stood for
digital video express. But like DVD, the acronym has become the
name.
</P>
<P>
   Divx discs are DVDs with coding that allows them to be played
only once and only in special players. Zenith Corp. is making the
first player, which accommodates both Divx discs and regular DVDs
and sells for $499 _ a little more than the lowest-priced DVD
players.
</P>
<P>
   Each Divx disc costs $4.49, compared with about $25 for a DVD.
But if a viewer plays the Divx disc after an initial two-day
viewing period, the owner will be charged about $3. The accounting
is done by the Divx central computer, which is connected to the
Divx player by a phone line.
</P>
<P>
   When Circuit City announced the Divx concept last fall, it was
greeted with howls of vitriol from DVD supporters who complained
that the new format would confuse consumers and threaten the
success of DVD. Lieberfarb was among the most vocal critics.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints were so loud that some in the industry predicted
that Divx would never get off the ground _ especially because
Warner Bros. and a few other studios, including Columbia Tri-Star,
have refused to issue movies in the Divx format, fearing it would
undermine the success of DVD.
</P>
<P>
   But on June 7, Divx discs and players went on sale in 45 Circuit
City and Good Guys stores in Richmond and San Francisco. Circuit
City also began advertising Divx on television and in newspapers in
both places.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Home Video countered with a program to encourage video
stores in those two cities and three others to rent DVDs and DVD
players. The Yankelovich survey showed that most people wanted to
be able to rent DVDs just as they do videotapes. But video dealers
have been slow to stock the discs because few people own DVD
players.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Divx and Warner sales programs are so new that neither
company is ready to release results, though Richard Sharp, chief
executive of Circuit City Stores Inc., dismissively said: ``We've
been in some of their stores, and they are offering only about 40
titles'' for rent.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharp is able to do little better. As of Wednesday, only 45
movies were available in the Divx format. Sharp predicts the total
will be 400 by the end of the year. By comparison, 1,400 movies
were available on DVD on July 1; 180 of those were issued in June
alone.
</P>
<P>
   When Divx players go on sale nationally this fall, Circuit City
plans to begin a $100 million advertising campaign. Warner,
meanwhile, says it will offer its DVD rental program nationally in
the fall as well, though Lieberfarb said Warner and allied
companies would spend considerably less than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks Divx, like DVD, must gain a foothold before
pay-per-view services proliferate. Sharp agrees but says he has
five years before that happens.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp predicts that Divx will succeed because the concept offers
several advantages that his research indicates consumers
appreciate. Chief among them is that for about the cost of renting
a videotape, a Divx buyer can take a disc home and keep it,
eliminating return trips to the video store and late fees.
</P>
<P>
   But those two attributes have turned out to be liabilities as
well. The nation's video-rental dealers hate Divx. ``It undermines
the entire business'' by reducing traffic in the stores, Eves said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, no video store has agreed to sell Divx discs. They
can be bought only at at Circuit City and Good Guys stores and the
Divx site on the Internet at www.divx.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing a kind of chicken-and-egg problem,'' Sharp said.
``In time, I think the power of the Divx format will overpower
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
