<SLUG> BC-NAACP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP convention to open amid bright financial outlook, high
morale
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four years ago the nation's oldest civil rights
organization faced a bleak future.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
was $4.8 million in debt and in the midst of a leadership crisis.
Critics questioned the organization's relevancy and morale among
members was low.
</P>
<P>
   As it prepares for its national convention in Atlanta Saturday _
the first time the organization has met here in 36 years _ the
NAACP's financial outlook is decidedly brighter. Morale has
returned and its leadership has begun to restore the organization's
luster. Perhaps its biggest accomplishment is a $2 million budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership of Myrlie Evers Williams did it,'' said Julian
Bond, who replaced Williams as board chairman six months ago. ``She
brought Kweisi Mfume to the president's job, and that combination
of leadership turned the organization around.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention, themed ``Preparing Tomorrow's Leaders Today,''
run-- through July 16 at the Georgia World Congress Center.
Speakers include Vice President Al Gore, Gen. Colin Powell, Ted
Turner and the Rev. Jesse Jackson. More than 6,000 people are
expected to attend. Planned events include an anti-violence march
and rally, a job fair, concerts and workshops. Most events are open
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   A special gospel concert featuring a 200-voice community choir
will be held on Saturday in honor of Jondelle Johnson, the longtime
executive director of the Atlanta NAACP branch who died in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel she'll be in the big NAACP office in the sky listening
in on Saturday,'' said R.L. White, president of the Atlanta branch.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP decided to return to Atlanta because it is now
considered a mecca for blacks, many of whom work in corporations
like Coca Cola, Delta Airlines and NationsBank, which are helping
to sponsor the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time the convention was here there were segregation
signs _ 'whites only,' 'blacks only' water fountains and things,''
said Jesse Hill Jr., former president of Atlanta Life Insurance who
sought corporate support for the convention. ``Given the leadership
of Atlanta, we expected (segregationist laws) to change much
faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, a former Georgia state senator, said the annual convention
is a chance for members to rededicate themselves to tackling issues
that impact minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention is a gathering of the NAACP family,'' Bond
said. ``It allows for an exchange of ideas and to hear new ways of
attacking old problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
