</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Week in Review
 &HT;    (EDS: Sunday games not added are Oakland-Anaheim and
Seattle-Texas.)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Yankees 6-0 (61-20), Red Sox 5-1 (52-33), Blue Jays
5-1 (46-42) Orioles 1-5 (38-50), Devil Rays 0-6 (34-52).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Yankees 13-3, Red Sox 9-7, Blue Jays 9-7,
Orioles 5-11, Devil Rays 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: AL teams took the overall interleague series
from the NL 114-110 as the Yankees had the best record at 13-3. The
NL had won 117-97 last year. The Yankees became the first team ever
to win 60 of its first 80 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Boston's Nomar Garciaparra had his 24-game
hitting streak stopped Saturday by the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Red Sox starter Pedro Martinez is 4-0 in his
last four starts with a 0.93 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Yankees starter Hideki Irabu, who has gone
winless in his last four starts, has given up eight homers in his
last 11 2/3 innings after giving up just five in his first 11
starts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Not like they need him, but Yankees designated
hitter Chili Davis is expected to come off the DL after the break.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: Tampa Bay ace Wilson Alvarez should be back after
the All-Star break, making what was expected to be his last rehab
start Sunday at Class AAA Durham.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Indians 4-2 (50-35), Tigers 4-2 (34-50), Royals 3-3
(38-48), Twins 2-4 (40-46), White Sox 2-4 (35-51).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Indians 10-6, Twins 7-9, White Sox 7-9,
Tigers 7-9, Royals 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: At the break this are by far the worst division
in baseball with just one winning team.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: His power numbers may be lousy (1 HR, 23 RBI),
but Kansas City's Hal Morris is third in the league with a .348
average.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: In a recent at-bat between Cleveland pitcher
Bartolo Colon and Rick Guttierez, the Astros shortstop struck out
on the 20th pitch thrown to him. That's right, Guttierez fouled off
14 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Indians starter Charles Nagy has allowed 25
homers, that is halfway to the major league record which was set by
Bert Blyleven with the Twins in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The White Sox place closer Matt Karchner on the
disabled list with a strained left abductor muscle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The White Sox are shopping outfielder Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: A's 4-1 (40-45), Mariners 3-2 (37-50), Rangers 1-4
(47-39), Angels 1-4 (49-36).
</P>
<P>
   _ Interleague records: Angels 10-6, Rangers 8-8, A's 8-8,
Mariners 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The A's enjoyed their first winning month in
two years (15-13) while the Rangers blew a good chance to get back
into first with the Angels struggling.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. hit the most
interleague homers in the majors with 10. He also homered in four
straight games last week.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Anaheim's Chuck Finley has the best ERA in the
division at 3.05.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: On Saturday the Rangers' Tom Goodwin collected
his first extra base hit in 45 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Angels righthander Mike James is still having
problems with his right forearm and doctors are recommending
season-ending exploratory surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Rangers beat the Mariners 9-2 Saturday in a
game that took 6 hours, 9 minutes to complete because of rain. The
day just so happened to mark the 13th anniversary of the Mets 16-13
win over the Braves in 19 innings that lasted 6 hours, 10 minutes
and ended at 3:55 a.m.
</P>
