<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDER REACTION RAISES DOUBTS ABOUT AT&AMP;T-TCI DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of AT&AMP;T Corp. have fallen 16 percent since its planned
acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc. for $31.8 billion in stock
was announced last month, leading some to speculate that the deal
may have to be renegotiated in light of the poor shareholder
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AT&AMP;T closed Thursday at $54.875, a 52-week low, down
from $65.375 on June 23, the day before the acquisition was
formally announced. The drop is leading many on Wall Street to
wonder if it is a good wedding for the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Tele-Communications, Leo Hindery Jr., was
quoted in The Los Angeles Times on Friday as acknowledging that the
companies might have to renegotiate the deal in light of the poor
shareholder reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery could not be reached for comment Sunday. However,
another person involved in the talks said that there were no plans
at this time to renegotiate terms of the deal and that it would be
``ridiculous'' to think of renegotiating so soon after the deal had
been announced, and before its implications could be absorbed by
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which is based in Basking Ridge, N.J., has not yet filed
complete details of the acquisition of Tele-Communications with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, after some recent mergers have been announced,
shares of both the acquiring companies and the acquired companies
have risen. For example, the stock prices of both Travelers Group
and Citicorp were up for weeks after their merger was announced in
April.
</P>
<P>
   And another person acquainted with both the chief executive of
AT&AMP;T, C. Michael Armstrong, and John Malone, chairman of
Tele-Communications, said the two remained heavily committed to the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are expected to speak at this week's annual summer
conference of media executives held by Allen &AMP; Co. in Sun Valley,
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has said that it will have to pay a $1.75 billion fee if it
fails to win shareholder and regulator approval for the
acquisition. This is about the same amount Worldcom Inc. would have
to pay MCI Communications Corp. if that acquisition fails to take
place.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup fee represents roughly $3 a share to
Tele-Communication's shareholders. An investment banker who
declined to be quoted said, ``Investors tend to see breakup fees as
one-time payments regardless of size,'' and he added that even if
there is some opposition to the AT&AMP;T-TCI deal, it is sometimes
difficult to rally the necessary majority to block a major merger.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T did negotiate a ``collar'' for the deal, meaning that
regardless of how much AT&AMP;T stock falls, the telecommunications
giant will not have to guarantee Tele-Communications any additional
cash or stock per share.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the acquisition, AT&AMP;T will also assume TCI's debt
of about $11 billion. The $31.8 billion purchase price also does
not include $5.5 billion in cash AT&AMP;T will pay to repurchase shares
that AT&AMP;T issued to TCI in a previous transaction and to acquire
its interest in a cable-modem venture that delivers high-speed
Internet data over television cables. But in announcing the deal,
the companies added these amounts to their calculation of the
value, for a total of $48.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Combining AT&AMP;T's financial muscle and nation-spanning
communications network with Tele-Communications' wires into
millions of homes would create a communications behemoth with a
reach unrivaled since AT&AMP;T spun off its local phone operations in
1984 in an antitrust settlement with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   If investors remain extremely skeptical about the price of the
deal, it is in large part because of the high cost associated with
upgrading cable's one-way video to a two-way delivery system that
can deliver voice and data as well as video.
</P>
</TEXT>
