<SLUG> BC-ALLSTAR-AARON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aaron recalls Home Run Derby of old
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Years ago before there was a home run hitting contest
at the All-Star Game, there was a televised program called ``Home
Run Derby.'' It was the prelude to what fans will watch tonight,
when the best power hitters in baseball slug it out at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Home Run Derby' was a blast,'' said Hank Aaron, the show's
top money-winner. ``I had fun, but the real reason I did it was
because of the money. Back then that was good money for me, and I
took the money I won and bought a grocery store for my father.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a rather simple format. Two hitters would get three outs
per inning and play nine innings. Anything that didn't go over the
fence was an out. A called strike by the umpire was an out. The
player with the most home runs after nine innings received the
winner's total of $2,000. The loser got $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   A player who hit three homers in a row got a bonus of $500 and
another $500 for four straight.
</P>
<P>
   The setting was empty Wrigley Field in south-central Los
Angeles, where minor league teams, owned by the same chewing gum
tycoon from Chicago, had played for years. It was 339 feet down the
left- and right-field lines. The power alleys were 345.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great for me, because I pulled a lot of balls to
left,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   The television shows were taped after the 1959 season, and some
of the greatest hitters of all-time participated. The first matchup
was between Mickey Mantle and Willie Mays. Mantle beat Mays with a
home run in the bottom of the ninth to win 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   But Aaron enjoyed the most success during his four days of
competition.
</P>
<P>
   He beat Ken Boyer 9-6, Jim Lemon 6-4, Eddie Mathews 4-3, Al
Kaline 5-1, Duke Snider 3-1 and Bob Allison 3-2. He finally was
beaten by Wally Post 7-4, but Aaron made $13,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to have to be good, because I would have
one shot,'' Aaron said. ``The one thing I remember the most is
beating my teammate, Mathews. I remember hating facing him. I think
we were the only teammates to face each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron beat Mathews with a two-out homer in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The show was broadcasted in 1960. Mark Scott, the announcer and
creator, died of a heart attack. The tapes then sat on a shelf at
the MGM studios for more than 25 years before ESPN bought the
rights in 1988. They sometimes are shown on the Classic Sports
Network.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only time Aaron ever participated in such a contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a few of them during the season, and I didn't
participate in them because they messed up my swing,'' he said. ``I
never thought home runs were all that exciting. I still think the
triple is the most exciting thing in baseball. To me, a triple is
like a guy taking the ball on his 1-yard line and running 99 yards
for a touchdown. Don't get me wrong; home runs are important. They
win a lot of games. But I never understood, and still don't
understand, why fans are so obsessed with them. I think watching a
guy hit a ball over the fence and trot around the bases is actually
pretty boring.''
</P>
<P>
   1960 HR DERBY TV RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Player W-L HR Earnings
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron 6-1 34 $13,500
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Mantle 4-1 44 $10,000
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Jensen 2-2 29 $8,500
</P>
<P>
   Willie Mays 3-2 35 $8,000
</P>
