<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last play of game becomes a sideshow in Braves-Mets contest
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ New York catcher Mike Piazza says he didn't bobble the
throw. Manager Bobby Valentine accused Atlanta's Michael Tucker of
a dirty and illegal slide and reliever John Franco claims home
plate umpire Angel Hernandez still doesn't know what exactly
happened.
</P>
<P>
   This much is crystal clear: New York's blueprint for catching
the Braves in the National League East _ pulling within five games
before slugger Todd Hundley's return from the disabled list later
this month _ must be reconditioned.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets head into the All-Star break, they find themselves
trailing the Braves by 12 1/2 games after Atlanta's three-game
sweep this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And the final play in Sunday's 3-2 loss _ Walt Weiss' sacrifice
fly that scored Tucker from third for the winning run in the 11th
inning _ was an opportunity for some Mets to vent their
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is I've got more wound marks on my catcher,''
Valentine said. ``(Piazza) has got spike marks that are five inches
deep. I've got a wounded catcher and another loss. It's a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' said Piazza, who says he won't
require stitches in his right thigh. ``I looked over at their bench
and they were jumping up and down. I didn't know what the hell was
going on because I had the ball. I thought he was out and I was
ready to go to the next inning. That's a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' liner off Franco was caught by left fielder Bernard
Gilkey, whose one-hop throw to Piazza beat Tucker to the plate.
Valentine claims Tucker slid with his leg high, so Tucker could
have never touched home plate. ``(Tucker) hasn't hit the ground
yet,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   After Hernandez called Tucker safe, though, Valentine says he
believed Piazza dropped the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Mike dropped the ball. The ball beat him easily and
the guy jumped into Mike's lap,'' Valentine said. ``(Hernandez)
said he slid under the tag.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco claims Hernandez offered conflicting events.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, (Hernandez) said he dropped the ball,'' Franco said.
``Then he said his leg got under. He doesn't even know.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco and Valentine immediately swarmed Hernandez, and umpire
crew chief Randy Marsh said both Mets made contact with Hernandez.
Valentine and Franco could face suspensions and possibly fines from
NL president Leonard Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Marsh) had better look at the (expletive) film,'' Valentine
said. ``I never touched him. If there was any contact out there, it
was because they were trying to walk off the field. ... It was
really hard to appeal it to third base. That (umpire) was already
in the dressing room.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Marsh offered the only interpretation that really
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there was a bobble there,'' Marsh said. ``But
looking at the tape, it looked like Piazza bent over trying to
smother it. But the bottom line was (Tucker) got his foot down in
there, before (Piazza) was even doing that, before he put the tag
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
