<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-DISNEY-ART-NYT     07-05 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-DISNEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PICKET LINE WITH MICKEY, PLUTO AND CAPTAIN HOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARNE-LA-VALLEE, France _ Mickey Mouse has been on the picket
lines here at Disneyland Paris for almost two weeks. Captain Hook
wants more money, and so does Pluto, who says he loves his work but
hardly has a bone to gnaw on come the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't hope to find a more wholesome-looking group of
French labor militants, all with Disneyland regulation haircuts and
cheerfully greeting French, German, Belgian and Italian visitors on
their way in for an afternoon of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love working here,'' said Arnaud M., a 26-year-old Parisian
who wears a Pluto costume in the daily parades down Main Street USA
when he's working, but was as reluctant to say so as he was to see
his last name published in a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to spoil the illusion for the kids,'' he said as
he and about 50 fellow strikers, some wearing prisoner costumes
with balls and chains, demonstrated cheerfully for higher wages
outside the amusement park's main gate. ``And I don't want to run
the risk of retaliation by management after the strike is over.''
</P>
<P>
   French fascination with American popular culture is almost as
strong as French attraction to the benefits of the European welfare
state, but the clash produced a Disneyland strike as the summer
season began _ another summer that the park expects to be
profitable, after starting up heavily in the red in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney asked us to help them out at the beginning by making
sacrifices, and we accepted,'' said Isabelle Perche, a member of
the French Christian Workers' Confederation who is a technician at
the park. ``Now they won't recognize they have an obligation to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Euro Disney SCA, the company that runs the park, lost nearly $1
billion in the 1992-93 season under American management but then
hired a French chief executive, Philippe Bourguignon, and lowered
admission prices. It reported a profit of more than $36 million
last year, the third consecutive year it was in the black.
</P>
<P>
   Isabelle Clap, a spokeswoman for the company, said it was
talking with the striking employees through the weekend in hopes of
reaching a settlement. Only 40 out of 13,000 employees were
striking Saturday, the company said, not causing any disruptions to
its operations, including the parade, which had a full complement
of 12 floats.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the 13,000 are union members, Miss Perche said, and none
of the parade workers are, though hers is not the only union that
has been offering them advice; the Communist General Confederation
of Labor has also supported their demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of employees who sympathize with the demands
they are making,'' said Miss Perche. She said she earned about $880
a month after payroll deductions and taxes, for a 39-hour week
running attractions at the park, barely above the French minimum
wage, about $6.75 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has raised the minimum wage by about 2 percent
a year, so mostly Disneyland has just kept even with that,'' one of
the strikers said.
</P>
<P>
   A youth who said he had played Captain Hook in the parade for
five years said there had been as many as 200 Disney employees on
the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us earn about 7,500 francs a month gross,'' he said,
the equivalent of about $1,250. ``What we want is recognition that
under French law we should be paid as amusement park performance
artists, which would give us about 9,500.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the equivalent of $1,580; French law also requires
employers to pay about 40 percent more in payroll taxes and
insurance and unemployment benefits, and grant all employees five
weeks of paid vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Other amusement parks in France were only seasonal, Arnaud M.
(Pluto) said, one of many reasons why he had been happy to stay at
Disneyland, open 365 days a year, for seven years, though he might
have been able to find more lucrative employment elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just fantastic to see the expressions on the faces of
little kids when you come up to them in your costume and say
hello,'' he said. ``I love what I do, but the costumes are hot and
heavy in the summer and on cold winter days you freeze, but the
show goes on no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Michel Dompnier, the Disneyland Paris labor relations director,
said the company had increased wages by an average of 8 percent
over the last three years, above the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   He offered parade performers a chance to make more money by
paying them higher salaries when they worked in special shows, for
which they would have to audition, and unspecified improvements in
working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The company would also make what he called ``an additional
effort in the field of training.'' Miss Perche said permanent
employees often found themselves obliged to train temporary hires
but were not given extra compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Disneyland employees in the United States probably make more
money than their French counterparts by working overtime, Miss
Perche said, but French practice is to discourage overtime and
create jobs instead. Soon Disneyland, like all other French
employers, will have to reduce the work week to 35 hours, with no
cut in pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our way of seeing things is different,'' she said. ``I don't
think you can compare the two worlds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
