<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-AIRPORT-COX-     07-05 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-AIRPORT-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    DRAMATIC NEW $9.1 BILLION HONG KONG AIRPORT DEBUTS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE: Updates with airport opening as planned.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    EDS: For Monday AMs. With sidebar COX-AIRPORT-STATS. Please note
Atlanta, Denver, angles.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Jumbojets from around the globe on Monday
inaugurated the new $9.1 billion Hong Kong International Airport,
one of the most advanced and architecturally dramatic airports in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay Pacific was accorded the honor of the first flight when
its 15-hour nonstop jumbo jet Flight CX 889 from New York landed 10
minutes early, at 6:20 a.m. (6:20 p.m. Sunday EDT). That was
followed by about 30 more takeoffs and landings within the first
hour of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Though air travel has been diminished by the Asian financial
crisis, more than 30 million passengers a year are expected to pass
through the soaring white glass-and-steel terminal that is
described as the world's largest public building.
</P>
<P>
   Following nine years of planning, the most crucial hours in
opening the airport were the final 13 leading up to the first
commercial flights.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 5:30 p.m. Sunday evening, thousands of workers
undertook a Promethean transfer of airport loading ramps, fueling
trucks and other equipment to the new airport. The Chinese news
agency Xinhua called the move from Hong Kong's old Kai Tak airport
the biggest peacetime transfer of material ever.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong roads were closed, hundreds of police called out to
keep the order and curious locals shooed away from the 18-mile road
corridor separating the two air fields.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 vehicles in 16 convoys were scripted to haul the
apparatus necessary to make Hong Kong International function, from
tractors and pallet pushers to 70,000 sets of silverware for the
catering service.
</P>
<P>
   Heavier equipment was slotted to sail on 14 barges westward
through Victoria Harbor to the new facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every airport has its problems,'' said the airport's corporate
development director Clinton Leeks in an interview. ``I don't know
what ours will be. We'll find out, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the airport's attractions is the Airport Express, a rail
link that connects passengers at speeds of up to 81 MPH with two
downtown check-in terminals in Hong Kong center and Kowloon. The
train takes just 23 minutes to reach the airport, which is built on
the island of Chek Lap Kok in the South China Sea 18 miles west of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Another attraction -- if it works -- is one of the world's
largest baggage handling conveyer systems. It promises to deliver
arriving luggage to the baggage carousels in 15 minutes, the
average length of time it will take passengers to have their
passports stamped and reach the baggage area.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong airport overseers originally planned to use a
computerized baggage routing system. But after dispatching an
inspection team to the new Denver airport, they decided to defer
plans for a Denver-like automatic routing system until it can be
proven at other airports.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the new Hong Kong airport recruited an army of baggage
handlers big enough to unload and route 20,000 bags an hour along
nine miles of conveyer belts.
</P>
<P>
   While landing, passengers will look down on a single gigantic
Y-shaped terminal three-quarters of a mile long that resembles the
profile of an airplane in flight. Once inside the terminal, they
will be under a giant lightweight vaulted roof big enough to
contain 85 American football fields.
</P>
<P>
   The terminal's top level is for check-in and passport control,
the middle level is for duty-free shops and departure gates, and
the bottom level is for arrivals and baggage carousels.
</P>
<P>
   ``To know where to go, you simply follow the roof,'' the British
architect Sir Norman Foster has said. ``You follow the lines of the
vaulted arch structure, and although you are moving through a
variety of spaces, you always know where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Foster has told local journalists that his design was
inspired by an old aerial photograph of Atlanta's wedge-shaped
airport terminal in the 1930s. He said he was trying to capture the
``simplicity'' of the old Atlanta airport and ``achieve that
simplicity in an international airport.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Hong Kong International, which is designed mainly for
jumbojets, has 38 terminal-side ``air bridges'' that can handle
Boeing 747s or European Airbuses. It is building 10 positions for
the 600-passenger Airbus super-jumbojets that are now under
development in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hong Kong is under Chinese sovereignty, passengers will
find that Chinese censorship rules do not apply here. One of the
books prominently displayed in an airport bookshop is ``The Private
Life of Chairman Mao'' by the late communist leader Mao Tse-tung's
private physician Li Zhisui, a book banned in mainland China
because of its graphic descriptions of Mao's sexual adventures.
</P>
<P>
   On its opening day, the new Hong Kong airport expects about half
the traffic volume of the world's three busiest airports, Chicago
O'Hare (69 million passengers in 1966), Atlanta's Hartsfield (63
million in 1966) and Dallas/Fort Worth (58 million in 1966).
</P>
<P>
   But within a decade, Hong Kong airport authorities plan to open
second huge terminal, this one X-shaped, that they say will
increase the passenger capacity to 89 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong will compete with new-generation airports in Tokyo,
Singapore, Kuala Lumpur and Seoul to become the dominant Asian hub
in 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   While Monday was the first day of commercial flights, the
airport opened to several VIP flights last Thursday - one by
President Jiang Zemin and another by President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong International Airport is part of a $20 billion air,
road and rail transportation plan that Hong Kong's British colonial
rulers announced in 1989. Beijing raised angry objections because
of the large cost, but after negotiations China and Britain reached
agreement in 1994, three years before the British handed over Hong
Kong to Chinese rule.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Hong Kong poured out in the last few days to say
good-bye to the old airport, whose downtown Kowloon location made
it a nuisance to neighboring residents and a great convenience to
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday and Sunday thousands perched on the bridges and
waterfront rocks to photograph the last thunderous jet arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   Through the final day aircraft continued gliding down between
mountains and skyscrapers in the sharp right turn that for years
has paralyzed unwitting passengers wondering why their pilot was
hurtling them into the high-rise core of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at Chek Lap Kok will be neither so frightening nor so
exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will still see sights,'' insisted Lily Mg, a 20-year-old
college student working with the Airport Authority this summer,
``but it won't be in such close proximity that you think you'll
land in someone's flat.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
