<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1111 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-POLITICS-ART     07-05 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABSENT A BATTLE CRY, WAR FOR THE HOUSE IS FOUGHT AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A graphic on the 10 hottest congressional races is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After two congressional elections that were seen as
referendums on the nation's direction, this year's battle for
control of the House is being fought the old-fashioned way _
candidate by candidate and district by district.
</P>
<P>
   In a year marked by a pro-incumbent contentment with the
economy, only 65 House races are even considered by the political
parties to be truly competitive. Yet with the Republicans holding
one of the slimmest majorities of this century, the Democrats need
a net gain of just 11 seats to reclaim control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers mean that Rep. Newt Gingrich's longevity as
Speaker could depend less on sweeping political themes than on a
chain of local circumstances: the decision by Rep. Wes Watkins,
R-Okla., not to retire after all, or the question of whether voters
in Hawaii decide to punish Democrats, like Rep. Neil Abercrombie,
for the local economic recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time you don't have a presidential race going on and you
don't have a national wave one way or another,'' said Rep. Martin
Frost of Texas, chairman of the House Democrats' election
committee. ``So it's really trench warfare, district by district.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates across the nation, of course, are still striking
certain common chords. Democrats, for instance, are riding the
reform of managed health care as a central campaign theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are key issues out there that are going to have an
impact,'' said Rep. Frank Pallone of New Jersey, one of the
Democrats considered potentially vulnerable by Republicans this
year. ``The one I'm focusing on is managed-care reform. And I think
people will respond because they think this is a do-nothing
Congress that is not focusing on key issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich sent his incumbents out to campaign over the July 4th
Congressional recess on a message of tax-cutting. Rep. John Linder,
the Georgian who heads the Republicans' re-election effort, said
his party will be stressing ``that we have balanced the budget with
tax cuts and put people back to work'' who had been on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time in almost a decade, the words of the late
House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill seem most apt: ``All politics is
local.'' Strategists for the two parties sense none of the volatile
anti-Washington animus that gave a national cast to recent
elections, when voters rallied against a recession, entrenched
incumbents or legislative overreaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-four was an election where the Republicans didn't want
to talk about anything but Bill Clinton,'' said Geoffrey Garin, a
Democratic pollster, ``ninety-six an election where Democrats
didn't want to talk about anything but Newt Gingrich. Ninety-eight
will be a different kind of election where candidates talk about
each other. There's not a single issue that's driving the election
from border to border and coast to coast.''
</P>
<P>
   In their drive to hold the majority won four years ago,
Republicans have history on their side. Traditionally, the party in
the White House loses seats in its sixth year in office. And
Republicans are forecasting at least a 10-seat gain in November.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican incumbents, though, are being forced to struggle
for their seats. Rep. Connie Morella, a moderate from Maryland, is
thought to be facing the strongest, most well-financed challenger
of her six terms in Ralph Neas, the former executive director of
the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Neas has accused Ms. Morella of moving to the right during her
years in office. After appearing at a Fourth of July parade this
weekend, however, Ms. Morella said that by putting an emphasis on
health care, technology issues and education, she was a ``good
mirror of my district.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats see several reasons why they may be able to defy
history, starting with the fact that retirements from Congress left
them with fewer vulnerable open seats to defend this year than the
Republicans. They also boast some well-funded candidates who may be
able to overcome the GOP's usual advantage in raising money. And
even Republicans concede that the voters' ``six-year itch'' for
change may have come four years early, in 1994, when Republicans
took control of the House for the first time in nearly half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an 11-seat margin, one or two breaks the right way can
make the big difference,'' said Mark Mellman, a Democratic
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   There's no better barometer of how small events can make a
difference in the electoral math this year than the sharp mood
swings among House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   They started the year confident of a serene election, then began
to panic in late spring that they could lose the House. Now, they
have been bolstered by a handful of recent developments that have
even nonpartisan campaign handicappers like Stuart Rothenberg and
Charlie Cook calling it unlikely that the Democrats can take the
majority.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For one, Republican leaders made a successful appeal to Watkins
to reconsider his plans to retire. Watkins, a longtime Democrat who
changed parties and ran for Congress as a Republican in 1996, was
considered the sole Republican who could hold a seat so Democratic
that his district was long ago dubbed ``Little Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the California primary in June saw the triumph of
two moderate Republicans who are considered the party's strongest
candidates to run in districts in Sacramento and the Los Angeles
area, now held by Democrats Vic Fazio, who is retiring, and Jane
Harman, who made an unsuccessful bid for her party's gubernatorial
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And in a special election in Albuquerque, N.M., to replace Rep.
Steven Schiff, who died of skin cancer, Republican Heather Wilson
won the seat after a Green Party candidate siphoned votes from Phil
Maloof, the Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to have some momentum from this,'' said Linder.
Democrats still say they can secure a majority of the 435 House
seats by winning eight of the 10 most competitive seats being
vacated by Republicans and then defeating nine of the weakest GOP
incumbents. That still leaves room for the Democrats to lose a
handful of their own seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans counter that they can increase their majority by
at least 10. They are counting on winning five of the seats where
Democratic incumbents are retiring and defeating 10 other
Democrats. Those calculations allow them to lose as many as five of
their own seats, although Mary Crawford, a spokeswoman for the
Republican election effort, said, ``Our folks really believe that
unless something dramatic happens we won't lose a single
incumbent.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are targeting freshman lawmakers who are less
entrenched, such as Rep. Vince Snowbarger, R-Kan., and Rep. James
Maloney, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans are also fighting hardest in swing
districts that are seeing the retirement of incumbents,
particularly in the Middle West and along the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   In California alone, eight seats are considered competitive. The
politically volatile North Coast California district where Rep.
Frank Riggs is retiring could be one of the most difficult for the
Republicans to retain. State Sen. Mike Thompson, a Democrat, is
opposing Mark Luce, the Napa County supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats are likely to have trouble holding onto the
California seats of Fazio and Ms. Harman. The districts lean
Republican and the nomination of two moderate Republicans who
support abortion rights, businessman Doug Ose and Assemblyman
Steven Kuykendall, is thought to give the GOP an edge. They are
facing Sandie Dunn, a lawyer, and Janice Hahn, a businesswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, the Republicans are counting on popular
governors at the top of the ticket to carry weak incumbents. Gov.
Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania is expected to help Rep. Jon Fox of the
Philadelphia suburbs. Fox won by only 84 votes in 1996 over Joseph
Hoeffel, and had to come through a primary fight this spring.
Hoeffel, a county commissioner, is challenging him again.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say they will be able to do well in some unexpected
places, because this year their candidates better match the
philosophy of their districts. In an open seat in Kentucky, for
example, the Democrat, Ken Lucas, is a county judge who is an
anti-abortion social conservative. He faces Republican state Sen.
Gex Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign year might yet turn more volatile in its last
weeks. In 1994, the collapse of President Clinton's health-care
plan and the legislative maneuvering over the crime bill late in
the Congressional session helped propel the Republicans into the
majority. And two years ago, support for Democrats began to drop as
questions about President Clinton's campaign financing emerged in
late October.
</P>
<P>
   A wild card for both parties is the course of the investigation
of Clinton by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel. ``The big
question none of us has been able to answer,'' said Ralph Reed, a
Republican strategist, ``is what happens with the scandal?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
