</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wild ending sends Braves to break with 12 1/2 game lead in NL
East
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The season's first half didn't merely end Sunday. It
went out with a Grade B riot, Braves prancing off one side of
Turner Field with their most dominant start ever, the Mets in
purple rage slam-dancing the umpires off the other side like a
lynch mob looking for a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'd ever been so pursued after the last out before,
crew chief Randy Marsh replied, ''Dominican winter league. Then
when you get off the field, they have the paddy wagon to take you
back to the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves beat New York 3-2 in the 11th inning on the merit of
Walt Weiss' so short sacrifice fly and an ensuing collision at home
plate between Michael Tucker and Mets catcher Mike Piazza. Plate
ump Angel Hernandez called Tucker safe and provoking nearly a
minute of civil disobedience as New York pitcher John Franco,
manager Bobby Valentine and Piazza and eventually the whole Mets
roster made for an umpire mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets cried rotten call and illegal slide. The Braves
celebrated around Tucker's right foot, which the team claims found
the plate beneath Piazza. Anyone who says he has no doubts about
the play isn't being truthful. But what remained afterwards was a
three-game sweep of the Mets, an eight-game Atlanta win streak, a
12-1/2 game lead in the NL East (the Braves' biggest ever) and 59
wins by a club that just last week was turned sideways.
</P>
<P>
   ''You gotta give an A to the first half,'' said third baseman
Chipper Jones. ''There's not much more we could have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Seanez, Atlanta's fifth pitcher of the day, earned his
first victory as a Brave after the bullpen shut out New York for
the last four innings. The Braves had men in scoring position in
both the ninth and 10th but loaded the bases on Franco on two hit
batters and a single. That brought up Weiss, who worked out a 2-1
count before sending a liner into left.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I hit it, I said, alright, base hit. Game over,'' Weiss
said. ''But the outfield was playing right behind the infield and
when (Bernard Gilkey) caught it, I didn't think Tuck had a chance
to score.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tucker tagged up anyway, Gilkey's throw came on one hop and
Piazza cradled the ball waiting the the collision, which Tucker
provided an instant later.
</P>
<P>
   ''He made a very illegal slide, cut him up and never touched the
plate,'' said Valentine. ``He landed in his lap.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he landed all over him and while video replays can
support either team, Hernandez ruled Tucker's foot reached the
plate before any contact with the catcher's mitt.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the ball gets there,'' asked Tucker, ''and he tags you on
your knee, where's the rest of your foot at?''
</P>
<P>
   On the All-Star break, that's where.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
