u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN06-COX     07-05 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pete Sampras wins fifth Wimbledon
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The brown, dried out grass on Centre Court
feels as comfortable as his own practice court to Pete Sampras _
even on the last day of Wimbledon, when the stands are filled with
distractions and the turf pocked with wear.
</P>
<P>
   It is a homey place, where Sampras can curse the bad bounces or
bless the hard ground, even though he still gets more nervous for a
final here than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The top seed did all three Sunday before defeating 14th seed
Goran Ivanisevic 6-7 (2-7), 7-6 (11-9), 6-4, 3-6, 6-2 in 2 hours,
52 minutes and then taking the fifth victory lap of his career
around his favorite court in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to all the finals I've played, this is by far the
toughest,'' Sampras said. ``Obviously, you never forget the first
one, but it's hard to believe that I've won five.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic, the 26-year-old soccer-loving Croatian, wasbereft
after losing what he called his best chance at a Grand Slam title.
Following the match, he briefly displayed the second-place trophy
for the crowd, but his drooping head and shoulders expressed his
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot cheer for anybody now,'' he said, explaining that he
will not go to France to watch his country play in the World Cup
semifinals Wednesday. ``I can only kill myself. It's the worst
moment of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Sampras, this comes close to the best of his life.
</P>
<P>
   His five Wimbledon titles tie the Open Era record set by Bjorn
Borg in 1980. It also gives Sampras 11 Grand Slam victories in his
10-year career. His goal has long been to break Roy Emerson's
record of 12 Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Laver and Borg, both Sampras' heroes when he was growing up
in Los Angeles, are the only two others to win 11 Grand Slams.
Sampras said he believes he can win six Wimbledons, but he said
Sunday was a day to celebrate No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking much about next year,'' Sampras said. ``(This
year) is going to take a little bit of time to sink in because as a
kid when I saw Borg's five, I never thought that I would be in a
position to tie it. It's a little overwhelming to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory also ensures Sampras, 26, will remain No. 1 in the
world _ a loss would have moved Marcelo Rios ahead of him _ and
should help quiet the critics charging that Sampras was distracted
and his career was waning.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a year since his last Grand Slam victory, longer
than between any Grand Slam victories since the 1994 and 1995
Wimbledon. He had heard the talk but didn't pay much attention to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play at a certain level for a number of years and you
don'tplay well for three months or four months and people think
you're done,'' Sampras said. ``It's flattering to be at that
standard, but now I guess I'm out of my slump.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. Part of the reason for the `slump' is that
Sampras has lost eight matches this year, only won two titles and
players, even himself, finally consider the five-year No. 1
beatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts the most,'' Ivanisevic said, comparing his three
losses in the Wimbledon final. ``Because this time I had the
chance. He didn't play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Both started nervously, each double faulting often and blowing
break-point chances in the first set before heading to a tiebreaker
that Ivanisevic won easily. The second set also went to a
tiebreaker, which Sampras won and considered a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic got two second serves, when he was up 6-5 and 8-7 in
the tiebreaker. He only needed one to win the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew these two set points are going to my backhand, and I
missed them both, which is ridiculous,'' Ivanisevic said.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras won the tiebreaker on his third set point. In the next
set, he earned a service break and that was all he needed to win.
In the fourth, Ivanisevic earned the break _ on a string of four
stunning passing shots _ and won the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit four great shots,'' Sampras said. ``That's too good. I
knew it was going to a fifth set at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't a good set. Sampras broke Ivanisevic in the sixth
game, and the world's 25th-ranked player started to resemble the
moody, inconsistent player he has the reputation of being.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fourth and fifth sets, my legs were not fresh, like I
was supposed to be, and I didn't move into the net,'' Ivanisevic
said.``Yes. Five-four against (Richard) Krajicek cost me this
final.''
</P>
<P>
   He lost two match points at 5-4 in the fourth set of his
semifinal against Krajicek on Friday. He lost that set and played
another 77 minutes in the fifth before winning 15-13.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have the energy or the mental fight for another
longfifth set. Sampras broke Ivanisevic at love in the final game.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Ivanisevic's self-loathing after the match,
Sampraspraised his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to win this event, I feel,'' Sampras said. ``His
game is too big and his serve is too big. You just need a little
bit of luck to win any major and he just hasn't seemed to have
gotten that in his three finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Clarke writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
