<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE PIRACY AND A RETRACTED RELEASE 
BUYING CARS ONLINE WITH `REASONABLE OFFERS' 
A WINDOWLESS LINE OF COMPUTERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.J., Calif.)   (jw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFTWARE PIRACY AND A RETRACTED RELEASE
</P>
<P>
   The Software Publishers Association got a little ahead of itself
last week in promoting its efforts to crack down on software
piracy. Last Monday, it sent out a two-page press release
indicating that it had reached an out-of-court settlement for
$150,000 with a New Jersey medical supply company. The release
stated that the company, Edison-based International Technidyne
Corp., agreed that it had used unlicensed or pirated software from
23 of the association's companies.
</P>
<P>
   There was just one catch: The company had agreed to settle, but
not to have the settlement disclosed. Hours after the release went
out, company lawyers called the Software Publishers Association and
demanded a retraction. The trade group acquiesced, distributing a
new release, which read in its entirety:
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier today the Software Publishers Association (SPA) issued
a press release entitled `Software Piracy Costs NJ Firm $150,000.'
SPA retracts the release. Neither SPA nor the company concerned
will now comment publicly. SPA apologizes for any inconvenience
this may have caused.''
</P>
<P>
   David Phelps, a spokesman for the Software Publishers, explained
afterward that the organization had been eager to get its latest
victory to the press. ``As a good PR department, we wanted to get
the news out,'' Phelps said, but ``we didn't look closely enough''
at the settlement agreement. ``We've got to take our licks on this
one,'' he said, adding that the trade group will be more cautious
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The association has good reason to highlight its victories. For
one, it needs to justify its existence to some 1,200 members,
including most of the major software makers in the United States.
Less cynically, it hopes to drive home the message that it will
pursue and audit companies that don't pay for the software they
use.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Feldman, president of International Technidyne, had little
to say on the matter. ``We feel bound by the confidentiality
agreement,'' Feldman said. ``We're surprised to have to comment on
this at all.''
</P>
<P>
   BUYING CARS ONLINE WITH `REASONABLE OFFERS'
</P>
<P>
   Will car dealers be more willing than airlines to leap at
dollars dangled under their noses?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question facing Priceline, an Internet service that
is meant to let consumers buy things by making ``reasonable
offers'' that sellers can choose whether to accept.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline's first service, for air tickets, met a chilly
response from airlines, which do not want to undercut their high
last-minute fares for business travelers by letting customers
propose their own discounted offers. Only a few domestic airlines
have agreed to participate, and so Priceline can fill only about a
quarter of customer offers, which must be within 15 percent of the
lowest published fare.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Priceline plans to introduce a car-buying service
with fewer restrictions than its airline service, and it may have a
better chance of acceptance among the many highly competitive car
dealers. In essence, consumers log on to Priceline.com and specify
the cars they are looking for along with the options and colors
they would accept, and the price they will pay. These offers are
sent by fax to every car dealer within the region specified by the
buyer. The first dealer to call and accept the bid sells the car.
Dealers can also submit a counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   In existing online car buying services, like Autoweb, Carpoint
and Autobytel, customers enter the car they want. Then, typically,
one dealer calls them back to name a price and try to close a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about our service is that you never talk to a
car salesman,'' said Jay Walker, Priceline's chairman. ``You show
up with your check and you drive the car home.''
</P>
<P>
   A WINDOWLESS LINE OF COMPUTERS
</P>
<P>
   As a market test, Ralph Nader's Consumer Project on Technology
recently tried to order a personal computer from a dozen companies
without Microsoft's Windows as the operating system. No luck,
reported David Chun, the Nader summer intern who made the calls to
Dell Computer, Gateway, IBM and others _ not even when he asked for
a PC with no operating system at all.
</P>
<P>
   He should have called VA Research in Mountain View, Calif. The
upstart computer maker specializes in machines that run Linux, a
freeware version of the Unix operating system. Linux (pronounced
(LINN-uks) originated in 1991, written by a young Finnish
programmer, Linus Torvalds.
</P>
<P>
   VA Research began in 1993 as a part-time venture for Larry
Augustin, then working on his doctorate in electrical engineering
at Stanford University. He could not afford a costly Sun
Microsystems work station, so he decided to build his own
high-powered machine, using Linux and off-the-shelf hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Linux has become a more mainstream operating system,
and VA Research is beginning to take off, but Augustin, 35,
declines to disclose revenues for the private company. VA
Research's machines start at $1,500, but the line extends to server
models that can cost tens of thousands of dollars. Its customers
include Southwestern Bell, a unit of SBC Communications Inc., which
uses the Linux machines in its call-processing centers.
</P>
<P>
   Linux users worldwide now number about 6 million, tiny compared
with the more than 300 million for Windows. Still, as Augustin sees
it: ``Microsoft is always going to get its share. But Linux does
have a future as a genuine alternative to Windows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
