<HEADER>
A1139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-HORSEMEAT-VOTE-     07-05 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HORSEMEAT-VOTE-ART-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO HORSEMEAT, CALIFORNIA VOTERS CAN JUST SAY NEIGH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTELOPE VALLEY, Calif. _ The scenery around the retirement
community that Linda Moss manages here is flat, chalky and
desolate, and the slow-moving, spindly-legged retirees don't have
much to occupy their days.
</P>
<P>
   But the sun is reliable, the company is dependable and the
alternative might be considered harsh. The roughly 300 residents in
Ms. Moss' care almost exited life as sausages or steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moss runs a rescue center in this dust bowl between Los
Angeles and the Mojave Desert for old, disabled or unwanted horses
that were bound for slaughterhouses in Texas or Nebraska and for
sale abroad to French, Belgian or Japanese restaurants and meat
shops.
</P>
<P>
   The animals on her 40-acre ranch are refugees from an industry
and culinary tradition of which few Americans are even aware. They
are also poster creatures for one of the latest initiative drives
in the nation's most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   Come November, Californians, who recently weighed in on the
fates of bilingual education and affirmative action, will be asked
to decide the destiny of horses: specifically, whether to make it
illegal to participate in the sale or purchase of a horse pegged
for human ingestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the least we can do for a nice animal that's given so
much to us,'' Cathleen Doyle, one of the initiative's principal
backers, said as she walked with Ms. Moss among the Arabians,
Clydesdales and thoroughbreds at the Equus Sanctuary here.
</P>
<P>
   These women and their allies have named the initiative ``Save
the Horses'' and hitched it to a number of informal slogans,
including ``Off the Table, In the Stable'' and ``Just Say Neigh.''
It is intended to spare what Ms. Doyle estimated to be about 10,000
horses in California every year from winding up as breakfast, lunch
or dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But the referendum also draws attention to people's complicated,
contradictory attitudes toward the animals they raise and to the
fuzzy, fickle lines they draw between acceptable and unacceptable
uses of different beasts.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the supporters of ``Save the Horses'' happily chew the
flesh of cows and pigs and issue no particular lament over horses
dragging heavy carriages of wealthy tourists through American
cities in the oppressive summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   But sirloin of pinto? ``It just strikes the wrong chord,'' said
Bill Hemby, a legislative advocate for the California Organization
of Police and Sheriffs, one of several groups to endorse the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give you a hard and fast ideological reason,'' Hemby
said. ``I guess it's just that if we're going to breed horses or
dogs for pleasure or show, we have an obligation not to eat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the referendum say that's a silly strain of
sentimentalism that ignores the logic of finding a profitable use
for unneeded horses and that disingenuously equates horses with
household pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want horses recognized as `companion animals,' '' said
Brent Heberlein, general manager of Beltex Corp. in Fort Worth,
Texas, which slaughters horses from all over the country and
exports their meat, mostly to France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean everybody's going to be walking their horse
around the block before work in the morning?'' Heberlein asked.
``Or taking it to the 7-Eleven to pick up a quart of milk?''
</P>
<P>
   Although few if any restaurants or stores in the United States
sell horsemeat, similar establishments in other countries do, and
animal welfare advocates estimate that about 100,000 horses are
slaughtered in the United States every year to supply those foreign
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand additional horses from the United States are
transported to Mexico or Canada to be killed there. Advocates said
they have received reports of horses being flown to Japan to be
eaten raw and thinly sliced, like sashimi.
</P>
<P>
   This trade has existed for decades and is not only legal, but
also regulated by the Department of Agriculture. Horse owners get
several hundred dollars from traders, and the slaughterhouses that
buy and kill the horses send the low-fat, high-protein meat to
countries where it fetches as much as $15 a pound and is eaten by
people who could well afford other foods.
</P>
<P>
   The California measure, the first of its kind, would affect only
animals and transactions within the state, making it a crime to
sell or buy a horse, mule, donkey or meat from any of these animals
if it is intended to feed people. But its supporters say they hope
it will spark similar referendums in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative's promoters do not oppose the rendering of horses
into products from pet food to paint thinner because horses used
for these purposes are killed painlessly.
</P>
<P>
   But horses to be eaten by people cannot be pumped full of drugs,
which would taint their meat. Like cattle, they must be
slaughtered, and the method is similar: a long metal nail is shot
into their heads to knock them out, then they are hoisted into the
air and drained of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Trina Bellak, an executive with the Humane Society of the United
States, said a horse's experience of this is more terrifying than a
cow's. Because a horse is more likely to thrash its head in the
killing stall, Ms. Bellak said, several metal nails are sometimes
need to topple the animal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bellak also said that the way horses are transported to
slaughterhouses, packed into trucks for trips that can last two
days, disregards their panicky reaction to crowding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horses get very territorial and have a personal space issue,''
Ms. Bellak said.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond all this, supporters of ``Save the Horses'' say they
object to what they see as a violation of the unspoken human
covenant with horses, which have long been treated with more
affection than common livestock.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a pig, after all, that Elizabeth Taylor rode in
``National Velvet,'' and neither ``My Friend Flicka'' nor ``Black
Beauty'' is easily imagined with a cow in the title roles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Doyle noted that many states have laws that forbid the
killing of cats or dogs for food, even though there are countries
where people eat these animals. She argued that horses deserve
equal protection.
</P>
<P>
   And she took pains to distinguish and distance herself and the
initiative from efforts to end the use of animals in medical
testing or ban fur. ``We are not animal rights activists,'' Ms.
Doyle said. ``We are equine preservationists. We are horse people.
We do horse issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heberlein said that horse owners deserve to be able to
salvage some money for animals that are more expensive to support _
and to euthanize _ than cats or dogs.
</P>
<P>
   It can cost several hundred dollars to have a horse humanely
killed and carted away by a rendering company, and the initiative's
critics warn that owners denied any other option might abandon
unwanted horses.
</P>
<P>
   The handful of horse sanctuaries throughout California,
supported by private donations, can only buy and support a tiny
percentage of the horses at the auctions that supply
slaughterhouses.
</P>
<P>
   The Redwings Horse Sanctuary in Carmel has just 38 horses on a
patch of land with a spectacular view of the Pacific. One of them,
Mirage, was gestating in his mother's belly when she was rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty close call there, huh, fellow?'' Barbara Clarke, the
director of Redwings, said as she stroked his mane.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clarke also has a few horses that she said were rescued as
young, healthy ponies. They had been taken from their mothers so
that their mothers would get pregnant again quickly. The reason,
she said, is that the hormone-dense urine of pregnant mares is used
in a drug for post-menopausal women.
</P>
<P>
   And she has a pen of six aggressively friendly donkeys that she
said might have become ``donkey jerky'' if they had not ended up
with her.
</P>
<P>
   At the Equus Sanctuary, Ms. Moss attributes extraordinary
sensitivity to the horses in her care.
</P>
<P>
   In a brochure, she describes their condition just before rescue
as hopeless and devastated by their betrayal. One horse, Mack, is
identified as one of the ``elder members of our non-human sector.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the tragedies of our society,'' the brochure muses,
``is the abandonment of senior citizens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
