<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1141 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-600&AMP;ADD-N     07-05 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TIE RECORD FOR MOST WINS IN 81 GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa.)  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time a major league baseball team won 61 of
its first 81 games, Theodore Roosevelt was president of the United
States, Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt were newlyweds and a
precocius child named George Herman Ruth, later known as the Babe,
had just left his father's saloon in Baltimore for a school for
wayward boys. The last time until Sunday, that is, when the Yankees
defeated the Baltimore Orioles to make their record 61-20, equaling
the start of the 1907 Chicago Cubs and the 1902 Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees of 1927 are generally considered to be the greatest
team of all time, its lineup graced by the famed Murderers Row;
that group won 57 of its first 81 games. Whether the Yankees of
1998 will be compared favorably to the '27 Yankees, the 1961
Yankees, the 1976 Cincinnati Reds or any of baseball's other great
teams will depend on whether they win the World Series, and whether
they continue to win at such an astounding rate during the regular
season. They are on a pace to win 122 games, which would shatter
the existing 20th century records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be proud,'' said David Cone, who is one of three
Yankee pitchers with 10 or more victories. ``It's a great start.
It's a great accomplishment to be named with the best teams of
all-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, has a lineup stocked with
stars, like right fielder Paul O'Neill, but also capable veteran
role players, like Darryl Strawberry, and a pitching staff that
includes the likes of Cone and David Wells, who pitched a perfect
game May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the obvious talent, however, the Yankees seem to possess
a karma; good things happen for them. Orlando Hernandez, the
defector from Cuba who has been a wild success, was promoted to the
big leagues last month only because a Jack Russell terrier
belonging to David Cone's mother bit Cone on the hand, forcing him
to miss a start. On Sunday, the Yankees scored the only run of the
game when Chad Curtis was hit by a pitch with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have their own little Truman Show,'' said Scott Erickson,
the Baltimore pitcher, referring to the movie about a man who
doesn't know his life is scripted to perfection. ``Everything goes
right for the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch Rickey, the legendary baseball executive, once said that
luck is the residue of design, and this Yankee team resulted from
the evolution of George Steinbrenner, the team's principal owner.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Steinbrenner invested heavily in free agents and
traded away his organization's top prospects, and through this
approach, the Yankees eventually were left with an aged team and a
barren farm system. But Steinbrenner placed more emphasis on
developing prospects, and his executives, in turn, concentrated on
scouting the personalities of prospective Yankees, as well as their
talents.
</P>
<P>
   The farm system regenerated and now the Yankees are built around
home-grown players, like shortstop Derek Jeter, center fielder
Bernie Williams and reliever Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Already they had O'Neill and Tino Martinez, great hitters who
seethe with intensity. Before this season, they added Scott
Brosius, a very likeable and highly respected third baseman, who
Torre says maintains his focus from pitch to pitch as well as
anybody he has ever seen, and Chuck Knoblauch, a leadoff hitter who
engages opposing pitchers in a tireless tug-of-war almost every
time he bats. ``I've never seen a team that is as focused as this
one,'' said Steinbrenner, whose teams have won championships in
1977, 1978 and 1996.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Sesame Street'' producers might consider using the Yankees as
an example of unselfishness. This is cooperation: Joe Girardi, the
regular catcher when the Yankees won the World Series two years
ago, tutors Jorge Posada on a daily basis, even as Posada has
gradually assumed Girardi's playing time. Tim Raines and
Strawberry, superstars when they were younger, are sometimes
removed for pinch-hitters and must share playing time. ``You're
talking about real professionalism,'' Cone said earlier this year.
``Those guys want to play as much as anybody, but what is most
important to them is winning. That's what everybody is all about
here, is winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Brosius: ``The core of the team is the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said in spring training that to manage this group, he
needed merely to stay out of the way and let them play. He has been
more proactive than that, of course _ he reined in Wells in early
May, pushing him to be more consistent in his approach to
conditioning, and Wells has been nearly unbeatable since.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre has watched the talent, intensity and the
unselfishness translate into success nobody could have envisioned,
despite a myriad of injuries, distractions and odd circumstances.
After opening the season by losing their first three games and four
of their first five, Torre answered questions about whether
Steinbrenner might be inclined to change managers. The Yankees
proceeded to win 22 of their next 24 games, despite losing the
slugger Chili Davis to ankle surgery and their closer, Rivera, for
two weeks with a strained muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Wells pitched his perfect game, the Yankees
played the Orioles for the first time, and after Baltimore's
Armando Benitez hit Martinez with a pitch, the teams engaged in a
frightening brawl. As Torre decried Benitez's act, it was apparent
he was pleased how his players defended each other during the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' offense carried the team into early June, batting
.300 through the first 59 games and averaging more than 6.5 runs
per game. But just as Jeter and Williams suffered injuries, the
starting pitching, bolstered by the ascendence of Hernandez and the
improvement of Cone and Wells, became dominant. The Yankees'
starters have a 2.73 earned run average over the last 31 games,
with a 19-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is always that the pitching is intact,'' said
Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is expected to rejoin the Yankees later this week,
Davis sometime next month, and there is no sign of let-up from the
pitching. The Yankees already are beyond the hardest part of their
schedule, and 42 of their remaining 81 games are at Yankee Stadium,
where they have won 33 of 39 this season. They could approach 120
victories, an almost unimaginable achievement.
</P>
<P>
   But that would only fuel the pressure on the Yankees, as they
pursued their ultimate goal through the playoff land mines and the
World Series. Winning all these games is nice, Girardi said Sunday,
but they would be satisfied winning just one game: The last game
they play, in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
