<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-MERGER-450(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEA DELEGATES VOTE DOWN MERGER WITH AFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Delegates at the National Education Association's
convention voted overwhelmingly Sunday against merging with the
American Federation of Teachers, frustrating plans to create a
stronger organization to fight what union leaders see as an
unprecedented assault against public education.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, which would have created the largest union in American
history with 3.3 million members, is a serious blow to the
leadership's designs of creating a unified voice to combat a wave
of critics, most notably supporters of vouchers, a growing movement
to allow use of taxpayer money to help pay for students to attend
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The merger needed a two-thirds vote for approval. The delegates
stunned the NEA leadership _ and themselves _ by casting only 4,091
votes for the merger, or 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging his disappointment, Bob Chase, president of the
2.3 million-member association, said that he would continue pushing
for a merger, although with many details changed, because in his
view his union's members still support the ultimate goal of
unification with the teachers' federation.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the vote, Chase, who appeared
dejected and exhausted, said: ``The vast majority of delegates are
in favor of unity. They do want to see the two organizations come
together. Obviously they didn't think this plan was the best way to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Sandra Feldman, president of the 950,000-member
American Federation of Teachers, said she was disappointed by the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates gave a host of reasons for rejecting the merger. Many
said that under the agreement, the combined union would be
undemocratic. Others said the teachers' federation was too militant
for their tastes. Many said they did not like the fact that the
merger would make the education association part of the AFL-CIO.
And many said they were happy with the association as it is.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining his vote against merging, Bruce Jensen, an elementary
school teacher in Moulton, Iowa, said: ``The members have taken
great pride in the history, autonomy and independence of the
National Education Association. They were worried that this would
reduce its independence.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, opponents of the merger had predicted that they
might block it by obtaining 40 percent of the vote. On Sunday, many
opponents acknowledged they were shocked when they got far more
than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said that notwithstanding the vote, he would continue with
policies under which the union has shifted away from its
us-vs.-them emphasis on wages and benefits and toward a focus on
working with school districts to improve education.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the convention on Monday, the nearly 10,000 delegates will
consider whether to authorize renewed negotiations with the
federation to produce a merger agreement more to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Krimmel, a supporter of the merger who teaches special
education in Holland, Pa., said: ``We've suffered a blow, but not a
fatal blow. Just as teachers ask, `How can students learn if they
don't have a full stomach and a safe environment?' I don't know how
we as educators can battle foes of public education if we're still
fighting against ourselves. I still hope we'll unify eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Many delegates objected to specific parts of the merger
document, known as the Principles of Unity.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent criticism was that the new organization would be less
democratic than the NEA because the dominant body would be a
37-member executive board. Many delegates said this showed that the
teachers' federation had emerged victorious in the merger
negotiations, because the governing structure would be more like
that of the heavily centralized federation than like that of the
bottom-up NEA, where the 10,000-delegate assembly dominates.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why many Massachusetts delegates voted no, Kenneth
Hamilton, president of the Newton Teachers Association, said, ``The
organization spelled out in the Principles of Unity was less
democratic, less grass-roots than the NEA and more of a top-down
leadership organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Hamilton said he would support a renewed push to
negotiate a merger. But, he added: ``It has to have the new
organization look more like the NEA than the AFT. This document was
just the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   The education association was founded in 1857 as a professional
organization, and for more than a century it shunned collective
bargaining. But when the teachers' federation used strikes and
militancy to win far better wages and benefits in the 1960s and
1970s, the NEA transformed itself into a union that also emphasized
wages and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's vote follows three decades of on-again, off-again
efforts to merge the two unions. For decades they were archrivals,
badmouthing each other, raiding each other's locals for members,
and spending more than $100 million in seeking to outdo each other
in wooing teachers from hundreds of school districts across the
nation. The association has been the dominant union in suburban and
rural school districts, while the federation dominates in cities.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the unions have signed a nonaggression
pact, pledging not to raid each other and agreeing to discuss a
merger. In February, negotiators for the two unions announced the
merger plan, which was largely made possible by the education
association easing its long-time opposition to joining the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   But for many members, becoming part of the AFL-CIO remained a
major sticking point. A number of them said that joining would
reduce their independence and force them to focus on issues other
than education, because most of the labor federation's members are
not teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Many members voiced discomfort with joining the labor federation
because they saw it as blue-collar and confrontational, even though
47 percent of its members are white-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Woods, a vocational educational teacher in Millport,
Ala., who voted against the merger, said: ``We'd go along with it
if there wasn't affiliation with the AFL-CIO. It's the unionization
part. We don't consider ourselves a union. We're not into the
boycotting and rioting. We generally associate that with unions.''
</P>
<P>
   In her statement, Ms. Feldman, the teacher federation's
president, said that four years of merger talks had helped the two
groups recognize that they have much in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both organizations share the goals of improving education for
America's 50 million students, fighting for the dignity and
well-being of the nation's educators, and of course putting an end
to vouchers and other privatization attempts that can't possibly
succeed for the majority of our students,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative critics of the teachers' unions applauded Sunday's
vote after many had denounced the proposed merger, partly because
it would produce a more potent teachers' organization.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Fossedal, chairman of the the Alexis de Tocqueville
Institution, a public policy center that supports school vouchers,
said, ``Today's vote to preserve at least some choice and
competition is a victory for teachers, parents and children.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chase said the NEA's foes were wrong to applaud the vote and
insisted that the two teachers' groups would continue their close
cooperation on many issues, like school funding and fighting
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are people out there who opposed this and take
comfort in this, I think their comfort will be misplaced,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
