<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SMOKING TRIAL TESTS INDUSTRY'S RESOLVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The resolve of cigarette makers to fight lawsuits following the
collapse of last year's nationwide settlement plan faces its
toughest test Monday with the start of a large class-action case
brought on behalf of smokers in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The case, in which an estimated 100,000 to 200,000 people are
seeking some $25 billion in compensatory and punitive damages, is
the nation's first class-action lawsuit involving smokers to come
to trial. Jury selection will begin Monday and is expected to take
three to five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will unfold in stages, with the first one determining
whether producers are liable for tobacco-related health problems
and should face punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The case comes at an uncertain point in the course of tobacco
litigation. Last month, in a rare victory for plaintiffs, a Florida
jury ordered Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. to pay $1 million,
including $500,000 in punitive damages, to the family of a smoker.
But just days later, a Florida appeals court struck down a 1996
jury award of $750,000 against Brown &AMP; Williamson, holding that the
smoker in that case had waited too long to sue and that evidence
had been improperly admitted at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sugarman, a law professor at the University of
California at Berkeley and an expert on tobacco litigation, said he
believed that the trial's first phase would be critical. The
industry will try to knock out the case, he said, and if that
fails, it will move to settle it, despite recent tough talk against
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the plaintiffs must hope that if they can win Round 1
then the industry will come to the bargaining table,'' Sugarman
said.
</P>
<P>
   If jurors hold producers liable, and there is no settlement, the
jury will next hear the cases of six smokers representing the
class. In the third stage, the claim of each class member will be
reviewed to see whether their illness was smoking-related.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Rosenblatt, the Miami lawyer who brought the lawsuit,
estimated the number of class members at 100,000 to 200,000. And
legal experts like Sugarman said that a case-by-case review of
those claims would be so cumbersome that producers would be likely
to settle if the case proved unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, no one is talking about settling. Robert C. Heim, a
lawyer for Philip Morris, said that tobacco producers planned to
stake their defense on data showing that the public was aware of
smoking risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are dealing with the issue of personal choice and
responsibility,'' Heim said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit claims that the industry knowingly addicted smokers and
then failed to adequately warn them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thrust of our case is that the tobacco industry attempted
through diversionary tactics to keep alive a nonexistent scientific
controversy about smoking and health,'' Rosenblatt said.
</P>
<P>
   He is no stranger to the tobacco industry. Last year, he and his
wife, Susan, who is also a lawyer, scored a major victory when
producers agreed to pay $300 million to settle a lawsuit brought on
behalf of 60,000 flight attendants who had claimed injury from
secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   But the case also generated some disputes. Alan Morrison, a
lawyer with Public Citizen, an advocacy group, said that his group
objected to the settlement on behalf of some flight attendants
because its financial benefits went to establish a nonprofit
foundation to research smoking-related diseases rather than to
class members. And he described as excessive the $49 million in
fees and expenses paid under the settlement to the Rosenblatts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was obviously able to persuade the tobacco industry to part
with over $350 million and for that I give him great credit,''
Morrison said. ``But our problem is that the money did not go to
the class.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Judge Robert Kaye, who oversaw the flight attendant
case and was assigned to handle the new lawsuit, backed the
settlement. And Rosenblatt, who said he could not discuss the
matter because it was under appeal, said that flight attendants did
not show up at a recent court hearing to object to the settlement
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The lead plaintiff in the current case is Dr. Howard Engle, a
retired pediatrician in Miami Beach who filed suit in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
