<HEADLINE>
GET IN THAT KITCHEN AND PREPARE TO BLAST OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you've got three pots steaming over here and five dirty bowls
in the sink over there, and the person who shares your bed and
board strolls into the kitchen, surveys the situation and comments:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, you're making this meal look very complicated. After all,
this isn't rocket science.''
</P>
<P>
   Right, it isn't. Cooking is more complicated than rocket
science.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to take my word for it. Ask Jay McCarthy. He
studied aerospace engineering at Texas A&AMP;M and worked in the
industry, including a short stint at The Boeing Co. He lived in the
Seattle area, did some cooking in his spare time, shopped for local
produce at the Pike Place Market and ate at Ray's Boathouse when he
could afford a good meal.
</P>
<P>
   He is now one of the hottest chefs in Texas. He started his own
cafe, Mestana, in San Antonio and it has been so successful he has
plans for another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never regretted the career change for a minute,''
McCarthy commented when we crossed paths a couple of months ago.
``Every day is a challenge. And believe me, there are as many
details you have to deal with in the restaurant business as in
aerospace engineering. And I once ran a machine shop and turned out
probes for the Martian atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. I once cooked bouillabaisse for 35 people in a strange
kitchen on two electric burners. And they all wanted to eat at
once. From what McCarthy says, there can't be much more pressure
than that in the planning, development and construction of a
booster rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCarthy's enthusiasm is barely dimmed by the facts of his
profession. He admitted under questioning that his work day begins
sometime between 6 and 8 a.m. and rarely ends before 11:30 p.m.,
six days a week. If he were working at Boeing, the company would
owe him two 737s, just in overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   Here is one of McCarthy's favorite recipes:
</P>
<P>
   Beef Tostada
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup beef cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup black beans, drained
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup Monterey jack cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   Peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   Flour tortillas or fry bread
</P>
<P>
   Multiply the above ingredients by the total number of guests.
</P>
<P>
   Use a good grade of top round or tenderloin beef and cut into
small cubes, no bigger than one-half inch.
</P>
<P>
   Just so this recipe doesn't get as simple as rocket science,
McCarthy prefers to serve each tostada portion over a freshly
cooked, five-inch circle of Indian fry bread rather than the
traditional warmed tortilla. (I know, you flunked physics, so you
are going to opt for the tortilla rather than the more complicated
fry bread. Me too.)
</P>
<P>
   Heat a skillet over medium high heat. Add a bit of peanut oil
and sear beef cubes. Add the garlic and saute 3 to 4 minutes more.
Add the tomatoes, corn and black beans and heat through. Place a
tortilla or a round of fry bread on each plate. Add cheese on top
and heat each dish in a 200-degree oven until melted.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy was born in New York and raised in Jamaica, but he has
cooked in all parts of the country and specializes in what he terms
``Caribbean Rim Cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Intermediate Eater specializes in Three Alarm Chili, spicy
chicken wings, tuna casseroles and Son of a Gun Stew, but sometimes
I will spread my wings and fly with something like this Asian
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Lemon Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon sherry
</P>
<P>
   Salt, freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 boned chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   Cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons catsup
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one large lemon
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup sliced green onions
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup carrots, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup snow peas
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sliced water chestnuts
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half cups fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Pound the chicken breasts (skinned or unskinned) with a Ming
dynasty baseball bat until one-half inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   OK, moosh together 1 tablespoon of canola oil, 2 teaspoons of
soy sauce, the sherry and some freshly ground pepper. Rub this into
the chicken, then lightly coat the breasts with cornstarch.
Refrigerate at least 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then you are supposed to construct some lemon sauce, combining
in a saucepan } cup water, the sugar, catsup, lemon juice, 1
teaspoon oil and a dash of salt. Bring to a boil, stirring. Mix 2
teaspoons of cornstarch with a bit of water and stir this paste
into the sauce. Stir until thickened, then keep sauce over a low
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Coat a skillet with enough canola oil to cover the bottom and
brown the chicken breasts on both sides. Remove to a board and cut
the chicken into strips, three-quarters inch wide. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   To the same oiled skillet add the vegetables and stir-fry until
tender but still crisp. Dump this mess on a warm platter. Top with
the chicken, then spoon the sauce over all. If you want to go first
class, scatter toasted almond slices over the top. This will serve
four with rice, and if that doesn't taste better than NASA rations,
then John Glenn is a rickshaw driver in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
