<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook: Bumped umpires will hand over decision to NL
president
 &HT;    by Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Though his office may not address the issue until
after the All-Star break, the conclusion of Sunday's Braves-Mets
game is headed for the desk of National League president Len
Coleman, who is certain to discipline the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Both crew chief Randy Marsh and plate umpire Angel Hernandez
were bumped in what became a Mets team meeting around the crew
after Hernandez's game-ending call Sunday. Manager Bobby Valentine
and reliever John Franco both face suspensions and Franco, who had
contact with both umpires, could face a week or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we do is file a report with Len Coleman with the league,''
said Marsh, who spoke on behalf of the crew. ``We do not recommend
fines. We have no say-so in that. I'm sure he'll review the tapes.
There was contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsh backed up Hernandez's call, which the crew was able to
review on tape immediately afterwards. Hernandez declined to speak
with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there was a bobble there, but looking at the
tape, it looked like (Mike) Piazza was bending over, trying to
smother it,'' said Marsh. ``But the bottom line is, (Michael
Tucker) got his foot down in there before he was even doing that,
before he put the tag on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost....
</P>
<P>
   Missed it by that much. Braves starter Denny Neagle gave up the
two Mets runs in the sixth that tied the game and did not play into
the decision. That left Neagle at 9-6 and just one win shy of some
history. With Greg Maddux (12-2), Tom Glavine (12-3) and Kevin
Millwood (10-4) all with double-digit victories, Neagle could have
comprised the first rotation in 21 years with 10 or more each at
the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   No NL team since the 1977 Los Angeles Dodgers had four starters
with 10 or more wins at the break. Said manager Bobby Cox,
``Neagle's going to get over-looked. He's had a great first-half.
His numbers are just as close. For me, he's popping the ball
super.''
</P>
<P>
   The '77 Dodgers reached the break with Doug Rau at 11-1, Tommy
John at 10-4, Rick Rhoden at 10-6 and Don Sutton at 10-4. ``I'd
forgotten about that,'' Sutton said. ``Maybe because it's because I
went 4-4 in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching plans
</P>
<P>
   The match-ups for the Florida series and note both All-Stars
Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine will have eight days between starts:
(Thursday) John Smoltz (5-2) vs. Livan Hernandez (7-4); (Friday)
Denny Neagle (9-6) vs. Jesus Sanchez (3-6); (Saturday) Maddux
(12-2) vs. Ryan Dempster (1-3); (Sunday) Glavine (12-3) vs. Brian
Meadows (6-6).
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   When Neagle was called for a balk when throwing over to first in
the sixth inning, it marked the club's first balk of the year,
coming in the 782nd inning of the season. The Braves hold the NL
record for fewest balks in a season (0), set in 1948 in Boston and
then tied in 1957 in Milwaukee. . . Surprisingly, Piazza was back
in the lineup after taking a bat to the head Saturday night on a
swing by Gerald Williams. Piazza was groggy when he returned to the
Mets clubhouse late from tests at Piedmont Hospital but was back
out on the field 13 hours later, but equipped with the helmet-style
catcher's mask. . . . Sunday's attendance of 40,430 extended to 13
straight games the string of 40,000-plus crowds (home and road) to
see the Braves play. The last such attendance streak was 16 games
and came before the last players' strike (June 13-29, 1994). . . .
Pedro Borbon, 0-2 with a 5.54 ERA on a re-han assignment with Class
AA Greenville, has that assignment extended another 15 days through
July 18. A team may extend re-hab assignments indefinitely, as long
as both parties agree to the extension. Borbon has allowed eight
earned runs on 14 hits in 13 innings, walking 12 and striking out
four.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
