<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    18-hole playoff will decide U.S. Women's Open winner
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ After four days watching the field being battered
and windblown by Blackwolf Run Golf Course, what could be more
fitting as a conclusion for the U.S. Women's Open?
</P>
<P>
   Overtime, of course. No reason to stop the torture. Surely,
there are more bogeys out there amongst the wild fescue, even on a
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament was handed a sudden change of plans Sunday
afternoon. Just when it appeared that Korea's Se Ri Pak had a firm
grip on a second major championship, Duke University junior Jenny
Chuasiriporn decided to provide a dramatic reminder of the United
States Golf Association's antiquated playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the line from her brother and caddie, Mike, Chuasiriporn
aimed a foot to the left, made solid contact and watched bug-eyed
as a 45-foot putt found the center of the cup at the 18th hole
Sunday for birdie. When Pak, who had taken a two-shot lead to the
17th tee, bogeyed the hole and then missed a 10-foot birdie putt at
18, the two players wound up tied at 6-over-par 290, forcing an
18-hole playoff beginning today at 11 a.m. (CDT).
</P>
<P>
   ''It was on line for about 10 feet,'' said Chuasiriporn, a
Baltimore, Md., native whose parents are from Thailand, ''and I
thought, 'My God, it might be going in.' The last 15 feet, my eyes
probably popped out. I really didn't expect it to go in. I was
thinking 2-putt.''
</P>
<P>
   The two 20-year-olds would have just as soon headed to a sudden
death playoff, but the USGA remains the only golf organization that
decides its championships by an 18-hole playoff. Which, history has
proven, often is sudden death for TV ratings.
</P>
<P>
   As an added problem, there is rain in the forecast for today.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-hole score of 6-over posted by the two players was the
highest since Jan Stephenson won the tournament in 1983. The last
Women's Open playoff came in 1992, when Patti Sheehan defeated Juli
Inkster.
</P>
<P>
   One already settled issue is the money. With Chuasiriporn an
amateur, the winner's check of $267,000 will go to Pak.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, who bogeyed the 17th hole by missing the green and then a
4-foot putt, shot a 76. She was still smiling, seemed not the least
bit disappointed and envisioned a playoff that will ''feel like a
practice round.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn actually was unaware of Pak's bogey at the 17th and
thought the Korean could two-putt for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just going out to have fun,'' the amateur said of the
playoff. ''I have nothing to lose from here on out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's Liselotte Neumann, a shot off the lead after 54 holes,
finished third at 291 on a 76. Scotland's Mhairi McKay slipped to a
78 and tied for seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
