<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIRES-HELP-COX     07-05 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-HELP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia, Florida National Guards combine to battle fires
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUNNELL, Fla. _ The Blackhawk UH-60s crews dive toward the
flames and empty 660-gallon buckets of water about 30 feet above
the trees, trying to slow a blaze burning relentlessly Sunday
toward subdivisions in Flagler County, where thousands of people
have fled their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The two helicopters then circle around to Crescent Lake and dip
out another load. It's a task they repeat again and again, making
up to 40 fire attacks an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say this is about as hazardous as it gets,'' said Staff
Sgt. Timothy Loveless, a Georgia National Guard crew chief who
hangs out of the helicopter on approach to eyeball the water drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tree exploded under me and all I could see was fire. I
thought my feet were on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Loveless and 26 fellow Georgians are members of the Guard's
171st Aviation Battalion, which is made up of Georgia and Florida
units. They've been flying out of St. Augustine since June 27,
fighting the wildfires ravaging Florida, after fighting fires in
Waycross, Ga., for a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the National Guard is all about,'' said Brig.
Gen. Tom McCullough of metro Atlanta, who toured the devastated
stretch of northeast Florida by air Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a mission like this, they go home and morale is high
because they feel like they've helped people.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard officials have informally named the helicopter mission
``Operation Wetdown.'' Acres of blackened landscape are visible
from the air, but for the most part, the burned land is surrounded
by oceans of green where the flames haven't penetrated.
</P>
<P>
   An east wind had given the firefighters an advantage by slowing
the fires' advance and allowed crews to contain them. Yet black
smoke billowed from a hot fire 13 miles west of Bunnell while white
smoke rose from smoldering pine needles and palmetto, and a shift
in the wind or a pickup in gusts could easily turn the
``contained'' acres into another firestorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a bed of pine needles built up over the years and it's
just like gasoline,'' said Staff Sgt. Nicholas Cox, a crew chief
from Lakeland, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Brock Gaston of Marietta, Ga. pointed to areas where the
helicopter crews had been dumping loads over Flagler County, which
Gov. Lawton Chiles ordered evacuated Friday when authorities feared
three fires would converge, creating a firestorm that might make it
impossible for the county's 40,000 residents to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where we've been working,'' Gaston told the general.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out as a small fire and we were able to keep it off
of the houses. Then two days later we lost all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The crews refill their huge buckets _ which dangle on 15-foot
cables below the choppers _ from the St. Johns River and the lakes
and ponds dotting the region. They use the closest body of water
because time is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few ponds over here we just emptied out getting
water to throw on those fires,'' Gaston said.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter crews rarely manage to put out a fire _ ground
crews have to extinguish them _ but aim to control the fast-moving
wildfires. Each day brings a new threat that a lightning strike or
spark will generate a new fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to slow it down so that the tractors and
bulldozers can cut a fire break through the trees,'' said Sgt.
Phillip Banzhof, a crew chief from Cumming, just north of Atlanta.
``Some of the areas you can't get in because it's so hot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said putting a bucket on these fires is like spitting
on a campfire,'' said Staff Sgt. Michael Callanan, also of Cumming.
</P>
<P>
   The crew chiefs guide the pilots over the fires, and the
Blackhawks disappear into the smoke as they aim to dump the loads
of water and foam 30 feet above the trees. Sometimes the smoke is
so thick that it forces them higher because of the risk of getting
tangled in trees and power lines, and that decreases their
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be able to see the fire _ if we hang a bucket up in
those trees it could be disastrous,'' said Chief Warrant Officer
Kevin Zemetis of Marietta, a helicopter pilot. ``Besides snagging
power lines or trees, the next biggest hazard is dropping 5,600
pounds of water on firefighters on the ground. Three tons of water
landing on somebody could hurt them pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, none of the helicopter crews have been hurt and the
firefighters on the ground have suffered only minor injuries _
except for one who was seriously injured Sunday when a tree fell on
his bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
   The crews take their orders from the Florida Division of
Forestry in Tallahassee, which has expertise in fighting fires, and
from a ranger in an observation helicopter. Sometimes the experts
make mistakes. In one instance last week, the guardsmen spotted a
plume of smoke and radioed to ask if they should water it and were
told it didn't pose a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one that turned into an inferno,'' Loveless said.
</P>
<P>
   But when Gaston's crew spotted a plume of smoke in St. Johns
County during a mop-up mission and radioed for instructions, they
were given the go-ahead to extinguish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to kill it before it got started,'' Gaston said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the one silver lining in the dark clouds of smoke over
Florida is that the disaster provides excellent _ and federally
financed _ training for the aviation battalion's wartime mission of
hauling equipment into combat zones, said Col. Art Bruno, who is
director of operation for the battalion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this a high-hazard mission,'' said Bruno, of
Ellenwood, Ga. ``In our wartime mission, we do a lot of
sling-loading. Sling-loading 600 gallons of water is similar to
sling-loading a humvee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida unit has six Blackhawks and the Georgia unit has
five, along with two observation helicopters and a Chinook. The
Blackhawks can be flown only 500 hours before being grounded for
maintenance for 25 days. Florida lost one to maintenance last week
and is about ready to lose another. Georgia has a couple that are
soon to be grounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that if you fly them this much, you can't do
the maintenance and so you have to ground them,'' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
