r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHR     07-05 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOUR BOSS IS A CONSTANT MICRO-MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:  My boss constantly micro-manages me. He's always checking up on
me and telling me how to do things that I can do perfectly well on
my own. It's gotten to a point where I feel like punching him. What
can I do?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Refraining from punching him is a good start. Then, do a
little informal research to find out whether your boss tends to
micro-manage all his employees _ or whether you've been singled
out.
</P>
<P>
   If you're the only one, that should raise a warning flag about
your performance and career prospects, according to Russell Wild,
author of the book, ``Games Bosses Play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably something wrong (with your work), but he
lacks the time or guts to sit down and talk to you about it,'' Wild
said. ``You need to sit down with him and see what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if he micro-manages everyone, you can relax a
little. It may be frustrating to deal with, but at least it's not a
sign that your job is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   You can try to head off this kind of micro-management by asking
your boss in advance how he wants particular tasks done. Or try
setting up a time line of progress reports: If the boss knows that
he's going to get an update from you every day at 4:30, maybe he
won't come by your desk each hour to ask how things are going.
</P>
<P>
   Even with such efforts, your boss still may feel a compulsion to
meddle. You may have to accept that this is part of his
personality, built up over a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop taking it so personally, and keep your cool,'' Wild said.
``You're not likely to change him unless you get him into therapy
for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; My wife works part time as a sales clerk and is paid on an
hourly basis. The company often asks her to attend functions
outside her normal work hours, such as evening receptions for
customers. But the company refuses to pay her for this time. My
wife has decided not to go to any more of these functions unless
they pay her. Can they fire her or penalize her for not attending
these events?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; California law says that nonexempt employees must be paid
for every hour they work. And after-hours functions are considered
work time if attendance is mandatory, according to Sharon Grodin,
an attorney with Crosby Heafey Roach &AMP; May in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   So your wife is right. She should be paid for attending these
events if the company says they're part of her job. If she's not
paid _ or if she's fired for refusing to work without pay _ she can
file a complaint with the California Labor Commissioner at (415)
557-7878.
</P>
<P>
   But reality often is more complicated than the letter of the
law. Company officials may decide to penalize your wife in ways too
subtle to be covered by the Labor Commissioner, who primarily
oversees wage disputes. If your wife's supervisors feel that she's
uncooperative, they may quietly put her in the office doghouse _
denying her the best assignments or handing her the least-desirable
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Grodin suggests that your wife try to remain in the firm's good
graces by offering to help in other ways that don't involve working
for free. For instance, she could volunteer to prepare refreshments
or decorations for these receptions during her regular work hours.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, employers should clearly indicate when attendance at
after-hours events is mandatory _ and when it truly is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies can say things like, `We'd be delighted to have you
there, but your time is your own,''' Grodin said. ``If they frame
it that way, they have no obligation to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I have a friend who works for a straight sales commission,
with no fixed salary. The company holds back 20 percent of her
commissions for one year, ostensibly in case the customer never
pays up. However, the company seems to have a pattern of firing
salespeople within seven to eight months and keeping that 20
percent of their commissions for ``administrative expenses.'' Is
this legal?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; It's completely legal for firms to place conditions on
payment of sales commissions, as long as they have a reasonable
business justification for it, according to Jamie Johnson, an
attorney with Brobeck Phleger &AMP; Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   So there's nothing wrong with this company holding onto some
portion of each commission until it can see whether the account is
paid in full.
</P>
<P>
   ``But holding on to it for a full year may be kind of stretching
it,'' Johnson added. ``The time frame should be tied to their
collection cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   What IS illegal is firing people in order to deprive them of
their wages _ for instance, terminating a longtime employee without
good cause one week before he or she is supposed to get a $10,000
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Is that what's going on here? It's hard to say without knowing
more of the details of this case.
</P>
<P>
   The rules governing commissions vary from company to company and
contract to contract. If your friend is worried that her company is
ripping off its salespeople, she probably should consult a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many detailed plans, and they're so fact-specific
that she should have it checked by an attorney,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Have a question about your workplace or career, your boss or an
employee? Send it to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San Francisco
Chronicle, 901 Mission Street, San Francisco 94103. Or send e-mail
to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415) 764-2815. We can't respond to
each query in person, but we will answer as many in print as we
can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
