<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAPRUDER-JFK-FILM-NYT     07-05 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPRUDER-JFK-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT AND ZAPRUDER FAMILY DEBATE THE PRICE OF HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The images are burned into the American
consciousness: The motorcycles appear. Then comes the open
limousine. President John F. Kennedy can be recognized. All of a
sudden his head jerks. Jacqueline Kennedy in her pillbox hat is
climbing over the back seat. The car speeds away.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-second silent home movie of the Kennedy assassination,
taken by a Dallas dress manufacturer, Abraham Zapruder, is probably
the most famous historical film clip and the most widely
scrutinized piece of murder evidence ever.
</P>
<P>
   So how much is it worth?
</P>
<P>
   That is now a matter of serious dispute between the government
and the Zapruder family. After months of negotiations between two
of the most prominent lawyers in Washington, they are still
millions of dollars apart.
</P>
<P>
   Zapruder's heirs (he died of cancer in 1970 at age 66) want the
government to pay them $18.5 million for the original film and its
copyright. They are represented by Robert Bennett, the lawyer who
represents President Clinton in the Paula Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The government originally offered $750,000 and then raised its
offer to $3 million, but it has refused to go higher. The chief
negotiator for the government is Frank Hunger, who is the assistant
attorney general in charge of the Justice Department's civil
division and who is also the brother-in-law of Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of this month, regardless of the outcome of the
legal haggling, a digitally enhanced version will be in video
stores across the country, to be rented or bought. Assassination
buffs and conspiracy purveyors will then be free to analyze the
evidence to their hearts' content on their own VCR's.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides want the government to take ownership of the original
8-millimeter film and its copyright from the Zapruders. The
government has actually had possession of the film since 1978, when
the family deposited it for safekeeping in a freezer at the
National Archives. The only problem is the money.
</P>
<P>
   The film has no intrinsic value, because the copies are of much
higher quality than the original. And because the video is about to
be widely available, the copyright is not worth anything, the
lawyers agree. The question is, how much is the film worth to
collectors as a historical relic?
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said that professional appraisers he retained had found
the value to be as high as $70 million. An official at the Justice
Department said that its appraisals were no higher than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett compares the film to an original manuscript of the
Declaration of Independence. It is, he argues, as if the government
looked at such a manuscript ``and said, how much is the paper
worth, how much is the ink worth?''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department maintains that a more apt analogy is a
piece of computer software that is widely available and can be
reproduced at will.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett says that the last thing the Zapruders want is to
auction the film, which they view as a national treasure, to the
highest bidder. The Justice Department says that it has a
responsibility to protect the taxpayers from being bilked.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's most recent offer, he said, was to enter binding
arbitration by an impartial judge with the price to be no higher
than $30 million. The Justice Department has not responded, but an
official said that arbitration was a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations were stimulated by a declaration in April 1997
by the Assassination Records Review Board that the film belonged to
the federal government. The board, created by a 1992 law and given
the mandate to amass all relevant evidence in the Kennedy case,
gave the government and the Zapruder family until August to agree
on how to transfer ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Zapruder family has been careful to avoid
any appearance of profiteering. Copies of the film have been given
without cost to researchers. Bennett estimated that in 35 years,
the family had made less than $1 million selling rights for
commercial use.
</P>
<P>
   The new videos that will be in the stores this month do not look
like a big money-maker either.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Zapruders entered a partnership with MPI Home Video
in Orland Park, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which specializes in historical documentaries, made
a digitally enlarged, frame-by-frame copy of the film, and produced
a 45-minute video titled ``Image of an Assassination: A New Look at
the Zapruder Film.'' In addition to the 26 seconds that Zapruder
recorded, the video includes a narrative and interviews with
Zapruder's business associates, photography experts and employees
of the National Archives.
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in studying each frame, the digitalization
allows, for the first time, an examination of the images between
the sprocket holes on the original film.
</P>
<P>
   Waleed B. Ali, the chief executive officer of MPI, said that he
expected about 250,000 videos to be sold. Originally, the retail
price will be $19.98 for a conventional VHS videotape and $24.98
for a DVD compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bennett nor Ali would discuss the financial
arrangements. But they said that the Zapruder family would receive
no more than about $3 on each video and that the heirs might not
even recapture what they spent to make the video.
</P>
<P>
   The family's main interest in making Abraham Zapruder's home
movie so widely available, Bennett said, is to rid itself of the
administrative burden of having to decide who can have access to
it, when and for how much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
