A1169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-AIRPORT-ART-     07-05 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-AIRPORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG'S FAST FLIGHT TO NEW AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In less time than it takes to fly from London to New
York, Hong Kong closed down its international airport Monday just
after midnight and moved the contents 19 miles west to a new $20
billion airport in time for the first flight to land at 6:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time a city has switched airports in a
one-day move _ Denver and Munich, Germany, did it. But no
municipality has attempted to do it on quite the same scale or with
the same bravado as Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at midnight, when the last plane took off and the
runway lights at Kai Tak Airport were switched off, a convoy of
1,100 vehicles began rumbling out of the airport and onto
residential streets in Kowloon toward Hong Kong International
Airport, which is built on reclaimed land off Lantau Island.
</P>
<P>
   The move marked the end of Kai Tak, a 73-year-old doyenne of
airports that won the hearts of some people here for its in-town
location and stopped the hearts of others with its spectacular,
roof-skimming approaches.
</P>
<P>
   But for the people working on the move, this was no time for
nostalgia. At a dock next to the runway, cranes were busy hauling
baggage loaders, pallet pushers, and other assorted airport
vehicles onto 14 barges, which later steamed through Victoria
Harbor to the new airport. Thirty-one passenger planes transported
still more equipment from the old airport to its giant successor.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the person who was supervising this vast movement of
men and materiel _ an operation the local government has been
promoting for weeks as ``The Night'' and regularly compares to
D-Day?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all in the planning,'' said Police Superintendent Steve
Wordsworth as he monitored the activity on a bank of television and
radar screens from his airport command center. ``Panic doesn't
help.''
</P>
<P>
   A stout, balding 38-year-old with an easy manner, Wordsworth
said he had been planning the move for 18 months. The Airport
Authority recruited a retired British Army colonel with experience
in logistics to advise him. And it held a full dress rehearsal,
with 40 vehicles, on April 29.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wordsworth admitted his ice-water-in-veins demeanor was a
bit of an act. The move posed immense logistical challenges: a
crowded winding route, a tight timetable and sporadic heavy rain.
And the new airport could not open without the equipment from the
old one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think I was calm, cool and collected, but look at my
nails,'' he said with a chuckle, offering up a set of well-chewed
cuticles.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's airport hand over has generated more interest here
than any event since the real hand over, when this former British
colony reverted to Chinese rule. Hong Kong marked the first
anniversary of that milestone last week, with back-to-back visits
from President Jiang Zemin of China and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the local newspapers still managed to put the visits in the
context of the new airport. They noted that the Chinese leader
became the first passenger to depart from the airport, after a
dedication ceremony on Thursday. Eight hours later, Air Force One
landed at the airport, making the American president the first
passenger to arrive there.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the interest in airports stems from the fact that Kai
Tak holds a special space in the memories and imagination of people
here. The airport is in the middle of town, just across the harbor
from Hong Kong's skyscrapers. Its dramatic approach, in which
pilots veer sharply right to avoid a hill and skim the rooftops and
clothes-lines of Kowloon, is a legend in the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Larry Walters, a pilot with United Airlines, landed the
airline's last flight, a 747 from Los Angeles, here on Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always fun for us,'' he said, ``We actually got to use
our skills a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Hong Kong families turned out with cameras to take
a last tour of Kai Tak's somewhat worn terminal building. Some even
booked rooms at the adjacent Regal Airport Hotel, which offered a
special one-night package of dinner and a room with a view of the
runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sad about its closing,'' said Stephen Chu, a
46-year-old university lecturer, as he waited to check in for a
flight to Melbourne, Australia. ``I've been using it since I was a
boy. It's been a part of our lives for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Chu said he remembered a tearful farewell in the departure
lounge four years ago when he saw off his parents, who were
immigrating to Canada. He now lives in Kowloon Tong, a neighborhood
under the old flight path, so close to the planes, he said, that he
would ``wave to the people in the windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hong Kong has a new airport with a host of superlatives:
the world's largest terminal, one of the world's largest airport
shopping malls, and one of the biggest hotels. At $20 billion, it
is the second-most-expensive airport, after Kansai International in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even Clinton expressed regret about the end of Kai Tak _
saying in a speech after he arrived here last week that landing
there on a previous visit ``was one of the most exciting and
uncertain experiences of my lifetime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
