<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1173 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENS-TECHWORKERS-SFC     07-05 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-TECHWORKERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRMS HIRING TEEN TECHIES TO SOLVE LABOR CRUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Morgan McNamara had all the technical skills necessary to land a
job at LineX, an Internet service provider in San Rafael. He also
had more than enough enthusiasm and dedication.
<TEXT>
<P>
   McNamara was lacking just one thing _ a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   So McNamara, who is 16, had his parents pick him up after school
each day and drive him to LineX. There he would field phone calls
from customers twice his age who were having trouble connecting to
the Internet, sending e-mail or viewing Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the customers can tell my age,'' McNamara
said. ``No one has ever asked. And if I can solve problems just the
same as the other reps, then I don't think it should make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   LineX is one of a number of Bay Area employers that have found a
novel solution to the tight and pricey high-tech labor market _
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. labor officials estimate that there are 22,000 16-to
19-year-olds working in the data-processing and computer
industries. That represents 1.4 percent of all employees in those
industries, up from 0.8 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Many are college students or high school graduates. But some
like McNamara are younger _ high school students with side careers
as Web masters, network technicians or programmers.
</P>
<P>
   Igor Kazakov, 15, was hired last year as a ninth grader to
manage the Web site of a video game retailer in Mill Valley.
</P>
<P>
   And Will Hayes, 17, landed work building a Web site for a small
solar energy company in Richmond while still a junior. This summer,
he's continuing to develop Web sites while also doing computer work
as an intern at MPR Associates, a market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went to work in a law firm or a doctor's office, I'd
probably just be someone who was in the way,'' Hayes said. ``But
when it comes to computers, older people are always asking me
questions about how to do things. Younger people are looked on with
a lot more respect (in technology) than in other fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies are hiring teenage techies for several reasons. Some
small, struggling entrepreneurs turn to the son or daughter of a
friend to build them a Web site because they simply can't afford to
hire an adult professional.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Pyle, chief executive of H-Ion Solar Inc., estimates that
it would have cost him $500 or $1,000 for an adult to develop his
Web site. Instead, he hired Hayes, the son of one of the company's
directors, for about $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked a lot better than I thought it would _ as well as if
I hired a 35-year-old professional,'' said Pyle, whose firm makes
equipment such as a hydrogen-powered tabletop grill. ``We were
happy to have the page and got it at a good price. And Will had
something that's in the alley of what he's interested in doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Other employers use teens not just to cut costs, but because
they simply can't find enough adult technical experts.
</P>
<P>
   Contra Costa County officials say they have a chronic problem
filling technical vacancies because public-sector salaries and
benefits lag far behind those offered in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Contra Costa hired five high school interns,
initially as a community service. But the students proved so
capable that they became an integral part of the county's computer
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of my total networking staff are either contractors,
trainees or in high school,'' said John Forberg, deputy director of
information services for the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids don't understand the term, `You can't do this
because it was tried before and didn't work,' '' said Steven
Steinbrecher, chief information officer for Contra Costa &UR;  &LR; County.
``It forces my regular employees to stand back and look at their
work and say, `Hm, there's competition out there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, there are some places where workplace and
school-age cultures don't exactly match.
</P>
<P>
   Contra Costa intern Rex Fujikawa, 19, kept his ponytail but was
told to remove his green-sparkle nail polish when he started work
for the county last summer.
</P>
<P>
   And Ted Biggs, 18, comes to work at the Contra Costa County
offices in a shirt and tie _ plus four earrings and four bracelets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right about now last year, I'd be over at the skate park,
listening to some punk concert,'' grinned Biggs, who is developing
standard procedures on how to make all the county's desktop
computers Year 2000-compliant. ``I never thought that this summer
I'd be working for `the man.' ''
</P>
<P>
   County officials say the main area where the students need
guidance is not in handling technical problems, but in learning
about office politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to prepare them for the fact that sometimes customers
lie and say things like `I didn't delete those files,' '' Forberg
said. ``It's tough for a younger person when an older person does
that intentionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers wonder whether the growing use of teen computer
experts could further undermine the job prospects of older
programmers, who already complain about age bias within the
technology world.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, teens are a lot cheaper than older workers: Contra
Costa pays its interns about $10 an hour for work that would cost
$65 to $200 an hour from an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get tons of e-mail from older programmers, age 40 and up,
who can't find work,'' said Norman Matloff, a computer science
professor at the University of California at Davis. ``There are a
lot of older programmers out there that companies could hire. ...
This is part of a bigger picture where employers want cheap
labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers like Matloff also worry that some tech-savvy teens
will find the job market so lucrative and alluring that they forgo
college _ a decision that could severely limit their career options
down the line.
</P>
<P>
   In Contra Costa County, officials make sure that isn't going to
happen. They keep tabs on their interns' grades during the school
year and gear the internship program toward kids who intend to go
to college.
</P>
<P>
   For many teens, money isn't the point _ though it's great to be
paid for doing something they'd be doing as a hobby anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest thrill is being treated like an adult _ working on
sophisticated equipment they'd never see at school and having carte
blanche to spend hours and hours solving real-world technical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I go in to work, I have an attitude of `This is it;
I'm going to blow their mind and show them I know more than they
ever expect,' '' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd pay THEM to let me be here 12 hours a day!'' said
Fujikawa, who is personally overseeing the launch of a
network-computer system for the county. ``The reality is, 14- or
16-year-olds can make $25 to $40 an hour these days if they have
the right skills. A lot of my college friends do work as
contractors when they're on break ... It's really amazing that what
a bunch of teenagers call fun sells in mainstream America.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
