<SLUG> BC-TEN--WIMBLEDON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Sampras wins fifth Wimbledon crown
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ Pete Sampras is dead even with Bjorn Borg. And
Goran Ivanisevic, who's catching up with Ken Rosewall in a less
auspicious category, feels dead inside.
</P>
<P>
   The thrill of victory, expressed by a screaming, fist-pumping
Sampras, and the agony of defeat, which turned Ivanisevic
inconsolable, could not be more obviously contrasted than at
Wimbledon on Sunday, where Sampras celebrated his fifth men's
singles title in six years to tie Borg's modern record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' Sampras said, ``I'm out of my slump. It's hard to
believe. I'm just a little overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic's post-mortem?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst moment of my life the worst thing ever,'' he
said, holding his head in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras would be aced 32 times by the bearded, bazooka-launching
Croatian, whom he had defeated in straight sets for the 1994
championship. He dropped an early tiebreaker badly and got blown
off the court in the lone break of the fourth set, when Ivanisevic
blasted four return winners by him.
</P>
<P>
   But the top-seeded, still No. 1-ranked American kept his wits
and finished impressively, taking a 6-7 (7-2), 7-6 (11-9), 6-4,
3-6, 6-2 victory that concluded in slightly less than 2{ hours with
Sampras breaking Ivanisevic at love.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody does that to Ivanisevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit three first serves, and he hit three returns like (it
was) a woman serving,'' Ivanisevic said. ``They were not going
anywhere; no pace, no nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men had been struggling through difficult years. Now,
presto, Sampras has fixed his, cementing his top ranking _ which
could have been lost Sunday _ after a long shaky patch dating to an
early exit from the Australian Open. But for Ivanisevic, whose
ranking has plummeted from second to 25th in the four years since
that last Wimbledon final against Sampras, a bad run just became a
lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   He had lost nine first-round matches in 1998 and failed to reach
the second round in four of five majors. Making the final here
should have provided a welcome respite, but he refused to see it
that way in his gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Even Croatia's stunning World Cup victory over Germany the
previous evening was no longer enough to pick him up after three
losses in three Wimbledon finals.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would go on to France to root for his country's
soccer team this week, Ivanisevic said: ``I cannot cheer anybody
now. I can only kill myself. I am not good for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Borg had set the 20th-century Wimbledon record with five
consecutive triumphs from 1976 through 1980. William Renshaw holds
the overall record with seven in eight years, but the last of them
came in 1888, when the so-called Challenge Round system was in
place. Then, a standing champion had to win only one match to hold
on to the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum, just Rosewall, who went 0-4
between 1954 and 1974, has more finals defeats without a victory
than Ivanisevic in this century. Jimmy Connors lost four as well,
but he also won twice.
</P>
<P>
   At least Ivanisevic's travails have lasted the relatively brief
span of seven fortnights, beginning with his defeat by Andre Agassi
in 1992. In that tournament's semifinals, Ivanisevic had eliminated
Sampras, whose match record here since is 39-1, his single loss
coming in the '96 quarterfinals to the eventual champion, Richard
Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras and the lefthanded Ivanisevic, born roughly a month
apart in 1971, are more similar than not, two mammoth servers who
find these slippery lawns to be custom-made for their power games.
But Sampras has won 11 Grand Slam titles, one shy of Roy Emerson's
record; Ivanisevic must live with the fact he's the best player on
the Association of Tennis Professionals Tour without a single Slam
to his name.
</P>
<P>
   Jana Novotna had flung the same monkey off her back in the
women's final Saturday. But the 14th-seeded Ivanisevic, facing a
far more difficult obstacle in Sampras than Novotna had in Nathalie
Tauziat, wasn't up to his challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He came close. He did well, actually, putting Sampras in a quick
hole with a strong first-set tiebreaker and then reaching set point
twice _ against Sampras second serves _ in the second-set breaker.
Sampras admitted feeling the match ``slipping away'' there, saying:
``I thought, `God, this could be Goran's year.'''
</P>
<P>
   But once they reached the fifth set, the champion's resolve in
Sampras and the ingrained also-ran's mentality in Ivanisevic came
to the fore. Sampras never has lost a five-setter at Wimbledon. Nor
a final.
</P>
<P>
   His victims, besides Ivanisevic, have been Jim Courier, Boris
Becker and, last year, Cedric Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to all the finals I've played,'' he said, ``this was
by far the toughest. I didn't think I was quite in control of the
match. Goran was playing huge and, you know, the fifth set that's
anybody's ballgame. You just have to stay patient with Goran. He's
going to pop his aces. There's nothing you can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a bit lucky out there today. I raised my level just
enough, and before I knew it, I'd won it. It's hard to believe I've
got five. I never thought Borg's (record) would be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Sampras said, ``but right now I just want to
enjoy this one as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sampras celebrated, doing the traditional champion's walk
around the court, raising the cup to the crowd, Ivanisevic put his
head under a towel. You could see he was talking to himself. The
subject matter?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's between me,'' he said, ``and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic finally did rise and, without smiling, acknowledge
the fans, who had favored him for most of the afternoon. His mood
hadn't lightened when he surfaced for his news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had too many chances to let this match go,'' Ivanisevic
said. ``Pete didn't play that well. If I go up 2-0, I don't think
he would come back. No chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough. My legs were not there at the end. I gave
everything in that fourth set, and then it was like somebody hit
me. He went up. I went down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic had needed five sets to defeat Krajicek in the
semifinals Friday, and the fifth went 15-13. But Sampras said he
didn't see any fatigue in Ivanisevic's body language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sense it one bit,'' he said. ``I thought his serve
was still coming in real big. In the fifth set of a Wimbledon
final, you just have to suck it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras believes Ivanisevic eventually will win Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, his game is too big, and his serve is too big for him
not to,'' Sampras said. ``It's not really much that separates us.''
</P>
<P>
   Except those 11 Slams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
