<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A HIGH FIVE TO BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Take these five sure-fire ways to keep baseball's
post-strike momentum going somewhat forward in the second half of
nineteen-and-uh-ninety-eight to your next town hollerin' meeting
and shove it in the suggestion box with two pennies taped around
it:
</P>
<P>
   1. Allow Mark McGwire to use an aluminum bat against any team
that issues him an intentional walk _ and !ital!then force them to
pitch to him. That chicken-livered strategy will end !ital!really
fast.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bud Selig out, Ben Stein in for permanent commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   3. No more criss-cross mowing on infield or outfield grass. It's
starting to look like some strange crop circle phenomenon, or, in
the Dodgers' case, a subliminal promotion of the ``X Files.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Make Cracker Jacks start giving away good prizes again.
</P>
<P>
   5. Have Tony Danza come to the mound and bring in Bruce Willis
to pitch to Demi Moore at ``Hollywood Stars'' night.
</P>
<P>
   Count 'em: Only 14 players and two coaches remain from the
Dodgers' Opening Day roster....
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lasorda will announce soon he has officially called off
the search for a non-interim general manager....
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager Dusty Baker said it about the Edison Field rock
formation out in center field when he saw it for the first time
last week: ``You expect to see Fred Flintstone coming out of there.
With Barney.''...
</P>
<P>
   With Steve Duchesne back on the Kings' payroll at almost $4
million a year (a bit more expensive than if he stayed and Wayne
Gretzky hadn't forced them to ship him out seven years ago),
restricted free-agent Rob Blake will likely re-sign for about $6
million a pop. But his agent is awaiting the outcome of Uwe Krupp's
contract talks to get a range on a final figure....
</P>
<P>
   Kings GM Dave Taylor might be more disappointed he couldn't also
sign up Geoff Courtnall instead of Brett Hull in the Blues' garage
sale....
</P>
<P>
   Jeers _ a long, standing one _ to TV Guide's guide-dogs who
today release a sexy ``Special Collectors' Editon'' issue touting
the ranking of ``TV's 50 Greatest Sports Moments.'' They list the
``Miracle On Ice'' !ital!Number 23 and Kirk Gibson '88 World Series
home run !ital!Number 29 after putting Torvill and Dean's perfect
6.0 at the '84 Winter Olympics in the top 10....
</P>
<P>
   In one of those Harris Poll surveys (of 1,000 adults from June
17-22), 74 percent said they've read or heard about the World Cup,
52 percent said they knew it's a soccer event and 25 percent said
they knew it's in France.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if they watched any games on TV, 19 percent said they did.
Of that 19 percent, they were asked how much they enjoyed watching.
``Not much'' came in with 45 percent....
</P>
<P>
   The title of Deion Sanders' harrowing autobiography, due out in
October, is ``Power, Money &AMP; Sex: How Success Almost Ruined My
Life.'' Which manages to include almost every buzzword needed these
days to sell a reputed piece of non-fiction....
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson's talk show just isn't the same without his
patented opening monologue....
</P>
<P>
   NFL decision-makers agree Houston has lapped L.A. in the bid to
get a franchise back....
</P>
<P>
   The ``1998 Best Sports Cities'' list by The Sporting News: 1.
Detroit, 2. Boston, 3. Dallas-Ft. Worth, 4. Chicago, 5. Denver, 6.
Philadelphia, 7. New York, 8. Miami-Fort Lauderdale, 9. San
Francisco-Oakland-San Jose, 10. Baltimore-Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and L.A. is 11th....
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant's agent, Arn Tellem, was included in Ad Age
magazine's ``Marketing 100,'' which lauds those ``visionaries who
latch onto an idea, run with it and achieve their goal of greater
sales or recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Tellem to Kobe: ``Try dunking more.'' Kobe to Tellem: ``OK.''...
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 folks who list ``actor'' on their income tax
forms auditioned for the role of Michael Jordan in a made-for-cable
bioflick planned for the Fox Family Channel....
</P>
<P>
   Just when Shaquille O'Neal and his pals are being locked out by
their employers, he finds out his deal with Reebok is over after
six years (he's probably going to hook up with Adidas). More
break-ups between athletic endorsers and shoe companies are bound
to happen in the next year or so, say business analysts....
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reebok CEO Paul Fireman is constructing a new $12
million, 27,000-square-foot home in Brookline, Mass. &QL;
</P>
