<SLUG> BC-SOC--CROATS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
World Cup's Cinderella wears Croatian slipper
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MARSEILLE, France _ Cinderella is from Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
   She has thick, dark facial hair, smokes non-filters in the
locker room and likes to eat blood sausage and sweetbreads. And we
aren't talking croissants, here.
</P>
<P>
   She is at the World Cup, and the gown she wears is a soccer
jersey that looks like a tablecloth from a Sicilian bistro.
</P>
<P>
   She wears cleats and is not afraid to use them on people's
knees. And if you try to intimidate her, she'll push back and curse
you like a Marine on three-day leave.
</P>
<P>
   She is Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   The little tough guys had their day Saturday at a place called
Stade Gerland in Lyon, where the German stars strutted in like
studs but walked away purring like kittens or whining like an '87
Jetta in need of a new alternator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe we beat Germany?'' chain-smoking Croatia coach
Miroslav Blazevic said. ``Nobody beats Germany like we did. Not in
this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it. On an unforgettable Saturday, the Croats stuck one
in the Germans' throats 3-0, sending the World Cup into a tizzy and
rendering every pre-1991 World Atlas useless once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   This tiny, new, previously unidentifiable nation, where the
entire population (4.7 million) numbers less than the number of
registered soccer players in Germany (6.2 million), pulled off the
upset of the World Cup, if not the past four or five World Cups.
</P>
<P>
   And with the victory, which sends Croatia into Wednesday's
semifinal against France, it might have accomplished in one
unforgettable evening what the past seven war-laced years at home
could not.
</P>
<P>
   It made people notice the Croatian flag. It gave the
red-and-white checkerboard-lined Croatia jerseys an indisputable
aura. And it gave the Croatian people something about which to feel
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we played that game, most of the world didn't know who
we were,'' said Croatia forward Davor Suker, who capped the
extraordinary rout with a goal in the 86th minute. ``Now, everyone
knows. This is the greatest day in the history of Croatian
football.''
</P>
<P>
   The upset indeed figures to be etched into World Cup lore.
Certainly, it brought unprecedented attention to a small strip of a
nation on the Dalmatian coast.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia, which became independent of Yugoslavia in 1991 and made
Zagreb its capital, has warred with Serbia off and on since. It is
a scenic Eastern European nation whose people are known to love to
eat red meat when they're not feasting on soccer and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But prior to 1991, not only did Croatia not have a history of
soccer, it had little history at all and nothing in the way of
direction. No soccer balls. No federation. No national programs.
There were only remnants of what the Yugoslavian republic had
built.
</P>
<P>
   At USA '94, Croatia did not compete because it still had not
fielded a national team.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nation rich in athletic talent and its passion for
sports, but it was an infant among world powers in terms of
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball, which is hugely popular in Croatia, provided such
NBA players as Toni Kukoc and Dino Radja.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia also quickly cobbled together an admirable Olympic
program after gaining independence and even won the gold medal in
team handball in 1996. It also competed well in track and field and
other events at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia also counts tennis among its more popular sports.
Sunday, Goran Ivanisevic battled Pete Sampras for the Wimbledon
crown but lost in five sets.
</P>
<P>
   Like most European nations, however, Croatia considers soccer
its national sport.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was Germany that Croatia beat. It outbattled,
outsmarted and stood toe-to-toe against a three-time World Cup
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are aware of what we have done,'' defender
Slaven Bilic said. ``This is a dream come true, but we are not
afraid of anybody. When coach Blazevic told us two years ago that
we were the best in the world, we all laughed. But we are laughing
less and less now.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory over Germany only proved the kind of serious
contender this team is. It is the first nation to advance this far
in its first World Cup appearance since Portugal made the
semifinals in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   But from the outset of this World Cup, Croatia has proved
Cinderella has learned tough lessons well.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial first-half red card drawn by Croatia's Suker against
Germany's Christian Woerns on Saturday was something most observers
would have expected to occur the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup rookies should have been the ones losing their
cool in what was a physical game, not the 12-time quarterfinalists
proudly schooled in prevailing against all odds and instigators.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Germans cried foul and complained about the
red card _ ironic, considering Germany benefited from a similar
call in ousting Croatia from the 1996 European Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The match was billed as a David and Goliath encounter, but we
can now ask the question, `Who was who?''' Suker said. ``We were
better than Germany in every aspect of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the attack against me, we knew how to take control of
the game, and we did. The German players' reactions were not
justified, because last time at Euro 96, we paid the price of a
refereeing decision. Justice was ours in this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Could the ultimate prize be next?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the best team in the world (Saturday night),''
goalkeeper Drazen Ladic said. ``We will battle anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the style of this team.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they are such battlers because of the ravages of war
their country has experienced, or perhaps it is a result of
coaching philosophy. But Croatia has gained a reputation for
fighting until the last man falls.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Croatian midfielder Mario Stanic collapsed while
walking off the field after the victory, fainting from exhaustion
and having to be revived by trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are tough and do not give up,'' German coach Berti Vogts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Croatia gained independence from the Yugoslavian
republic, Suker once was suspended from the national team for going
into the stands and fending off a Serbian police officer who was
beating a Croatian fan.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Goran Vlaovic came back from brain surgery just months
ago to earn a spot on the World Cup team. And Ladic began the World
Cup with a broken bone in his hand, which goalkeepers tend to use
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you beat us, you earned the victory,'' Suker said. ``We
have 10 men who run the entire field. We play with our hearts. We
want to show that not always do the big teams win.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest fell Saturday night. Next come the World Cup
host and 80,000 fans at Stade de France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never has a country so small come up with a game like we
played against Germany,'' Ladic said. ``Many people in our country
had a bad time in the war. We dedicate this tournament to them. We
hope we can give them some more joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of millions of people are expected to watch Wednesday's
semifinal. Take notice, world. Cinderella is on a rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to the last four teams, you are no impostor,''
Suker said. ``Before the World Cup we believed that the more games
we played, the better we would become. I think we'll play even
better against France. I think we could go all the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
