<HEADER>
A1177 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONECONOMICS-COLUMN-SF     07-05 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONECONOMICS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DARK SIDE OF WORKING FOR A SMALL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Small may be beautiful, but not when it comes to your paycheck _
and maybe not when it comes to your employer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Workers earn significantly lower wages and fewer benefits at
small companies, according to a long line of studies capped by a
controversial new report issued last week by the left-leaning
Economic Policy Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The report challenges America's love affair with small
businesses by asserting that they aren't such great places to work
after all and don't deserve the special breaks they enjoy from
government health, safety and labor regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the report has ticked off the small-business lobby.
``Hogwash,'' said Jim Weidman, a spokesman for the National
Federation of Independent Business in Washington, D.C. ``These
people just drive me nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   But economists Dale Belman at the University of Wisconsin and
Erica Groshen at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, authors of
the EPI study, can't be dismissed so quickly. They use a special
1993 supplement to the Census Bureau's Current Population Survey to
match wages and benefits to firm size.
</P>
<P>
   The data show that employees at firms with more than 1,000
workers made an average wage of $13.05 an hour in 1993 _ 39 percent
more than the $9.39 average at firms with fewer than 25 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The gap in benefits was even larger. Among employees of large
firms, 69 percent were covered by a pension plan. At the smallest
companies, the figure was only 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The same story held for health insurance. At big enterprises, 78
percent of workers were covered by health plans at their firm,
compared with 30 percent of workers at small companies.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps as a result of better pay, workers at large
companies stuck with their employers longer. Average job tenure at
large companies was 8.5 years, nearly twice the 4.4-year average at
small firms.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these differences have nothing to do with the firms as
such; they reflect, for instance, the fact that young adults, who
earn less because of their inexperience, are more likely to work at
small firms.
</P>
<P>
   But when Belman and Groshen controlled for factors such as age,
education and occupation, they found that a large wage gap remained
between large and small firms. And they showed that the gap hasn't
diminished since at least the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Economists still don't understand just why large firms pay more.
Surveys show that large firms train workers more, so one
possibility is that their employees are more productive as a
result. High wages, in turn, encourage workers to stick around
longer with the firm, so the firm enjoys the full fruits of their
training.
</P>
<P>
   Belman argues that researchers should nail down the reason so
smaller businesses could benefit from whatever it is large
businesses are doing right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's a combination of training and job security that
supports high productivity and high wages,'' he said. ``Or maybe
it's that large firms invest more capital to make employees more
productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Belman emphasized the need for balance rather than worship in
discussions of small business. ``I'm not saying mom and pop grocery
stores or startups are bad things, but we should know as we
celebrate them that they carry real disadvantages for their
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Given those disadvantages, Belman also questions whether small
firms should continue to be exempt from minimum-wage laws, the
Toxic Substance Control Act, Occupational Safety and Health
Administration inspections and other government regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these regulations are important to employees, we shouldn't
distinguish by firm size,'' he said. ``Being injured or killed at a
firm with fewer than 20 employees is as serious as being injured at
a large firm which is inspected by OSHA.''
</P>
<P>
   Small-business spokesman Weidman isn't impressed by the data
analyzed by Belman and Groshen. He noted that many workers at small
firms get benefits from spouses or parents who are covered by
larger companies. And he cited an Inc./Gallup poll last year that
found much higher levels of job satisfaction among workers in small
companies than large ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, workers at small firms don't understand how bad
off they are,'' Weidman said sarcastically. ``I'm just glad EPI is
there to straighten them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Another point in favor of small business: Every successful big
firm started out small. If you dampen the dynamism of small
business, you won't get as many large firms that pay high wages.
</P>
<P>
   David Birch, head of Cognetics Inc. in Cambridge, Mass., finds
that a disproportionate amount of job growth in America comes from
fewer than 400,000 companies that double in size every four years,
which he calls ``gazelles.'' More than a third of gazelles start
their growth spurt with fewer than 100 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Besides growing far faster than average, gazelles pay more than
average, too. Birch concedes that most small businesses, like the
local barber shop or hardware store, pay less than large firms. But
growing small firms break the mold. From 1992 to 1996, firms with
fewer than 100 employees created 87 percent of new high-wage jobs _
paying about $30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Such growth won't occur if excessive regulations strangle
emerging businesses, Birch argues. ``I don't know which of the 1.3
million firms that start up every year will become gazelles,'' he
said. ``So you have to keep throwing seeds and hope some will
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Marshall can be reached by e-mail at
marshall &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
