<HEADLINE>
IN FLORIDA, STOICISM AND THANKFULNESS FOR WHAT'S LEFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add map note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. GRAPHIC MAP is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIMS, Fla. _ Ed Callahan, who served all over the world with the
Army Special Forces and has the tattoos to prove it, stood in front
of a pile of melted glass, scorched metal and blackened wood and
talked tough about the wildfire that leaped out of the Florida
palmettos and consumed his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It don't bother me,'' he said of the once-immaculate,
middle-class house with a pool that he and his wife had filled with
memories and treasures from his postings in Asia and elsewhere.
Like dozens of others in central and northeast Florida last week,
he and his family left their house when the wildfire threatened,
and returned to find it in ashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all insured,'' said Callahan, a retired master sergeant.
``We'll re-do it. Make it even better.''
</P>
<P>
   As he talked, his wife, Setsuko, squatted in the ruin of the
house. A small woman, she had a smudge of soot on her face as she
carefully poked and sifted through a powdery ash, digging up wine
glasses that had melted into misshapen lumps, uncovering shards of
china, then moving on, foot by foot.
</P>
<P>
   She was looking for something in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my wedding ring,'' she said, and kept on digging.
</P>
<P>
   Even as wildfires raged in counties in northeastern and central
Florida, firefighters, blessed with a few scattered rain showers,
less dry wind and a higher humidity over the weekend, began gaining
ground in fire-ravaged areas instead of just grimly holding it. As
the smoke cleared, those here returned to find the result of the
roaring, popping orange flames that had forced evacuations in
scenes that have haunted the state since May.
</P>
<P>
   In Mims, a small town in Brevard County near Florida's east
central coast, hundreds of people returned to their homes this
weekend. A dozen or so, like the Callahans on Golden Shores Drive,
lost everything they could not hurriedly stuff into their car.
Others, like Frank Kirkland in the Hog Valley neighborhood near
Interstate 95, came home to find some yards and outbuildings
burned, but found with relief that firefighters had killed the
blaze just as it touched their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they hadn't been standing right there,'' almost with their
backs to his mobile home, ``it wouldn't be here,'' said Kirkland,
who used to work at the Kennedy Space Center and now raises deer
dogs and pot-bellied pigs.
</P>
<P>
   And still others, like the Mayhew family just outside Mims,
defied evacuation orders and fought the wildfire themselves,
pumping water from a nearby pond and saving a cluster of mobile
homes, although, as 21-year-old Donnie Mayhew said, it almost
seemed as if the fire was determined to have them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd put it out in one place and it would come at us from
someplace else,'' Mayhew said. ``I've never seen fire like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has, at least here.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency said 1,946 fires have
burned 458,288 acres since June 1, causing an estimated $276
million in damage _ the worst disaster since Hurricane Andrew _ and
injuring 95 people, mostly firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   In the area around Mims and nearby Scottsmoor, about 15 miles
south of the Kennedy Space Center, at least 30 houses have been
destroyed, as about 60 fires continued to burn in the surrounding
county.
</P>
<P>
   To the north, in Flagler County, a mandatory evacuation of
30,000 people remained in effect, as people waited in shelters and
wondered what they would find back home.
</P>
<P>
   People here hope for rain, maybe even a tropical storm, but any
heavy rain _ if it comes at all _ is still days away, forecasters
say.
</P>
<P>
   In Mims, a part of Florida where orange groves, dense scrub and
green inlets provide scenery for U.S. Highway 1, retirees,
blue-collar workers and charter boat captains have watched for days
as the flames threatened five-bedroom dream homes and double-wide
trailers, which were dream houses, too, for some here. Black smut
streaked several roofs of the houses still standing, and vinyl
siding hung wrinkled and warped from others.
</P>
<P>
   Bedsheets, tied to fences and mailboxes, flapped softly in the
faint breeze. ``Thank You, Firefighters,'' they say.
</P>
<P>
   And here and there are big piles of ash, where the flames either
attacked houses before firefighters could get there, or, in the
case of a few, drove them away when they did. That is what happened
to the Callahan house, where it got so hot firefighters had to
throw down their hoses and run. They returned a while later, to
apologize. But they did not have to.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan, who served in Vietnam, said he did not want anyone to
get hurt trying to save things that could be replaced. He and his
wife and daughter, 21-year-old Naomi, were fine. So were their two
dogs, two cats and a bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're luckier than other people,'' said Callahan. Some
material things, of course, could not be replaced. ``All my
medals,'' he said. ``But hell, I know what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hog Valley, a more rural road where acres of palmettos are
now blackened nubs, Donnie Mayhew sat in deep shade and described
the wildfire that left the landscape this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought it ourselves,'' he said, but he wasn't bragging.
``We were lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   It began, last week, as a glow in the distance. Then, quickly,
it was racing toward the cluster of mobile homes where Mayhew, his
father, Bill, and other family and friends live.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear it coming, crackling and roaring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no steadily marching line of flame. It burned
erratically as the wind shifted and swirled, and new fires sprang
up.
</P>
<P>
   His family had a pond, a pump and a generator to run it. The
generator saved them, after the fires burned down the power poles.
</P>
<P>
   They sprayed the houses and then focused on the fire line
itself, but every time it would seem like they had won, ``the wind
would shift, and it would come at us from the other end.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of people here, everything they have is contained in
the aluminum walls of those mobile homes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to stay until we couldn't stay no more,'' said
Mayhew.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, Frank Kirkland dumped a bucketful of water
over the head of a pot-bellied pig named Little Bit. The fire had
reached up to the wire of the pen she shared with three babies,
and, apparently, just stopped. She snorted gratefully as the cool
water trickled over her ears.
</P>
<P>
   His emotions were mixed. The firefighters saved his mobile home
at the very last minute but the flames destroyed a building he
called ``my pavilion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a TV, five picnic tables, a jukebox,'' he said. He had
planned a big party for the Fourth of July, and had stored two
whole hogs in a refrigerator, planning to barbecue them.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the refrigerator and gazed down at the meat that had
sizzled inside the freezer as the flames roared around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't get good and done,'' he said, as the stench of rotting
meat filled the air.
</P>
<P>
   For others, there were no mixed blessings, only a feeling that
something terrible had passed them by.
</P>
<P>
   In the shade of a tree near U.S. 1, three firefighters from
Okeechobee _ part of the hundreds who have come here from around
the state and country _ rested between emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   A man they had never seen walked up and thanked them. ``You guys
saved my house, twice,'' said Chet Richards, shaking their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters, Steve Weeks, Jim Fusco and Herb Smith, said it
is something that happens a lot to the firefighters here.
</P>
<P>
   A woman drove up and asked them if they were hungry, and left
them with bags of food and a giant tub of chocolate chip cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't walk around the corner without somebody bringing you
food,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   It makes it worthwhile, the men said, when it seems like the
ground underneath is about to melt their feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
