<SLUG> BC-STREETSMARTS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REDNECK' RESTAURANT HAS POTENTIAL FOR INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK VEVERKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
You might be a ``redneck'' if ... you invested in comedian Jeff
Foxworthy's nascent restaurant and barbecue sauce company.
<TEXT>
<P>
   More important, you might be a fool when you consider the fates
of Boston Chicken, Planet Hollywood and Kenny Rogers Roasters, the
latter of which is in Chapter 11. They're all publicly held
restaurant chains that have burned long-term investors. So, the
safe thing would be to take a pass on Redneck Foods of Asheville,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But if you still have barbecue on the brain after the holiday
weekend and have a penchant for risk, you might want to take a
flier on Redneck Foods (RDNK). Its 1.9 million public shares are
trading over the counter at just less than $3 after peaking at
around $4.
</P>
<P>
   OK, perhaps I got too close to the fireworks over the weekend or
sampled too much sauce, but Redneck's shares could be a compelling
growth play.
</P>
<P>
   For all of their faults, a bundle of money was made on the
upward trajectory of restaurant companies Boston Chicken and
Rainforest Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, &UR;  &LR; calling the top of the stock is the name of the
game. Boston Chicken now is running from the farmer's ax, trading
at around $1, and Rainforest is off about 45 percent from its
all-time high of $25.33 in December.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Redneck literally is just getting off the ground. It
only has one store, which opened in April near the entrance of
DisneyWorld in Florida. And early reports on the food and concept
are promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crowded all of the time,'' says regular customer Leonard
Jagnandan, an operations manager for a Miami food distributor.
</P>
<P>
   While a lot can go wrong between now and 450 restaurants,
Redneck has some intriguing possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The company is a combination play. It's both a celebrity-driven
concept, a la Planet Hollywood, Hard Rock Cafe or All Star Cafe,
and a fast-food chain rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   The key difference is that its goal is to become a national
chain of fast-food restaurants that sells affordable barbecue ribs,
chicken and pork meals. That's different from its sagging big-box
celebrity cafe rivals that are tourist destinations in major
cities, says Redneck President David Womick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be selling $30 T-shirts and $10 burgers, Womick
says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Redneck plans to keep keep average tabs less than a $8
head so that it can get repeat business from families.
</P>
<P>
   Womick, incidentally, came up with the concept and approached
Foxworthy through his agent. He brings to the table solid
restaurant experience as a director for Arby's International and an
owner of franchised restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Redneck's sells T-shirts and caps because merchandise
margins can be far more lucrative than those of food. So far,
nonfood revenues account for 17 percent of store sales, with
T-shirts starting at $12.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the restaurants, Redneck is rolling out a line of
branded foods. The company already supplies Wal-Mart with its Jeff
Foxworthy-brand barbecue sauces, which will be sold through the
Arkansas discounter's ``super center'' grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're wondering if the sauces are any good, two of
Redneck's three sauces took awards at the National Barbecue
Association's annual blind-tasting in February in Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Redneck has a recognizable brand and spokesman in
Foxworthy. Although his recent TV series recently was canceled, the
affable comedian from Atlanta has an incredibly loyal following.
</P>
<P>
   His comedy CDs and books are top-sellers, and his mug is all
over the tube. He has a current HBO special, and his stand-up act
plays to full houses.
</P>
<P>
   Foxworthy may be the perfect pitchman for Redneck. He is a
self-confessed barbecue addict who insists that the food be fresh
and the sauces be tangy. ``I didn't want (the restaurants) to be
cheesy,'' Foxworthy says.
</P>
<P>
   More than his image is at stake. Although Foxworthy has not
pumped any cash into the deal, he holds a 25 percent equity stake
in Redneck. He has a contract that commits him to only four
personal appearances at stores per year. But Womick says that he
has a verbal commitment from the star to visit every restaurant
until ``there's so many that we make him squeal.''
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous other risks. Redneck is a bulletin board
stock that can't qualify for Nasdaq until its price rises above $4
and the company lists assets of $4 million. As of October,
Redneck's assets were $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company expects to grow through acquisition and
franchising. While buying existing chains can be less expensive
than opening new stores from scratch, it also is more difficult to
create a consistent level of quality and service chain-wide.
</P>
<P>
   Womick says an acquisition is in the works and that Redneck will
have 30 restaurants by the end of the year. Eight will be
company-owned, and 22 will be owned by franchisees.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential pitfall with Redneck's strategy is that Womick
plans to simultaneously develop a second concept called
``Smokehouse Grille,'' which will be larger and more upscale.
Launching a nationwide chain of fast-food restaurants is one thing,
but trying to develop steak houses on the side seems like more than
a full plate. Womick, though, believes that he can pull it off. ``I
think I'm right on target,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Between Womick's hubris and Foxworthy's humor, it boils down to
the combined performances of two of the company's largest
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Says Foxworthy:``I don't want this to be another Kenny Rogers
Roasters.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Veverka can be reached by snail-mail at 901 Mission St.,
S.F. 94103, phone at (415) 777-8444, or e-mail at
mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. He also appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak program
on Tuesdays and Thursdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
