<TEXT>
<P>
   Playoff or not, pro tour can wait
</P>
<P>
   By Glenn Sheeley
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   KOHLER, Wis. _ Whatever happens in today's U.S. Women's Open
playoff, Duke's Jenny Chuasiriporn insists there will be no changes
to her amateur status. She might turn away Se Ri Pak today, but she
will not turn pro. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think about turning pro,'' said the 20-year-old
from Baltimore, Md., a senior this fall. ``I'm really looking
forward to my last year at Duke. ... I don't want to turn pro at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The only amateur to win the U.S. Women's Open was Catherine
Lacoste in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn's original plans today were to join her fellow
Curtis Cup team members for four days of practice in Minnesota. She
had checked out of her Kohler hotel. Her parents, who operate a
restaurant in Baltimore called The Bangkok Palace, were headed
home. Now they will be hanging on every shot in the 18-hole playoff
with another 20-year-old, South Korea's Se Ri Pak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we probably have the same amount of pressure because
she already has won her major,'' said Chuasiriporn, referring to
the McDonald's LPGA title Pak won in May. ``I never want to put too
many expectations on myself. I'm just out there to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak is attempting to become the first rookie to win two majors
in a season since Juli Inkster in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn was the 1997 winner of the Eastern Amateur, the
1996 and 1997 winner of the ACC championship and finished fifth in
the 1998 NCAAs. She also won this year's Harder Hall Invitational
and was runner-up in the North &AMP; South Women's Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   As if Sunday's 45-foot birdie putt that tied Pak was not
indication enough, Chuasiriporn's putter has been her most improved
weapon since the NCAAs. ``I was really just trying to get
comfortable with one stroke because I was wavering between
different styles,'' she said. ``I think I've finally kind of
figured it out.''
</P>
<P>
   LPGA courses too easy?
</P>
<P>
   Why was everybody complaining about tough conditions at
Blackwolf Run? Most LPGA players, said Sweden's Helen Alfredsson,
are spoiled with the easier conditions at the average LPGA tour
stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's tough, why is it crazy?'' Alfredsson said. ``Yes,
it's a course where every time you hit a shot, you go, `Phew!' But
in order to get better, sometimes you have to get tougher, not
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfredsson tied for the day's low round with a 73 during
Saturday's windy, wild conditions and tied for 13th Sunday with a
another 73, finishing at 12-over. She suggested that low scores on
the LPGA ``are not necessarily indicative that we're playing well,
but that courses might be too easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying the score is ``all relative,'' Alfredsson had no problem
with a Women's Open champion finishing several shots over par
``unless you (media) guys make us look like idiots by saying we
can't play because we're women.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Rosie Jones, who had a relatively strong weekend with
scores of 74-76 and tied for 19th at 298, was not in total
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday and Friday they (the USGA) made it so tough,'' she
said, ``it made you a little scared going into the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson lets it slip away
</P>
<P>
   Chris Johnson was at 6-over par with five holes to play and in
good position, but double-bogeyed the 14th and bogeyed the 15th.
Earlier, she doubled the ninth hole. ``I had some chances,'' she
said after tying for fourth at 8-over 292, ``and I didn't make the
most of them.'' ... Danielle Ammaccapane, who closed with a 71,
also finished 8-over after bogeying the 18th, but somehow decided,
``You know what, shooting even par on this golf course, especially
on Sunday, I'm just thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
