<HEADLINE>
BRITISH TROOPS BLOCK PROTESTANT MARCH IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds: UPDATES with minor disturbances Sunday night in Belfast, new
13th graf; deletes `and no violence followed' from 3rd graf.)  (ART ADV: A map of Portadown is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ The British government used
hundreds of combat-ready army troops and Northern Ireland policemen
Sunday to prevent several thousand Protestants from marching, as
Protestants have since 1807, through a small Roman Catholic enclave
in this town.
</P>
<P>
   The government acted to prevent clashes between the Catholic
minority and the Protestant majority in this predominantly
Protestant British province.
</P>
<P>
   The marchers, members of the patriotic Orange Order wearing
black suits and orange sashes, dispersed after one of their leaders
walked up to a huge concrete roadblock and spoke a message of
protest through a high chain fence, blocking the road to the
Catholic area. But there was no one on the other side to listen.
</P>
<P>
   The government feared that the annual march might lead to
rioting and vandalism, as it did in the last three years.
Widespread violence could endanger the recently approved peace
agreement, which spells out drastic political reforms that will
give Catholics more power in the North.
</P>
<P>
   The government was clearly gambling that this year would be
different, that Protestants, many of whom voted for the peace
agreement in a referendum in May, would be less angry at Catholics
and the government now than in 1996, when the province was racked
in turmoil for four days and night.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a government ban on the march through the Drumcree enclave
was announced several days beforehand, but the decision was
reversed because Protestant rioters wreaked millions of dollars of
property damage. The Protestant violence and the decision to let
them march provoked retaliation by Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the British official in charge of Northern Ireland,
Mo Mowlam, agreed and allowed the march after police forcibly
lifted protesting Catholics, often roughly, from the road. But this
year, approving the ban, she said that the rights of the
Protestants and Catholics had to be balanced.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 200 marchers remained quietly on the side of a hill
between the Church of Ireland church at Drumcree, where they had
attended an annual service. The Orangemen, and a few women, looked
across a small stream, its banks scooped steeper by British
diggers, at several rows of four-foot-high barbed wire coils and
armed security forces. Many said it looked like a battlefield from
a World War II movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only God will save us,'' said the Rev. John Pickering, who
spoke to the church's congregation before it left to confront
British officials. But no officials, not even a soldier or a
policeman, were at the roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a total disgrace,'' said Harold Gracey, head of the
local Orange Order. ``We'll stay here until we are allowed our
legitimate right to walk on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour after he spoke, most Orangemen had left the area, but
some set up a British Union Jack and a white Ulster flag on the
side of the stream, facing the security forces about 500 yards
away.
</P>
<P>
   Two men not wearing Orange Order regalia were arrested after
they made a brief attempt to cross the barbed wire. Several tents
were put up by people who said they intended to stay all night.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, Protestants protesting the ban on the march
created disturbances in Belfast and other towns. Some roads and
streets were blocked, bus service in Belfast was suspended and a
few cars were burned, police said. There also were instances of
youths throwing stones at policemen, but police said there were no
reports of clashes between Protestants and Catholics and no serious
injuries reported.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Catholics in Drumcree, Breandan MacCionnaith,
urged Catholics to be wary of Protestants trying to sneak through
the British lines to demonstrate. His warning seemed intended to
keep the issue alive politically, as the area is ringed with
troops, policemen, armored Land Rovers and Saxon military troop
carriers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The all-male Protestant Orange Order says that marching is a
matter of freedom of assembly, a basic democratic right. Generally,
the 3,000 Protestant parades held each summer celebrate the victory
at the Battle of the Boyne in 1690, of the Protestant William of
Orange over his father-in-law, King James II. The victory
established the Protestant Ascendancy, and British rule in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics feel that the marches, only a handful of which are
contentious, are offensive and triumphalist as the Orangemen strut
stiffly by to the martial music of loud drums. Only one group, the
Edgarstown Drum and Accordion Band, marched up to the roadblock
Sunday, thumping and wheezing its martial airs through the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the marchers Sunday milled around, chatting, even
smiling, looking at the gray sky threatening rain, seeing a single
police helicopter hovering at about 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   One angry man explained why Orangemen refused to negotiate with
Mr. MacConnaith, the Catholic leader, identifying him as ``the one
who blew up the Legion Hall in Thomas Street.'' MacCionnaith served
time in a British prison as an Irish Republican Army operative
convicted for his role in the destruction of the British social
club hall in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Notably absent Sunday was David Trimble, an Orangeman and leader
of the Ulster Unionist Party, who was chosen last Wednesday as
First Minister of the new Northern Ireland Assembly, the engine of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, now committed to trying to cooperate with Catholics in
political reforms, was a star of the 1995 Drumcree march when he
raised his arm in triumph after walking past the Catholic homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
