<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-600     07-05 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS SQUEAKS OUT A 5TH WIMBLEDON TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Pete Sampras is a historical, not
hysterical, sort of guy. He reacted to his latest triumph on
Wimbledon's Center Court, the garden spot that has now provided
five of his 11 Grand Slam championships and left him one Slam title
shy of equaling Roy Emerson's career record, with consummate
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   First he put a conciliatory arm around the shoulders of
Croatia's despondent Goran Ivanisevic, the combustible serving
machine he outlasted, 6-7 (2-7), 7-6 (11-9), 6-4, 3-6, 6-2, in a
thoroughly tense finale in which the defending champion twice
eluded set points that would have given Ivanisevic a potentially
bulletproof two sets-to-none lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for Goran,'' Sampras said. ``I've lost a couple of
Grand Slam finals, and it's the toughest defeat in tennis. There
was almost nothing that separated Goran and I at this stage of the
tournament. I just managed to squeak this one out.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Ivanisevic settled into his change-over chair and put a
towel over his head like a blindfold, Sampras felt free to step
onto the court that has been kindest to him in his superlative
career and celebrate this Wimbledon title. It was a championship
that tied him with Bjorn Borg not just here at Wimbledon, but on
the career list for men's Grand Slam titles. Martina Navratilova
holds the record in women's Grand Slam events.
</P>
<P>
   Up went Sampras' arms and, for the first time in nearly three
hours, he proved he had teeth in his mouth when he unclenched his
jaw and cast a relieved glance in the direction of his girlfriend,
Kimberly Williams, and coach, Paul Annacone. He finally felt it was
safe to smile.
</P>
<P>
   With this historic 11th Grand Slam title, the 26-year-old
Sampras, who maintains that his Slam career is far from finished,
tied his original role model, Rod Laver, and Borg. Sampras had
always expressed quiet confidence that he would play this game long
enough to break Emerson's record, which could happen as soon as the
1999 Australian Open if he commandeers a fifth U.S. Open title
later this summer. But he seemed genuinely stunned at equaling
Borg's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a little bit of time to sink in; as a kid,
when I saw Borg's five, I never thought I would be in a position to
tie it, and it's a little overwhelming to think about,'' said
Sampras, who had not passed a Slam quarterfinal since his fourth
Wimbledon crown last year _ a minor slump for a player of his
repute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I guess I'm out of my slump,'' he said, playing down his
reaction to the criticism that accompanied him at this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't avoid it,'' he said of the comments, some of them
from fellow players, regarding his inauspicious 1998 season and
apparently sagging motivation. ``But my goal here was to try to
win, and I wasn't going to let any wasted emotion overtake that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras termed it a footnote that this title also resolidified
his position as No. 1 in the world. That designation would have
gone to Chile's Marcelo Rios had Ivanisevic imitated Jana Novotna,
Wimbledon's 1998 women's champion, and finally broken through on
his third attempt to win this title.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, whose fifth Wimbledon title arrived on the 18th
anniversary of Borg's record fifth consecutive championship, had
zipped through a dress rehearsal for Sunday's match when he
defeated the Croat here in straight sets for the 1994 title. But
the reprise was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who likens these duels with Ivanisevic to
roller-coaster rides, had anticipated a rough trip, and he got one:
This was the first time that Sampras, now 11-2 in Grand Slam
finals, was stretched to a fifth set.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Luckily for him, the 14th-seeded Ivanisevic had soldiered
through a 15-13 fifth set in his semifinal upset of Richard
Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon champion. Once Sampras and his
challenger ventured into five-set territory Sunday, the fatigued
Croat, who managed to deliver just two of his 32 aces in the
deciding set, all but raised a white flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fifth set, gone; my legs were not there,'' said
Ivanisevic, who traced his miseries to his failure to convert
either of the two match points he held on serve in the fourth set
of his epic against Krajicek. ``That cost me this final today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, I had the chance, because he didn't play well. In
'94, we play two sets, and then the third set, he killed me,'' the
Croat said of his 0-6 no-show in the final set of his 1994
Wimbledon final against Sampras. ``But today was very close, a lot
of everything, it was interesting, but now it's the worst moment of
my life. You know, I've had some bad moments, when you are sick or
when somebody dies, but for me this is the worst thing ever,
because nobody's died yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He then implied that this was the kind of loss that turns
players like him suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only kill myself, I can't cheer anybody now,'' said
Ivanisevic, referring to his sudden inability to get excited about
Croatia's surge to the World Cup semifinals. After using this Grand
Slam event to cure a slump that was far more debilitating than
Sampras' (coming into this event, Ivanisevic had stumbled in the
opening round of three straight Grand Slam events and seen his
ranking plummet to No. 24, a faux pas overlooked by Wimbledon's
selective seeding committee), Ivanisevic was inconsolable after
falling just short in the final. And Sampras understood why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the match slipping away in the second-set tie
breaker,'' Sampras admitted. ``I thought, `God, this could be
Goran's year.' There was a shot he missed by about an inch, I was
down some set points, he hits some second serves, and if he
converts on one of those, it's two sets to love and I'm digging
myself a big hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of making that mistake, Sampras, whose slow start was
evident in his being out-aced by 13-0 in the first set, came up
with service winners to the backhand side on both of Ivanisevic's
set points in the second-set tie breaker and converted his third
set point when the Croat netted a forehand return.
</P>
<P>
   Using that momentum, Sampras broke Ivanisevic with a crosscourt
backhand return to go ahead, 3-2, in the third set and went on to
win it with an ace. But the Croat reasserted himself with three
beautiful running forehand passing shots and took a 4-2 lead in the
fourth set, which he pocketed with an ace of his own to send the
match to the fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras went up by 5-2 there and, slightly to his surprise,
broke his exhausted opponent at love for the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't take these titles for granted,'' Sampras said, ``and
compared to all the finals I've played, this is by far the
toughest. I didn't think I was quite in control of the match, and
Goran was playing huge. In fact, he's going to win this event, I
feel. His game is too big and his serve is too big and I would be
frustrated if I was in his shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Pete Sampras, 16-year-old Serena Williams isn't chasing
history quite yet; instead, she's trying to keep up with her
18-year-old sister, Venus, who already owns a pair of mixed-doubles
Grand Slam titles with Justin Gimelstob. On Sunday the younger
Williams and her new partner, Max Mirnyi of Belarus, defeated
fifth-seeded Mirjana Lucic and Mahesh Bhupathi, 6-4, 6-4, to claim
the mixed doubles title. In the women's doubles final, the
top-seeded partnership of Jana Novotna, this year's singles
champion, and Martina Hingis, last year's singles champion,
defeated second-seeded Lindsay Davenport and Natasha Zvereva, 6-3,
3-6, 8-6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
