<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENTLE ZEPHYR FORCES CONE TO ALTER STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Cone played Yankee Stadium Sunday like a golfer
might have. It was as if he lugged a few blades of grass to the top
of the mound, flipped them upward, read the gusting air currents
and adjusted his pitching to honor the whims of Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that a heavy crosswind would minimize the
effectiveness of three of his primary pitches, Cone changed his
approach and pitched eight innings in the Yankees' 1-0 shutout of
Baltimore, before 52,506, becoming the American League's second
12-game winner. In completing a three-game sweep of the Orioles,
the Yankees improved their record to 61-20, matching the best mark
of the 20th century, previously established by the 1902 Pittsburgh
Pirates and the 1907 Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees already have an 11-game lead in the AL East, ahead
of Boston; they lead the Orioles (38-50), who were thought to be
their biggest challenge, by 26{ games, 30 games in the loss column.
After returning Thursday from the three-day All-Star Game break
that begins Sunday, the Yankees need to win only 39 of their final
81 games to achieve 100 victories.
</P>
<P>
   It does not seem to matter who plays for the Yankees, or who
does not play: so long as they wear pinstripes, they will win.
Already Manager Joe Torre was without Bernie Williams, the injured
center fielder, and Chuck Knoblauch and slugger Darryl Strawberry,
both of whom were nursing sore knees. Nevertheless, Torre decided
to give third baseman Scott Brosius a day off. The Yankees'
starting lineup included Dale Sveum, the seldom-used utility
infielder who has seven hits this season; Luis Sojo, making his
third start at second base this year, and rookie outfielder Ricky
Ledee, who likely will be returned to Class AAA Columbus once
Williams returns.
</P>
<P>
   And yet they found a way to win. The Yankees forced Scott
Erickson, Baltimore's hard-throwing sinkerballer, to throw 29
pitches in the first inning, and with one out in the third, Sojo
bounced a grounder off Erickson's glove for an infield single. Paul
O'Neill lined a single to left-center field, and Sojo took third.
Tino Martinez then battled Erickson for 10 pitches, fouling off
five before striking out, and Tim Raines walked after a 7-pitch
at-bat, filling the bases. Already Erickson had thrown 64 pitches
in two and two-thirds innings, 27 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Chad Curtis, Erickson threw a slider with his first
pitch, and it was high, far off target, evidence that he was weary
from working so long in the inning. Mike Flanagan, the pitching
coach, went to the mound to give Erickson a breather.
</P>
<P>
   But Erickson's next pitch grazed Curtis' left shoulder,
ricocheting off Curtis' left hand, to force home Sojo. Like a boxer
recovering from an early knockdown, Erickson recovered the next
inning and mowed down the Yankees the rest of the day. ``By the
fourth or fifth inning, I knew that one run might just about be
it,'' Cone said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One would be enough for Cone _ remarkably, catcher Joe Girardi
said later, noting that Cone's stuff was quite ordinary. As he
warmed up before the game, Cone noticed immediately that the wind
was blowing from left to right, from the Yankees' dugout on the
first-base side to the Baltimore dugout on the third-base side, and
it was hampering the movement on his slider, his forkball and his
four-seam fastball. ``He had to do a little inventing,'' Girardi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cone is used to changing according to weather conditions: he
prefers the heat and loses his grip in extreme cold. Sunday he
changed his arm angle repeatedly, altered the timing of his
delivery from pitch to pitch and threw more sinking fastballs and
different styles of breaking balls, pitches that worked with the
wind currents, rather than against them. And the Yankees'
meteorologist dominated.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed only seven hits, walked none _ he has not walked a
batter in his last three starts, encompassing 24 innings _ and
always overcame challenges. The Orioles were 0-for-6 with runners
in scoring position; over Cone's last eight starts, opponents are
5-for-37 (.132) with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   It was Girardi who came the closest to knocking out Cone, in the
eighth: as Girardi fired a throw to second base on an attempted
steal, the ball skimmed Cone's right ear. Cone got through the
inning and made a half-hearted attempt to persuade Torre to leave
him in for the ninth. But Mariano Rivera relieved for the ninth,
retired Baltimore in order and Yankees players showered and rushed
out of the clubhouse quickly, off to a well-deserved three days of
rest and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Orioles, who have had their share of bad blood
and hit batsmen this season, engaged in another tete-a-tete in the
first inning Sunday. David Cone hit Brady Anderson in the leg in
the top of the first, and when the Yankees came to bat, Baltimore's
Scott Erickson threw his first pitch behind the back of Derek
Jeter. Ken Kaiser, the home-plate umpire, spoke sharply with
players from both teams and stemmed the ugliness. ... The Yankees'
rotation for the first five games after the All-Star Game break
will be Andy Pettitte, Hideki Irabu, David Cone, David Wells and
Orlando Hernandez _ which will allow Cone to get an extra day of
rest. ... The April 26 rainout with Detroit will be made up as part
of a twi-night doubleheader on Monday, July 20. The first pitch is
scheduled for 4:05 p.m. at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
