<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE REST IS HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTHAMPTON, N.Y. _ Letters, handwritten notes and the
contemporaneous recollections of yesterday's insiders helped us
understand ``the way it really was'' in America's past. But
technology, fear of prosecution and the blindness of publishers
threaten to deny tomorrow's historians access to this generation's
primary sources.
</P>
<P>
   The revealing personal letter of the past has been engulfed in
today's tide of telephonic chatter, short bursts of e-mail, and
computer revisions that leave no trace of editing's second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep notes?'' a White House aide asked me incredulously, when
I expressed the hope that he would create the factual basis for a
memoir. ``They'd be subpoenaed in a minute. And your old boss
proved how taping can kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the recollections of insiders, set down as soon as
possible after power passes, to show the motivation of leaders and
quirks of fate that shape our lives. Lately, the insiders have been
letting down the side.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the primary sources that gave us Robert E. Sherwood's
``Roosevelt and Hopkins'' or speechwriter Samuel Rosenman's
``Working with Roosevelt'' or ``The Secret Diaries of Harold
Ickes''? (If Ickes' son published a secret diary today, the whole
Chinese connection of the DNC might be marching off to jail.)
</P>
<P>
   What recent diplomats enlivened history with the human element
as did Dean Acheson and Henry Kissinger? Neither Jimmy Carter's
Cyrus Vance nor George Bush's James Baker illuminated the
landscape; Ronald Reagan's George Shultz did a solid job, but hopes
are low for Bill Clinton's Warren Christopher or security spinster
Sandy Berger. Maybe Strobe Talbott, a former Time columnist, will
season friendship with firsthand fact.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush, six years into retirement, is still fumbling
through his own book. Reagan's in-house historian, Edmund Morris,
has been laboring on an opus so magnum it will appear this fall
after more than a decade in preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Speechwriters have a special obligation to observe character,
report anecdote and explicate policy, as Peggy Noonan faithfully
did with Reagan and Bush. But Pat Buchanan, unique in his closeness
to both Nixon and Reagan, has written only about his own life and
ideas. David Gergen was also at the center in two administrations;
where's his inside account?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps publishers need prodding. The last Nixon insider who
hasn't spilled anything is Ron Ziegler, who escaped the Inquisition
but was on the scene at the most dramatic administration's most
dramatic moments. He has notes, vivid memories, and the sense of
humor necessary for a book tour; maybe he needs an agent.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Packwood diaries? Now that charges of
transgressions are seen by feminists to have been relatively mild
to the point of quaintness, his two-decade account of Senate
operations _ a book including a searchable compact disc, Pepysian
in its detail, inserted in the back cover _ would be an invaluable
resource for tomorrow's political scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of CDs, triangulator Richard Morris _ whose rushed-out
memoir was too much about himself, but who writes a lively weekly
column for ``the Hill'' _ has an archive on his computer recounting
notes he took of hundreds of meetings with Clinton and White House
aides, as well as drafts of speeches and political commercials.
Some prestigious university press should snap that up.
</P>
<P>
   Even though burdened with the fear of subpoenaed notes, Clinton
insiders should consider history as part of their permanent
campaign. Confidants like Bruce Lindsey and Sidney Blumenthal may
have to delay publication until the statutes of limitation run, but
the rush of voluntary revelations then should settle many questions
resolutely resisted now.
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos' sympathetic but not sycophantic book will
break the ice. Let's hear from Leon Panetta on the welfare-policy
turnaround, Ira Magaziner on Hillarycare, Mike McCurry or Betty
Currie on life inside the bunker, Charles Ruff on privilege,
Hickman Ewing on Ken Starr, John Huang on changing policy with
contributions, Madeleine Albright on Life With Holbrooke and
William Cohen's Pentagon Poems.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together with congressional reports and the Clintons'
memoirs, the fulfillment of the insiders' obligation to history
will give us a base on which to draw more profound judgments. Can't
wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
