<HEADER>
A1207 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NY-SAKS-RETAIL-ART-     07-05 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-SAKS-RETAIL-ART-790(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TENNESSEE COMPANY WILL ACQUIRE SAKS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Resending to corrrect slug)  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saks Fifth Avenue, one of the most venerable names in
retail, said Sunday that it would be acquired for $2.1 billion by
Proffitt's Inc., a Southern retailing company that is all but
unknown to New York shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal would represent the end of an era for Saks,
whose founders, Horace Saks and Bernard Gimbel, probably never
imagined that the famous store on natty Fifth Avenue would one day
be part of a retail conglomerate based in Alcoa, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Since Saks was founded in 1924, it has undergone several changes
of ownership, managing to escape the fate of many famous New York
stores. It avoided extinction, unlike B. Altman and Gimbel's, and
it was not swallowed up by a giant retail company, as was Macy's
when it was acquired by Federated Department Stores.
</P>
<P>
   For shoppers on Fifth Avenue looking for the latest Gucci shoe,
the change of ownership will not be noticeable, but those living in
the Midwest, where some of Saks' less profitable stores are, may
see a different name above the door. And some of Proffitt's stores
may change their name to Saks. In fact, Proffitt's will rename
itself Saks Inc., seeking some of the glamour of the famous name.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just one Saks Fifth Avenue, and the power of the
brand is exactly where retail is going,'' said Robert Bradley
Martin, Proffitt's chief executive, who will be the chairman and
chief executive of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   The merger serves as a near-exit strategy for the largest
shareholder of Saks Holdings Inc., the Bahrain-based investment
company Investcorp International, which bought the retailer for
$1.6 billion in 1990 and had been hoping in recent years to make a
killing the way it did with other luxury investments like Tiffany &AMP;
Co. and Gucci Group.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bank initially sold 20 percent of Saks to the
public in 1995 for $425 million and followed up with another stock
offering, it now finds itself and its clients not cashing out as
they had hoped, but rather holding 12 percent of Proffitt's.
</P>
<P>
   Still, based on Thursday's closing stock prices, Investcorp and
other shareholders in Saks now own stock worth about 15 percent
more than last week, assuming shareholders of both companies
approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Proffitts does not seem to be the best match for
Saks. Proffitt's runs 234 stores that serve middle-income shoppers
in the South and Midwest with names like Proffitt's, Younkers,
Carson Pirie Scott, and Herbergers. Most of the stores resemble
Macy's in terms of what they sell _ lots of Tommy Hilfiger, Liz
Claiborne, Nine West and Estee Lauder.
</P>
<P>
   Saks has the opposite strategy at its 95 stores nationwide. Many
of the brands that Proffitt's specializes in were evicted from Saks
two years ago in an effort to give the retailer a tonier image. Its
staples are Gucci, Oscar de la Renta and Yves St. Laurent, all
names not carried even in Proffitt's most upscale store, Parisian.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of merchandise synergies, there are none,'' Martin
admitted. ``But we'll buy telecommunications, transportation, paper
supplies and other things at an enormous cost savings. This deal is
not built on merchandise synergies.''
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's, which was founded in 1919 with a handful of stores
in Knoxville, Tenn., has built its fortunes on the success of
acquisitions. In the last three years, it has acquired a dizzying
seven names, including Carson Pirie Scott in the Midwest, and has
slowly built up a portfolio, creating $3.5 billion in revenue. As a
result of the acquisitions, sales and profit margins have risen
smartly as expenses have become lower.
</P>
<P>
   While the company was attracted to operational cost savings with
the Saks acquisition, it is also eager to tap into the Saks fashion
savvy that has been lacking at Proffitt's.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will form a product-development unit that will
build up private-label programs for all the divisions. Saks already
has a strong variety of private-label brands, and Proffitt's has
said that it wants 12 percent of its merchandise to be private
label.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the two stores now have access to each other's geographic
regions. Expanding on both coasts, for example, ``would be a good
supplement to what Proffitt's does in the Midwest,'' said Isaac
Lagnado, a retail consultant in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Other plans for the new company include greater international
use of the Saks name, an increase in the number of domestic stores,
and an expanded use of the database of Saks credit-card holders and
catalog shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Proffitt's will keep its headquarters in Tennessee, while Saks
will be run more or less independent of the company's other
divisions, by its current management team out of New York.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Philip B. Miller, the chief executive of Saks, Brian
Kendrick, the retailer's chief operating officer, and Martin sat in
Miller's opulent office across the street from the company's
flagship store, talking of how enthusiastic they were about the
deal. ``Brad has demonstrated that he has the vision and financial
acumen to assemble businesses,'' Miller said of Martin. Martin
added, ``This is a deal I am really excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   But although both are powerful retail executives in their own
right, their backgrounds and manner could not be more dissimilar.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 60, has been a retailer for his entire career. He began
at Filene's; he has been chairman of Marshall Field's and president
of Neiman Marcus and has held executive positions at Lord &AMP; Taylor
and Bloomingdale's. Martin, 46, fell into retail almost by accident
after serving in the Tennessee House of Representatives for 10
years and dabbling in real estate. In 1984, he bought Proffitt's,
noting that his wife liked to shop there. He took it public in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is the epitome of a New York retailer, with custom
chalk-striped suits, burgundy suspenders and matching tie.
</P>
<P>
   His year-round tan suggests time spent at exotic outposts, and
his expensive wing-tipped shoes show that he cares about the sport
of shopping. His eyes light up when he talks about fashion; he
hobnobs with the likes of the designer Isaac Mizrahi, whom he
honored at a charity event he ran last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Martin looks like a high school vice principal. On Sunday he was
wearing a checked shirt, a casual floral tie and the sort of
nondescript plain black shoes that get replaced every two years
when their soles wear thin.
</P>
<P>
   His most famous friends are Lamar Alexander, the Tennessee
Republican and former governor, with whom Martin once ran a
business, and Bob Keeshan, known to the rest of the world as
Captain Kangaroo.
</P>
<P>
   Martin turns a conversation about retail to the area of cost
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, shareholders of Saks Holdings would
be given 0.82 share of Proffitt's in exchange for each Saks share,
representing a transaction of about $2.1 billion, or a little less
than Saks' annual sales of $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Thursday's closing stock prices, each share of Saks
would be worth about $33.36; the stock closed last week at $29, up
$1.625. That 15 percent premium, however, is likely to change as
Wall Street reacts on Monday to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   And shareholders may do better with shares in the new company.
Saks went public at $25 a share and has averaged about $23 this
year. By contrast, Proffitt's shares closed at $40.6875 Thursday, a
48 percent increase since the beginning of the year and far more in
line with Standard &AMP; Poor's retail index, which is up about 30
percent to date.
</P>
<P>
   Saks was represented in the deal by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Proffitt's was represented by Salomon Smith
Barney Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
