<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-PORTADOWN-BOS &LR;      07-05 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-PORTADOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY FRUSTRATES EFFORT TO MARCH BY ORANGE ORDER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ Several thousand Protestants were
stymied Sunday in their efforts to march through a Catholic
neighborhood, leading to a standoff that could last indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant members of the Orange Order, who insist it is their
right to march the route they have followed since 1807, have vowed
to stay here until they are allowed to walk down the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   Separating them from their goal are more than 2,000 police
officers and British soldiers, a deep moat, a half-mile of barbed
wire, metal barriers, and a British government apparently
determined to prove that it will respect the concerns of Catholic
nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics say the new political settlement guaranteeing equal
rights for them compels the British government to prevent the
Orangemen, so named for William of Orange, a 17th-century Dutch
king who ruled Britain with Queen Mary, from forcing their way
through the neighborhood. William is a hero to Ulster Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constant drone of British Army helicopters, the
standoff at Drumcree Church began almost anticlimactically, as a
few hundred Orangemen gathered in a field, surrounded by barbed
wire, and heavily-armed police and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   As dusk settled in this most bitterly divided town in Northern
Ireland, an eerie quiet suggested the intimidation and violence
promised here would manifest themselves elsewhere. Most of the
Orangemen went home, to collect provisions, many of them vowing to
return.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, there were no violent confrontations, but
loyalists torched cars and threw gasoline bombs in Sandy Row, a
loyalist enclave just outside Belfast city center, 35 miles
northwest of here. Some sources there suggested the unrest had more
to do with a dispute at a bar than the standoff at Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
   The security measures taken by the British Army and the Royal
Ulster Constabulary left the Orangemen unsure of what to do. When
the midday service at Drumcree Chruch ended, the Orangemen walked
down the hill to an ugly steel barrier that prevented them from
proceeding up to the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike two years ago, when the police held the line for five
days before giving in, touching off the worst rioting in Northern
Ireland in years, there were no face-to-face confrontations between
police and the Orangemen. Instead, an Orange Order leader stood in
the shadow of the 20-foot-high barrier, cursing the barbed wire as
he read out a protest to the hundreds of reporters gathered at the
barrier before leading the parade back the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Again, unlike two years ago, when the fields surrounding
Drumcree Church were flooded with Orangemen wearing the sashes that
signify their loyalty to the British crown, there was only a token
presence of Orangemen throughout the day. Some suggested hundreds
or thousands of supporters would flock here over the next few days,
building pressure to let them march the rest of their traditional
route.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about their strategy, Orange leaders were coy. David
Burrows, a leader of the Portadown lodge, said Orangemen from
throughout Northern Ireland would fill the fields.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long they were prepared to stay, David Jones, a local
Orange leader, said, ``As long as it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Ingram, the British minister in charge of security, said it
was up to the police to decide whether the Orangemen are allowed to
stay there for as long as they want.
</P>
<P>
   On the nationalist side, Breandan Mac Cionnaith, leader of the
Garvaghy Road residents' group, said it was up to the British
government to prove its word by safeguarding the concerns of
nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Orange Order does not intend to listen to reason from any
quarter,'' said Mac Cionnaith.
</P>
<P>
   Orange Order officials estimated the marchers at 8,000. But a
count of those marching in the parade up to Drumcree Church by The
Boston Globe and The Irish Times placed the figure at about 2,500.
Police did not provide an estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the count, it was considerably larger than the roughly
1,500 members of the Portadown lodge that organizes the annual
march. Orangemen say the march and church service is to commemorate
the thousands of Ulstermen, both Protestant and Catholic, who died
at the Battle of the Somme in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   But Catholic nationalists consider the parade provocative and
offensive and do not want it in their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Garvaghy Road residents agreed to let the march proceed
with the understanding that there would be no triumphalist
displays, and with a promise from the local police commander that
any future parades would require the consent of residents. But
after the Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble and the Rev. Ian
Paisley, a fundamentalist preacher who leads the most
uncompromising of unionists, were photographed dancing gleefully
down the road and proclaiming a ``victory'' in getting the parade
through, Mac Cionnaith and the residents dug in their heels.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after police relented against the loyalist threat and
beat nationalists off the road to let the parade pass, widespread
rioting flared throughout Northern Ireland. Last year, the police
chief, Ronnie Flanagan, decided that letting the parade through was
the ``lesser of two evils.'' Again, residents were beaten off the
road so the parade could pass. Again, rioting flared.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Parades Commission, created by the British
government to arbitrate the issue of contentious parades, ruled
that in the interest of stability throughout Northern Ireland the
march would be routed away from the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   Orangemen, who pride themselves on being tough on law and order,
say they do not recognize the legitimacy of the Parades Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Up on the Corcrain Road, Gloria McLaughlin, 55, brought her two
grandchildren to see the Orangemen march up to Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't let them walk back the way they want, pet,'' she
explained to her 7-year-old granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Her 4-year-old grandson said he did not understand. ``It's
because of the terrorists, love,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin, who is Protestant, said she used to live in the
adjacent Catholic housing project, but had been forced out, and
considered the curtailing of the Orange parade the latest in a
series of humiliations Protestants had suffered in recent years.
She blamed the IRA and its political supporters in Sinn Fein for
isolating Protestant unionists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my best friends are Catholics,'' McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, people on and along the Garvaghy Road
relished a quiet first Sunday in July, their first in at least four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wee bit of quiet will do us good,'' said Mary Murphy,
walking a half-dozen of her grandchildren back from the convenience
store.
</P>
<P>
   But Frankie Hamill saw little reason to be pleased, despite the
buffer zones between his community and Protestant unionists
fashioned by heavily armed police and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Hamill stood outside St. John the Baptist church as passing
Orangemen stamped up and down on the pavement. It was, he said, an
insult to the memory of his cousin, Robert Hamill, who was stomped
to death by a loyalist mob last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the mindset,'' Hamill said. ``It hasn't changed. No
matter what year it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
