<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/3/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- July 3, 1998 -- IMMIGRANT-WELCOME-2, 7-3 --
Julie Horvath-Krol, an actress from Hungary, says: don't wait in
lines Q make an appointment. If Independence Day celebrates America
Q fireworks, parades and cascades of red, white and blue Q then it
also celebrates what it means to be an American. And being an
American usually means being an immigrant or a descendant of
immigrants. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- July 3, 1998 -- IMMIGRANT-WELCOME-1, 7-3 --
Dame Babou says immigrants need advice on where to learn English.
``I've observed people who ordered the same type of food for six
months, nine months, simply because they didn't know the word for
the other foods,'' says Babou, 45, who emigrated from Senegal 10
years ago and now works as a radio and newspaper correspondent in
Manhattan. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BOSTON -- July 3, 1998 -- JULY4-BOSTON-POPS, 7-3 --
David Mugar, a millionaire businessman who has sponsored Boston's
Fourth of July concerts since fireworks were added 25 years ago,
reviews preparations at the Hatch Shell, where the concert will be
held on Friday. ``I came up with the idea, just by luck, I guess
now, of having fireworks at the end of it,'' he says. (Ed Quinn/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico -- July 3, 1998 -- NAFTA-ENVIRON,
7-3 -- The ``black ditch'' in Ciudad Juarez, which serves as a
primitive method of sewage disposal for a city with a population of
1.2 million. Every day the Mexican city across the Rio Grande from
El Paso produces 75 million gallons of raw sewage, much of which
finds its way to the river, the prime source of water for nearly
every community in both Mexico and the United States between here
and the Gulf of Mexico. (Bruce Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) TAMAQUA, Pa. -- July 3, 1998 --
MOLLY-MAGUIRES-MEMORIES-2, 7-3 -- Not long ago, the violent era of
the Molly Maguires was a taboo subject around Tamaqua. Now, it is
the stuff of a summer festival. Chilling scenes of the past are
re-enacted, like final blessings for the condemned. (Tim
Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) TAMAQUA, Pa. -- July 3, 1998 --
MOLLY-MAGUIRES-MEMORIES-1, 7-3 -- Not long ago, the violent era of
the Molly Maguires was a taboo subject around Tamaqua. Now, it is
the stuff of a summer festival. Chilling scenes of the past are
re-enacted, like this appointment with the gallows. (Tim
Shaffer/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 3, 1998 -- NY-AMUSEMENT-PARK, 7-3 --
Megan Gentile aboard a helicopter ride Friday at South Beach
Amusement Park, which is for sale. The park is the heart of the
Staten Island summer, an acre of Americana almost in the shadow of
the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge. It is the final remnant of a
continuous string of amusement parks Q replete with Ferris wheels,
sideshows and tens of thousands of weekend visitors Q that once
rivaled Coney Island. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- July 3, 1998 -- SURVEILLANCE, 7-3 -- A
window display for the ``Police Pictures'' show at Grey Art
Gallery. Surveillance is out of hand. Walk into an apartment lobby
and you are on camera. Ride on an elevator and the guards in the
lobby watch you adjusting your pants. Get some money from a cash
machine and you'll be caught on film counting your bills. Busy
intersections are under 24-hour surveillance. There are cameras in
public squares. Don't bother destroying them. They'll only catch
you on tape doing it. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- July 3, 1998 -- CHINA-PEONY, 7-3 -- Chen
Shi-Zheng, director of the magnificent production of the Chinese
opera ``The Peony Pavilion'' by the Shanghai Kunqu Opera Company
that was to have opened the Lincoln Center Festival next Tuesday
evening. But the project ran aground at the last minute on the
stony will of Ma Bomin, the director of the Shanghai Municipal
Bureau of Culture. ``This has been the longest two weeks of my
life,'' says Chen, 35. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) STAMFORD, Ct. -- July 3, 1998 -- CENDANT-FORBES, 7-3 --
Walter Forbes, Cendant's chairman, has kept a low profile since the
company reported the discovery of accounting irregularities in
April. But he says he still intends to take over as chief executive
in 2000. (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) VALLEY FORGE, Pa. -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY
5 -- MUTFUND-VANGUARD, 7-3 -- Discount brokerage services ``are
never going to be a dominant part of what we are,'' says John
Brennan, chairman and chief executive of the Vanguard Group. ``My
job is to keep people focused on what it is that made us successful
in the first place,'' namely, ``a high value, client-first
philosophy.'' (Jonathan Levine/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ANDERSON, Ind. -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5
-- EARN-MEDICAL-SAVINGS, 7-3 -- Julie Griswold of Anderson signed
up for a medical savings account to salt away tax-free money, but
the move didn't work out so well for her. ``If you are healthy or
if you make a lot of money, it's a great plan,'' says Ms. Griswold,
who earns about $26,000 a year and has had to postpone further
tests because of her medical bills. ``But if things start to go
wrong and you don't have a high income, it's not.'' (Tom
Strickland/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PALM DESERT, Calif. -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 5 -- SERIAL-MERGERS-2, 7-3 -- Richard Heckmann is the chief
executive of United States Filter Corp., which has completed more
than 150 acquisitions since 1991. Keeping track of all of the
company's activities is nearly impossible. And the sheer number of
purchases means that most investors do not know how quickly certain
businesses are growing and how profitable they are. (Davis
Barber/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHARLOTTE, N.C. -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5
-- SERIAL-MERGERS-1, 7-3 -- Edward Crutchfield, the chairman of
First Union, which has made more than 70 acquisitions since 1985.
Crutchfield is telling analysts and investors that the bank will no
longer pursue deals in which it must pay a premium. (Nancy
Pierce/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
BANK-MERGERS, 7-3 -- At a public hearing in Manhattan last month,
community activists protest the pending Citicorp-Travelers Group
merger by chanting and raising red umbrellas Q Traveler's logo. As
part of their merger application, Citicorp and Travelers, which
will be known as Citigroup, have promised the Federal Reserve that
they will make $115 billion in loans to low-income and minority
communities over the next 10 years. (John Sotomayor/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) DENVER -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
MUTFUND-QUARTER-3, 7-3 -- Scott Schoelzel found firm ground in a
spongy spring quarter. Big technology bets did the trick for his
Janus 20 portfolio, which, as its name implies, holds just 20
stocks. (Ellen Jaskol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
MUTFUND-QUARTER-2, 7-3 -- Tracy Stouffer, of Federated
International Small Co., looked to Europe. ``We're not getting any
small-cap effect in emerging markets because all the companies are
becoming smaller and smaller, the result of shrinking prices and
currency erosion,'' she says. Her fund, which ended in third place
on the list of diversified international stock funds for the second
quarter, returned 10.5 percent. (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ATLANTA -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
MUTFUND-QUARTER-1, 7-3 -- Michael Orkin of Caldwell &AMP; Orkin Market
Opportunity found firm ground in a spongy spring quarter. His fund,
based in Atlanta, landed the No.12 position on the list of
best-performing United States diversified funds in the second
quarter, with a 10.1 percent return. Much of that is attributable
to Orkin's short-selling, which involves betting on a decline,
rather than an increase, in the price of a stock. (Alan S.
Weiner/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) EDGEWATER, N.J. -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5
-- YEOHLEE-SHOP, 7-3 -- At Yaohan Plaza, the riverfront Japanese
mall in Edgewater, Yeohlee Teng, the Malaysian-born New York
designer, has a field day. Badtz Maru pops up everywhere here. His
pudgy cartoon features glower on miniaturized note pads and canvas
backpacks, and he puffs himself up importantly on a child's lunch
box, where he caught Yeohlee's eye. The mall is a mecca for
homesick Japanese. (David Corio/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ROCKLIN, Calif. -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5
-- FUNDS-WATCH, 7-3 -- Jack Bowers, the editor of Fidelity Monitor
in Rocklin, has devised a system for selecting sector funds. ``If a
sector is cheap and performs well, it tends to continue to
outperform six months past the point at which it is no longer
considered a good value,'' he says. (Don Preisler/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
ABOUT-CARS-CADILLAC, 7-3 -- The DeVille boasts ``X Files''
engineering, but the container is still all Lawrence Welk. It has
been 20 years since Cadillac had a record sales year. What has
happened to this American icon underscores a marketing adage: Great
brands don't die; they kill themselves. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
CAR-SMART-CORVETTE, 7-3 -- The new-generation Corvette convertible,
left, and removable-top model, are now on the market. A
million-plus Corvettes have been built in more than four decades,
more than any other single sports car ever. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HARTFORD, Conn. -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5
-- SPEND-CAR-LEASE, 7-3 -- Leigh Gold of West Hartford says she
thought she was buying a Volvo station wagon. But after her last
payment, she says, she was told that she had only been leasing it Q
and that she would have to pay an additional $1,000 to buy it
outright. (George Ruhe/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 3, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 5 --
KARAOKE-NIGHTLIFE, 7-3 -- Performers at the Lansky Lounge on the
Lower East Side have included David Lee Roth. This truly odd moment
Q a rock star performing a karaoke version of his own recording Q
was part of a reawakened interest among New York hipsters in the
sing-along pastime imported from Japan. (Miles Ladin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
