<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HOMERUNS-725(2TAK     07-05 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMERUNS-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MARIS CHASE TOPS AN EXCITING FIRST HALF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The highlight of the All-Star Game festivities could be
the home run contest at Coors Field on Monday night, but it will be
the home run contest that resumes after Tuesday night's All-Star
Game that will command the attention of fans and baseball people
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of Roger Maris' 37-year-old record of 61 home runs
in a single season clearly dominated the first half of the season
and will intensify as the games and weeks go by and the season
approaches September, the 15th round of this heavyweight
championship fight.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire. Ken Griffey Jr. Sammy Sosa. Take your pick, or sit
back and enjoy as these magical hitters chase Maris and each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing close,'' Tom Kelly, the Minnesota Twins'
manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrific for the game,'' said Andy MacPhail, the
president of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the election of Bud Selig as commissioner on Thursday
can overshadow the significance of the home run chase for this
season, a development that can forever eradicate the lingering ill
feeling over the 1994-95 labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the season, on the other hand, was not
consumed completely by McGwire and friends. The Yankees' start _
``It's more than a start,'' Kelly said _ has been a mind-boggling
development in itself. Not only are the Yankees threatening to
shatter the Chicago Cubs' 92-year-old record of 116 victories, but
they have also rendered their owner silent. Who can complain about
a 61-20 record?
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox have also had an impressive first half, but
it's their typical luck that they should have this kind of season
when the Yankees have given new meaning to the musical title ``Damn
Yankees.'' Boston's current winning percentage would compute to 99
victories over an entire season, but that total would get the Red
Sox a wild-card spot at best.
</P>
<P>
   The same division, on the other hand, has produced the most
stunning development on the loss side of the ledger. It would have
been thought impossible for a team with a $69 million payroll, the
highest in the sport's history, to be 26{ games out at the All-Star
Game break, but that is precisely where the Baltimore Orioles find
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As surprisingly bad as the Seattle Mariners have been and as
mysteriously as the Colorado Rockies have lost their lust for
offense, their failures pale in comparison with the collapse of the
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, no team has brewed an in-season transformation like
the Los Angeles Dodgers have.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doing a frighteningly good imitation of the Yankees of other
years, the Dodgers fired their general manager and manager,
jettisoned their best hitter and their best rookie and resurrected
as interim general manager the former manager who insists he bleeds
Dodger blue. They still don't look, smell or feel like a contender.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Marlins weren't a contender from Day 1 of the
season, but they nevertheless continued to decimate their team in
the first half, leaving themselves with not even a skeleton of the
team that won the World Series last year.
</P>
<P>
   The season has produced some scintillating individual
performances besides the Maris matter. David Wells pitched a
perfect game for the Yankees. Kerry Wood, an awe-inspiring rookie,
struck out 20 for the Chicago Cubs at the age of 20, breaking the
National League record and tying the major-league mark. Greg Maddux
of Atlanta leaped halfway to his fifth Cy Young award with a 12-2
record and a 1.54 earned run average. Juan Gonzalez of Texas
entered his final game before the break with 97 runs batted in,
making him a genuine threat to Hack Wilson's 68-year-old record of
190. Rickey Henderson, 39, leads the majors in stolen bases with
37.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was notable, too, for the emergence of two more
members of the Cuban contingent. Rolando Arrojo has a 10-5 record
for Tampa Bay as a rookie, and Orlando Hernandez, technically a
rookie but pitching like some of the best veterans, has a 3-1
record and 2.08 ERA in six starts for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers that were most captivating and compelling
entering Sunday night were 37, 35 and 33, the home run totals,
respectively, of McGwire, Griffey and Sosa. In a late development,
there is also 30, which Greg Vaughn reached with a pair of home
runs Sunday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Griffey led the chase approaching mid-May, having hit 15 home
runs to McGwire's 13. McGwire snatched the lead when he slugged his
16th on May 16 and then created some distance between him and
Griffey with a three-homer flurry at Philadelphia on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was not a part of the competition for the first eight weeks
of the season, but he leaped in conspicuously by hitting 21 home
runs in 22 games from May 25 through June 21. Griffey, who had
slipped back, produced his own hot streak, hitting seven in nine
recent games.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire has always been a threat if he can stay healthy,''
MacPhail said. ``He might have broken the record prior to this year
if he could have played with the frequency he's played with this
year. I think he has to be the favorite if he can stay healthy.
That's the primary question _ not will he hit enough of them, but
will he play enough?''
</P>
<P>
   The home run derby clearly has aroused fans. Batting practice
has become a required part of any fan's attendance at a Cardinals
game. In Cincinnati last Friday night, the Reds' game with St.
Louis drew a crowd of 41,302, including 9,338 who bought their
tickets that day.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, whose Twins recently entertained McGwire, said: ``I think
it's fun. When McGwire was here last week, there was a big crowd
for batting practice and a big crowd for the game, so obviously
people want to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Sosa has become a matinee _ and an evening _ idol.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable, the chanting that goes on,'' MacPhail said.
``The electricity when he comes to the plate has been remarkable.
When he hit the ball across the street onto a porch, there was a
sign the next day saying, `Sammy was here.''' And this weekend, in
a takeoff on July 4 and the patriotic symbol of Uncle Sam, some
Cubs fans proclaimed it ``Uncle Sammy weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   As the challengers reached the All-Star Game break, though,
there was one note of caution. McGwire, Griffey and Sosa hit no
home runs Friday or Saturday, marking the first time since April
18-19 that none of them had hit a home run in two successive games
when they all had played. McGwire furthermore didn't hit any home
runs in his last five games, and Sosa sat out Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a sign; maybe it's just a lull before the real home
run storm. Whatever it was, Kelly said he did not believe anything
had come close this season to competing with the Maris pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York you had the interleague play with the two teams,''
he said. ``That was good for the city, but it hasn't got rave
reviews anywhere else. I'm sure the Yankee record is some sort of
topic in New York, too, but they're not talking about it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans in many places, however, are finding baseball the thing to
do this summer. The Dodgers and the Giants drew 98,000 fans for
their first two games in San Francisco this weekend. In southern
California, the Oakland Athletics and the Angels played their first
two games before 83,000, while the Colorado Rockies and the Padres
attracted 102,000 for two games in San Diego, including the majors'
biggest crowd of the season on Saturday night, 61,148.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, Griffey and Sosa didn't play in any of those games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
