Setsuko Callahan combs the charred remains for signs of something
in particular. ``I lost my wedding ring,'' she says. In other parts
of Florida, people are hoping for rain, maybe even a tropical
storm, but any heavy rain - if it comes at all - is still days
away, forecasters say. (Terry Renna/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1998 -- BBA-YANKEES, 7-5 -- New York
Yankees manager Joe Torre, left, congratulates first baseman Tino
Martinez following a 1-0 shutout of the Baltimore Orioles on
Sunday. The win moves the Yankees record to 61-20 at the half-way
point in the season, which ties the Major League record for most
wins in the first 81 games with the 1902 Pittsburgh Pirates and the
1907 Chicago Cubs. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1998 -- NY-SAKS-RETAIL, 7-5 -- Philip
Miller, left, the chief executive officer of Saks, and Robert
Bradley Martin, the chief executive of Proffitt's, meet to discuss
Proffitt's $2.1 billion acquisition of Saks. The proposed deal
would represent the end of an era for Saks, whose founders Horace
Saks and Bernard Gimbel would likely never have imagined the store
as famous as the avenue on which it sits would one day be part of a
retail conglomerate based in Alcoa, Tenn. (Frances Roberts/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CARMEL, Calif. -- July 5, 1998 -- CALIF-HORSEMEAT-VOTE-2,
7-5 -- In an upcoming referendum, Californians will be asked to
decide whether to make it illegal to participate in the sale or
purchase of a horse pegged for human ingestion. Barbara Clarke,
director of Redwings Horse Sanctuary, a center that rescues horses
from slaughter, also has six resident donkeys in her care that she
says might have become ``donkey jerky'' if they had not ended up
with her. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CARMEL, Calif. -- July 5, 1998 -- CALIF-HORSEMEAT-VOTE-1,
7-5 -- Californians, who recently weighed in on the fates of
bilingual education and affirmative action, will be asked to decide
the destiny of horses: specifically, whether to make it illegal to
participate in the sale or purchase of a horse pegged for human
ingestion. These adult horses have been rescued from slaughter and
now run free to graze in a large pasture at the Redwings Horse
Sanctuary in Carmel. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 5, 1998 -- MEDIA-TALK, 7-5 -- To
challenge a cultural trade gap, the German government and a
division of the German Publishers and Booksellers Association have
established a German book office in New York to increase sales of
English-language rights for translated German books. Michael
Naumann, a former German publisher who now heads Henry Holt &AMP; Co.,
declined to join the group's board. ``I don't really see a profound
reason for their presence here,'' he says. (Don Hogan Charles/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DALY CITY, Calif. -- July 5, 1998 -- MOVIE-DISKS, 7-5 --
Carlos Montecino, left, shows DIVX, an upstart hybrid DVD format,
to a Circuit City customer in Daly City. By late June, a little
more than a year after the introduction of DVDs, manufacturers had
sold nearly 600,000 DVD players - that's faster than either compact
disk players or VCRs did at the corresponding points after they
were introduced. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- July 5, 1998 -- E-MAIL-IGNORE, 7-5 --
Paul Raskin, left, heads a unit that oversees the flow of customer
e-mail at Charles Schwab in San Francisco. The discount brokerage
is actively trying to increase the percentage of customer queries
handled by e-mail rather than by phone. E-mail now accounts for
one-third of customer inquiries to the electronic brokerage
services unit, receiving up to 15,000 electronic messages a week.
(Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
