<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKEES' TORRE TAKES NOTHING FOR GRANTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the 61st time this season, the Yankees did Sunday
what they have done with regularity since April: They won.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-0 victory over Baltimore boosted the Yankees' record to
61-20. Now at the major-league All-Star Game break, the Yankees are
being touted as the best team in the history of the game. At this
point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   That little proviso hangs like a banner inside a Yankee locker
room filled with lofty talk of destiny _ mostly from outsiders.
This team, whose whole is not obscured by its individual parts, has
crushed opponents in every conceivable manner: the long ball, the
short ball, a finesse team roaring in like an angry bull in a china
closet. Brawling, playing it straight.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Yankees are 61-20 at the midway point, but now the
challenges intensify. Can the team sustain this pace? Will it let
down? How can the team stay focused?
</P>
<P>
   ``The record means a lot to me,'' Joe Torre, the manager, said
Sunday. ``That means you've had a dominant first half. But you need
to play two halves. So you have to be very cautious and not get
yourself too overconfident and thinking that you don't have to work
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a veteran team, and there are enough terrifying frames
of reference to keep everyone on his toes. Some current team
members were on the roster in 1996 when the Yankees saw a
commanding lead shrink to nearly nothing. ``I'm here to remind
them,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said this team has been as disciplined as any team he
has been around in terms of focus and determination. ``Today is
another example of it,'' he said. ``On a day that the All-Star
break is coming, sometimes people tend to leave a day ahead of
time. But it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a deeper frame of reference for Torre on the folly of
arrogance before the deed is done. Torre was 14 when his beloved
New York Giants humbly crept into the 1954 World Series against the
murderous Cleveland Indians, who barreled into the Series with 111
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I remember vividly,'' Torre recalled, ``is
Cleveland going in to play the Giants thinking it was going to be
tough and then all of a sudden, boom boom boom. They beat them four
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi was not quite 5 in 1969, in Peoria, Ill., when his
Cubs, much like the Yankees though nothing nearly as dramatic,
bolted out of the blocks and led the National League by a
comfortable margin at the All-Star Game break. They leveled out in
August, then lost eight straight in September while the hot Mets
won 10 straight and wound up winning by eight games. ``That was a
killer,'' Girardi said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Orioles streamed out of the Stadium Sunday afternoon,
Elrod Hendricks, Baltimore's bullpen coach, stood next to the team
bus. Hendricks was in his second season with Baltimore in 1969 when
the Orioles were a slick-fielding, heavy-hitting team with the best
pitching staff in baseball: Jim Palmer, Mike Cuellar and Dave
McNally. The Mets beat them. In five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between us and the Yankees is that we already
had reached the World Series,'' said Hendricks, who acknowledged
that the Yankees enjoyed the best first half in the history of
baseball _ ``but it is just one half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are on a breathtaking pace toward posterity. The
players walk the line between living in the moment and looking
toward the next three months of the season. The Yankees are being
compared with the 1906 Chicago Cubs, who won 116 games but didn't
win the World Series. The Yankees' midpoint record is tied for the
best ever with the 1907 Cubs, who went on to sweep Detroit in the
World Series, and the 1902 Pittsburgh Pirates, who finished with a
record 27{-game lead before there was a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, is that the Yankees are only halfway
through. ``Anything can happen.'' Hendricks said.
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue, injuries, breaks starting to go the other way. This is
all part of the suspense to come: The challenge is not whether the
Yankees will reach the World Series, or even whether they will keep
winning. Will they, can they keep winning at this breakneck pace?
Girardi said the team didn't care about posterity. ``We just want
to reach the World Series,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Cleveland keeps finding its way into this pretty
Yankees picture. The other day, Dwight Gooden, the former Yankee
and Met, won his second game of the season. Some recalled his
no-hitter at Yankee Stadium in 1996 as the culmination of a steep
comeback. Who says he won't have a similar rebirth this fall? Just
in time for the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   Torre thinks about his Giants' great autumn of 1954 and how his
beloved team started winning at the right time. ``They got hot.
That's what scares you about postseason,'' he said. ``In spite of
what you're supposed to do, you still have to go out there and play
the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
