A1234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MALNOURISHED-CHILD     07-05 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MALNOURISHED-CHILD-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSTER MOTHER ARRESTED DAY AFTER MALNOURISHED CHILD IS FOUND
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN with ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after a severely malnourished 2-year-old boy
was discovered in an apartment on Staten Island, the child's foster
mother was arrested Sunday as she returned home from a long holiday
weekend, and a horrendous picture began to emerge of the life of a
child who had apparently been isolated, neglected and starved.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Dennis Davis, who will be 3 on Sept. 15 but weighs only
18 pounds (less than half the normal weight of a child his age),
was in stable condition at the Sisters of Charity Medical Center.
He was being fed intravenously and was expected to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The foster mother, Deanna Allston, 31, was charged with reckless
endangerment and endangering the welfare of a child. Police said
she had left Dennis, hidden in a back room, and four other foster
children with her 19-year-old brother on Thursday for what she said
was an overnight trip.
</P>
<P>
   As police and child welfare authorities began investigations,
officials had only sketchy information about the case, leaving
unanswered questions about Ms. Allston, the conditions under which
five children in her care were kept, and why caseworkers had not
detected the obvious problems of an emaciated boy.
</P>
<P>
   The caseworker for the Catholic Home Bureau, which placed Dennis
with Ms. Allston in his infancy under a contract with the city's
Administration for Children's Services, could not be reached
Sunday, and officials said records showed only that a caseworker
who was not the boy's regular monitor had seen him on June 15 and
had said he seemed thin. His last recorded weight _ the date was
unclear _ was 23 pounds, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and a sister described Ms. Allston as a secretive
woman who worked for the foster agency that had placed children in
her care, who took good care of four of the children, but
apparently turned Dennis into a kind of infant nonperson who was
hidden away most of the time in a dark, stifling room on a stained
mattress, fed just enough to survive and often left alone on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to keep him in a carriage with the door closed,''
Chaniqua Allston, 23, said of her sister, recalling a visit. ``All
the other kids were around the house. I said, `Why is he in that
room?' She was like, `Don't go in there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Chaniqua Allston, whose 4-year-old daughter, Nataysia, was one
of the five children in Deanna Allston's custody, said she had not
seen Dennis for more than a year and had asked her sister last
December what had happened to the boy. ``She said, `Oh, I don't
have him no more.'''
</P>
<P>
   When her sister went out on weekends, Chaniqua Allston said, she
took four of the children, including Nataysia, to the home of a
baby sitter approved by the Catholic Home Bureau. But she never had
the baby sitter in her apartment, and she apparently left Dennis
home alone when she went out, Chaniqua said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no signs that the other children in her care were
mistreated, one official familiar with the case said. The natural
mother of three of them _ Michael Hayton, 5, and his brothers,
Sheron, 6, and Bruce, 1 _ saw them last Wednesday or Thursday, and
found nothing evidently wrong, the official said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The plight of the dehydrated, malnourished boy apparently came
to light only because Deanna Allston did not follow her usual
routine, her sister and welfare officials said. On Thursday, Deanna
Allston told the agency she was going away and that her usual
approved baby sitter would be in charge of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for reasons that were unexplained Sunday, she enlisted
her brother, Aaron, of Staten Island, as a baby sitter and left him
in charge of the children at her flat on the second floor of a
two-family house in a middle-class neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   According to Chaniqua Allston, Aaron was unaware that Dennis was
still in his sister's custody, and had no idea the child was in a
back room. She said Deanna had told Aaron she would visit an
amusement park in Pennsylvania with a friend, and would be back on
Friday. But Friday passed and she did not return. She had still not
returned by Saturday afternoon, Chaniqua said, when Dennis _ to
Aaron's amazement _ crawled out of the back room.
</P>
<P>
   The child was skeletal.
</P>
<P>
   Chaniqua Allston said her brother called her and said: ``I don't
want to stay here. I'm scared. It feels like somebody died in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaniqua Allston, who also lives on Staten Island, went
immediately to her sister's apartment. She was stunned at Dennis'
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``His legs were like sticks,'' she said. ``His skin color had
changed. The blood, like the dark blood color, was showing through
his skin. He looked like he was about to die. I was scared.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been kept in a dark, airless back room with plastic over
the windows, she said. A mattress stained with urine and vomit was
on the floor. She tried to talk to the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Dennis. Dennis.' He was not responding to me, and he
couldn't walk. He couldn't cry. He didn't make a sound. He was
awake, but he was just sitting there. He was just looking around,
rocking his head back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   She called 911. The police arrived shortly afterward and took
the five children to the hospital. Dennis and Michael Hayton were
admitted and the others were treated and released to child welfare
authorities, who said they would be placed in new foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael was suffering from sickle cell anemia and appeared to be
slightly undernourished, but he was in stable condition and was
even ``up and around,'' talking to hospital workers, officials
said. But Dennis was severely dehydrated and malnourished. He
immediately consumed seven bottles of formula, they said, and was
being given nutritional supplements intravenously.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been to hell and back, that's for sure,'' said
hospital spokesman William McCann.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
