<SLUG> BC-DWARF-CONVENTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE PEOPLE KICK OFF CONVENTION WITH CALIFORNIA BEACH PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE CONDON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Southern California plays host to so many kinds
of beach parties _ volleyball beach parties, sand castle-building
beach parties, barbecue beach parties _ that they usually don't
draw much attention.
</P>
<P>
   But the bash held Sunday on Topanga State Beach was just a bit
different.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dwarf beach party. More than 100 self-described
``little people'' took over the beach from the surfer dudes for a
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a family reunion,'' Donna Ryan, a Columbus,
Ohio, resident attending the party, said while other partygoers
threw Frisbees and played in the sand nearby. ``Around here you are
not different.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration was one of many events being held this week as
part of the Little People of America's 1998 National Conference.
About 1,500 people from around the world at or under 4 feet, 10
inches in height, and their families, descended on the Warner
Center Marriott hotel in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The conference features a variety of sports events, held at
California State University, Northridge, as well as more than 40
discussion groups and workshops on topics of concern to
participants. The subjects include developmental milestones,
managed care and disabilities in the '90s, parenting, driving
issues, adoption, orthopedic concerns, neurological problems, and
women's sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   There are also seminars about mixed couples, where one person is
short-statured and a spouse is average height. The conference also
includes a dating game event and a fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just about letting little people know there are other
little people out there,'' said Roy Rudd, a 46-year-old Wal-Mart
management executive in from Bentonville, Ark., to attend the
conference. ``We're just a little bit shorter than everybody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Little People of America was founded in 1957 by 3-foot-9-inch
actor Billy Barty as a way for short-statured people to get
together. Today, the organization hosts the annual conference and
provides information on medical, social and discrimination issues
for little people, including youths.
</P>
<P>
   Conference participant Jeff Patterson, a 29-year-old resident of
Tuscon, Ariz., spent Sunday afternoon at the beach bodysurfing with
two friends. He's spending most of his time participating in the
sports events, such as volleyball, power lifting, softball,
basketball, and track and field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps a lot athletically to be able to compete with people
my own size,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   A business account executive with AirTouch Cellular, Patterson
said he was ``flabbergasted'' when he attended his first Little
People of America Conference nine years ago _ the first time he was
ever around so many people like himself. His only regret is that he
didn't start going to the conferences when he was younger.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd said that growing up in rural Arkansas, he didn't meet
another little person until he was in high school. He joined Little
People of America eight years ago when his son, Daniel, was born.
Rudd said it's important to him that Daniel and his 6-year-old
daughter, both of whom are also dwarfs, grow up knowing other
children who are shorter than everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said her most difficult struggle has been against job
discrimination. She's a special education teacher, but she had
trouble getting a job because, at 4-foot-5, no one thought she
could keep order in the classroom. But once she was hired, she
proved them wrong, using a big voice to make up for her small
stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very mouthy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the conference, Rudd said, is that once a year
he gets to talk to everyone ``eye-to-eye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Average people see each other eye-to-eye every day. We're more
at eye-to-butt level,'' he joked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
