u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-FARMERS-COX     07-05 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-FARMERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP aids black farmers
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The plight of the nation's black farmers and black
land loss will be featured at the national convention of the NAACP
meeting in Atlanta this week.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of the nation's estimated 18,000 black farmers are
expected for the NAACP convention that begins Saturday, which will
include a ``walk for support'' demonstration in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the verge of extinction and if we lose all of our
land we have lost our heritage,'' said John Boyd, president of the
National Black Farmers Association, founded in 1995. He said he and
other farmers will be seeking the support of the NAACP and other
national civil rights groups in their fight to stem the tide of
loan denials and foreclosures among black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd will be one of the participants in a panel discussion, ``A
Journey, a Challenge, a Commitment in Support of America's Black
Farmers,'' scheduled for 9 a.m. July 15 at the Georgia World
Congress Center. Other scheduled panelists are Gary Grant,
president of the Black Farmers and Agriculturists Association,
founded in 1997; Ralph Paige of the Federation of Southern
Cooperatives; and a representative of Secretary of Agriculture Dan
Glickman's office.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman acknowledges that current and past administrations have
discriminated against black farmers by denying them loans based on
the color of their skin. About 600 black farmers in Georgia and 14
other states believe the secretary's forthright statements will
help them prevail in the $2.5 billion discrimination suit they have
pending in the U.S. District Court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the U.S. House of Representatives passed an
agricultural appropriations bill, backed by House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, which was amended to waive the two-year statute of
limitations barring the filing of discrimination complaints.
Attorneys for the Justice Department said the number of black
farmers complaining about discrimination had to be limited based on
the two-year requirement in the Equal Credit Opportunity Act. The
waiver opens the door for any black farmers to lodge complaints
with the federal courts including the U.S. Federal Court of Claims,
and the secretary of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the public to know that we are talking about the
demise of a large segment of our society,'' Grant said. ``Most of
the black farmers who are part of the pending lawsuit are either on
the verge of being put out of farming or they have been put out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
