<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY HENRY SCHULMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
Giants' 1st Half 
Ends With Flourish  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO After the Giants lost the last two games of their
interleague series against the A's, manager Dusty Baker gave his
team a manDate.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We asked to win the last three series before the All-Star
break against Texas, Anaheim and the Dodgers,'' Baker said. ``Two
out of three, two out of three and two out of three.''
</P>
<P>
   Done, done and done.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point we had 46 victories. We wanted to go into the
break with 52. We did, and that's a good first half,'' Baker said.
``Hopefully we'll be in a position to have a good second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker had plenty of reason for optimism as he left for a fishing
trip to Montana. The Giants finalized his mandate Sunday by beating
the Dodgers 3-0 in front of 40,111 at 3Com Park, with Shawn Estes
evening his record to 7-7 on the strength of 62/3 shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Giants finished the first half 51-36 and led the
National League West by six games. This year they went 52-37 but
trail the first-place San Diego Padres by 5 1/2. When asked which
of his two teams was better, Baker said this year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give us Jeff Kent the last three weeks, are you going
to tell me we wouldn't have been markedly better?'' Baker said.
``Jeff was hot when he got hurt. If the Chicago Bulls lose Scottie
Pippen, you can't tell me the Bulls aren't going to be a worse
team. They would be a worse team with Michael (Jordan) and without
Scottie. It's the same on this team with Jeff and Barry (Bonds).''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Giants have been worse without Kent. They were 41-24
when he sprained his right knee against Seattle on June 9 and 11-13
since. But in taking six of their last eight games the Giants
proved to themselves that they could win without him, even against
good teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last week, week and a half we accepted the fact that he's
not around,'' said catcher Brent Mayne, who went 3-for-3 with an
RBI Sunday. ``We had that big winning streak, and then we lost
Jeff, and then we lost all those games to San Diego. That was a big
downer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us a long time to realize we're not going to have Jeff
in the four hole, and the last week, week and a half we came
together,'' Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's win was important for the team, but even more so for
Estes. Improving to .500 was an important psychological barrier for
the left-hander after a disappointing first half. Had he lost, he
would have been the only Giants starter to end it with a losing
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can pretty much go into the second half like it's a new
season and put the first half behind me,'' Estes said. ``My goal in
the second half is to finish strong. Who's to say I can't have a
second half this year like the first half I had last year?''
</P>
<P>
   Estes will get a quick chance to start on that 12-2 run he's
looking for when he starts the Giants' next game Friday night in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Estes scattered eight hits in his 6 2/3 innings, getting into
trouble as he often has this year but making great pitches to
escape. Those pitches eluded him when he was torched for four-run
innings in each of his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   His best Houdini job came in the sixth inning, with the Giants
leading 2-0. Raul Mondesi hit a leadoff single, and with one out
Estes walked Eric Karros and Bobby Bonilla to load the bases. He
had Bonilla 0-2. But Estes settled down and got Charles Johnson to
ground his first pitch to third. Charlie Hayes stepped on the bag
and threw to first for the inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds rewarded Estes by leading off the bottom of the
sixth with a triple and scoring the Giants' third run on J.T.
Snow's sacrifice fly. Baker said Bonds played an ``exhilarating
game'' after managing two hits in his previous 28 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants scored their first two runs off Dodgers starter
Darren Dreifort in the fifth inning on a walk to Snow, a Hayes
single through the left side of the infield, Mayne's RBI hit under
Karros' glove at first and a Rey Sanchez double-play ball that
brought Hayes home.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Reed relieved Estes in the seventh and quieted another
Dodger outburst by getting Mondesi to ground out. He also pitched a
strong eighth, and Robb Nen struck out two of four batters in the
ninth to earn his 25th save, tying him for the major-league lead
with Anaheim's Troy Percival and San Diego's Trevor Hoffman. &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
