<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ARMAGEDDON' HOLIDAY WEEKEND EARNIGNS LESS THAN EARTH-SHATTERING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The monster asteroid failed to deliver
mega-grosses as ``Armageddon'' fell short of expectations with an
estimated $34 million at 3,127 theaters nationwide during the
Friday-Sunday period and $52.5 million in its first five days,
studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The initial numbers for the $140 million Disney project came in
well under the past two major Fourth of July holiday openings _
$84.1 million for the first five days of ``Men In Black'' last year
and $85 million for ``Independence Day'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a disaster for Disney, but it's certainly a
disappointment,'' said analyst Arthur Rockwell of Drake Capital
Securities. ``It's not an auspicious beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon,'' starring Bruce Willis as the leader of a band of
oil drillers trying to nuke an asteroid headed for Earth, had been
so heavily hyped that no other films opened against it. But
Paramount's move to roll out a similar movie, ``Deep Impact,''
eight weeks ago clearly cut into ``Armageddon's'' audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Impact,'' with a comet menacing the planet, opened with
$41.1 million and has grossed $137 million domestically. ``It's
tough having two meteor movies playing at almost the same time,''
Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon,'' launched with a $60 million marketing push, also
suffered from an inability to draw significant numbers of families
and children, according to Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel
Source tracking service. ``It's only attracting young males and a
little bit of the date crowd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' opened with $9.7 million Wednesday, followed by
$8.8 million Thursday, $13.6 million Friday, $11.1 million Saturday
and an estimated $9.3 million Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Several other factors hampered ``Armageddon,'' including mostly
negative reviews; its 2-hour, 20-minute length, viewed as excessive
for an action movie; the fact that the Fourth of July fell on a
Saturday, usually the heaviest day for moviegoing; and audiences
losing the appetite for films focused on the possible end of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has seen everything blown up in these big
special-effects films,'' Bucksbaum said. ``You can't top it
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``Armageddon'' will be lucky to wind up grossing
$140 million domestically, although the film should perform well
overseas due to Willis' strong appeal in foreign territories.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said the key for ``Armageddon'' will be how well it
performs during the coming weekend, when it faces openings from
Warner Bros.' ``Lethal Weapon 4'' and DreamWorks' ``Small
Soldiers.'' He also said the less-than-stellar numbers for
``Armageddon'' doesn't mean studios will stop funding big-budget
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studios still have to go for home runs, especially during
these key periods, but the picture has to deliver,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second weekend of 20th Century Fox's ``Dr. Dolittle''
finished a respectable second, with $17.6 million at 2,869 theaters
from Friday to Sunday, giving the Eddie Murphy comedy $62.7 million
after 10 days and a decent shot at the $100 million mark by the end
of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's third weekend of ``Mulan,'' with Murphy as the voice of
a wisecracking dragon, came in third with $10.7 million at 2,953
theaters to push its 17-day take past $76 million. The studio's
36th animated movie should finish above the $100 million grossed by
its ``Hercules'' last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's second weekend of ``Out of Sight'' followed with
$6.3 million at 2,110 sites as the George Clooney comedy-romance
dropped 47 percent from its opening despite strong critical
support. Fox's third weekend of ``The X-Files'' suffered an even
sharper falloff in fifth with $6 million at 2,605 theaters, losing
55 percent of its audience from the previous weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's fifth weekend of ``The Truman Show'' came in sixth
with $5.7 million at 2,756 locations, giving the comedy-fantasy
$109.5 million in 31 days. The Jim Carrey project is now the 122nd
highest domestic grosser in Hollywood history, trailing ``Star Trek
IV's'' $109.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's fourth weekend of ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' finished
seventh with $4.9 million at 2,479 theaters to go past $55 million
in 17 days, topping Warner's fifth weekend of ``A Perfect Murder,''
with $3.3 million at 2,070 locations for $61 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Fox's sixth weekend of ``Hope
Floats,'' with $1.5 million at 1,264 sites, and Disney's eighth
weekend of ``The Horse Whisperer,'' with $1.2 million at 1,048
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   New Line's second weekend of its revamped ``Gone With the Wind''
continued to perform respectably with $820,000 at 214 theaters. The
cinema classic now has $194.7 million overall and is at 25th place
on the all-time domestic list. ``Deep Impact'' took in $745,000 at
1,116 screens to give it 71st place on the list after ``Platoon''
at $138 million.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's 29th weekend of ``Titanic'' grossed $575,000 at 618
sites and has now taken in $588.2 million after 192 days.
``Titanic'' leads ``Star Wars'' as best domestic grosser by $127
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
