<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1332 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-KEOWN-SFCHRON &LR;      07-05 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEOWN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By TIM KEOWN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So now baseball's OK again. Cool, even. It's not too
old-fashioned or too slow or too boring. The people who play it
aren't the horrible ingrates they used to be, and now everyone is
rushing to christen baseball's renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that baseball matters again started with Mark McGwire
and took off from there. It went through Kerry Wood and the New
York Yankees, picked up with Sammy Sosa and grabbed ahold of Juan
Gonzalez. It figures to stay alive with Greg Maddux and Ivan
Rodriguez, and with any luck a decent pennant race will break out
in your neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is on such a high that it's hard to conceive that the
people running the game could manage to bring it down.
</P>
<P>
   And this isn't mere conjecture. There's proof that baseball is
in a hermetically sealed dreamworld, and it comes in the human form
of Albert Belle. He's the worst guy ever, right? The symbol of
everything that made baseball a bloated, self-important relic. He's
one of the reasons people who never paid much attention to baseball
swore it off anyway, just because it sounded good.
</P>
<P>
   But the other day Belle was asked if he wanted to be traded away
from the Chicago White Sox. The amazing thing isn't that Belle
answered the question _ although that ranks high _ but what he
said: ``I told Jerry Manuel I'm going down with the ship, that I
made a choice to play with the White Sox when I signed a contract
and I'm going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the wonderful events of the first half of the season _
McGwire's homers, Wood's 20 strikeouts, Sosa's Byzantine post-homer
celebration _ those few words prove more than anything.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Belle, saying something the fans would want to hear.
Albert Belle, espousing loyalty and persistence. Albert Belle,
ambassador to the game.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange way, maybe baseball's resurgence is best measured
by calculating the bad things that haven't happened instead of the
good things that have.
</P>
<P>
   While basketball players fight over the right to smoke dope,
baseball has been showcasing great players who seem to be decent
people. It's hard to find fault with the public personas of Tony
Gwynn or Maddux, Ivan or Alex Rodriguez, Andres Galarraga or Curt
Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   The good deeds performed by Pedro and Ramon Martinez in their
Dominican hometown are more impressive than a thousand United Way
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably just a stroke of blind luck for baseball, but a
deep and solid group of individual players seems to have arrived on
the scene just as people began looking for dynamic individuals to
carry the sport.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't done through marketing or slogan-writers, that's for
sure. Nike hasn't had anything to do with it. It's as close to a
grassroots movement that is possible in a day of electronic
immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   (There's even something charming, in a strictly negative
postmodern sense, about watching big-salaried teams such as the
Orioles and Dodgers dive-bombing their way through the standings.
Just an added bonus to boost the enjoyment of the game.)
</P>
<P>
   Here's a bold statement that can be neither proved nor refuted:
If you created one lineup from Tuesday's All-Star Game, it would be
able to stand up against an All-Star lineup from any other decade.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, let's go another step: The only decade that could
legitimately compete with the players of the '90s would be the
'60s. Everyone else would have to sit in the back seat _ if they
were allowed in the car at all.
</P>
<P>
   Could you imagine thinking along those lines as recently as two
years ago? For the most part, the same players were doing many of
the same things, but the game was mired in the scorched earth of
post-strike. Baseball was an anachronism, too slow and too boring.
Baseball was typified by the grumbling visage of Bobby Cox,
scratching his head and complaining about another strike call.
Baseball was your father and grandfather sitting on the back porch
with a crackly old radio and a bottle of Homemade Hell, telling a
hundred stories about the 1960 Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the pertinent question is this: Are these truly the
glory days, or is everyone just now willing to acknowledge it?
</P>
<P>
   Not that long ago, you'd tell someone you were interested in a
baseball game and they'd look at you as if you were going to sit
outside a grammar school with a bag of candy. Now you're considered
hopelessly inept if the Cardinals are in the bottom of the fifth
and you don't know whether McGwire has homered yet.
</P>
<P>
   Someday we'll be talking about Pedro Martinez, McGwire and Sosa,
Gwynn and Maddux. And the sad truth is, we'll have a hundred boring
stories about the '95 Braves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
