<SLUG> BC-FLA-ANIMALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fires wreaking havoc with Florida animal population
 &HT;    By John Holland
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ A mother turkey leads her three chicks
through a scorched forrest so hot the birds can barely hobble
forward, Baby deer roam busy streets, apparently lost or orphaned
by the 10-week old blaze. Diamonback rattlesnakes pop up in
nieghborhoods and parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   The raging fires that forced more than 50,000 Central Florida
residents from their homes have left thousands of wild animals dead
or homeless, wildlife experts said.
</P>
<P>
   During the next few days, many more injured birds, racoons,
snakes and skunks are expected to hobble out of the woods in need
of help. ``They are like people who are discombulated by a
traumatic event,'' said Sabrina Keen, a wildlife biologist from
Oregon working for the Bureau of Land Management. ``They are very
stressed and very scared, just like we'd be, so you have to take
that into account and be careful and compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Local animal shelters are already picking up injured racoons,
birds and baby deer wandering into yards, and expect many more
phone calls soon. In general, they are telling people to take care
of the animals until the shelter employees arrive.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions, however.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, a firefighter was bitten badly by a river otter who
got trapped in the blaze. When the firefighter tried to pick the
small animal up and take it to water, the scared otter lashed out,
biting through a leather glove and drawing blood.
</P>
<P>
   Snakes, many of them poisonous, are also creating problems.
Firefighters and National Guardsman battling the fire and digging
ditches have been slowed by rattlesnakes and other varieties.
Saturday, a firefighter killed a 4-foot rattlesnake, then bit it
before a live television audience.
</P>
<P>
   Rattlesnakes, dead and alive, are turning up in most
neighborhoods, and one was killed at the main emergency command
post in Ormond Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no reported bites, officials are very
worried. They also strongly warn residents returning home not to
explore their burned-out backyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those animals are very confused and they aren't happy campers
right now,'' said Ormond Beach Fire Chief Barry Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Several veterans and licensed wildlife handlers are helping out.
Workers at the Wildlife Refuge near Orlando are caring for a fawn
whose four paws were burned, and will take the animal to their vet
this morning.
</P>
<P>
   In Volusia County, Mary Keller has been doctoring wild birds for
30 years. She's already picked up a wild eagle and received several
calls Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very upsetting because these birds are very frightened
and hurt,'' Keller said. ``In all of these things, everyone forgets
about the little creatures.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some benefits to the fire. Deer and birds are
ingesting ashes, a great source of pottassium, while the brush
needed for ground nests should grow back quickly. Keen, the
wildlife biologist, said four-legged animals like deer and racoons
probably escaped the flames, while slow-moving tortoises ground
dwelling animals faced longer odds.
</P>
<P>
   A local man with a videocamera filmed a mother turkey and three
younger ones desparately trying to escape the flames in Volusia
County on Thursday, and turkey and tortoise sightings have become
common in the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very sad situation, but the reality is that a lot of
animals are going to die because of this fire,'' Keen said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
