<SLUG> BC-ZAPATA-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAPATA IN DEALS TO BUY 21 INTERNET PROPERTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been two months since Avram Glazer announced in
advertisements in national newspapers that he wanted to buy World
Wide Web sites. On Monday, Glazer and his Zapata Corp. will
disclose the results of his search: letters of intent to buy 21
properties and aggregate them under one site, www.Zap.com.
</P>
<P>
   The sites range from the search engine, Starting Point, to a
chat network, Chat Planet, to a variety of electronic commerce
offerings, including Bibliofind, Mass Music and Virtual Technology,
which sells computer equipment. Terms are not being disclosed, but
Glazer described them as ``substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second step of Glazer's plan to make Zapata ``No. 1
or No. 2 on the Internet.'' The first step, taken in April, was
acquiring the online magazines Word and Charged.
</P>
<P>
   Those acquisitions were part of an announced new strategy for
the company, which was founded as an oil business in 1953 by a
young George Bush and more recently had concentrated on processing
protein extracted from fish and other sea life.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Glazer also made a play to purchase the Web search
service Excite, but was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Glazer contends that the user traffic generated by the combined
sites he is acquiring would make Zap, ``among the top 10 largest
Internet sites in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Media Metrix, a Web measurement company, said Glazer's
numbers were not realistic. An analysis of the traffic of 15 of the
sites found that of all Web users, 2.1 percent, or just over
900,000 people, visited the sites in May.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Glazer said that once he grouped all the sites
together under the Zap.com domain, the audience for each site would
grow ``exponentially.''
</P>
<P>
   He compared his strategy to the so-called portals that companies
like Excite, Yahoo and Infoseek operate _ doorway services through
which users pass on their way to other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of a portal plus, though we're different than the
other portal sites,'' he said. ``We plan a network of sites, which
the other portals don't have. It's a cross between a portal and
America Online.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-05-98 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980705.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1340 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-SFCHRON     07-05 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STEVE KETTMANN 
</HEADLINE>
  
Mitchell Ends A's Half With a Bang  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ This Kevin Mitchell comeback and this scrappy 1998
Oakland A's team are showing themselves to be a lot more than the
lovable jokes they've seemed to some people.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell finally homered for the A's, sending a ball just over
the right-center field fence at Edison Field Sunday to tie the game
4-4 in the eighth. Then Mitchell came up in the ninth with the
bases loaded and fought off several 95-mph pitches from Angels
closer Troy Percival before drawing a walk to force home the
game-winning run in the A's 5-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just realized the bases were loaded,'' Mitchell said. ``All
I could do was sit there and look for heaters. The first ball he
threw, I didn't even see it. It was like he humped up a little and
threw even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the home run, which ended a career-high homerless streak
of 122 at-bats, Mitchell said: ``I'm getting old, man. I'm no young
stud anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's (41-45) swept the first-place Angels in three games to
pull within four games of .500 at the All-Star break, and they
pulled off the sweep even after Anaheim manager Terry Collins gave
his team a kick in the pants by saying they did not show enough
energy the first two games of this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great way to finish the half,'' manager Art Howe said
after calling a quick postgame meeting to congratulate the team on
its better-than-expected first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us, `Good job, good first half,''' Mitchell said. ``He
said, `It puts us into the thick of things. Let's keep playing.'''
</P>
<P>
   The A's won five of six to wrap up the first half. That means
that as much as that other team in the Bay Area gobbles up the
lion's share of attention, the A's are only 21/2 games farther
behind the Angels in the American League West than the Giants are
behind the first-place Padres in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   That does not make the low-payroll A's anyone's pick to win
anything this year, except maybe a prize for Best Showing by a Team
the Year After Losing a Ruthian Slugger, but they are lucky enough
to be in a division without a dominating team. The Angels are a
good team, but they have looked wobbly lately; it's not just that
they have lost five straight, it's  &LR; how  &LR; they have lost five
straight.
</P>
<P>
   People in baseball watch ``SportsCenter'' as compulsively as
White House staffers read the New York Times. So just last Tuesday,
the Angels saw Mike Fetters use the old
fake-to-third-throw-to-first move to pick off hapless Padres
pinch-runner Ruben Rivera to end that day's game. Even so, Fetters
got out of a first-and-third, one-out jam in the seventh Sunday by
picking off pinch-runner Damon Mashore using the very same move.
Some in the Angels dugout felt Fetters balked, but that wasn't the
way the umpires saw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told (Mashore) about Fetters' third-and-first move,''
Collins said. ``(But) that was not the ballgame, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but once Fetters struck out Cecil Fielder to end the
seventh with the Angels failing to pad their 4-3 lead, the A's had
a little extra hop in their steps. Mitchell was the next man to
bat, and he reached out to crank an outside breaking ball from
starter Chuck Finley. Once his homer tied it, the A's were free and
easy, and the Angels were bogged down by thoughts of oh-not-again.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Mike Blowers bobbled Darin Erstad's grounder in the
ninth to give the Angels a leadoff baserunner, Billy Taylor took
care of business for his 18th save. Just the day earlier, Blowers
had helped Taylor with his defense, and the A's veteran closer made
sure to return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I'll pick you up right here,''' Taylor said.
``This sweep is very big for us. I think that gives us a lot of
momentum going into the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
