<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SUBWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SAMPLING THE KINDNESS OF STRANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rush hour is not a great time to be trying to get
from Times Square to Columbus Circle on the Nos. 1 or 9 trains. Not
in July. Not if you're pregnant. And certainly not if you are
expecting twins.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the point. Would the spectacle of what looks like _
and indeed is _ considerable discomfort in a fellow traveler
provoke from subway riders a show of sympathy? How long would it
take for pity to kick in and a seat to be offered up?
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of science, this columnist set out to
investigate in a more or less systematic fashion. Over a two-day
period, she and her beach ball-shaped belly made 20 rush-hour trips
on some of the busiest lines in the city, the Lexington Avenue and
the Broadway IRT. She picked out only the most crowded subway cars
and discounted any trips where even a single open seat was
available.
</P>
<P>
   What she discovered through her discomfort was oddly comforting.
</P>
<P>
   The farthest she had to travel before being offered a seat was
two stops on a local train. On 55 percent of her trips, she
received an offer almost immediately. For 25 percent of the time,
it took only one stop.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, empathy, or at least courtesy, appeared to be
universal, cutting across racial, sexual, ethnic and, to the extent
that it is possible to determine such things on the subway, class
distinctions. Seats were readily offered by white, black and
Hispanic riders, by teen-agers in outrageously baggy shorts and by
middle-aged women in business suits.
</P>
<P>
   By rumor, by reputation and even by scientific study, New
Yorkers are widely held to be a tough crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Robert Levine, chairman of the psychology
department at California State University at Fresno, performed an
elaborate study measuring helpfulness in 36 American cities. The
transplanted Brooklynite surprised no one by discovering that New
Yorkers were the least willing to assist a stranger with a small
act of kindness, like mailing a lost letter or giving change for a
quarter. And when they did help, they were demonstrably the
surliest.
</P>
<P>
   What did Levine think of this columnist's rather more sunny
findings?
</P>
<P>
   He claimed not to be shocked at all. ``It doesn't surprise me
that you are getting treated pretty nicely,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The subway seat experiment, he pointed out, was framed in such a
way that made it easy for New Yorkers to show their best side.
Giving up a seat is an act of generosity that by its very nature
limits contact: you stay, I leave.
</P>
<P>
   In his study, Levine said, New Yorkers had also been willing to
practice this kind of help-and-run philanthropy. What they had
balked at was entering more open-ended relationships with
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   In other cities, people encountering a researcher posing as a
blind pedestrian on a street corner would often come up alongside
and offer to guide him across. In New York, they were more likely
to start across the street themselves and then call back, ``The
light's green!''
</P>
<P>
   ``When people did help,'' he explained, ``it was always where
there was no commitment for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on Levine's grim interpretation of the data, this
columnist had to agree that he had a point. In all her trips, no
one stopped to chat with her after giving up a seat. In several
cases, even the offer itself was made wordlessly through a kind of
urban pantomime.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, the generous rider accompanied the offer with an
apology. ``I'm sorry, I just noticed,'' one woman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't looking,'' said another, who had been deeply immersed
in her copy of The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting to be noticed on a subway, one is forced to notice just
how actively people are trying not to notice one another,
retreating behind newspapers, books, catalogs, makeup mirrors or
plain fatigue. At one point, on the uptown No. 1, this columnist
found herself standing in front of three riders, all of whom were
either genuinely asleep or feigning it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she would like to draw if not exactly a happy conclusion
about the state of civility in the city, then at least not an
ungrateful one. Even if the pregnant-woman-needing-a-subway-seat
experiment didn't test the trickier question of trust and
commitment, it did test for simple fellow-feeling. And it was a
relief, quite literally, to be offered all those seats by so many
well-meaning strangers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
