<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES POLITICIANS LOOKING AHEAD TO 21ST CENTURY CONTESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles -- In the political arena of Los Angeles -- heated
up by charter reform, secession and term limits -- it's already
2001 and the race for mayor is on.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is in some governmental meeting, a cable talk show or
a news conference, the 2001 campaign has politicians beginning to
position and posture for the right to succeed Mayor Richard
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   --Los Angeles County Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky announces plans
for an initiative to block all future rail construction, after a
line is built to North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   --Councilwoman Laura Chick announces she will hold hearings into
whether police let a terrorist bank robber bleed to death in last
year's North Hollywood shootout.
</P>
<P>
   --City Attorney James Hahn has a series of news conferences
announcing legal action against the proposed Ward Valley nuclear
dump, against the Census Bureau for a potential undercount of
ethnic minorities and against California Insurance Commissioner
Chuck Quackenbush over auto insurance rates.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't even include folks like Assembly Speaker Antonio
Villaraigosa, county Supervisor Gloria Molina, City Councilman Nate
Holden and Parks Commission President Steve Soboroff, among others,
all of whom have become increasingly active in recent months,
seizing every opportunity to make headlines.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, public interest appears to be peaking in a
city that has become notorious for its voter apathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some pretty interesting debate going on in this city
about the nature of government and politics that I haven't seen
since Tom Bradley was elected mayor in 1973,'' political analyst
Sherry Bebitch Jeffe said. ``This is something a political
scientist lives for.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the reason for the heightened debate is due to Riordan.
He was the force behind term limits that will take him out of
office in 2001 and create the open field. Many of the council
members who would run for mayor or other citywide office also are
termed out of their council seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this era of term limits, none of them are secure in their
jobs,'' Democratic political consultant Joe Cerrell. ``Once they
get elected the first time, they begin looking for what their next
job will be.''
</P>
<P>
   With his election as a citizen-politician and vow to turn L.A.
around in 1993, Riordan also has been the catalyst for many of the
heightened expectations that have heated up the debate.
</P>
<P>
   To head off San Fernando Valley efforts to secede from the city,
Riordan became the driving force behind an elected panel to reform
Los Angeles' Byzantine City Charter, prompting the City Council to
respond by creating its own commission.
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer, the City Council has left the comfort of its
chambers at least once a month and routinely drawn hundreds of
people to its meetings, compared to the two dozen or three dozen
who venture downtown. But several meetings have added fuel to the
political fires because their start was delayed for an hour or so
by the lack of a 10-member quorum.
</P>
<P>
   In the current climate, issues that might have created small
ripples have gotten far more attention from the media and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels very volatile. ... There is a strong feeling of
frustration and anger,'' Chick said. ``Conflict is usually not
easy, and it means you have to work it out. But at least people are
active, interested and involved. Out of that can come good
things.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the case with the federal civil rights lawsuit filed
against the city by the West Valley Girls Softball League &UR;  &LR; -- a
question of equal access to the city parks' playing fields for boys
and girls that turned into a dispute with repercussions for the
mayoral politics of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Chick, who had been working with the girls softball league to
try to find a solution, wants to develop an overall city policy on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Feuer also jumped into the act, holding a
hearing last week to begin collecting information on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffe, however, said she doesn't believe the one issue will have
long-term implications, beyond possibly raising Soboroff's profile.
</P>
<P>
   Soboroff is the least known of all the officials considering a
run for mayor in 2001, despite his high-profile assignments on the
Parks Commission and as Riordan's personal choice to head a citizen
committee to oversee school bond spending.
</P>
<P>
   In those roles, Soboroff has positioned himself as the outside
critic. But the softball suit places him squarely in the middle of
both defending a city agency and finding a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of positive stuff happening,'' he said. ``People
are coming together and trying to work something out. What I see is
all of us coming together and trying to use this to make Valley
baseball a model for the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Many political insiders believe Soboroff walked into a political
minefield by calling for hearings on the issue to promote more
playing fields citywide. But it's a gamble that could pay off in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always seen as the mayor's guy, which is not necessarily
bad,'' Jeffe said of Soboroff. ``But if it raises his profile _
particularly in the Valley _ it can only help him.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Fernando Valley almost certainly will be crucial in
2001. The Valley provided Riordan with the margin needed for his
first election, and it was the Valley that made up better than half
the vote in last year's election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
